<HEADER>
A0777 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DECADE17-COX     10-16 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DECADE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NAME GAME: WHAT WILL THE NEXT DECADE BE CALLED?
 &HT;    350&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ How about the ``Naughties?''
</P>
<P>
   Or is it ``Noughties?'' Spelling is only one complication of the
coming linguistic crisis: What will we call the next decade?
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, that's a good question,'' said Gerald Celente, director of
the Trends Research Institute and a futurist paid to ponder such
imponderables. ``Looking at the scope of the whole new millennium,
this will be the Starter Decade. I'd call it the 'First Decade.'
That's the way it will be looked at.''
</P>
<P>
   But somehow the ``Sixth Decade'' doesn't inspire images of
protests and Vietnam and bell-bottoms and Beatles like ``the
Sixties'' does. Think of the Thirties, and the Great Depression
comes to mind. For Baby Boomers, the Fifties will always conjure up
memories of Howdy Doody and Elvis and Ike.
</P>
<P>
   So be it the ``Naughts'' or the ``Oh Ohs'' or the ``Aughts'' or
the ``Zeroes'' or the ``Pre-Teens,'' the years 2000 to 2009 will
have to be called something.
</P>
<P>
   Well, what did Americans dub the first decade of the 20th
century?
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't any widely applied nickname, said Kenneth
Cmiel(cq), a professor of cultural history at the University of
Iowa and the author of ``Democratic Eloquence,'' a book on American
language.
</P>
<P>
   ``The naming of decades is a 20th-century thing that begins in
the 1930s,'' when folks looked back longingly on the ``roaring
Twenties,'' he explained. Four decades had passed before the 1890s
acquired the ``Gay Nineties'' moniker.
</P>
<P>
   The naming of decades came about as people began thinking in
shorter time frames, said Cmiel. And some of the 20th century's
momentous events _ the stock market crashed in 1929; World War II
began in 1939 _ divided history fairly neatly into decades.
</P>
<P>
   Decadism has also been boosted by recurring nostalgia fads, said
Cmiel. This began in the early 1970s with the movie ``American
Graffiti'' and the TV show ``Happy Days,'' and the time frame is
now so compressed that a movie like ``The Wedding Singer'' can look
back fondly at the Eighties.
</P>
<P>
   As to what to call the next decade, though, Cmiel concedes, ``I
have no clue.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if this problem sneaked up on a
vocabulary-challenged nation. Way back on May 7, 1989, the ``On
Language'' column of New York Times writer William Safire asked the
key question: ``What are we going to call the decade after the
decade of the Nineties?''
</P>
<P>
   Safire's readers suggested ``the Aughties'' or ``the Double
Naughties'' or ``the Zeroes,'' but no consensus was reached. More
recently, on the Internet, Joe Lavin's Humor Column conducted an
online survey and came up with advocates for ``the Ohs'' and the
``Uh Ohs'' and ``the Naughty Aughts.''
</P>
<P>
   There does seem to be some literary precedence for the
``Aughts''. In ``The Music Man,'' Professor Harold Hill claimed to
be a graduate of the Gary Conservatory, Class of Aught Five.
</P>
<P>
   However, the dictionary declares that ``aught'' is a corruption
of the term ``naught.'' Editorializing on this issue, The New York
Times opined that calling the decade ``the Aughts'' would be like
calling this publication ``an ewspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the term ``naught'' has an archaic air about it, and
worse, is defined as ``nothing'' or ``inconsequential'' _ hardly
desirable for the opening decade of a brand new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a spelling quandary. Is it ``Naught'' or
``Nought?'' ``Aught'' or ``Ought?'' Dictionaries list all the
versions.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post recently launched a contest to name the
decade, concluding with ``In the true spirit of the oughts, the
prize is nought.''
</P>
<P>
   A computer search on the topic turned up suggested decade names
of the Zips, the Zeds, the Zeroes, the Zilches, the Nadas and the
Nils _ which share the shortcoming that they all essentially mean
``the Nothings.'' Nobody will want to grow up during the Nadas.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times editorialized in favor of the ``Ohs.''
Indeed, a radio station in 2525 might well specialize in ``Golden
Oldies from the Ohs.'' And every year in the decade will contain
some ``Ohs.'' Calling the decade the ``Oh Ohs'' might offend
purists who would point out that the first year, 2000, is really an
``Oh Oh Oh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose you have to call it 'the Units','' Merriam-Webster
Dictionary editor Fred Mish told the Boston Globe. ``I don't know
what else you would use between zero and ten. Then, of course,
we're off the hook, since everyone can agree on the teens.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh-oh. What about 2011 and 2012?
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
