<HEADER>
A0797 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-RECORD17-COX     10-16 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-RECORD17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'DO-NOTHING CONGRESS' DID MORE THAN SOME RECALL
 &HT;    With CLINTON-CONGRESS.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Before ending in a pre-election flurry of budget
compromises and partisan jabs, this ``do-nothing Congress'' did
more than a lot of people recall.
</P>
<P>
   The most upbeat evaluation of the 105th Congress, which met for
far fewer days and passed far fewer laws than the average Congress
before it, came from House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first Congress since the 1920s to deliver a projected
10 years of a balanced budget _ a $1.6 trillion surplus over the
next 10 years,'' Gingrich said, ``setting the stage for us to come
back next year in a bipartisan way and save Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   The most scorching assessment came from his Democratic
counterpart, House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-S.D., who
recalled that his fellow Missourian, President Harry Truman, had
excoriated the 80th Congress as the ``Do-Nothing Congress'' in
1948.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Congress would make the 80th Congress look energetic and
effective,'' Gephardt said. ``They did rename (Washington's)
National Airport for Ronald Reagan, if you think that's an
important thing to have accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said, ``''I think it is their desire to please special
interests that has kept them from bring up the patient's bill of
rights, kept them from bringing up tobacco legislation and
(Democratic) education legislation, and interested them in a tax
cut when they should have been saving the money for Social Security
first.''
</P>
<P>
   The actual record of the Republican-controlled Congress, as it
alternated between cooperation and confrontation with the
Democratic White House, supports both Gingrich's and Gephardt's
views.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, President Clinton and Congress did indeed put off
action on some complex legislative dilemmas, including badly needed
new regulatory methods of dealing with the dangerously
fast-changing world of banks, investments and electric utilities.
</P>
<P>
   But that year they also agreed on a bipartisan five-year plan
that slowed the pace of projected spending increases by enough to
balance the federal budget for the first time in three decades. If
the nation never has another recession, even Gingrich's highly
unlikely dream of pain-free cures for Social Security's problems
could come true.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, they also adopted $95 billion in net tax cuts _ the
first tax bill since 1981 to contain more cuts than increases. It
included credits of $500 a child for families and lower tax rates
on estates and capital gains, as well as enough narrowly targeted
tax breaks to add 285 sections and 824 amendments to the U.S. tax
code.
</P>
<P>
   This year, of course, Congress killed the national tobacco
settlement and campaign finance reforms favored by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But together they also agreed on a bipartisan plan to overhaul
the Internal Revenue Service. They hope it will keep the IRS from
irritating taxpayers or treading on their rights while enforcing
the more complex tax code.
</P>
<P>
   Congress and Clinton this year also agreed on less publicized,
but potentially significant laws: job-training revisions, an
overhaul of low-income housing programs, and a humongous injection
of funds into highways and mass transit.
</P>
<P>
   Though they couldn't compete for headlines with congressional
action on the ethics of Gingrich in 1997 and of Clinton in 1998,
those low-profile laws adopted by big, bipartisan votes could
change life for millions of American workers, poor families and
commuters in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   This year's major reforms included:
</P>
<P>
   _ Job-training revisions. Ending a six-year stalemate over how
to fix federal job-training programs so diverse that nobody even
checked to see which ones were effective, Congress and the
administration agreed on a law simplifying the programs, giving
state and local officials more autonomy, and building in some
monitoring programs designed to find out which methods work best.
</P>
<P>
   _ Low-income housing overhaul. Three years of agonizing
negotiations between the Senate, the House and the White House
resulted in a 400-page law that retiring Rep. Joseph P. Kennedy,
D-Mass., described as ``the first major overhaul of the public
housing of this country in 60 years.'' As an alternative to using
public housing to warehouse the poorest of the poor, the bill
phases in programs that reward work by subsidized tenants, and
gives local officials more flexibility in programs designed to
provide affordable apartments to poor people or help them pay their
rent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Highways and mass transit. The six-year surface transportation
bill, guaranteeing each state at least 90.5 cents for each dollar
raised by federal gasoline taxes within its boundaries, allocates
$216 billion. That included a record $12 billion for bus and rail
projects and $9 billion for ``pork barrel'' projects specified by
individual members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
