<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0810 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKCHOI17-COX     10-16 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKCHOI17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Foreign Student' strong novel that stirs war, love, class,
culture
 &HT;    By Diane Roberts
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The curse and the blessing of the South is that it
functions as a sort of national theater, acting out the subjects _
race, history, class _ that the rest of the country assumes
immunity from. While mainstream America cheerfully dismisses the
past as irrelevant, the South is still the designated land of
suffering, poverty, prejudice: America's ``old country.''
</P>
<P>
   While these powerful images may be, by now, gross stereotyping,
their core truth feeds Southern writers on a rich diet of subtlety,
profundity and irony lacking in other American fiction, say, the
Updike school of high WASP suffering or the McInerneyesque
chronicles of People magazine partygoing. So it's good to report
that Susan Choi believes in the old-time religion of William
Faulkner, Ralph Ellison and Eudora Welty. Her first novel is a
strong, graceful piece of prose that stirs war, love, class and
culture together in a strange and beautiful alchemy.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of ``The Foreign Student'' conjures the sort of
mythic dream time Faulkner raises in ``Absalom, Absalom'' or Welty
evokes in her Morgana stories, the never-never ``before the war''
when rich families closed up their townhouses and moved to their
country estates. Only this is not Jefferson or Jackson but Seoul,
and the war is the Korean War. Chang ``Chuck'' Ahn is the child of
privileged Koreans who lose everything in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Barely surviving the ravages of the civil war, in 1955 Chuck
manages to escape on a church scholarship to the University of the
South in Sewanee, Tenn. There he meets Katherine Monroe, the child
of privileged Southerners who is trapped in a destructive
relationship with a dilettante professor. Chang and Katherine are
hurt, haunted people who manage, almost blindly, to come together
and heal each other.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Choi was born in Indiana and raised in Texas, and her
father was Korean. So who knows if she defines herself as
``Southern''? But in this work she is helping to reinvent ``the
Southern novel'' for the new millennium. She explores race and
class, but bypasses the expected avenues of Jim Crow, shack
dwellers and white columns in favor of looking at the South through
the eyes of a man who has no purchase on its magisterial systems of
prejudice. The South in the mid-1950s was working itself into a
decadelong series of explosions, but Choi resists the temptation to
overcontextualize her story. Chuck does not understand much of what
he sees. Sewanee, that double shrine to plantation-caste
Episcopalianism and the Lost Cause, is just a beautiful opportunity
to him. His civil war, his ruined lands, are behind him in Korea.
But in inviting the comparison, Choi slyly makes the South and the
great Southern obsession _ memory _ fresh.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck is the most compelling character in the novel: intricately
realized, constantly surprising, struggling for survival both in
Korea and in the United States. But maybe Choi exhausted herself in
creating him _ Katherine is at best enigmatic, at worst
two-dimensional. While she certainly militates against the
stereotype of the ``Southern belle,'' the creature of white gloves
and empty-headed grace her mother wishes her to be, her spikiness
and eccentricity read like decoration. Her motives and her feelings
remain opaque.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Foreign Student'' isn't exactly a love story, even though
Katherine and Chuck, two exiles, are strongly drawn to each other
in their loneliness. It's definitely a story about the
paradoxically crushing and liberating qualities of memory _ how the
weight of the past can warp the present.
</P>
<P>
   Choi is not quite in control of her ambitious material and her
potentially complex characters. But she writes with an authority
and tough beauty astonishing in a first novel. At times, she sounds
very much like Faulkner:
</P>
<P>
   ``He had thought he would always have two things, the great
space within him where his home had to live, and that diminishment,
when his body had imploded. Between the two, the excess of memory
and its absence, was left a story he couldn't describe. But the
story had begun to circumvent these difficulties. It grew shorter
and simpler. It would close around that event as his memory had
closed around the torture and his body around the wound, and,
constricting, leave no absence behind.''
</P>
<P>
   The South is not, of course, an ancient culture the way Korea
is, but it is America's land of memory. Choi has elegantly and
profoundly tied these two bleeding lands together in a novel that
forces us to see old landscapes anew.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
