<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Next thing you know, they'll be making round footballs
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since my wife, aka Mrs. Christopher Columbus, never misses a
chance to tack on a few frequent flyer points, we took a Delta
peanut and pretzel flight to watch our University of Georgia
student-athletes do battle with Louisiana State's student-athletes
in Baton Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   The way you go to a Georgia football game in Baton Rouge is
first you fly to New Orleans and spend Friday night barking on
Bourbon Street. Then you take a bus and a box lunch the rest of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   If Quincy Carter is perfect and Champ Bailey is sensational, as
they were, you can do some more barking in Baton Rouge, which is
French for Red Stick. Although I'm a loyal Bulldog fan I have
trouble being a comfortable barker, even on Bourbon Street. I'm a
little self-conscious yelling ``How 'Bout them Dawgs!'' while
high-fiving a perfect stranger.
</P>
<P>
   I'd hate for Mrs. Cole to hear me using bad English while
representing my university in public. I know I'd be in big trouble
with my former boss in the Atlanta Journal sports department.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was suspected of Georgia Tech leanings, Colonel Ed
Danforth, when he was sports editor, wouldn't let us use ``Dogs''
for Bulldogs even when we needed to shorten a headline. He
contended that student-athletes representing a state university
deserved more dignity.
</P>
<P>
   The next time Quincy Carter throws a sizzling touchdown pass to
one of his fellow student-athletes I'm going to high-five somebody
and yell: ``How about those Bulldogs! Woof! Woof!''
</P>
<P>
   College football has changed a bit now that stadiums can seat
the combined populations of Macon and Columbus. Ladies wear cutoffs
and bikini halters instead of church clothes, and professional
baseball players play quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I like to visit Baton Rouge. It's a throwback to
another era. Or was. Even Saturday night in Baton Rouge has
changed. The LSU defenders who called themselves Chinese Bandits
would be politically incorrect today. Mike the Tiger has lost his
voice.
</P>
<P>
   Before tickets cost half a car payment and 6-foot-2, 255 pounds
wasn't too small for a lineman, before The Swamp, Death Valley and
Between the Hedges _ Saturday night in Baton Rouge was the snakepit
of college football.
</P>
<P>
   While other campuses were happy with crowds of 30,000 to 40,000,
the LSU stadium seated 70,000. The way it got to be so over-sized
for the era was because Huey Long was governor of Louisiana and a
football fan.
</P>
<P>
   The Kingfish decided the university needed more dormitories,
which unlike stadiums, are built with taxpayer dollars. The
dormitories he built at LSU just happened to have 70,000 football
seats leaning against their backside. In order to fill the stadium
they had to sell about 50,000 ``family seats'' at $1 a head. Then
they had to play night games so 50,000 Cajuns would have time to
finish their shift, get drunk, and drive their pickups to the game.
Saturday Night in Baton Rouge with all those screaming Cajuns and
Mike the Tiger roaring became the most dreaded stop in college
football.
</P>
<P>
   They kept Mike, a huge Bengal, in a cage near the visiting
players' tunnel. His cage had a microphone. When visiting teams
trotted out on the field the LSU cheerleaders tapped Mike with an
electric cattle prod. Mike let out a terrible roar, and drunk
Cajuns screamed. It was terrifying. One Saturday night Coach Bobby
Dodd invited me to join him when his Georgia Tech team took the
field. It scared me, and I didn't have to play.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't hear anything from Mike on our latest visit to Baton
Rouge. I understand his role has been eliminated by the Society for
Prevention of Cruelty to Animals. If Huey Long were still governor
this couldn't have happened. The Kingfish would find a loophole.
When Ringling Bros. circus scheduled a Saturday night opening in
Baton Rouge, threatening to siphon off the football crowd, Gov.
Long reminded circus officials of the Louisiana Dipping Law
requiring all animals to be submerged in an antiseptic before
crossing the state line. Faced with the sudden task of dipping
lions, tigers and elephants, the circus had to punt.
</P>
<P>
   College football is an interesting business. I've often wondered
what someone opening a time capsule several thousand years from now
would think of newspaper headlines in football season: Georgia Tech
Explodes. Wildcats Devour Tigers. Georgia Bombs LSU. How 'Bout Them
Dawgs!
</P>
<P>
   When we were all worked up earlier in the century after Georgia
beat Notre Dame for a national championship, a man from Stockbridge
wrote to ask if it was really better than when he gathered his
Scout troop on Saturday mornings and drove the boys over to Athens
so they could usher in Sanford Stadium and see the game for free.
</P>
<P>
   College football, like everything else, barely favors what it
used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
