<DOCNO> NYT19981016.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0813 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUPIL17-COX     10-16 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUPIL17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Apt Pupil' director Bryan Singer is committed to original ideas
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If anyone has doubted the cultlike fascination
``The Usual Suspects'' exerted on a generation of teen and
twenty-something film dweebs, they need only to have witnessed the
scene in the lobby of the Paramount last Thursday after the
screening of Bryan Singer's latest flick, ``Apt Pupil.'' The dweebs
_ starry eyes, goatees, baseballs caps and all _ were out in force
pinning against a table the lionized director of ``Usual Suspects
.'' For a full 40 minutes he fielded queries like a Real Nice Guy,
as he signed random pieces of paper and was X-rayed in the bleached
lightning of cheap cameras.
</P>
<P>
   This is what happens when you're an impossibly young and hugely
successful director of hip, violent and overly clever crime
thrillers. This is what happened to Quentin Tarantino. And, a
little later, what happened to the 32-year-old Singer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Usual Suspects,'' filmed when Singer was 28, was a solid
box-office success and landed its screenwriter, Christopher
McQuarrie, and supporting actor Kevin Spacey Academy Awards in
1995. Its stylish bravado _ testosteronic bloodletting, flashy
visuals, hairpin structure _ marked the arrival of an audacious new
filmmaker. (Singer's first feature was 1992's ``Public Access.'')
</P>
<P>
   Opening Oct. 23, ``Apt Pupil'' is Singer's long-awaited
follow-up. It's a creepy thriller based on the Stephen King novella
about a teen-ager (Brad Renfro) who blackmails an elderly Nazi war
criminal named Kurt Dussander (Ian McKellan) who's been living
incognito in town. The screenplay is by first-time scripter Brandon
Boyce.
</P>
<P>
   When his fans finally cleared, Singer sprung atop the counter of
the Par- amount bar, where he sat cross-legged and talked briefly
about ``Pupil'' and his current project, ``The X-Men,'' which is
based on the comic book.
</P>
<P>
   He was also forthcoming about the well-publicized controversy
that tainted the production of ``Apt Pupil.'' A group of underage
actors filed a lawsuit alleging that Singer's crew forced them to
get completely naked for a shower scene, which is illegal under
child labor laws. The teen-age actors and their parents are suing
Singer and TriStar Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   A diminutive man, whose fierce blue eyes accent a feline
intensity, Singer wore a black velour shirt, blue jeans and
tennies. He looked no older than 22. No older than many of his
die-hard fans. Q: What attracted you to ``Apt Pupil''? A: Well, the
idea that this awful thing that happened so long ago, the way
Stephen King viewed it as a collective evil, almost like a golem,
almost like a monster in itself and how it crept through the
decades into contemporary society. That interested me, and how it
manifested itself in this young boy through (the character)
Dussander. I found that fascinating. It was a real horror film as
opposed to a supernatural one, though I do love supernatural horror
films. My favorite horror film is by far ``The Exorcist.'' This is
a horror film to me; a more psychological horror film. If you had
to coin a new phrase, you could perhaps call it a ``social horror
film.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think it's risky at this point in your career to
continue to work with first-time writers?
</P>
<P>
   A: I have faith in people and my abil- ity to work with writers.
I work very closely with writers from page one. I think Brandon
exhibited himself well in the prose he had written and his overall
intelligence as a human being, and I had faith that he could write
the script. Ultimately he wrote some scenes and we did some work
together on spec so we could establish that it was possible.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You knew Brandon before this?
</P>
<P>
   A: I've known Brandon since he was 11 years old. He was my
family's paper boy. He was delivering newspapers one day, and we
struck up a friendship when I was very young. We fell out of touch
for about six years when he moved, and then he popped up at USC
while I was attending school there. We ran into each other in a
dining hall and we struck up a more real friendship and have been
friends ever since. I have two best friends in my life, and one of
them is Brandon.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you guys do film stuff as kids?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah, he's acted in many films I did, as a kid in New Jersey,
and then he co-starred with Ethan Hawke (a close friend of
Singer's) in my short film ``Lion's Den.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: How does ``The X-Men'' fit into your vision as a director?
</P>
<P>
   A: Again, it's a very original idea and original concept and a
very effective and important one. It's all about the
disenfranchised , people who are looking for an identity, a place
in the world, and are trying to find it amidst prejudice. I think
it's an important concept, yet it's presented in a comic-book
universe, which allows it to reach so many young people, and that's
a key audience for that kind of ideology.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's your take on the on-set controversy surrounding ``Apt
Pupil''?
</P>
<P>
   A: My opinion is it was a group of people who saw this as an
opportunity to make quick money in a quick settlement from a very
wealthy studio and made a mistake, because the studio had no
interest in settling. It understood completely that absolutely
nothing had gone on inappropriately, esp- ecially in front of the
60 people who were there, including a state-appointed social worker
who was there the entire time. I find it odd that these people are
suing when they came back to work the following day and the day
after.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where does the suit stand now?
</P>
<P>
   A: Criminally, it's completely thrown out. The DA interviewed
everyone and did a thorough investigation and threw it completely
out. It lingers as a civil suit, but most of that civil suit _ the
initial and highly inflammatory, highly malicious civil suit _ has
been dismissed by the judge as well, and elements of that suit
continue to be dismissed, so at some point it may not exist at all.
</P>
<P>
   Q: As a young filmmaker with three finished films, do you have
any idea where you're going with your career, what kind of body of
work you're trying to forge?
</P>
<P>
   A: Just original movies, original ideas. When I say original I
don't mean my ideas, I mean things we haven't seen before. Now,
they may incorporate things we have seen before _ we've seen film
noir, we've seen bits and pieces of this movie. But the idea of a
child blackmailing a Nazi to hear of his past, or the idea of five
criminals who end up being the figment of some guy's perpetuation
of his own myth, or X-Men, a group of reluctant superheroes, you
know, they're all very unique, very special. They're not cast from
molds that we've seen before.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
