<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0815 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-GLENN17-COX     10-16 1455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GLENN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    John Glenn braces for his last adventure in space
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ From Friendship to Discovery, John Glenn has
been an American hero for more than three decades. Television was
there to beam his first space journey home to us, and it will be
there to record his last.
</P>
<P>
   As Glenn, 77, prepares to blast off Oct. 29 for a nine-day
mission aboard the Space Shuttle Discovery, television welcomes
back 81-year-old Walter Cronkite, the veteran newsman who covered
Glenn's first mission aboard Friendship 7 in 1962. Cronkite will
co-anchor CNN's coverage of the mission with Miles O'Brien, from
beginning to end, in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I'm delighted John is getting the flight,'' Cronkite
said in a phone call from New York before heading to Texas for his
first live broadcast since a '91 shuttle launch. ``But as I told
him, it's most unfair. I'm older than he is, and if they want to
test old age in space, I'm the one to send up there.''
</P>
<P>
   These two senior citizens, Glenn, a Democratic U.S. senator from
Ohio, and Cronkite, a retired CBS news anchor with a passion for
space, represent more than nostalgia. They represent a renewed
interest in exploration and adventure beyond earth, as well as
television's revived interest in covering it all live. And perhaps
the two men remind us of pride, patriotism and happier times.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the attention we're giving this flight, the hope is we
can re-ignite the public's interest in space flight,'' said
Cronkite. ``The public has become blase(accent). Shuttle launches
have become so routine they're scarcely covered by the press, but
we have an opportunity here to remind people we're out there in
space. NASA accepted John Glenn's mission for the same purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewers can expect lots of live coverage on all the news
networks for the scheduled 1 p.m. lift-off on Oct. 29 and for the
Nov. 7 return. In between, the astronaut team aboard Discovery will
transmit live broadcasts daily. Cable networks such as CNN and
MSNBC will carry them live; the broadcast networks likely will
excerpt the space telecasts on their evening newscasts and
newsmagazines. Live from orbit
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the things that's different for Glenn's mission
this time _ live pictures from space,'' said Bill Wheatley, vice
president of NBC News. ``And up-to-date graphics. But I think the
approach, in many ways, will be similar. You've got a rocket going
up in space from the Cape, and we're all going to follow the
count-down and lift-off.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cronkite sees a world of difference between this month's
mission coverage and his early days covering NASA rocket launches
for CBS radio and, later, for CBS television. In the late '50s, the
press wasn't allowed on Cape Canaveral in Florida so Cronkite
watched from a jetty, ``getting chewed up by mosquitoes up top and
rattlesnakes below,'' he said chuckling. Later, he graduated to
reporting from the back of his station wagon and finally, in the
'60s, to a trailer on the Cape. For the upcoming Glenn mission,
he'll be ensconced in relative luxury at Mission Control Center in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing a lot of homework just trying to catch up,'' said
Cronkite. ``All I've got is a lot of memories, so I'm trying to get
up to speed on the shuttle program. . . . I flunked my first year
of physics at the University of Texas, so I've always had a lot to
overcome preparing for these things.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a buzz about this mission we haven't heard in a long
time. NASA has been swamped with requests for media credentials.
Spokesman Doug Peterson said NASA has received more than 2,000 such
requests from journalists worldwide who want to cover the mission,
either from the control center in Houston or from the launch site
at Cape Canaveral. Last week NASA averaged a call every 10 minutes
from news organizations wanting an astronaut to provide commentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody sees a little bit of their own history in
John Glenn,'' NASA's Peterson said. ``And kids, there's a
tremendous interest among kids, who always seem to be turned on by
space. There's just been incredible interest in this flight.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early days of space travel, Americans were captivated by
the idea of going to the heavens, and when man set foot on the
moon, the world was transfixed by the grainy images and scratchy
audio . . . ``That's one small step for man, one giant leap for
mankind.'' The moon landing in the summer of '69 remains one of the
most-watched news events of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much was coming together in the '60s,'' said Robert
Thompson, director of the Center for the Study of Popular
Television at Syracuse University. ``There was a revolutionary new
mind-set. Not only was the space program new, but it was covered by
a medium that was new. It was a fascinating period for space and
TV. . . . The awe was not only that we were firing people into
orbit, but that television was letting us watch it. It was a
delightfully naive, jaw-dropping period.''
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, space travel and television grew up together; now
both, in many respects, are taken for granted. Space was the
future, the place to be, and TV was the miracle medium that would
entertain us, inform us and take us to the moon.
</P>
<P>
   But over the years, space flight has become ordinary, and
television technology is no longer new. In fact, TV technology is
primitive compared to computers.
</P>
<P>
   The Challenger disaster in 1986 sparked renewed interest for a
time, after the inspirational sight of schoolteacher Christa
McAuliffe soaring into space turned into a horror witnessed by
millions of children. And the Mars Pathfinder mission last year,
with the little Sojourner robot crawling over red-dirt hills,
attracted us briefly.
</P>
<P>
   On the entertainment front, Tom Hanks' movie ``Apollo 13'' and
his HBO docudrama ``From the Earth to the Moon'' were wildly
popular.
</P>
<P>
   But lift-offs and splash-downs are rarely covered live by TV
news any more. Missions come and go with only 30-second blips on
the evening news. NASA press conferences often attract only a
handful of journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Until now. Positive programming
</P>
<P>
   As the first American to orbit the earth prepares to return to
space, TV cameras have followed his training and will follow him
into space.
</P>
<P>
   Why has Glenn's return to space so captivated the American
public?
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, it's John Glenn,'' said NBC's Wheatley.
``He's 77 years old, one of the most famous Americans. He's a
remarkable story, highly inspirational, and that adds a little
romance to the topic.''
</P>
<P>
   And we shouldn't discount the timing. We had a long spring and
hot summer filled with depressing, distasteful news from
Washington. People are hungry for good news and inspiring stories.
Home-run sluggers Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa lifted our spirits
for a time, and now we have Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a perfect bit of counter-programming for the culture
right now,'' Thompson said. ``In many ways, we're seeing more a
sense of nostalgia. It's this great story of one of the guys who
started it all going up again.''
</P>
<P>
   But some believe we may never see the kind of enthusiasm for
space we had in the early days. Another manned mission to the moon
might get our attention, but possibly not in the breathtaking way
it did in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea of going to the heavens, of reaching into
space, was a remarkable concept in the '60s _ on a par with the
great explorers exploring the continents,'' said NBC's Wheatley.
``But once some of those basics were accomplished, concepts like
the shuttle had far less romance.'' Space travel, the sequel
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more cynical is Thompson's comparison of the Glenn
mission covered by Cronkite to TV recycling old shows such as
``Fantasy Island.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, one sees the space program going the same route
as entertainment genres, going back to what worked before,
Hollywood making films about old TV shows and TV making remakes of
old TV shows,'' Thompson said. ``It's almost like this is the
greatest hits of the space program. The cloud that seems to be all
over this is we are so much in this culture of recycling, renewal
and nostalgia.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cronkite firmly believes space exploration is the biggest
story of the 20th century, and he hopes the return of Glenn, along
with television's decision to beam the journey live, will remind
people of our past and future as travelers in the universe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Space is one of the great challenges we still face, our last
frontier,'' he said softly. ``I can't imagine anyone not being
excited about it. It's our last great adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
