<HEADER>
A0816 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SLAVERY17-COX     10-16 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SLAVERY17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Six-hour documentary on American's journey through slavery
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ How did a nation based on the concept of liberty
and justice for all come to justify the existence of slavery? This
mysterious paradox has puzzled and troubled us for generations.
</P>
<P>
   PBS's new 6-hour documentary series ``Africans in America:
America's Journey Through Slavery'' explores this difficult topic
through innovative historical research, personal stories and superb
filmmaking. The result is compelling television that peels back the
layers of America's ongoing struggle with racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we realize that we've spent more time as a people with
slavery than without it, we can begin to see it as a centerpiece of
our national identity,'' said executive producer Orlando Bagwell,
whose credits include ``Eyes on the Prize,'' ``Malcolm X: Make It
Plain'' and ``The Great Depression.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this is not a black history or a white history, but
a story that explores how white and black slavery and freedom are
connected at the hip. It's a story of our common pasts. ... It is a
uniquely American story. If we recognize our shared history, then
we're on the road to reconciling racial divisiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   The first episode, which airs tonight, focuses on the origins of
one of the largest forced migrations in recorded history. After the
arrival of the first Africans in Virginia in the early 1600s, the
groundwork for a system of racial slavery was established by
British colonists. In the second episode, the film juxtaposes the
colonists' revolt against the British with the seeds of revolt by
the slaves.
</P>
<P>
   The third and fourth episodes explores in depth the growing
revolutionary spirit among slaves and abolitionists through the
first 50 years of the new nation and concludes with the tensions
that exploded into the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Filmed on location in 12 states and three continents, ``Africans
in America'' uses a combination of first-person narratives,
interviews with historians and descendants of slaves and richly
evocative music. The soundtrack is from Bernice Johnson Reagon ,
founder of Sweet Honey in the Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Visually the story is told through the filmed interviews,
drawings and a few photos, as well as some artfully filmed new
footage, including scenes of a 17th-century ship bobbing in the
ocean, the African and American countryside and historic buildings
such as Mount Vernon.
</P>
<P>
   Slavery is a wrenching topic that has been explored before, but
Bagwell's documentary is the most complete record since Alex
Haley's autobiographical novel ``Roots.'' An educational outreach
program, including lessons, tapes and computer programs, is being
sponsored by PBS.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Johnson, author of ``Dream'' and ``Middle Passage,''
wrote a companion book for the series that includes 12 short
stories. Using fiction to provide easier access to history has been
used effectively many times, and Johnson, who also is interviewed
in the program, believes the one-two punch adds impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it might take time to move forward, because you can't
block out how we got to this moment in time,'' Johnson said. ``We
have to fully understand that history and its complexity and the
participation of all kinds of people who made this nation what it
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the existing research on the subject, it's not surprising
that there are few historical discoveries. Nevertheless, Bagwell
hopes his fresh and thorough treatment will dispel at least one
common misconception.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the very beginning, there was no slavery in the North
American colonies,'' he said. ``In the beginning, there were no
laws that governed this idea of servitude. Only gradually did
slavery become a reality in Virginia and the other 13 colonies.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the program, many Africans arrived as indentured
servants, along with many white indentured servants. Later
legalized, life-long slavery became associated exclusively with
people of color.
</P>
<P>
   One of several descendants of slaves interviewed for the program
is Karen Hughes White, who researched her family roots to Virginia
and to slaves owned by Thomas Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept meticulous records, so I was able to find out all of
the transactions from his farm accounts,'' White told reporters in
an interview. Like other proud African-Americans whose history
coincides with our founding fathers, White is philosophical about
the people who bought and sold her ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jefferson was a man of his time,'' White said. ``You can't
change that, but you can accept it for what it is. We are all
Americans, and we are products of slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``Africans in America'' takes pains to point out that
all of us, black and white, have been affected by our history of
slavery, adding to tensions that continue today.
</P>
<P>
   After spending nearly a decade researching and planning his
documentary, Bagwell said he found the creation of institutional
slavery in this country depressing, but he also found reason for
hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look not just at the evolution of slavery but how it became
an entrenched part of society,'' Bagwell said. ``And that goes
along with certain ideas about whiteness as well as blackness.
These ideas of race are things we construct, and that was the most
interesting and surprising element for me in doing the research. I
realized that this is something we have constructed, and therefore
there's also the possibility of deconstructing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
