<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-SENATE (San Francisco) _ In a race so tight it may not be
decided until the last votes are counted, Republican Matt Fong is
favored by a slim margin of voters in his bid to unseat Democratic
Sen. Barbara Boxer, according to a San Francisco Examiner-KTVU
poll. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GOV (San Francisco) _ As his campaign struggles to attract
moderate Democrats and independent voters, Republican Dan Lungren
has wrapped himself in the legacy of Ronald Reagan while remaining
unapologetic about a conservative record his opponent says is more
Gingrich than the Gipper. By ZACHARY COILE and ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA-CORRUPTION (Undated) _ San Francisco 49ers co-owner
Edward J. DeBartolo Jr. may have started a trend with his plea
bargain in the gambling corruption case the government is building
against former Louisiana Gov. Edwin W. Edwards. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   BALLOT-NAME (San Francisco) _ Threatening legal action,
Supervisor Mabel Teng lashed out at election officials for omitting
her Chinese name from absentee ballots, potentially costing her
thousands of votes. By JULIE CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-AUTHOR-PROFILE (Undated) _ Dr. Bob Arnot, the NBC News
medical correspondent, describes himself as a ``knowledge
engineer'' _ someone who finds cutting-edge research that has
immediate benefit on people's lives. But when his mother-in-law
developed breast cancer and his wife asked him what she could do to
keep from getting breast cancer, Arnot was at a loss. So he wrote a
book. By BARBARA KARKABI.
</P>
<P>
   PARIS-FASHION (Paris) _ The spring women's ready-to-wear
collections get under way in Paris. By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ When the new v.90 standard for 56K
modems was approved earlier this year, both users and manufacturers
breathed a sigh of relief. Burdened for months by competing 56K
standards, buyers were confused and held off upgrading to the
faster devices. With the arrival of v.90, there's now just one way
to get to 56K. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ The Windows' find function can
turn into a shortcut. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Undated) _ Author Nicholas Lore says there is a
strong connection between setting goals and accomplishing the
goals. People who write their goals down and review them often tend
to fulfill their goals, Lore says. By L.M. SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-CHARITY (San Francisco) _ You don't normally find
companies that give half of their annual profits to charities on
any fast-track to success lists. But Give Something Back, a
six-year-old office supply company, made Inc. magazine's new list
of the fastest growing private companies in the country. By
VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-REVIEW-LAWYERS (Undated) _ While ``ER'' remains at the top of
the ratings, legal shows have become dominant again on television.
But what do lawyers think of the modern-day legal dramas? Well,
they believe some are entertaining _ even beneficial _ as long as
you don't mind the fine points getting screwed up. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FIOM-REVIEW-BELOVED (Undated) _ ``Beloved'' is a deep, deep well
of a movie, a film that ripples with meaning and metaphor and
unnerving supernatural questions. Absorbing, confusing and
uncompromisingly dark, this interpretation of Toni Morrison's novel
challenges the very notion of what a movie can and should demand of
its viewers. It demands, first of all, attention. By AMY BIANCOLLI
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-GWYNN (New York) _ People here seem shocked to learn that
Tony Gwynn has never seen Yankee Stadium. I mean, everybody who's
anybody has seen Yankee Stadium, right? The Pope ... Jack Dempsey
... The Ritz Brothers. That, though, is the essential beauty of New
Yorkers. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Gov. George Pataki appears to have
his re-election bid all but wrapped up. But races further down the
ticket may not be the smooth cruises that Republicans had
envisioned _ not the 10 or so seats that they'd hoped to pick up in
the State Assembly and not the race to succeed Rep. Gerald B.H.
Solomon. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Whatever you do for a living,
imagine that your job requires you to do it while wearing a hot,
heavy, uncomfortable uniform in front of, say, 3,500 people.
Imagine that you are an opera star. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   LEWINSKY-SYMPATHY (San Francisco) _ Following the brouhaha over
the White House sexcapades, I've spent some time deciding who has
earned my sympathy. It's not Monica; she brought this on herself.
For the same reason, it isn't President Clinton. Hillary Rodham
made a conscious decision to marry the man; she's out. The two
people I came up with were Chelsea Clinton and Monica's father,
Bernard. By EVAN RAIL.
</P>
