<HEADLINE>
BUYING THE STORY ABOUT THE NEW BILL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: How can I read the secret information that is
recorded on the new $20 bill? Do I need a special magnetic stripe
reader, or is there a way to download it?
</P>
<P>
   _ Double Sawbuck
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DOUBLE: Well, it didn't take long for that rumor to get
started, did it? And I can remember when all we had to worry about
were the United Nations shock troops massing on our borders and
patrolling the skies in their black helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   They're still there, of course, but there is no secret chip
embedded in the bill. There is, however, a micro-cam cleverly
concealed in each of Andrew Jackson's eyes. Haven't you noticed the
way the portrait's eyes follow you, no matter where you stand?
</P>
<P>
   The real changes in the 20 are primarily to make it tougher on
counterfeiters. There's no electronic wizardry involved, at least
none that I can talk about without violating the federal Big Scary
Secrets Act of 1968. The only thing vaguely suspicious about the
new bill is that it looks like it was designed by the lowest
bidder, whose last experience must have been at Parker Brothers
churning out Monopoly money. And if there's any nefarious plot
behind anything, it's one designed to keep U.S. dollars at home,
since the new bill is much too embarrassing to show to foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Is there a way to deactivate the 3.5-inch
floppy via software to keep people from inserting virus-loaded
disks?
</P>
<P>
   _ Germ-Free
</P>
<P>
   DEAR FREE: You could try deactivating the floppy drive through
your setup program. (Oh, get the manual out. I can't be expected to
tell you how to do everything.) Just be forewarned that your
particular setup may automatically recognize the drive and
reactivate it. Either that, or it could refuse to let you reboot at
all.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose you might find some drive-locking software, or you
could pop the top on your PC and yank the power and data cables
out. There are even real locks you can stick in the drive, but
guess what? Even if you stuffed the floppy drive full of aged
Gouda, you'd still be susceptible to viruses in things you download
from the Internet. Go buy a good virus scanner that has free
monthly updates.
</P>
<P>
   STUPID SOFTWARE TRICK: Proving once again that Microsoft
engineers have way too much time on their hands, check out this
Windows 98 silliness:
</P>
<P>
   Use Windows Explorer to open up the Windows folder. Click into
Application Data, then Microsoft, then Welcome. Look for a file
called Weldata.exe and right-click on it. Select Create Shortcut
from the menu that pops up.
</P>
<P>
   Now right-click on the shortcut you just made and select
Properties from the menu. In the Target box, after the stuff that's
already there, add a space, then 
``You(underscore)are(underscore)a(underscore)real(underscore)rascal'
' minus the quotes, of course. In the Run box, select Minimized.
Now click on OK.
</P>
<P>
   When you double-click on the shortcut, you'll get the names of
the Win98 developers, so you finally know who to blame. And don't
let them distract you with that slide show of the Microsoft campus
and Seattle. I think that's how Janet Reno got sidetracked.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay offers occasionally
accurate advice about most things electronic. He can be reached on
Internet at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via snail-mail at Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101; or fax: (817)
390-7257. His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
