<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   DECADE17-COX_WASHINGTON _ How about the ``Naughties?''
</P>
<P>
   Or is it ``Noughties?'' Spelling is only one complication of the
coming linguistic crisis: What will we call the next decade?
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, that's a good question,'' said Gerald Celente, director of
the Trends Research Institute and a futurist paid to ponder such
imponderables. (DART, Cox Washington Bureau). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   REALSTYLE _ Fifth installment in series on designers/companies
whose clothes people actually wear. Featured designer: Ellen Tracy.
(Anna, Palm Beach Post). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT
</P>
<P>
   BKCHOI _ ATLANTA _ The curse and the blessing of the South is
that it functions as a sort of national theater, acting out the
subjects _ race, history, class _ that the rest of the country
assumes immunity from. While mainstream America cheerfully
dismisses the past as irrelevant, the South is still the designated
land of suffering, poverty, prejudice: America's ``old country.''
While these powerful images may be, by now, gross stereotyping,
their core truth feeds Southern writers on a rich diet of subtlety,
profundity and irony lacking in other American fiction, say, the
Updike school of high WASP suffering or the McInerneyesque
chronicles of People magazine partygoing. So it's good to report
that Susan Choi believes in the old-time religion of William
Faulkner, Ralph Ellison and Eudora Welty. Her first novel is a
strong, graceful piece of prose that stirs war, love, class and
culture together in a strange and beautiful alchemy. (Roberts,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   STAFFBOOKS _ ATLANTA _ Books by writers at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution that were recently published. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   PUPIL _ AUSTIN, Texas _ If anyone has doubted the cultlike
fascination ``The Usual Suspects'' exerted on a generation of teen
and twenty-something film dweebs, they need only to have witnessed
the scene in the lobby of the Paramount last Thursday after the
screening of Bryan Singer's latest flick, ``Apt Pupil.'' This is
what happens when you're an impossibly young and hugely successful
director of hip, violent and overly clever crime thrillers. This is
what happened to Quentin Tarantino. And, a little later, what
happened to the 32-year-old Singer. (Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TV-GLENN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ From Friendship to Discovery, John
Glenn has been an American hero for more than three decades.
Television was there to beam his first space journey home to us,
and it will be there to record his last. (Holloway, Austin
American-Statesman). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TV-SLAVERY _ AUSTIN, Texas _ How did a nation based on the
concept of liberty and justice for all come to justify the
existence of slavery? This mysterious paradox has puzzled and
troubled us for generations. PBS's new 6-hour documentary series
``Africans in America: America's Journey Through Slavery'' explores
this difficult topic through innovative historical research,
personal stories and superb filmmaking. The result is compelling
television that peels back the layers of America's ongoing struggle
with racism. (Holloway, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-POPE_VATICAN CITY_A look at Pope John Paul II who on
Friday
</P>
<P>
   marked 20 years at the head of the billion-strong Catholic
Church. At 78,
</P>
<P>
   he is fragile and fading. Yet, he continues to enliven his
church wile
</P>
<P>
   defending its traditional_and, to some, controversial_doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   HOME &AMP; GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   PAINT _ You know about coordinating wardrobe colors. But have
you ever thought about what your house is wearing? By coordinating
exterior paint color with landscape plants you can enhance your
home's ``curb appeal,'' as real estate agents call it, by making it
more inviting. It can be as simple as complementing a red front
door with red geraniums near the steps. Or you can think of the
total picture, blending architectural styles with period plants _
roses and old-fashioned annuals planted against a Victorian
cottage, red Japanese maples and ferns to accent a contemporay
home. (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS and
LAYOUT
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   PAINT-TIPS _ Tips on selecting the right color paint for your
home's exterior. (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 6-8.
</P>
<P>
   LEEMAY-COLUMN _ Lee ponders the beauty of pregnant onions -- a
type of houseplant -- and other beauties of nature. The plant gets
it name by producing little offsets about the size of peas under
the skin of the mother bulb that sits above the soil. Each baby can
sprout and become a mother when it touches dirt. (May, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
