<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIRL POWER ON THE OPERA STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Whatever you do for a living, imagine that your
job requires you to do it while wearing a hot, heavy, uncomfortable
uniform in front of, say, 3,500 people. Imagine that you have been
working for several weeks on a special project. You have eaten and
slept the thing, tended to every nuance and detail. More than
anything, you want the project to be perfect and pleasing.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you present it. Within 48 hours, because it is their
job, several people publicly assess your project. Almost all of
them say it stunk. They say that everything you are trained to do,
you did badly. They use terms like ``inadequate,'' ``regrettable,''
``desperate,'' ``acidic,'' ``ungovernable'' and ``squally.'' They
call the boss who gave you the project ``deluded.''
</P>
<P>
   The really bad news? Because it is your job, you get to go out a
few days later in your hot, heavy, uncomfortable uniform and
present the project again to another 3,500 people _ most of whom
have read the scathing public assessments.
</P>
<P>
   How would you feel? What would you do? Until I met a German
opera singer named Gabriele Schnaut, I figured I would call in
sick, grab my passport and Visa card and head for the Great Barrier
Reef. But Schnaut changed me.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, as a supernumerary (extra actor) for the San
Francisco Opera, I portrayed one of Schnaut's handmaidens in
Puccini's ``Turandot.'' We weren't even remotely buddies but, from
a close perspective, I watched her work hard through weeks of
rehearsals, a nerve-wracking opening night of the autumn opera
season and six more performances. During that time, she was
meticulous and careful about her interpretation of the icy,
rage-filled Chinese princess who finally learns that love is all
that really matters.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some opera divas I have worked with, Schnaut was kind to
us lowly extras; she treated us as if we were intelligent human
beings instead of flesh-upholstered furniture. Sometimes onstage,
when she sang the killer, second-act aria, ``In questa reggia,'' it
was hard not to shout; I was that moved by her performance. One
night, she was so great, she made me cry, and I had to have my
garish red and white makeup redone between acts.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the local critics blasted her. And when I say ``blasted
her,'' I mean her. (Critics never just say they didn't like
somebody or that a production failed. They write personally,
pointedly and meanly, as if a phalanx of idiots and no-goods had
betrayed all of humanity.)
</P>
<P>
   In the five days between the reviews and the second performance
of ``Turandot,'' I could not imagine how bad it felt to be Gabriele
Schnaut. Every time I thought about being her and going back
onstage to sing some of the toughest music ever written for the
female voice, I found myself curling up in the fetal position.
</P>
<P>
   When the second performance came, however, Schnaut did something
that pro basketball people call ``putting on a clinic.'' In Act II,
she mounted a center stage stairway in her hot, heavy and
uncomfortable princess garb, opened her mouth and sang ``In questa
reggia'' with a beauty and fury that I have rarely seen. In 25
years in the newspaper business, I have encountered and written
about some mighty powerful women, but nobody was as possessed of
personal power as Schnaut was that night.
</P>
<P>
   When the act was over and the singer had disappeared into her
dressing room, I asked her wardrobe people to please tell her that
one of the handmaidens said she had kicked ass. It was the best
term I could think of.
</P>
<P>
   At the next performance, before we went onstage, I asked her if
the message had been conveyed. ``Yah,'' she said in a delightful
German accent. ``They say that I kicked the ass.'' But she looked
at me quizzically so I corrected the phrase and explained what it
meant.
</P>
<P>
   She nodded, revisiting that night. ``I was furious,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Gabriele Schnaut joined my Girl Power hall of fame.
Lie down and die because a handful of folks eviscerated you in
print? Feign illness and slink off to the Great Barrier Reef in
defeat? Not this dame. She fought back with everything she had, and
she not only survived, she prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   What a role model. From now on, as far as I'm concerned, the
translation of ``In questa reggia'' is: ``'Cause I'm woman _
W-O-M-A-N.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
