<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT ALL GOP RACES IN NEW YORK WILL BE AS EASY AS PATAKI'S 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New York Gov. George Pataki seems to be in the
same enviable position in which Edwin Edwards found himself when he
ran for re-election as governor of Louisiana a few years back.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards bragged that the only way he could lose would be if he
were caught in bed with a dead girl or a live boy. And, in Pataki's
case, the live boy could give him a big boost in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   That's not true, however, for any other New York Republican
running this year. Polling numbers show New Yorkers, unlike voters
in the Heartland, increasingly hostile to Republicans over this
Zippergate scandal in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   That explains why both Pataki and Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, whose
re-election bid is hardly a sure thing, have maintained stony
silences on the issue. Neither has uttered a word on Zippergate,
and each quite clearly would bite his tongue in half before doing
so.
</P>
<P>
   It also indicates that races further down the ticket may not be
the smooth cruises that Republicans had envisioned _ not the 10 or
so seats that they'd hoped to pick up in the State Assembly and not
the race in New York's 22nd Congressional District.
</P>
<P>
   The 22nd stretches from up near the Canadian border down to New
York City's northern suburbs. For two decades, it has been
represented by Gerald B.H. Solomon. He's one of the most
conservative members of the House of Representatives. As chairman
of the House Rules Committee, Solomon has been one of the House's
most powerful members for the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   But the district has changed since Solomon took office in the
1970s. What was once a conservative rural district is now,
overwhelmingly, a collection of suburban communities where voting
patterns have moderated.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP maintains a 2-1 enrollment edge in the district, but a
large percentage of the voters are affiliated with neither major
party, and Bill Clinton won this congressional district in 1996.
That same year, a personable actor/farmer named Steve James spent a
little money on some clever television ads. Against Solomon, a
nine-term incumbent, James polled two in five votes cast.
</P>
<P>
   That's why, when Solomon unexpectedly announced his retirement
this year, the state's Republican leadership stepped in to ensure
that the local Republican organization did not select a
right-winger to succeed him. Instead, state Republican chief Bill
Powers anointed John Sweeney, a high-ranking Pataki aide. Sweeney
is a gregarious, middle-of-the-road sort and a longtime political
operative who's never held elected office. Meanwhile, the Democrats
were unable to persuade James to run again. And, on such short
notice, they were unable to find another candidate with big name
recognition in the district. They settled instead on Jean
Bordewich, a Red Hook council member. She's also a moderate and
perfectly plausible in the 22nd. But she's from the district's
southern tip and lacks the cash to build celebrity in the Albany
metro area, where most of votes are.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney's strategy in this race has been to lie low _ to do his
utmost to deny Bordewich visibility in metro Albany and to trumpet
his role in the Pataki administration through a ceaseless barrage
of broadcast ads. Chances are this strategy will work. Powers is a
brilliant tactician and he has taken a personal interest in this
race.
</P>
<P>
   But conservatives in the district waged a bitter primary fight
against Sweeney. They could sit home in November, or even vote for
Bordewich, just to punish the state GOP organization. So if
Bordewich can build visibility during the campaign's last few
weeks, voters in the 22nd could end up with a genuine horse race.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Sweeney should win this and probably will.
</P>
<P>
   But his road is rockier than Pataki's.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
