<HEADLINE>
HOW LAWYERS JUDGE TV LEGAL DRAMAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Lawyers often warn juries that the justice system
doesn't play out in real life the way it does on television. No,
there aren't any quirky bird whistles (a la ``Ally McBeal's''' John
``The Biscuit'' Cage) or daily dramatics as in ``Law and Order.''
</P>
<P>
   The law, a tangled mass of tedium, arcane and dramatic, has a
history as a literary vehicle dating back to the Greeks. The Bible
also had some serious courtroom drama (the Garden of Eden ruling,
Solomon vowing to split a kid, Pontius Pilate washing his hands),
and, of course, Shakespeare was a big fan of attorneys (``King
Henry'' 'nuf said).
</P>
<P>
   The only thing hotter than writer/producer David E. Kelley right
now is his dueling hit shows, ``The Practice'' on ABC and ``Ally
McBeal'' on Fox. Outside of both qualifying as Emmy-nominated
programs, the disparate shows really share only one other quality:
They revolve around law firms.
</P>
<P>
   Cop shows. Doctor shows. The wheel spins constantly in the
television cycle. And while ``ER'' remains at the top of the
ratings, legal shows have become dominant again on television.
</P>
<P>
   But what do lawyers think of the modern-day legal dramas? Well,
they believe some are entertaining _ even beneficial _ as long as
you don't mind the fine points getting screwed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any show gets it exactly right,'' said Judith
Kaye, chief judge of the New York Court of Appeals. ``It is
entertainment and what goes on in the courts is real.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that she is complaining. ``The public appetite for these
shows is insatiable,'' Kaye said. ``I think it is positive in the
sense it encourages interest in the justice system. I (also) think
it is negative because it is not realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad medicine ruins doctor shows for doctors. Screw up the sports
and jock types get irked. By nature, the law is a contemplative
process, one which must be accelerated to make gripping television.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing about legal shows on TV is if you practice
law they are never really realistic, because frankly things are too
exciting,'' said Patrick Borchers, associate dean at the Albany Law
School. ``Every case goes to trial. Every lawyer is always doing
one closing argument an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a consensus for the most accurate legal show on
television, it's ``Law &AMP; Order,'' the NBC drama which follows one
case a week through the investigative and legal stages (the 1980s
``L.A. Law'' was effective in illustrating how much of law is
practiced in a conference room rather than a courtroom).
</P>
<P>
   That said, maybe the most unrealistic legal show is the most
famous.
</P>
<P>
   While not the first on television, the granddaddy of legal shows
is, of course, ``Perry Mason,'' which debuted on radio in 1943 and
on television 14 years later (the first courtroom television show
may have been ``Famous Jury Trials,'' which debuted in 1949).
Defense attorney Mason never lost a case to District Attorney
Hamilton Burger (Remember? Ham Burger.), and the real guilty
parties often revealed themselves under withering
cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   Today, lawyers routinely warn jurors that real trials are not
like ``Perry Mason.'' Not Stephen Coffey: The Albany defense
attorney wants jurors to look for the dramatic. And Coffey adds
there is even something lawyers can take away from the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best courtroom manner I've seen was `Perry Mason,''' he
said. ``The manner and the way he handled himself and the degree of
calm was tremendous. If you want to see how to have a real nice
manner _ Raymond Burr. The medium is the message.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-16-98 1256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
