<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1047 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-BELOVED-H     10-16 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-BELOVED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BELOVED' A POWERFUL LOOK AT LOVE, VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Beloved'' is a deep, deep well of a movie, a film that ripples
with meaning and metaphor and unnerving supernatural questions.
Absorbing, confusing and uncompromisingly dark, director Jonathan
Demme's much-awaited interpretation of Toni Morrison's novel
challenges the very notion of what a movie can and should demand of
its viewers.
</P>
<P>
   It demands, first of all, attention. It demands an understanding
of and appreciation for literary devices. It demands a patient,
almost Buddha-like acceptance of sudden leaps in time or logic. It
demands a bluntness of view and a willingness to watch scenes of
unbearable brutality. Finally, it demands time 171 minutes of it,
all of them jammed with subtlety.
</P>
<P>
   The result almost defies description. It should: A powerful work
of art ought to throw a hard visceral punch, it ought to provoke
the audience on a purely wordless level. And this one does. Even
when ``Beloved'' seems to falter even when its plot skips over
yawning gaps or its characters change abruptly, it still hits the
gut with almost sickening might. Despite its huge rush of advance
publicity and the reassuring omnipresence of its star, Oprah
Winfrey, ``Beloved'' is not tailored for mainstream consumption.
It's simply too difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for starters, the subject matter. Set during the
Reconstruction, the story concerns Sethe (Winfrey), an ex-slave
haunted by the ghost of her dead baby girl; how the baby died is a
hazy matter through most of the film, but this isn't some cute
little poltergeist. It shatters mirrors, flings a rabid dog across
a room, throws kitchen appliances and more or less terrorizes the
household. ``Now, what you go'n do that for?'' says Sethe's
surviving daughter, Denver (Kimberly Elise), after a spectral
tantrum inspires the family's two boys to run away for good.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Sethe regards her ghostly child with resignation, even love.
``My God, girl, what kinda evil you got in here?'' asks Paul D
(Danny Glover), an old friend and former slave who stands,
transfixed and haunted, at the threshold to Sethe's home. ``It
ain't evil,'' she says, beckoning him to enter. ``Just sad.''
</P>
<P>
   And jealous. The lost infant rages against Paul D, who earns
Sethe's affections and barely escapes death by flying furniture.
After a while, the haunting ends. But no sooner does the house
settle into a cozy new family life than an enigmatic young woman
(Thandie Newton) materializes on a tree stump in Sethe's front
yard, fast asleep and swarming with ladybugs. Innocent and eerily
unmarked, she barely speaks (although she gives her name as
``Beloved''), toddles like a 2-year-old, bears no callouses on her
feet and, after Sethe takes her in, soils her bed at night.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Denver recognizes Beloved as an adult incarnation of
the infant ghost. But Demme's film (his first since
``Philadelphia''), so madly and beautifully literary, suggests that
the woman might be something else entirely: She might be a metaphor
for Sethe's past in slavery (shown in excruciatingly intense
flashbacks), or she might come from the farthest reaches of the
character's tortured psyche. She might, in other words, be Sethe
herself.
</P>
<P>
   This is hefty material for a big-studio movie, and it doesn't
always work. As the ambiguities pile up, stacking layer after layer
of allegorical subtlety, they threaten to snuff out the film for
lack of oxygen there's no breathing room. Much hay has been made
over the film's recent screenplay disputes (three screenwriters are
credited: Akosua Busia, Adam Brooks and Richard LaGravenese), but
its claustrophobia has less to do with the script than Demme's
daredevil attempt to make a film as thick with ideas as Morrison's
brimming prose.
</P>
<P>
   Taken on its own terms, the movie succeeds profoundly. Winfrey
makes an impressively natural return to film following her
Oscar-nominated debut in ``The Color Purple,'' wearing Sethe's
tragic past like a plain and tattered cloak. Her matter-of-fact
acceptance of a sad, mean world picks up a soft glow from Glover's
performance, which is an absolute feat of understatement and
simplicity. He's a gentle man, shaped by gentle nuances. And
Thandie Newton (``Jefferson in Paris'') startles as the cryptic
Beloved, filling a blank-slate character with childlike
manipulativeness and monstrous strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beloved'' is not a simple film. It's not a flawless film. But
it is an extraordinary glimpse into the heart of slavery, a
heroically ambitious study of loss and love and violence that
speaks literally and figuratively with eloquent force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-16-98 1258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981016.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1105 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-LAPTOP-PART-2-CYB     10-16 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-LAPTOP-PART-2-CYBERTIMES-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVING TO A NEW LAPTOP: PART II 
</HEADLINE>
  By STEPHEN C. MILLER 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week I explained some of the reasons why moving your
programs and data to a new Windows-based laptop is no piece of
cake. In short, you need to reinstall all of your programs from the
original disks and update them with new patches and bug fixes. But
that's only half the job. You still need to move your critical data
and settings from the old computer to the new one.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've got your programs installed, you need to transfer
all your custom settings. If you really use your programs, you've
probably customized them to your individual needs and quirky work
habits. And transferring the settings is not as simple as resetting
your options on the new systems.
</P>
<P>
   For example, I get between 200 and 250 piece of e-mail a day. If
all of that mail got dumped into my in-box, I would never get any
work done because I'd be too busy reading mail. I'd also not be
able to easily separate the mail that needs to be answered right
away from that which can be deleted unread.
</P>
<P>
   My e-mail life is made manageable because I have filters to
automatically sort my mail. The mail from my boss is put in one
folder and the mail from the guy who thinks that the Pope is Satan
can go directly to trash. I have 57 filters that sort my e-mail
into 65 mailboxes. It took a long time to setup those filters and I
don't want to have to recreate them from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   In this example, it's not too difficult because my e-mail
program puts all the filters and mailbox information in one place.
The files are small and I can simply copy them to a floppy disk and
then copy them into the matching folder in the new computer.
</P>
<P>
   But with some programs, it is not easy to locate the files
control how you've customized a program. I know that many of you
don't like to read documentation _ in too many cases, with good
reason _ but the chances are good that there is a section in the
manual telling you where and how customization is handled.
</P>
<P>
   If no such section exists, you might need to contact the company
that developed the program. While waiting on hold is a hassle, most
vendors now have Web sites where you can e-mail your request and
quickly get an answer.
</P>
<P>
   Moving your data can be complicated by your own organizational
angst and the nature and size of the files. I have created
sub-folders on my hard drive to keep certain files in convenient
locations.
</P>
<P>
   All of my columns go in one folder, my book is in another
folder, training documentation is in yet another folder. I've got a
dozen or so multimedia presentations that are large and won't fit
on a single or even a half dozen floppy disks.
</P>
<P>
   If you're lucky enough to be on a LAN and have a PC card network
adapter in each laptop, you can create a transfer folder on the
network server and copy your folder structure from the old laptop
to the new one.
</P>
<P>
   For another real-life example, I have all my musings in a folder
called ``stories.'' I have several sub-folders under it. I simple
copy the ``stories'' folder to the network folder. Everything
within it gets copied as well.
</P>
<P>
   Once the copy is complete, I go to the same folder from the new
laptop and copy the ``stories'' folder intact quickly and easily.
</P>
<P>
   Another option for transferring files is a program like
Traveling Software's Laplink. Laplink connects the two computers
together via a cable and you can ``clone'' your folders to the new
system. Laplink, and other programs like it, is for moving data,
not applications.
</P>
<P>
   It can certainly copy over all the files in an application
folder but it can't know about the INI files, the DLL's or Registry
entries that are needed to make the program run properly. It could
lock up your system as the program searches in vain for the missing
piece of its code.
</P>
<P>
   One option I considered was using the backup from a mass storage
device like a SyQuest or Jaz drive. If you were just restoring to
your current system or even a system that was the same make and
model, it would work, but new systems have been tweaked and certain
system files have been changed.
</P>
<P>
   There are new audio and video drives optimized for your new
system. If you just restore from another machines, you could
overwrite those files and crash the system.
</P>
<P>
   I, like many other Windows users, wish that the process were
simpler. Maybe it will be in Windows NT 3000.
</P>
<P>
   As my many Mac readers keep pointing out, it is easier with a
Macintosh, but I and my company have invested a lot of money in
acquiring Windows applications. It is just not economically
feasible to switch to a Mac and buy all new programs just to avoid
the, albeit tedious, process of switching to a new computer every
year or so.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the chores, like spring-cleaning that has to be
done but nothing makes it pleasant. But at least when it's over,
the house is clean.
</P>
<P>
