<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAINING-IN-TECH-EDUCATION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDUCATORS EMPHASIZE TEACHER TRAINING IN TECHNOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
  By PAMELA MENDELS 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twice in as many weeks, education experts have trained their
spotlights on a seemingly simple concept: If the billions of
dollars being spent on technology in schools are to reap any
educational benefit, teachers need to know how to use the computers
that are purchased for their classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, officials at United States Department of
Education announced the winners of its annual Technology Innovation
Challenge Grant program, but stressed that this year there was
twist. For the first time since the award program was established
four years ago, grant money was only being given to teacher
training projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is imperative to have well-trained teachers. Otherwise, you
can't realize the benefit of your investment,'' explained Jenelle
V. Leonard, who is in charge of the challenge grant program for the
Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Then last week, the results of a new study of classroom computer
use appeared to support the new emphasis of the challenge grants.
The report found that computer-equipped students taught by
educators who had received technology training scored better on
achievement tests than other students.
</P>
<P>
   The message of these two developments was clear: The machine is
only as effective as the teacher using it.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem an obvious point, but it still has not been embraced
by the vast majority of American school districts. Technology
experts say a rule-of-thumb is that about 30 percent of a school or
district's technology budget should be devoted to what educators
call ``professional development.'' In fact, said Leonard, the
average amount spent ``is hovering around three to five percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Debate still rages about whether the $5 billion or so spent
annually on school technology as a whole is a wise investment, and
neither the grant program announcement nor the new report, titled
``Does it Compute?,'' is likely to settle the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The study, carried out by a researcher from the Educational
Testing Service in Princeton, N.J., found mixed results in its
examination of fourth graders and eighth graders who used computers
in their math lessons. The younger students using computers showed
only slight gains over others.
</P>
<P>
   Eighth graders who used computers for more sophisticated
purposes, such as simulations, made significant leaps, but lost
ground if they used computers primarily for drills.
</P>
<P>
   One finding, however, was beyond dispute: the central role of
the computer-savvy teacher. The researcher, Harold H. Wenglinsky,
found that eighth grade mathematics students in classes with
teachers who had received technology training were about 13 weeks
ahead of others in their mathematics skills. Wenglinsky described
this gain as ``tremendously significant,'' and asserted, ``Teacher
training played an absolutely critical role.''
</P>
<P>
   Because professional development was loosely defined, the study
_ paid for by the Educational Testing Service and commissioned by
Education Week's annual Technology Counts special report _ left
unanswered how much and what kind of training would do the most
good.
</P>
<P>
   But the innovation challenge grants, awarded to 20 projects at a
cost of about $30 million for this fiscal year, were awarded to a
wide variety of training programs.
</P>
<P>
   A project in West Virginia, for example, will train 1,680
teachers how to integrate technology into curriculum planning, and
culminate with the requirement that participating teachers post a
lesson they have crafted on a Web site available to other teachers.
</P>
<P>
   In El Paso, Texas, meanwhile, grant money will go to support,
among other things, getting 160 teachers through a masters degree
program in integrating technology into the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   A three-state project led by the Stevens Institute of Technology
in Hoboken, N.J., seeks to enlist community colleges to train
teachers in how to use the Internet in innovative ways to teach
science.
</P>
<P>
   In a 30-hour course, teachers will be introduced to activities
such as a collaborative project in which students measure the
boiling point of water where they live and compare their findings
to those of peers from a variety of other locations. The lesson
learned: boiling point varies with altitude.
</P>
<P>
   Edward A. Friedman, director of Stevens's Center for Improved
Engineering and Science Education, said such training projects are
necessary because too few teachers know how to use the expensive
hardware that is suddenly appearing in their classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mindless use of technology is to be deplored and there is
too much of that going on,'' he said. ``The acquisition of
technology by the schools has gone ahead of the knowledgeable use
by teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   But some observers remain skeptical that technology in schools
is worth the cost _ even with well-trained teachers.
</P>
<P>
   William L. Rukeyser, coordinator of Learning in the Real World,
a group that has urged greater caution about school wiring and
other technology projects, conceded this week ``training is better
than no training; that was underlined by the Educational Testing
Service study.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added: ``What are the indications that educational
technology, even when combined with training, is going to be cost
effective when measured against the alternative? That seems to be
one of the most basic questions, but one of the ones most rarely
asked.''
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES: (each address preceded by http://www.)
