<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANVAS-CYBERTIMES-ARTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS(AT)LARGE 
 ARTIST DROPS OILS FOR FLASH 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Jef is cq.) 
 By MATTHEW MIRAPAUL 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jef Morlan has given his brushes the brushoff. After 23 years of
painting, the artist has made the computer screen his canvas.
</P>
<P>
   The vibrant results can be viewed in Snarg, Morlan's ongoing
exhibition on the World Wide Web, a medium he now finds more
compelling than the oil-based pigments he spread for so long.
</P>
<P>
   Although young artists are increasingly accustomed to the idea
of cyberspace as a creative outlet, few professional artists are
willing to turn so completely toward new technology as the
43-year-old Morlan has by abandoning his easel and picking up a
keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't paint anymore,'' Morlan acknowledged recently during a
telephone interview from his home in Anacortes, Wash., near
Seattle. ``That's because of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't buy any supplies anymore _ no canvas, no paint,'' he
said. ``Distribution is instantaneous. When I was in a gallery, I'd
be lucky to get three, four hundred people a month at a show, and
on the Internet I'm getting at times over a thousand a day.''
</P>
<P>
   But the reasons for Morlan's commitment to the year-old Snarg
site extend beyond the way it lets him reach a wider audience. As a
musician, he relishes incorporating sound into his work. More
important, he values the Web's interactive elements.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about this medium that has changed me forever is
giving up control and allowing a piece to have a life of its own,''
he said. ``If I was ever to go back to painting, I would be a
graffiti artist, just to watch how people respond to and interact
with what I put on the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Navigating through the diverse areas of the Snarg site does
necessitate a fair amount of user interaction, although Morlan
always seems in command of the highly painterly visual output. The
site requires the Flash browser plug-in and, on occasion, some
patience while its contents download.
</P>
<P>
   An animated introduction greets visitors to the site, featuring
a new-age take on Leonardo da Vinci's Vitruvian Man, with a
portentous soundtrack accompanying Morlan's stylized graphics and
androgynous figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes your psyche and pulls you right in,'' Morlan said.
The introduction is intended to act as a transition from the
everyday Web to Snarg's utterly distinctive environment. ``I want
you to get the feeling you're immersed in it, that you've gone
somewhere else,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction leads to one of the most remarkable aesthetic
spaces in cyberspace, a series of chartreuse- and fuschia-hued
screens filled with rounded, abstract shapes and glistening orbs
that throb, bounce and collide. It is as if Miro had created a
pinball game after a trip to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   It seems as if a certain '60s, almost psychedelic sensibility is
at play here, a welcome change from the retro look of the 50's that
continues to be so prevalent in online graphic design, but
allusions to Matisse and Picasso also can be discerned.
</P>
<P>
   Morlan, however, cites different inspirations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to most modern artists, I was very, very much into
the Baroque _ and Rubens in particular,'' he explained, an
influence seen in his use of sensuous shapes and juicy surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   Morlan and his wife, Gael, actually spent most of 1997 working
in Antwerp, Belgium, the birthplace of Rubens. ``One of the great
things about living in Antwerp was that's where he was from and a
lot of the churches had his paintings,'' Morlan recalled.
</P>
<P>
   But after a year there, Morlan said, he finally burned out on
the work of a master he had long admired.
</P>
<P>
   New inspiration came quickly, though. During a visit to Spain,
he was exposed to the non-representational design work of the
Moorish artists who once practiced there. ``It was so open and such
a relief,'' he said. ``There's a freshness and airiness to it that
I just totally fell in love with.''
</P>
<P>
   Morlan said the discovery moved him further away from the oil
paintings of his past, although he continues to favor highly
saturated colors and to shun pure abstraction, which he considers
too sterile.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Snarg will ultimately land in a gallery space
divided into five sections. As hypnotic music composed by both
Morlans burbles in the background, they can explore the interactive
art in the ``Flashers'' and ``Just Because'' sections, or read
Gael's prose. Jef's earlier computer-generated work is showcased in
the ``Technobaroque'' area.
</P>
<P>
   But nowhere on the site will you learn that Snarg is, according
to Morlan, an acronym for the Sustainable New Arts Research Group,
an international consortium of Web-savvy creative types.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not really. ``It's a family nonsense word,'' he confessed.
``When something would come up, we'd just go, 'Well, snarg!' We're
kind of a goofy family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like giving a whole lot of information in Snarg,'' he
continued. ``I like it existing as an entity unto itself. You go
there, you have fun, you learn something _ you jump in Gael's and
my brain and leave.''
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES: (each address preceeded by http://www.)
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   _ Snarg: snarg.net/
</P>
<P>
