A1108 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRIVACY-CYBERTIMES-LA     10-16 1484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVACY-CYBERTIMES-LAW-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRICT EUROPEAN PRIVACY LAW PUTS PRESSURE ON U.S.
</HEADLINE>
  By CARL S. KAPLAN 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, Europeans have benefitted from strict and broad data
privacy laws that protect personal information, like where a
citizen lives, what he buys and how much money he makes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as European nations stand ready to put into effect a
continent-wide standard for data-privacy protection, some legal
experts say the tough privacy rules of the Old World are putting
pressure on American lawmakers and business leaders to enhance
lagging New World privacy laws and practices.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst is the European Union's Data Protection Directive,
a sweeping law passed three years ago that becomes effective Oct.
25.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the notion that privacy is a fundamental human right,
it establishes a common minimum standard of data privacy protection
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The directive has raised the visibility of privacy law in the
U.S.,'' said Peter Swire, a law professor at Ohio State University
and co-author, with Robert Litan, of a new book on the European
law, due to be published by the Brookings Institution this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the least defensible corporate practices in the U.S.
are coming under pressure,'' Swire said, noting that in recent
months the Federal Trade Commission has worked hard to protect
children's privacy on the Internet and an increasing number of Web
sites in the United States have posted privacy policies. ``I don't
think the timing is a coincidence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Europe's data law sets a ``standard of legal rights for
individuals in Europe that go far beyond the legal rights of
Americans,'' Swire said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the law requires that European citizens be told
what their personal data will be used for, Swire said. In addition,
citizens must have access to data about themselves in companies'
files, must have the ability to correct false information and must
be given notice and the opportunity to opt out before personal data
is transferred to a third party. There are additional, tighter
rules governing the use of ``sensitive'' personal data, like
information about health and religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   One aspect of the European data law has pleased some American
privacy experts. It's Article 25 _ a rule with a ripple effect.
</P>
<P>
   According to the law, electronically stored personal information
about European citizens may flow freely across the borders of all
15 nations of the European Union after Oct. 25. But it can only
flow to a country outside the union if the receiving nation has
``adequate'' data protection. If it does not, privacy officials in
the individual European countries can impose embargoes on the
dissemination of the data.
</P>
<P>
   Few observers think that the United States, in general, has
``adequate'' privacy protection by European standards, Swire said.
After all, he said, unlike the European Union nations, the United
States does not have a single, comprehensive privacy law or an
agency charged with administering such laws.
</P>
<P>
   This means that the European law could conceivably affect a wide
range of American businesses and workers _ from journalists based
in Europe who e-mail notes back to New York containing names and
address of European contacts, to transnational companies based in
the United States that maintain computerized records on their
European workers.
</P>
<P>
   In one legal case, Swire said, a Swedish court has already ruled
that sensitive health data about airline passengers may not be
transferred from Sweden to an airline's reservation computers in
the United States without the passengers' consent. That case may be
appealed to privacy authorities at the European Union headquarters
in Brussels, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is, as it's written, the law has broad impact,''
said Swire, whose book, ``None of Your Business: World Data Flows,
Electronic Commerce, and the European Privacy Directive,'' examines
the law's possible impact. ``The unknown is how strictly it will be
enforced. I think there are certain categories of data that
Europeans care most about: health data, employee records, direct
marketing, personal financial data. And it's most likely that we'll
see enforcement in areas such as those.''
</P>
<P>
   Swire said United States and European officials are continuing
to discuss the new law. U.S. officials, trumpeting American-style
self-regulation, want recognition of ``safe harbors'' for certain
business practices, while Europeans want to see some progress on
U.S. privacy laws and enforcement. The clash between cultural views
of privacy protection _ market forces versus comprehensive laws _
is now a subject of international debate.
</P>
<P>
   Why do Europeans value privacy so highly? Swire points out that
after the experiences of World War II, many Europeans were fearful
of government surveillance and Nazi-style snooping. The first
European data protection law was passed in a state of what was then
West Germany in the early 1970s. There is also more suspicion of
the private sector in Europe than in the United States, and less
support for a laissez-faire approach to the handling of personal
information, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Marc Rotenberg, director of the Electronic Privacy
Information Center, a privacy rights group, said that Americans
value privacy just as highly as Europeans, if not more so.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, we have a very strong tradition of privacy
protection,'' he said. ``What we don't have are adequate techniques
for enforcement, and we don't have a coherent approach to private
sector protection _ we have a patchwork quilt of laws. I think the
E.U. directive is a reminder that we have more work to do in the
U.S. to protect privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel Reidenberg, a professor at Fordham Law School in New York
and an expert in international privacy law, said he also believes
that Americans value privacy as much as Europeans, though he
conceded that European laws offered a high level of protection to
citizens with respect to private-sector abuses of personal
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Europe became focused on privacy as a result of
American initiatives in the early 1970s, such as the Fair Credit
Reporting Act,'' he said, referring to a landmark American privacy
law governing consumer credit information.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-PRIVACY-CYBERTIMES-LAW-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; (UNDATED: credit information.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reidenberg also predicted that over the next 5 to 10 years,
Congress will pass a comprehensive privacy law so as to meet the
European standard of ``adequate'' privacy protection. Otherwise, he
added, individual American companies and business sectors would
have to negotiate a series of private contracts and rulings with
European data privacy commissions. ``That's a lot harder than
saying there's a comprehensive law in the U.S. and everything is
fine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone agrees that the European law will lead to
similar legislation here. Charles Prescott, vice president of
international business development and government affairs for the
Direct Marketing Association, a trade group, said he believes there
is insufficient political will to pass a major privacy law in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't see that,'' he said. ``Also, we would have to set
up something with prosecutorial authority to enforce it. I don't
think the American people are ready for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Prescott predicted that industries and businesses in the United
States will become increasingly sensitized to privacy concerns and
enact stricter self-regulating codes that will be recognized by
European officials.
</P>
<P>
   The inevitable movement toward rough harmonization of American
and European notions of data privacy is a result of a linked world
where strongly held legal values are easily exported, said David
Post, a law professor at Temple University who has written
extensively about the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is going to be a back and forth on this, finding
something Americans and Europeans can live with,'' he said. ``It's
a way to have a cross-border dialogue that's appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The network (of data flows) does connect us,'' Post said.
``The E.U. directive was a kick in the pants.''
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
