<HEADER>
A1117 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HALLOWEEN-DANGER-LIFE     10-16 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALLOWEEN-DANGER-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRICK OR TREAT SMARTS
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By LIZA N. BURBY 
 c.1998 Child magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no doubt about it: For kids, Halloween is incredibly
exciting. But it's also potentially dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Safe Kids Campaign (NSKC) in
Washington, D.C., children under age 15 are four times more likely
to be hurt in a pedestrian accident on Halloween than on any other
night of the year. Injuries from falls and burns are common, too.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that there are some simple ways to keep your
kids safe without taking any of the fun out of the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what you need to know:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Think ahead &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A week or so before the big event, start talking about Halloween
safety, and be sure to communicate your rules clearly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are most likely to act impulsively when they're highly
stimulated,'' says Janette Benson, associate professor of
psychology at the University of Denver. ``Because they are so
focused on their goal _ in this case, the candy-they don't stop to
think before they act.''
</P>
<P>
   Take time to go over the rules when your children can focus on
what you're saying, then give a reminder on Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Shop wisely &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   Fires are the third-leading cause of accidental deaths among
children. So when you're assembling a costume:
</P>
<P>
   Look for masks, hats, wigs and clothing labeled ``flame
resistant.''
</P>
<P>
   Avoid outfits that have billowing material, long capes, or baggy
sleeves that could catch fire if brushed against candles or fit
jack-o'-lanterns.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dress for safety &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   Nothing takes the fun out of trick-or-treat time faster than a
Halloween ``boo''-boo caused by a slip or a fall. Be sure to:
</P>
<P>
   Hem your kids' costumes to mid-calf length or shorter to prevent
stumbles.
</P>
<P>
   Secure hats and wigs so they don't slip child down and block
your child's vision.
</P>
<P>
   Forget Mom's heels or Dad's boots, no matter how cute they look.
Choose comfy shoes with nonskid soles instead.
</P>
<P>
   Consider using face paint or makeup instead of a mask, which can
obstruct vision. If a mask is a must, cut the eye holes wide enough
so your child can see clearly in all directions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Boost visibility &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   Make sure trick-or-treaters can still see and be seen when the
sun goes down.
</P>
<P>
   Use bright or light-colored costumes that can be spotted easily
by drivers. Add color to all-black outfits by persuading your child
to wear fluorescent tights. And give your child a flashlight to
help her navigate.
</P>
<P>
   Secure reflective tape or stickers to costumes (brands
identified as ``retro-reflective'' work the best).
</P>
<P>
   If you can't incorporate reflective tape into your child's
costume, put some on her shoes or treat bag.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Devise a game plan &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   Before you set out trick-or-treating with kids, map a route of
familiar homes to visit and set a time limit. Get an early start
with young kids so you can be home before it's too dark.
</P>
<P>
   Remind kids not to dart into the street or cross between parked
cars-a risk when they're overexcited.
</P>
<P>
   Tell them to stop at corners and look left, right and left
before crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Evaluate your child's maturity before letting him trick-or-treat
without you. Most kids under 10 aren't ready to go it alone, says
Dr. Marilyn J. Bull, chair of the American Academy of Pediatrics'
section on injury and poison prevention.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Check the loot &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   Halloween's a time for treats, but be cautious. Inspect all
candy before kids start snacking, and throw out anything
suspicious, says Pam Kreppel, a registered dietitian at Nassau
County Medical Center in East Meadow, N.Y. Toss cracked or crushed
candies and items with loose or tipped wrappers.
</P>
<P>
   Remove treats that pose a choking hazard to kids under 4, warns
Kreppel. These include chewy candies with nuts or caramel; round,
hard candies; lollipops; and small, loose treats like gum balls.
Safer bets are plain chocolate bars, pretzels, or chocolate-covered
wafers.
</P>
<P>
   ( &UR; Liza N. Burby is a New York-based free-lance writer and a
mother of two. &LR; ) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
