A1123 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-LANDING-$ADV1     10-16 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-LANDING-$ADV18-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOESN'T THE PRESIDENT KNOW IT'S RUDE TO CUT IN LINE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ If Bill Clinton, who needs all the help he can
get to survive in office, is trying to make friends among the
American people, he's messed up today almost completely. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here I am on an airplane jetting from Burlington, Vt., (on a
recent Friday) to the City of Brotherly Love, where I hope to run
from one gate to another in time to catch a flight home to Kansas
City. Whether my luggage will make the tight connection is anyone's
guess. But I've quit worrying about that. After all, my luggage
often takes longer vacations than I do. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The problem, however, is that the pilot has just come on the
public address system to tell us that our landing will be delayed
20 minutes or more because we'll be circling up here in the clouds.
The air space, he explains, has been cleared over the Philadelphia
airport to allow Air Force One to land. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The president is flying to Philly from a fund-raising trip to
Cleveland (where he took in about $200,000 over lunch in a private
home). His job here in Pennsylvania is to raise half a million
dollars for the Democratic party. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (If I were in charge of his schedule I'd also have him
investigate why the Eagles and Phillies are so bad, but let it
go.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I know that the 100-plus people on this plane would be glad to
donate a few bucks to almost any cause if we could get where we
want to go on time. But nobody passes through the aisles of my
flight to take up a collection. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We all understand that from time to time the president of the
United States, who no doubt gets antsy sitting around Washington,
D.C., awaiting his possible political execution, feels like getting
out of town. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If I worked in Washington I'd be looking for excuses to spend
time elsewhere, too. (Even, if it comes to that, in Philadelphia.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And we know that presidents almost never get out of town on
railroads any more. Nor do they go to their three-limo garage, load
up the family bullet-proof sedan and jump on a nearby interstate
highway. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they travel by Air Force One. And the American people
wouldn't have it any other way. We don't want our chief executives
(even ones we want to boot out of office) to have to slum it. They
may be bums, but, darn it, they're our bums. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, why does the president's unscheduled airliner get to land
ahead of all the scheduled commercial flights that are trying to
get people to business appointments or _ in the case of my wife and
me _ back home from a vacation trip? It's not right. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I know there are security concerns. Terrorism is real.
Loonies with surface-to-air missiles might well try to take out a
presidential jet, short-circuiting the impeachment process. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But how many terrorists sit around near the Philadelphia airport
on the off-chance that Air Force One might wander in? And if you
clear the air of every plane but the president's, isn't it more
likely terrorists would have a clear shot at it? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After droning around up here for a while, the pilot comes back
on to say we've finally been cleared to land. So down we come
through the partly cloudy, and as we near touch-down (about which
the Eagles here seem to know little), the guy sitting to my right
nudges me and points out the window. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There it is,'' he says. ``Air Force One.'' He's right. There
it is. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And I'm thinking: Hey, Mr. President. You want us average
Americans to support your anti-impeachment drive? Well, go ahead
and fly in your fancy plane, but tell your pilot to get in line
with the rest of our planes for landing sequence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and no making eyes at the flight attendants. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This column is for release Sunday, Oct. 18.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
