<HEADER>
A1162 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FANTASY-FOOTBALL-AZR &LR;      10-16 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FANTASY-FOOTBALL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN SOLO QB ISN'T ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I bet this has happened to you.
</P>
<P>
   You're sitting on the couch watching your favorite NFL game,
waiting for the scores to scroll across the bottom of the screen.
This week, Brett Favre was off, so you took a chance with Buffalo
quarterback Rob Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The first scores appear. Buffalo and Indianapolis are tied, 0-0.
Nothing wrong with that. Johnson is just getting warmed up. Pretty
soon, the Colts will feel his special brand of wrath. Just a matter
of time.
</P>
<P>
   Tick, tick, tick. Your palms begin to sweat. The network breaks
in with a few quick highlights from other games. No sign of
Johnson. No sign of the Bills. No sign of anybody named Bill.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it's halftime. After pointless yammering from former
players _ all of whom have suffered several concussions _ we reach
the most crucial part of the halftime show: Bills-Colts highlights.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Flutie is throwing a touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm, you wonder. Why are they showing Canadian football
highlights on American television?
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, it sinks in. Flutie's not wearing one of those goofy CFL
uniforms. He's not even wearing his old Boston College uniform.
He's wearing a Buffalo Bills uniform. Johnson is sitting on the
bench, cradling bruised ribs.
</P>
<P>
   Expletive deleted.
</P>
<P>
   After sifting through the ashes of my torched FFL weekend, I
noticed that more than half the teams in the league have played
musical quarterbacks at one time or another.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Jets keep switching between Glenn Foley and Vinny
Testaverde, contingent upon whether Coach Bill Parcells can see his
shadow. Oakland has gone through three quarterbacks, including a
couple who will move on to promising careers as beer deliverymen
and food service technicians.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Hollas, repeat after me, ``You want fries with that?''
</P>
<P>
   In Baltimore, Eric Zeier has replaced Jim Harbaugh, whose body
is held together entirely with duct tape. Kerry Collins left
Carolina to pursue a career as a stand-up comic. (OK, he really
went to the Saints _ same difference). Rodney ``Re'' Peete now
flings the pigskin for the Beagles.
</P>
<P>
   So what's a fantasy owner to do? Well, in your league, you might
consider switching to team quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is relatively simple. Instead of selecting individual
quarterbacks (Y.A. Tittle, for example), you pick an entire team
(like the Chicago Staleys). You get the statistics from whoever
happens to show up and stand behind the center that day.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you started Johnson (don't rub it in) you would
have also have had Flutie, who gave Peyton Manning a lesson about
messin' with a quarterback on the verge of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, due to Flutie's limited knowledge of the Canadian
monetary system, he was being paid in something called ``beaver
bucks.'' Not accepted on the south side of Lake Erie.
</P>
<P>
   The team system won't help owners with good quarterbacks who
never get hurt, or if your quarterbacks come from a team like the
ugh, Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, if you're picking the Redskins, I would like to
invite you to play in my league _ immediately. &QL; 
Tip of the week
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota quarterback Randall Cunningham and his receivers
against the Deadskins secondary reminds me of a pack of wolves
being turned loose in a sausage factory. Whatever happens, it isn't
going to be pretty. &QL; 
Waiver wire
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, anybody who runs behind the mammoth Jacksonville
line will gain 100 yards, so I'd grab Jaguars rookie Tavian Banks.
He will spell Fred Taylor, whose shoulder injury will limit his
effectiveness this week. Buffalo wide receiver Eric Moulds would be
a nice pickup, despite the return of Andre Reed. In St. Louis, Amp
Lee could get the nod with everybody else in the backfield nursing
an injury. &QL; 
One-hit wonder
</P>
<P>
   This week it's my favorite ex-Cardinal, Carolina quarterback
Steve Beuerlein, who passed for 286 yards and three touchdowns
against Dallas. The Panthers stink on ice. &QL; 
Bill Muller's Fantasy Football notebook appears every Friday. He
can be reached at 444-8178 or at bill.muller(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
