<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GWYNN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG APPLE'S READY TO TAKE A OUT OF SAN DIEGO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ People here seem shocked to learn that Tony Gwynn has
never seen Yankee Stadium. I mean, everybody who's anybody has seen
Yankee Stadium, right? The Pope ... Jack Dempsey ... The Ritz
Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   That, though, is the essential beauty of New Yorkers. Their view
of the world has always had that tinge of ``Well, fine, but you
haven't seen us yet.'' They have known of Gwynn forever, since he
makes two trips to Shea Stadium every year, and because he has hit
.300 every year since that first unfortunate day in tee-ball back
in '61.
</P>
<P>
   But the World Series begins Saturday, and the locals believe the
San Diego Padres are finally going to see what New York really and
truly is. Not the New York the Mets inhabit _ that is, at least
these days, a sort of faux Gotham, a place not unlike your average
run-of-the-mill American burg.
</P>
<P>
   No, this is the New York where Frank Sinatra shouts at you
during batting practice, where the history alone makes it hard to
breathe, and where, thoughtfully, this Yankee team has come as
close to approaching those Yankee teams of the '20s, '30s, '40s and
'50s as any team ever.
</P>
<P>
   That's big. New York big. Bigger than the Giants ever were, or
the Knicks, or the Rangers, and never mind the Jets, Mets, Nets or
Islanders. These Yankees are New York the way New York used to be,
before it turned into, well, New York.
</P>
<P>
   And Tony Gwynn has never been here? Well, too bad for Tony
Gwynn.
</P>
<P>
   That's the sentiment here as the Series begins, with the two
most iconoclastic pitchers in the game prepared to face each other.
David Wells (who is pretty damned New York when you get right down
to it) and Kevin Brown (whose reputation is pretty damned New York
cab driver) go Saturday night to start an event that most people
believe will end with the Yankees meeting New York's every
expectation.
</P>
<P>
   That, ladies, gentlemen, boys, girls and street mimes, is saying
something.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, between now and first pitch you'll see a lot of tortured
numerology showing all the ways the Padres are doomed. Our
particular favorite is the one that shows that the only Series
since 1984 that lasted fewer than six games involved California
teams, and California teams lost all of them _ the '84 Padres, the
'88 and '90 A's, and the '89 Giants. This falls nicely into the
``See? Those West Coast types don't have the attention spans God
gave fruit flies'' theory that East Coasties like to cite when they
admit they don't pay much attention to us.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Padres seem like a much gamer underdog than you
might think, largely because they don't have a lot of guys who
blink in the spotlight, or worse, forget to blink entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to Gwynn. There is, as you know, no
legitimate case to be made for anyone else as the logical inheritor
of Ted Williams' place as the greatest hitter of his time. Gwynn's
place is secure, so he won't fail here because of flop sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, he is likely to thrive in the Series because everyone is
looking at him, because his skills have never gone into remission
for much longer than the length of his disappointing National
League series against Atlanta. It is hard to imagine him shriveling
under the glare of David Wells, David Cone or even Orlando
Hernandez, hitting .091 and leaving a million runners on base. He
is Tony Gwynn, and he will like Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Padres have pitching, better pitching than
confronted the Yankees against the Rangers or Indians. It is
reasonable to think that the Padres won't be straining under those
0-2, 0-3 and 0-5 first-inning burdens the Indians did.
</P>
<P>
   That makes this at least a winnable series for San Diego. Not
necessarily a winning one, mind you, because the Yankees are just
as good as they seem. George Steinbrenner was remarkably prescient
when he ripped them after they lost their first three games of the
regular season, anticipating as he did that he would never get
another chance to chew them out on the back pages of the tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   These Yankees have a chance to give New York the feeling that it
seemed to have in the first 60 years of this century, then seemed
to lose as rival centers of culture, commerce and curse words
sprang up.
</P>
<P>
   This time, one suspects the city will be disappointed if the
Yankees don't clinch the Series in San Diego, after four or five.
To their way of thinking, that's what true New Yorkers do _ come
in, blow the joint down, and leave.
</P>
<P>
   So they will welcome Tony Gwynn to Yankee Stadium Saturday
night. It's nice when a prominent outworlder gets a chance to see
the sights one can only see in New York, especially when they do
not expect to see him a second time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
