<SLUG> BC-TUVALU-NAME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE TUVALU HOPING TO SELL ITS GOOD NAME
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Never mind the palm trees, the tiny archipelago of
Tuvalu is more basket case than tropical paradise. The necklace of
nine coral atolls strung across a huge swath of South Pacific is
the smallest nation on earth _ total land area, 10 square miles _
and ranks among the very poorest and most remote.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the bad news: Scientists warn that if polar ice
caps melt due to global warning, Tuvalu _ its highest point rising
barely 15 feet above ocean level _ will probably be the first
country swallowed by the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes a Canadian company with a marketing vision that might
transform Tuvalu into an economic titan. Not to mention giving it
financial wherewithal to keep itself literally above water.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Toronto-based .TV Corporation put up for bid what
many Tuvaluans believe is the country's most precious asset: its
good name. Or, more precisely, license to use Tuvalu's ``domain
name,'' the abbreviation assigned every nation for use in Internet
addresses.
</P>
<P>
   The domain name given the United States, for example, is ``us.''
For Canada, it's ``ca.'' For Japan, it's ``jp.'' And so on.
</P>
<P>
   Thus was lucky Tuvalu awarded the domain name ``tv.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a gift from God,'' said Prime Minister Bikenibeau
Paeniu.
</P>
<P>
   Probably no other acronym is more internationally known. TV
means the same thing to denizens of Boston, Bosnia, and Borneo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're providing Internet-savvy companies with the opportunity
to brand their web sites with one of the most recognized words in
the world,'' said Jason Chapnik, president and chief executive
officer of .TV Corp, chosen by Tuvalu to manage global marketing
and licensing of the catchy domain name.
</P>
<P>
   The obscure Polynesian microstate, populated by 10,000 souls,
and the small Canadian firm, which has fewer than 10 employees, are
hoping that thousands of companies will fork out tens of millions
of dollars for the right to affix the ``tv'' suffix to their
Internet address, or Web site.
</P>
<P>
   As Tuvalu Foreign Affairs Minister Pokia Tihala recently told
Wired magazine: ``CNN.com? No, no. How about CNN.tv?''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, there is no television in Tuvalu, whose
communications infrastructure consists of one AM radio station and
130 telephones.
</P>
<P>
   Selling of the suffix began Wednesday when .TV Corp opened its
Internet address, www.internet.tv, to companies willing to plunk
down $1,000 to register a name ending with ``tv.'' In cases where
more than one outfit seeks the same name, the Toronto firm will
auction off rights beginning Feb. 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Response has been fantastic,'' said Chapnik.
</P>
<P>
   Chapnik refused to disclose financial details of the deal with
Tuvalu, but said that the country will reap the largest share of
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Paeniu, the prime minister, recently told his countrymen that
the arrangement will bring Tuvalu an income of more than $60
million a year, catapulting it to the ranks of the richest nations
in the world, per capita.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, Tuvalu remains a poverty-wracked backwater whose
subsistence fisherfolk average a couple hundred dollars in a good
year. The islands also export a few tons of coconuts and copra. But
the economy really runs on foreign aid from Australia, New Zealand,
and Britain, scraping by on a $4 million-per-year budget.
</P>
<P>
   National priorities are raising living standards and finding a
way to keep the semisubmerged atolls from disappearing under the
waves. No other land is more threatened by the ``Greenhouse
effect'' that some scientists predict will melt portions of the
polar icecaps and raise ocean levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people are already dreaming about what to do with this
money,'' Paeniu &UR;  &LR; said. ``We want to help ourselves and other
nations of the South Pacific.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
