<SLUG> BC-MASS-IRA-SUPPORT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOPERATION BOOSTING BOSTON-ULSTER LINKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Long regarded a hotbed of support for the Irish
Republican Army, the Boston area has evolved into a welcoming forum
where Northern Ireland's leaders can air their views, listen to
former enemies, and receive a remarkable array of practical
support.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, the top two officials in the new Northern
Ireland Assembly _ one Protestant, one Catholic _ sat side by side
in a New England Circle discussion at a downtown high-rise.
</P>
<P>
   In its wake, Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams will visit Greater
Boston this weekend. Irish President Mary McAleese, a native of
Northern Ireland, will speak at the John F. Kennedy School of
Government today. And 13 business and community development leaders
from Boston, under the auspices of the Friends of Belfast, will jet
to Northern Ireland tomorrow for a three-day trade mission.
</P>
<P>
   In ways both economically practical and intellectually
enlightened, these trans-Atlantic links serve to bolster the
growing sense that Boston has become a Geneva-like venue where
thoughts on Northern Ireland's centuries-old differences and future
direction will receive a fair and serious hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this deep feeling for Ireland here and for a wish to
have the Troubles and the violence resolved,'' British
Consul-General James Poston said yesterday. ``There is a strong
identification of the people here'' with Northern Ireland ``and a
generosity of spirit which leads people to try constructively to do
something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   That ccoperation, which predates the Good Friday accord brokered
by US envoy George Mitchell of Maine, has a basis in many aspects
of Boston life. From universities to businesses, from charitable
groups to City Hall, Boston and Ulster have forged links that grow
stronger every week.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to providing forums where Northern Ireland's leaders
can speak their minds, Bostonians have worked behind the scenes to
help bring parties together and improve the Ulster economy. That
labor has taken root in myriad ways, including:
</P>
<P>
   _Hundreds of jobs provided by Massachusetts businesses in
Northern Ireland, primarily in computer-related industries.
</P>
<P>
   _The Belfast Trade Festival, a Boston show at which 42 Belfast
companies will tout their businesses. The event, scheduled for the
World Trade Center next month, will be the largest such show ever
held outside Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   _Ongoing training at Boston College for the legislators elected
to the Northern Ireland Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   _A Kennedy School program in leadership, with local internships,
that has attracted government, business and civic leaders from both
Northern Ireland and the Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
   _An initiative at Boston University led by Elizabeth Shannon,
the widow of former US Ambassador to Ireland William Shannon, that
has reached out to Northern Irish women, particularly those
involved in community affairs.
</P>
<P>
   _Continuing philanthropic support from the American Ireland
Fund, a Boston-based organization that has raised more than $100
million in 20 years. Just last week, the fund contributed $50,000
to a memorial fund for the victims of the August explosion in
Omagh, Northern Ireland, that killed 29 people and wounded 330.
</P>
<P>
   _Attention from the New England Circle. The wide-ranging
discussion group created 25 years ago by the Dunfey family
continues to invite key players from Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The roundtable heard this week from David Trimble, head of the
Ulster Unionist Party and first minister of the new provincial
assembly, and Seamus Mallon, a leader of the Catholic-oriented
Social Democratic and Labour Party and deputy first minister of the
assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Dunfey, president of the circle, said that the difference
in Trimble, compared with his last visit to Boston in 1994, was
striking.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was speaking a different language, even the smile. He
exuded warmth,'' Dunfey said after the event. ``Four years ago it
was his first time in Boston, and I think the pressure was on. The
whole situation was different.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the circle has heard from speakers that long
regarded themselves as enemies. From Sinn Fein leader Adams, the
political voice of the IRA, to loyalists once jailed for the
killings of Catholics, the views of blood foes have been heard in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no place else I know of in the world where people from
both communities in Northern Ireland come on a regular basis for
ideas, for financial support for their projects, and for academic
and intellectual pursuits,'' said Francis Costello, a former aide
to US Representative Joseph Kennedy 2d and ex-Mayor Raymond Flynn
who acts as a trade consultant for the city of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   Costello will be among the contingent leaving Boston tomorrow
for Ulster. With him will be John Cullinane, the computer software
pioneer and philanthropist whose generosity has, among other
things, helped the only Irish language high school in Belfast to
survive.
</P>
<P>
   The mission hopes to build on the momentum generated this week
when Segue Software of Lexington announced it will open a
tehcnical-support call center in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of work is beyond governments,'' Costello explained.
``It really requires a comfort level of an American company with
Belfast, to get them a sense that they are welcome and wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Massachusetts companies that have reached that comfort
level include Stream International, which has 250 computer-support
jobs in Derry, Northern Ireland; and Liberty Mutual Group, whose
chief executive officer, Belfast native Ted Kelly, was instrumental
in expanding to Ulster.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Leary of the Boston-based Irish American Partnership, a
group that promotes economic development, also has been active in
the type of work that British consul Poston called ``enlightened
self-interest.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend's trade mission also will include Bostonians with
grassroots know-how such as Martin Nee, executive director of the
South Boston Neighborhood Development Corp., and William
Good, &UR;  &LR; chief of administrative services for the Boston Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Another New Englander helping to deal with the flashpoint issue
of police reform in Ulster is Kathleen O'Toole, the former
Massachusetts secretary for public safety who is serving on the
Northern Ireland Police Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the cross-ocean activity, the players in this
burgeoning partnership hope that interest in Northern Ireland will
not fade if the euphoria over the Good Friday accord dissipates
amid the hard work of institution-building.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're looking at now is for an entire society to begin
the process of repair, reconstruction and reconciliation,'' said
Kingsley Aikins, executive director of the American Ireland Fund.
``And that will take time because the wounds that have been left
from this very ugly and bitter civil war are very raw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope that people in North America don't forget about
Northern Ireland because there's an awful lot of work left to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
