<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIPARTISAN SHAM ON EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Public education, the abused afterthought of Capitol Hill, was
once again brought out of its dungeon for a ray of light, only to
be hurled back into the darkness with the spiders and cobwebs as
soon as Congress and the White House achieved the proper effect of
making people think they did something about it on the nearly
finished $500 billion spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans gave President Clinton $1.1 billion in the new
budget to hire 100,000 elementary school teachers to reduce class
size. It figures. The conservatives are always railing about the
futility of throwing money at social problems. Yet they gave
Clinton a victory destined to be labeled a failure.
</P>
<P>
   You could not tell that by the self-congratulations. Senator Ted
Kennedy, the Massachusetts Democrat, said the money was ``a
resounding victory for the children of this country. It's a
resounding victory for public education.'' Senate Democratic leader
Tom Daschle said the $1.1 billion was ``the biggest victory of all,
and the one we are most proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has made smaller classes a centerpiece of education
reform. Many education experts have scratched their heads,
wondering why. It seems logical that small classes produce smart
students, but there are yet few studies to actually prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Even if there were such studies, Clinton still has it backwards.
More teachers means nothing if they are not of the highest quality.
California, which two years ago began a drive to reduce class size
in the early grades from 30 students per class to 19, now has a
quagmire where 30 percent of public school teachers do not have
proper training or experience.
</P>
<P>
   More teachers also means little if there is no space to handle
schools that might shrink in class size but explode in room
numbers. On this score, the $500 billion spending package speaks
volumes. Clinton asked for $1 billion for school construction. The
$1 billion was part of Clinton's bid for a $5 billion, five-year
construction plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans refused. Clinton dropped the request.
</P>
<P>
   Thus we are about to get more teachers with nowhere to put them.
Three years ago, the General Accounting Office wrote that the
physical conditions of schools, ranging from lighting and heating
to air quality to physical security, are so bad it would take $112
billion over a three-year period to repair or upgrade them into
good condition. This year school districts started $15 billion in
building projects.
</P>
<P>
   That is woefully short of the $37.3 billion a year called for by
the GAO. When a Democratic president proposes so little to fix the
schools and a Republican-dominated Congress rejects even that, this
is not a ``huge win'' or a ``resounding victory.'' This is a
bipartisan sham.
</P>
<P>
   It is a sham because defense, already bloated with pork-barrel
projects that even the Pentagon has said it doesn't need, received
$9.7 billion in the spending package for military readiness, nearly
10 times more money than education. While 60 percent of American
schools have conditions that surely detract from student readiness
for the 21st century, affecting the ability to see, breathe,
concentrate, and feel safe, the defense budget includes $250,000
for ``pharmaco-kinetics research.''
</P>
<P>
   This ``research'' is actually a pork-barrel procurement of Stay
Alert caffeinated chewing gum in the Yorkville, Ill., hometown of
Republican Representative Dennis Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   While principals and school superintendents wait in vain for
what should be $37.3 billion a year for the next three years,
defense contractors are applauding an increase in procurement that
will give them $48.5 billion of business in fiscal 1999. In one
instance, Clinton asked for only one new C-130-J transport plane
from Lockheed. Congress decided to build six more at a cost of
nearly half a billion dollars. The plane factory just happens to be
next to House Speaker Newt Gingrich's district.
</P>
<P>
   At the last minute, senators and congressmen have reportedly
thrown in millions in the defense budget for businesses in their
home districts. A firm in Indiana that makes transmissions for
self-propelled howitzers that had lost a previous bid has
Republican Representative Peter Visclosky pushing to get it $4
million for research.
</P>
<P>
   Coal mining interests have Representative Paul Kanjorski, a
Pennsylvania Democrat, trying to add $4 million to Navy research to
``micronize'' coal to see if there are any uses for it. Senator Ted
Stevens, Republican of Alaska, is campaigning for $2.4 million in
Navy appropriations for a vacuum-pressure device that its inventor
claims will prevent oil spills but has been scoffed at by the Coast
Guard.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same Congress that tells you that it can deal with
education in only a piecemeal and wrongheaded way. House minority
leader Richard Gephardt said, ``We are going to make education the
number one issue in the country.'' After what happened this week in
Washington, it is clear that education is already back in the
dungeon, rotting to a state that will be even more rank when
Capitol Hill pulls it out for the ray of light, a light that is
merely the flash of a photo op.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
