<HEADLINE>
NOBEL-PRESTIGE-$ADV18 
 
UNIVERSITY OF TEXAS MEDICAL SCHOOL AT HOUSTON ON ITS WAY UP 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 18) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RUTH SoRELLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, the University of Texas Medical School at Houston has
labored under the sobriquet ``young.''
</P>
<P>
   Voted into being by the Texas Legislature in 1969, it has on
occasion been racked by open turf battles that spilled onto the
news pages. When compared to its older neighbor Baylor College of
Medicine, the school has been described as striving and ``number
two.''
</P>
<P>
   But with relative peace prevailing in recent years _ and with
this week's designation of its new chairman of integrative biology
as a Nobel Prize winner _ UT-Houston Medical School appears on its
way up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the exclamation point on the statement `We have arrived
_ finally. We are mature,' '' said Dr. M. David Low, president of
UT-Houston Health Science Center, which oversees the medical
school.
</P>
<P>
   Low and others credit the recent recruitment of Dr. Ferid Murad,
the Nobel winner announced Monday, as a signal that the school is
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Murad had been running a small biotech firm outside of Chicago,
but found little time for research, his first love. A search
committee looking for a chairman for the school's integrative
biology department sought him out. In the end, he was the
committee's top pick, said Low.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a lot of time and effort and convincing,'' he said.
``For most people of that caliber, the most important think they
have to believe is that their scientific future is secure.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading the effort were the school's dean, Dr. Maximillian Buja,
and chairman of the medicine department, Dr. James Willerson.
Willerson had known Murad when the two were interns and residents
at Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Murad had helped in an attempt to recruit Willerson to Stanford
University during the mid-1980s. When it came time for Willerson to
turn the tables, he was dogged.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is extremely bright and very hard-working,'' Willerson said
of Murad. ``He is committed to doing everything well, and he wants
everything around him to be done well. He is ambitious for the
health science center and the medical center. He wants both to
progress, and he will do everything he can to make sure they
will.''
</P>
<P>
   Willerson and Low both see Murad's Nobel status as a way to
attract better and brighter researchers, residents and students to
the school.
</P>
<P>
   Low sees three benefits:
</P>
<P>
   Publicity for the institution with stories worldwide identifying
Murad as a UT-Houston scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Exposure for the institution in the world of science, which can
translate into more high-caliber scientists seeking to come here.
</P>
<P>
   Easier access to foundations, corporations and drug companies
that can help finance basic research at the various institutions of
the health science center.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Low sees the award casting a positive light on the
entire Texas Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was musing on a motto we might try to promote, not just for
us but maybe for the whole medical center,'' he said. `` `Come work
or learn with the best.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Low hopes that more Nobel prizes will come in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Texas Medical Center has been home to two Nobel
Prize winners.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Roger Guillemin was at the Salk Institute in La Jolla,
Calif., when he won the Nobel in 1977. But he had done the seminal
work that won him the award while at Baylor College of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Murad did the work that won him the Nobel at the University of
Virginia and Stanford, but he was at UT-Houston Medical School when
he received the award.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to grow our own Nobelists,'' said Low. ``The
next step is to get a Nobel Prize based on work done here and have
the Nobel laureate stay here.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we'll take the Nobel Prize any honest way we can get
it.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-16-98 1419EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
