u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-BELOVED-BOS &LR;      10-16 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BELOVED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT EASY TO SIT THROUGH, BUT ``BELOVED'' IS MAGNIFICENT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELOVED &QC; 
Directed by: Jonathan Demme &QC; 
Screenplay by: Akosa Busia, Richard LaGravenese, Adam Brooks
(novel: Toni Morrison) &QC; 
Starring: Oprah Winfrey, Danny Glover, Thandie Newton, Kimberly
Elise, Beah Richards &QC; 
Playing at: Nickelodeon, suburbs &QC; 
Running time: 171 minutes &QC; 
Rated: R (violent images, sexuality and nudity) &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Beloved'' is a strong, dark, tangled powerhouse of a film that
comes to grips with the scars of slavery as no previous American
film has. It isn't easy to sit through, not because it runs nearly
three hours, but because the journey it takes is a slow and heavy
and sad one as it traces an enduring woman's tremendous effort to
put a lacerating and degrading past behind her eight years after
emancipation. It could almost be so-called emancipation, for Oprah
Winfrey's aching matriarch named Sethe still is imprisoned by the
pain of her past. One of her daughters is literally imprisoned in
their small house on the outskirts of Cincinnati, never leaving it.
</P>
<P>
   It's a haunted house, and director Jonathan Demme, maintaining a
meticulous fidelity to its source, Toni Morrison's landmark novel,
jolts us with ``Exorcist''-like effects that yank us into its
agitated soul. ``Beloved,'' however, is anything but an F/X
extravaganza. It's a love story and a ghost story of tormented
mother love, as Sethe feels both longing and guilt about Beloved,
the daughter she lost years ago when a Kentucky slaver caught up
with a runaway Sethe and exacted ugly and brutal revenge. The house
isn't an evil house, Sethe explains to Danny Glover's Paul D., a
slave alongside Sethe on the same plantation, who has sought her
out years later. It's just a sad one.
</P>
<P>
   He is one of two visitors who arrive at her door. The other is a
mysterious young woman played by Thandie Newton, who, dressed in
black and accompanied by a cloud of insects, staggers stiff-legged
to Sethe's front yard and collapses there like a broken rag doll.
Sethe takes her in and nurses her back to health. When her visitor
says in a cracked, otherworldly voice that her name is Beloved, the
same as Sethe's lost daughter, Sethe doesn't know what to think. Is
it her daughter back from the dead? Is her spirit resurfacing in
ways she can't fathom? Beloved's rolling eyes, animal growls, and
contorted features that sometimes subside into angelic repose
deepen the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The result is not resolution, at least not before much struggle.
It is the joint triumph of Winfrey and Demme that they convey the
pain and will to survival of a woman who has endured by maintaining
iron control. It isn't hardship that threatens to break her _ she's
used to that _ but tenderness. She and Glover's sweet, decent old
friend share a sex scene that is remarkable in its ability to
convey mutual solace. Eventually, the strong currents in the house
overwhelm Glover's gentle, open-hearted Paul D., but not before he
melts away some of the isolation permeating the place. There's
another sex scene that does not involve Sethe, and that one is
violent and scary.
</P>
<P>
   The house is a metaphor for Sethe, embodying, as it does,
sanctuary and continuity but also a profound malaise. Winfrey and
Demme never get so caught up with turning Sethe into an icon that
they scant visceral impact in the primal scenes, especially the
ones involving Newton's needy but increasingly wild creature whose
escalating unrest drives the story toward its climax. The
flashbacks are necessarily horrific in this story about the
internal devastation of slavery, including Morrison's irony in
calling the soul-crushing plantation Sweet Home. Winfrey is a
bulwark of strength as Sethe, filling the screen with fiery
commitment and oaken commitment, but never descending to
sentimentality or pathos.
</P>
<P>
   Admirably, the film tries to replicate Morrison's dense,
elliptical, incantatory construction. The danger it faces is
stasis. Sethe doesn't travel the usual arc of change we're used to
seeing in screen narratives. She is a woman essentially standing
her ground, or rather trying to find the strength to keep standing
it. Apart from being the driving force behind this film and its
genuflection to African-American endurance, Winfrey's
identification with Sethe's struggles results in wave after wave of
unstoppable conviction. She delivers a full-blooded performance of
enormous dignity that has Oscar contender written all over it.
</P>
<P>
   Glover's Paul D. will steal your heart, and Newton is amazing as
the enigmatic and otherworldly Beloved, never seeming merely showy,
despite the primal convulsiveness of her fiery, unpredictable
Beloved. It would be idle to pretend that the film doesn't
sometimes lose momentum, partly because the strength of its central
character consists not in going with the flow, but resisting it.
But its depth and quality and fidelity to Morrison's novel make it
a distinguished film. And to cap the succession of things Demme
does right, the film does come around to the largely silent and
watchful daughter played by Kimberly Elise.
</P>
<P>
   She, after all, represents the future. Although she doesn't say
much, she's always a vivid, watchful presence who obviously has
inherited her mother's strength. And it's thanks to that strength
that what could have been an anticlimactic ending becomes a
liberating one. Few films this year are likely to have the size and
reach and redemptive riches of ``Beloved.'' It has flaws, it has
imperfections, but it also achieves a magnificence few films even
attempt. You'd be missing an important work if you were to pass it
by.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
