<HEADLINE>
FAST-GROWING COMPANY IS ALSO A MAJOR GIVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ It's not standard business procedure for a
company to donate half its annual profits to charities. But don't
tell that to Give Something Back, a 6-year-old office supply
company that made Inc. magazine's latest list of the 500
fastest-growing private companies in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The company's two founders, Mike Hannigan and Sean Marx, are
true businessmen rather than just do-gooders. They say they run a
tight operation and have plans to expand Give Something Back into a
national chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``As aggressive as we have been in growing, we're actually
financially very conservative,'' said Hannigan, who previously
worked for Xerox and other copy product companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the nonprofit community, and the community in
general, will be better off if we focus on growth and can
eventually give away millions instead of just tens of thousands of
dollars,'' explained Marx, a former sales representative in the
copy supply business.
</P>
<P>
   Their company, which ranks 498th on the Inc. list, has donated
to food banks and the Habitat for Humanity, among others. In all,
the company plans to give away $250,000 to dozens of groups in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Hyatt, a senior editor at Inc. who is in charge of the
top-500 edition, said no other company on the list is so focused on
giving as the Oakland-based company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously there are companies that give something back, but
they don't usually put it foremost in their names,'' he said. ``It
is an extreme version of what some socially conscious companies
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hannigan, 49, and Marx, 32, met while working together in the
copier products industry. Hannigan approached Marx about starting
some kind of business based on the model of Newman's Own, the
spaghetti sauce and salad dressing company started by actor Paul
Newman that donates its profits to charities.
</P>
<P>
   The two decided to capitalize on their background in office
products as the basis for the company. They each pitched in $20,000
from personal savings to start the company.
</P>
<P>
   In the competitive world of office supply, Give Something Back
has managed to stand up to mega-office supply companies such as
Office Depot and OfficeMax by offering competitive pricing.
</P>
<P>
   Give Something Back has no retail locations and limited
warehouse space (the company mostly ships directly to clients) and
therefore has low overhead.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Hannigan and Marx say they cap their own salaries
at 75 percent of the industry average, or $6,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Arlington, Va.-based Business Products Industry
Association, about 14,000 commercial office supply stores existed
nationwide eight years ago. Fewer than half remain as of this year,
a reduction attributed to consolidation in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Give Something Back gives away all the profits left over after
taxes and retained earnings for growth. Essentially, the company's
managers keep enough money to be able to grow and keep their bank
from getting nervous, and give the rest away.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the company made $330,000 in net profit and gave away
$154,000. In 1997, earnings were $350,000 of which $160,000 was
donated. In 1999, the company expects to make about $500,000 and
donate $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sales growth has increased from $5 million in 1996 to more than
$13 million projected for this year. Sales goals for 1999 are $22
million, with more than $1 million in earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Hannigan said the 1996 opening of the first sales office outside
the San Francisco Bay area, in Sacramento, cut into 1997 profits.
Additional sales offices are planned for the Santa Clara-San Jose
area, San Diego and Portland, Ore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
