<HEADLINE>
FRAUGHT WITH DYSFUNCTION, ``TRINITY'' NEEDS PLOT DOCTOR
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRINITY &QC; 
Starring: Tate Donovan, Jill Clayburgh, John Spencer, Sam Trammell,
Justin Louis, Kim Raver, Bonnie Root, Charlotte Ross &QC; 
On: NBC, Ch.7 &QC; 
Time: Friday at 9 &QC; 
Rated: TV14 &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heavy is the word for ``Trinity,'' the new series from ``ER''
executive producer John Wells. ``Trinity'' is so crammed with
dysfunction and drama that it makes other hourlong dramas like
``NYPD Blue'' and ``Chicago Hope'' appear lighthearted. It
out-heavies even Wells's own intubation-fixated ``ER,'' presenting
us with such a glut of emotional and spiritual and criminal traumas
that it verges on self-parody. The themes in the premiere episode
alone _ alcoholism, adultery, unwanted pregnancy, a failing
marriage, sibling rivalry, union corruption, police intrigue,
religious quandary, a gay husband _ read like a list of chapters in
a book called ``Modern Urban Life,'' or, more specifically, ``TV
Cliches of Modern Urban Life.''
</P>
<P>
   All the heaviness of ``Trinity,'' which debuts tonight at 9 on
Ch.7, centers around the McCallister family, an Irish-Catholic clan
in New York's Hell's Kitchen. Each of the five adult children is a
familiar TV type who offers enough turmoil for a show of his or her
own. Kevin, played by Tate Donovan, is a liberal-minded priest who
plays basketball when he's not hearing confession. Like Kevin
Anderson on last season's ``Nothing Sacred,'' he makes waves with
his unconventional thinking. Bobby is the gritty cop who provides a
touch of ``NYPD Blue,'' neglecting his wife as he combs the streets
for clues to the death of another McCallister brother years ago.
Liam, the stock soap-opera hothead, works for a crooked union
organizer when he's not making eyes at Bobby's wife. Fiona is
another soap cliche, a high-powered, self-destructive stockbroker
who is having an affair with her married boss. And poor tatooed
Amanda is a pregnant substance abuser who is unsure of the identity
of the father.
</P>
<P>
   It's a hard show to warm up to, even while the TV season has
offered very little for fans of drama. There's simply not an
ordinary or sweet moment in the entire hour of ``Trinity,'' nor is
there one next week, as each of the siblings' subplots is forwarded
with equal thrust. With all of the action and conflict and
characters, none of the stories is given the chance to be fleshed
out or affecting. And what makes ``Trinity'' feel even more
cluttered is the way the lives of the siblings are so mixed
together. It's an unbelievably small world, this TV-ized Hell's
Kitchen, with the characters forever bumping into one another and
involved in one another's business. The acting on the show is fine
on all counts, but Wells will need to do some serious plot
doctoring and character nursing to turn ``Trinity'' around.
</P>
<P>
   The McCallister brood gathers for fraught dinners at the
apartment of their parents, played by John Spencer and Jill
Clayburgh. Neither of the elder McCallisters have been given much
screen time, but next week Clayburgh has a salient moment as she
asks her husband, ``When do we get to stop worrying about these
kids?'' At this pace, Mom, never.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-16-98 1428EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981016.0048 </DOCNO>
