<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1232 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-TETZLAFF-BOS &LR;      10-16 1348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TETZLAFF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN VIOLINIST CHRISTIAN TETZLAFF CARES ABOUT HIS CRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This week Christian Tetzlaff is playing a new concerto, for him,
with Bernard Haitink and the Boston Symphony Orchestra _ the
Sibelius. ``This isn't the very first time I am playing it,'' the
young German violinist said in his dressing room before rehearsal
Tuesday. ``I wouldn't come here with a concerto for the first time
_ I have played it in London and Helsinki already. This is a
concerto I didn't learn during my student time, so I have been
occupied with it for most of the last two years. You can learn
things more quickly when you are a student; there are fewer
distractions and you have real time to practice. I have never heard
a live performance of this concerto, and I listen to recordings
very little, so I did not really know it when I took it up two
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Tetzlaff is a meticulous craftsman who is noted for his ability
to master problem concertos and deliver their messages to the
public. He made his name with the Schoenberg (his American debut
was in this work, with the Cleveland Orchestra); with the BSO he
played the Schumann, the Berg, and the Ligeti before arriving at
the standard repertory with an incandescent performance of the
Beethoven at Tanglewood last summer.
</P>
<P>
   With a disarming smile, Tetzlaff admits that he was not always
so meticulous. He started to study the violin and the piano at 6.
``I was always interested in music, but far too little interested
in the violinistic things. I was 15 before I started to work
seriously; before that I was satisfied to be quite quick to pick
things up.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the judges of a competition in which Tetzlaff played was
Uwe-Martin Haiberg from the Lubeck Conservatory; one result of the
competition was that Tetzlaff went to work seriously on technique
and repertory with Haiberg. ``About 40 percent of our work was on
the technical side; the rest was music.'' Haiberg suggested that
Tetzlaff study all his concertos from the full orchestral score,
which is not the way most celebrity violinists are trained. ``This
has had many good consequences, and maybe a few that were not so
good. To be a successful performer, you have to feel good on the
stage, to be absolutely secure about the technical aspect of your
playing. It has taken me a long time to feel really comfortable
onstage.''
</P>
<P>
   Many prodigy-soloists have no idea of what it might be like to
participate in chamber music or play in an orchestra. Tetzlaff did
both. ``For 10 years, from the time I was 10 until I was 20 I
played in various youth orchestras, and I came for a year to the
Cincinnati College-Conservatory to study with Walter Levin of the
LaSalle Quartet.'' Levin's most prominent pupil was not a
violinist, but a young pianist named James Levine who wanted to be
a conductor. Tetzlaff has conducted some of his own performances of
the Mozart Violin Concertos, but says he has ``no ambitions in that
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Tetzlaff is 32; his countrywoman, Anne-Sophie Mutter, who is
just three years older, burst into the international spotlight many
years earlier than Tetzlaff because of the patronage of Herbert von
Karajan. ``My career was different; every year it became a little
bit more. There was no big event that made my career go; mostly I
got reinvited wherever I went. There was never a conductor who
said, `You are my boy.' There is no way I could have worked with
Karajan _ I was fiercely dedicated to a way of working that was
exactly the opposite of his. At the end of his career, Karajan was
obsessed with sound, and with greatness _ the greatness of the
music and his own greatness. ... The only one of the old conductors
I worked with was Sergiu Celibidache.''
</P>
<P>
   The concerto on that occasion was the Schoenberg; one was
surprised to learn that this was a work Celibidache knew. ``He
didn't,'' says Tetzlaff, shooting another grin. Cleveland's
Christoph von Dohnanyi was the first of the prominent international
conductors to engage Tetzlaff; last summer was his first appearance
with Seiji Ozawa; this week's concerts bring him his first concerts
with Haitink. Tetzlaff is quite impressed with the caliber of some
of the younger conductors he has worked with recently _ Britain's
22-year-old Daniel Harding, Antonio Pappano, Kent Nagano. ``This is
a very good generation of conductors.''
</P>
<P>
   Tetzlaff's devotion to the style of the composers has not led
him into experiments with old violins, bows, and ``historically
informed performance.'' ``I do not think some of those things are
necessary; on the other hand, you should not play Mozart without
reading the treatise about violin playing by his father Leopold.
Some traditions of violin playing are necessary; you need tradition
to tell you how to do certain things. But you don't have to belong
to the `Russian school' or the `Belgian school' or the `American
school.' You should be like an actor who gets into the style of
each of his parts.''
</P>
<P>
   And as for old instruments, Tetzlaff says, ``I prefer to
experiment with new violins.'' He has played old Italian
instruments, but will perform the Sibelius on a recent violin by
Peter Greiner that he acquired last New Year's Eve. ``I am using
this instrument because it is strong and nice; it sounds good.''
</P>
<P>
   Tetzlaff says he finds Sibelius a ``fantastic composer; his
music is very direct and emotional, but it is also written with
compositional skill. Some of Sibelius sounds quite modern, although
he did not take a way out of tonality like Schoenberg, Stravinsky,
or Bartok. Maybe it was for that reason serious people like the
critic Theodor Adorno attacked his music and called it rubbish. The
concerto is very physical, very wild, and you have to play the
violin in a different way; at the same time you have to understand
how vital the orchestra is _ there's a place in the slow movement
where you are playing the accompaniment, although some violinists
mistake it for the real thing. I do not think I would like to play
the Sibelius on a 10-concert tour; there would be too much
brain-ache and there is also the danger of muscle-ache!''
</P>
<P>
   The Schoenberg concerto is one of the pieces that put Tetzlaff
on the map. ``I learned it when I was 20, not for a performance,
but because I think it belongs among all the other major concertos.
I haven't played it in a long time now because there has to be a
very good conductor and a very good orchestra and enough rehearsal
time. I'm looking forward to playing it later this month in Hamburg
with Christoph von Eschenbach.'' Today Tetzlaff plays about 85
concerts a year. Last season he played the Mendelssohn Concerto 24
times, the Beethoven 22, using his own transcription of the
cadenzas Beethoven wrote for the version of the concerto he
prepared for piano _ he was not amused at Tanglewood to be
criticized in some quarters for the ``inappropriateness'' of a
cadenza that Beethoven wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He says he doesn't tire of the standard concertos. ``Every
single time I'm fascinated; every day you feel a little bit
different. I really enjoyed playing the Mendelssohn so often; you
are telling a story to the people who are listening, and your job
is to make it believable every time. There are some concertos I
love that I could not play so often: the Berg, for example, where
the feelings are so strong that to reproduce them night after night
would be very difficult.'' Tetzlaff has another ``new'' concerto in
his repertory, along with the Sibelius, the Shostakovich First; in
2000 he will play the premiere of the first concerto written
specifically for him, a work by Johannes Harneit.
</P>
<P>
   Home is outside Frankfurt. Tetzlaff's wife plays clarinet in the
Frankfurt Opera Orchestra, and they have three children, age 6, 4,
and 1. That is one reason why Tetzlaff controls his schedule
rigorously. ``If I work a week, I have to take a week off. My
children, my wife, and my home are the center of my life, and when
I am not there, I miss them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-16-98 1431EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981016.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1241 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOBEL-MURAD-PROFILE-2     10-16 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOBEL-MURAD-PROFILE-2TAKES$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOBEL-MURAD-PROFILE-$ADV18 
 
DOGGED PURSUIT OF NEW INFORMATION CHARACTERIZES NOBEL WINNER MURAD
AND HIS SUCCESS 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 18) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RUTH SoRELLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ After Dr. Ferid Murad learned he had won the Nobel
Prize for Medicine Monday morning, he still set aside 30 minutes to
meet with the trainees and scientists in his lab to discuss some
``fantastic data'' that one had uncovered over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Those close to him say it is a mark of the man that he would
take time on such a day for the younger scientists he is training.
It also is proof of his wife's assertion that the Nobel will not
change him or divert him from his single-minded pursuit of what he
loves _ science.
</P>
<P>
   Murad, 62, put it more simply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a data freak,'' he confessed. ``I can't go a day without
hearing good new data.''
</P>
<P>
   The dogged pursuit of new information characterizes Murad and
his success, capped this week by science's most prestigious award.
Friends describe him as competitive, brilliant, unassuming and
mild. His wife calls him a ``regular guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Willerson, chairman of medicine at the University of
Texas Medical School at Houston, said he pushed for Murad's
recruitment as chairman of the school's new integrative biology
department because of that love of ``data'' _ particularly in his
field, dealing with biologic effects of a chemical called nitric
oxide.
</P>
<P>
   Murad spent most of his adult life pursuing the story of nitric
oxide, a colorless odorless gas best known as an air pollutant. He
and his co-winners _ Robert F. Furchgott and Louis J. Ignarro _
proved its fundamental role in cells throughout the body.
</P>
<P>
   Little remains controversial about nitric oxide now, but for 18
years, Murad fought for recognition of the tiny molecule's
importance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unexpected that a free radical would work like this,''
said Murad, who maintained his work and studies despite the world
of medicine's indifference to his efforts.
</P>
<P>
   That is typical of him, said a lifelong friend, Ronald Delismon
of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were playing chess with him and he was losing, he never
gave up,'' said Delismon. ``He made you beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1990s, nitric oxide's importance became clear. In
1992, the journal Science named it molecule of the year. In 1996,
Furchgott and Murad received the Lasker Award, often dubbed the
American Nobel.
</P>
<P>
   Murad, new to Houston and UT, hopes his new celebrity will bring
grants and top-notch younger researchers to the school. But he
hopes the Nobel will not change him.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Murad, his wife of nearly 40 years, is confident it won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will go on doing the things he loves,'' she said. ``I'm
very proud of him.''
</P>
<P>
   The money from his share of the $978,000 prize will go toward
educating his five grandchildren and maybe to Indiana's DePauw
University, where he went on a full scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   One area of Murad's expertise that gets ignored frequently is
his skill as a physician, his wife said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won the prize for the `Art and Practice of Medicine' when
he was in medical school'' at Cleveland's Case Western University,
she said. ``In 1976, when I had a pulmonary embolism (a blood clot
in the lungs), he diagnosed it before anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   His concern for patients was evident last week as he talked to
24-year-old Sharon Jones as she cradled her very premature baby,
James Michael, on her chest in the Turner Neonatal Intensive Care
Unit at Hermann Children's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   While medicine has yet to take advantage of many potential
benefits of nitric oxide, it is already helping save the lives of
very premature newborns in neonatal units across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the infants in the Turner Unit will benefit from nitric
oxide used in small doses to open up their constricted pulmonary
arteries and allow their blood to be more fully oxygenated.
</P>
<P>
   Little Michael, born weighing 1 pound, 7.6 ounces, has not yet
had to have nitric oxide. But his mother and father drive in
regularly from Splendora to cuddle the infant born three months
early at a hospital in Humble.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Murad's big body, hugged by the yellow cotton gown
required in such nurseries, dwarfed the young mother as she cradled
her infant.
</P>
<P>
   But he leaned forward to catch her soft words, and he was
cautiously encouraging as he elicited the story about how Sharon
Jones had dropped out of college when her baby was born, and now
spent hours each day holding him close. His father takes the
weekend duty, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got married when I was 19,'' she said. ``We wanted to wait
a few years to have children, but ...''
</P>
<P>
   Even though a medical school planning committee was awaiting
Murad's appearance downstairs, he seemed in no hurry as he talked
to Jones and toured the unit with Dr. John Sparks, chairman of UT's
Pediatrics Department.
</P>
<P>
   Murad's enthusiasm for the treatment options offered by nitric
oxide is almost boundless, but his face and voice soften when he
talks about the use in keeping newborns healthy and whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been a real shot in the arm for the school,'' said
Sparks. Already, Murad has been working with pediatric researchers
like Dr. Michael Fant and Dr. Bruce Alpert, whose interests in
infant development and care of critically ill children overlaps
that of Murad.
</P>
<P>
   His interest is not limited to children, but as the father of
five, he has been necessarily involved with the younger generation.
</P>
<P>
   All his youngsters are grown and gone, but Monday morning's
first hours were spent tracking them down and telling them about
his Nobel.
</P>
<P>
   Another of those early communications was with Delismon, a
retired Boeing senior principal engineer who now lives in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so excited when I heard in on television,'' said
Delismon. ``I didn't even stay upstairs to hear the whole thing. I
ran downstairs and e-mailed him my congratulations.''
</P>
<P>
   The two grew up in Whiting, Ind., a town of 10,000 south of
Chicago. Their high school had only about 120 students in the
senior class.
</P>
<P>
   But the teachers were wonderful, said Delismon. ``They really
took an interest in us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Delismon, who describes his youthful self as 6 feet tall and 125
pounds, managed the swimming and football teams. Murad, he said,
lettered in track and football. Both were members of the men's glee
club and took roles in school and local operettas and musical
productions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always smooth,'' said Delismon. ``He was voted best
dressed in high school. The dress then was slacks and sweaters.''
</P>
<P>
   At lunch, the pair would eat at a small restaurant run by
Murad's parents, John and Josephine, Delismon said. It was a
favorite with teachers and students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just a bunch of gunky kids 16 and 17 years old,'' he
said. ``But they went out of their way to take an interest in us.
It was absolutely amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-16-98 1435EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981016.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1243 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOBEL-MURAD-PROFILE-2     10-16 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOBEL-MURAD-PROFILE-2DTAKE$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOBEL-MURAD-PROFILE-2NDTAKE-$ADV18 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 18) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  HOUSTON: absolutely amazing.``
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Murad's father had emigrated from Albania when he was only 16.
His wife was from St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they were living today, they would be so proud,'' said
Delismon.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Murad nor Delismon were valedictorian or salutatorian,
but ``we were up there,'' said Delismon. They competed mercilessly.
If one got a 95 on a test, the other got a 100. After graduation,
many of the students took a college algebra course from Indiana
University, Delismon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was another competition,'' he said. ``Did you get a hundred
on the exam? What? Only a 99? You dummy!
</P>
<P>
   ``We aced that class, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought his friend would win the Nobel Prize,
Delismon said, ``Never.''
</P>
<P>
   When Murad first made his nitric oxide discovery almost 20 years
ago, he told Delismon that it was important and might lead to some
kinds of awards. His friend remembers what he told Murad later.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were the only one who thought this work was important,''
said Delismon. ``You never give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Murad's interest in nitric oxide began early in his career, and
he continued to work in the field even when others thought his
pursuit fruitless because nitric oxide acted contrary to what was
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Because it has one electron free, nitric oxide is known as a
free radical. It readily combines with other chemicals in the body,
and exists in a pure state no longer than 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But those crucial 10 seconds allow the gas produced by one cell
to penetrate the outer membrane and regulate the function of
another cell. It was the first time that a gas had been found to
act as a ``signaling'' molecule that turns on the functions of
other cells.
</P>
<P>
   Further work in the field showed that this so-called
second-message molecule provides crucial signals in the
cardiovascular and nervous systems. It fights infections, regulates
blood pressure and governs the flow of blood to different organs.
</P>
<P>
   Delismon understands the basics of his friend's work, but Murad
laughs when asked about Delismon's.
</P>
<P>
   Most of it was top-secret for the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd say, `I would tell you about it, but then I'd have to
kill you,' '' Murad said.
</P>
<P>
   Delismon said he knows what Murad will say when they meet next:
``I'm ahead, one Nobel to nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The two parted ways when they went to college. Murad went to
DePauw, Delismon to the University of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   After getting his bachelor's degree, Murad was almost ready to
go Washington University in St. Louis when a fraternity brother
told him about an M.D.-Ph.D. program at Case Western. He obtained
both his medical degree and a doctorate in pharmacology there.
</P>
<P>
   At the prestigious Massachusetts General Hospital, where he did
his internship and residency with Willerson, he also worked with
future Nobel laureate Dr. Joseph Goldstein of UT Southwestern
Medical School in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very bright and hard working,'' said Willerson. ``He is
committed to doing everything well. He wants everything around him
to be done at a high level. He is ambitious for the Health Science
Center and the Texas Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at the same time, he is unassuming and shy.''
</P>
<P>
   And he is a regular guy, said wife Carol. Most people call him
``Fred'' rather than Ferid, an Albanian name his father gave him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And how many doctors do you know who have a radial saw in the
garage?'' asked his wife.
</P>
<P>
   He always has some kind building project, she said. He built a
garage at their Lake Tahoe home, she said, and a three-car garage
at their former place in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   He taught his son to build and fix the family cars. ``And,'' she
said, ``my oldest daughter can do a mean wallboard.''
</P>
<P>
   None of Murad's four daughters nor his son went into medicine,
although one is a medical editor and another a respiratory
therapist. ``I guess I scared them off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like many in the medical field, he has bounced from medical
school to medical school and even done a stint in the
pharmaceutical industry.
</P>
<P>
   He was at the University of Virginia in Charlottesville and at
Stanford University in California. In the early 1990s, he was vice
president for pharmaceutical research and development for Abbott
Laboratories in Illinois. ``Then I decided to create a biotech
company at the wrong time,'' he said. ``I spent most of my time
raising money.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not what he liked to do, and he left Molecular Geriatrics
Corp. in Lake Bluff, Ill., to return to academia where he could do
what he likes best _ research and teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really get my jollies when I go to the blackboard with my
trainees,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There they plan new experiments and mull over old ones. They
brainstorm new work that could take a couple of months or a couple
of years.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, his trainees are a new generation of Ferid Murad, just
as he is a product of the laboratories in which he was trained.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look on my trainees as scientific offspring,'' he said. ``I
follow what they are doing, and many have done well. They are
scattered around the globe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very likely that he will grow his own Nobel Prize
winners here,'' said Dr. M. David Low, president of the UT Health
Science Center. ``It is one of our challenges to make sure that all
the conditions are there so he can.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
