<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SHADRACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``SHADRACH'' NEVER RAISES ITS VOICE ABOVE A WHISPER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHADRACH
</P>
<P>
   Written by: Susanna Styron and Bridget Terry (based on the short
story by William Styron)
</P>
<P>
   Directed by: Susanna Styron
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Harvey Keitel, Andie MacDowell, John Franklin Sawyer,
Scott Terra, Daniel Treat
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 88 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 (profanity, racial epithets)
</P>
<P>
   Paul Whitehurst (Scott Terra) is a proper white child from a
proper white family in small-town Virginia. Doesn't have any
brothers and sisters, and while he seems a mite lonely at times,
his parents try to do right by him. He's clean, well fed, polite,
fears the Lord. This being the South, and this being 1935, Paul
doesn't have too many dealings with black folks. There's the
family's housekeeper, and he also sees them in the colored-only
balcony at the local movie house where he goes to see Stepin
Fetchit movies, but all that changes when he meets Shadrach (John
Franklin Sawyer).
</P>
<P>
   That's the old man Paul spies while playing marbles with his
best friend, Little Mole (Daniel Treat), the youngest of the Dabney
clan's seven children. The Dabneys, well, there's nothing else to
call them but white trash. The house is a wreck, and the front lawn
is littered with old appliances and rusted bed frames. The boys
don't bathe, and walk around with body odor so strong it could take
your sight. The girls get pregnant, and just seem to stay pregnant.
The mother of this brood, Trixie (Andie MacDowell), is a good
woman, if a little too fond of beer _ she goes to sleep with bottle
in hand, and greets the new day with a cold one in her grasp. Her
husband, Vernon (Harvey Keitel), is holding his family together,
but barely. He blames FDR _ ``Franklin D-as-in-disaster
Roosevelt,'' as he is fond of saying _ for the Depression. But
truth be told, the family has been on the skids since the
Confederacy fell and its tobacco plantation went belly up. The
Dabneys' sole source of income comes from Vernon's on-the-sly corn
liquor still.
</P>
<P>
   But back to Shadrach. He shows up one day at the Dabney home,
and takes an instant liking to Paul, who's staying with the clan
while his parents attend a funeral in Maryland. Shadrach reveals
he's 99 years old, and has walked all the way from Alabama to die
on Dabney land. He was born a slave on the Dabney plantation, and
was sold away from his family when he was barely a man. Now, at the
end of his life, he's come home to die. It's the final wish of a
man who has borne too long life's burdens, but there's a problem.
The sheriff says it's against the law for Vernon to plant Shadrach
in Dabney ground. And Vernon doesn't have the $35 for a ``proper
legal Negro burial'' with a colored undertaker in a colored
cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take long to figure out that Paul is going to learn
all kinds of eternal lessons from the old man, things about life
and death, the resilience of the spirit, and reclaiming yourself.
``Shadrach,'' based on a William Styron short story and adapted
here by his daughter Susanna, is a slight film that never reaches
beyond the surface. It's all pleasant and inoffensive enough, but
it should be so much more than a leisurely stroll through the
Depression-era South.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is Shadrach himself, played by newcomer
Sawyer, an 83-year-old retired postal worker. Make no mistake, with
his snow-white hair and face like aged ebony, Sawyer is a magnetic
presence. As the illiterate, incontinent Shadrach, Sawyer does
everything asked of him; unfortunately, it isn't much. He
occasionally utters ``Praise the Lord, praise his sweet name,'' but
that's it. He has precious little dialogue, so the audience must
rely on Paul's imagination to flesh out Shadrach's life and
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   This could have worked, but the film needs a more charismatic
youngster to portray Paul. Terra's a cute kid, but that's all. He's
the eyes and ears of the audience (his adult narration is supplied
by Martin Sheen), yet he doesn't register as enough of a presence
even when he wonders whether heaven has colored-only designations
on its water fouuntains and outhouses.
</P>
<P>
   It may say something about the film that the strongest
performance is delivered by McDowell, who has never been a
scintillating actress. She is far more convincing than she has any
right to be as a sassy, hard-drinking Southern gal, tossing off
lines like ``Boy, it's hot enough to kill a mule out here.''
Wrestling with his own dewdrop accent, Keitel's in overdrive mode,
playing much too big and blustery for the rather sedate proceedings
around him.
</P>
<P>
   Styron is an able, if unspectacular, director, but she's too
precious in her handing of the story. ``Shadrach'' should have the
power and majesty of make-you-wanna-shout gospel, but it never
raises its voice above a whisper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-16-98 1437EDT &QL; 
