A1248 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS &LR;      10-16 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO GENERATIONS OF BLUESMEN AVOIT THE FAD OF THE MINUTE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're not talking flavor-of-the-month artists here. We're
talking about two generations of bluesmen _ John Lee Hooker and
Billy Squier _ who function outside of passing trends and like it
that way.
</P>
<P>
   Hooker, the 81-year-old dean of blues boogie, and Squier, a
48-year-old Wellesley native who learned the blues through Eric
Clapton's albums, have no overripe ambitions at this point, other
than to make the best music they can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no big plans. Things just happen,'' says Hooker, whose
new album ``The Best of Friends'' is out Tuesday and features
collaborations with Clapton, Ben Harper, Ry Cooder, and Charlie
Musselwhite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hanging in there,'' Hooker adds from his San Francisco
home. ``I'm hanging on like a vine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a very uncalculated project,'' Squier says of
his own just released ``Acoustic Blues.'' ``This is not a career
record. When I made it, as far as I was concerned, my career was
over because I was fed up with the (record industry). I just
started exploring the guitar and seeing where it would take me.''
</P>
<P>
   Both records are small gems in the vast sea of fall releases.
Hooker's disc is really a ``best of'' duets record, collecting past
duets with buddies Van Morrison, Carlos Santana, and Bonnie Raitt,
along with three new tracks that should sustain interest in his
ever-influential career.
</P>
<P>
   The new songs include a fiery remake of Hooker's hit, ``Boogie
Chillen,'' with new riffs from Clapton. ``It's cooking, isn't it?''
says Hooker. ``It's a different version with a different beat and
more drive. And Clapton is the all-around man. I first played with
him a long time ago. He was with John Mayall and the Bluesbreakers
and they backed me on a tour of England in the '60s.''
</P>
<P>
   Hooker, who grew up in a sharecropping family just outside
Clarksdale, Miss., also teamed with slide guitarist Cooder for a
new romp through the shuffling ``Big Legs, Tight Skirt.'' The title
suggests that Hooker's blues may not always be politically correct,
but no one is going to question his authenticity. And the other
newly minted track is ``Burnin' Hell,'' a chooglin' number that
shows Hooker's religious side. ``I'm going to the church hall to
get down on my bended knee,'' he sings in his unmistakably gritty
voice.
</P>
<P>
   This track features new friend Ben Harper on slide (``He plays a
mixed blues and puts a real flavor to it,'' says Hooker) and old
friend Charlie Musselwhite on harmonica. ``I've known Charlie a
long time. He lived with me when he broke up with his wife,''
Hooker adds.
</P>
<P>
   As for Squier, the former Wellesley hellion (he can still recall
knotty moments with the local police) has left behind a rock 'n'
roll career that peaked in the '80s with such hits as ``The
Stroke'' and ``My Kinda Lover.'' He became disenchanted with the
music business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm cynical about it,'' says Squier, who lives in New York.
``It's now music in small letters and business in big letters.''
</P>
<P>
   Squier did well enough in his early years (three multi-platinum
albums) that he can now take a more casual approach. Hence
``Acoustic Blues,'' in which he plays solo acoustic guitar and
sings mature songs. He updates ``The Stroke'' in ``Stroke Me
Blues,'' takes a survivor's stance in ``Long Way to Fall,'' and
even remakes Joni Mitchell's ``The River.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I put my guitar in new tunings and took off to see where I
would get,'' says Squier. ``I was just writing songs. I wasn't even
thinking of recording them.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; uftagline &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Squier performs Monday night at 7 at Borders Books &AMP; Music,
Chestnut Hill. Call 617-630-1134.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
