<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAUX-SURVIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISIANA SENATOR FINDS SUCCESS IN THE MIDDLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Louisiana Senator John Breaux has seen one
Democratic colleague after another swept away by the Republican
sentiment that was washed over the South in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into the Nov. 3 elections, he has this recipe for
survival:
</P>
<P>
   ``Get to the mainstream, moderate, middle of the road,'' said
Breaux, speaking in a slight Cajun accent native to his home
parish. ``And pledge to make government work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in the fundamentals of the party, the goals of equal
opportunity and taking care of people who need help,'' said Breaux,
who is comfortably ahead in his reelection race. ``But if we have
problems with something like Medicare, and we need to change it to
save it, we've got to do it. We can't say we can never change.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern Democrats clearly can use some sort of change. The
party in recent years has made some moves toward the middle,
following the lead of the Democratic Leadership Council that Breaux
and his old friend Bill Clinton helped establish. ``Clinton took
our DLC mandate _ responsibility, opportunity, community _ and
carried Louisiana twice,'' Breaux said.
</P>
<P>
   But since Clinton's election in 1992, Democrats have lost eight
US Senate seats in the South, seeing their 15-7 advantage reversed
in six years.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades ago, Democrats held virtually every Senate seat in
the old Confederacy, giving the party a solid majority and
extending great power to such senior figures as Richard Russell and
Herman Talmadge in Georgia, John Stennis and James Eastland in
Mississippi, John Sparkman in Alabama, and Russell Long in
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic hegemony was first broken by the election of
Republicans in Texas and Tennessee and the defection of Senator
Strom Thurmond to the GOP in South Carolina. Then the
transformation gathered force.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans began to make big gains with the electorate in
the 1980s under Ronald Reagan,'' said Merle Black, a professor of
politics at Emory University. Though many states have no formal
party registration, Black said, exit polls in 1996 determined that
most white voters in the South call themselves Republicans and
identify with the party's conservative positions.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans had ``better candidates and aggressive campaigns
that appealed to the white swing voters,'' said Black, who
specializes in Southern politics.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic setbacks across Dixie during this decade are
directly related to the party's loss of power on Capitol Hill, and
there seems little chance that the Democrats will gain a Senate
seat in the region this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux, however, has been building seniority while other
Southern Democrats have been losing theirs. A fixture in Washington
since he was first elected to Congress in 1972 at age 28, Breaux
would become the region's senior Democrat if Senator Ernest
Hollings of South Carolina fails to win reelection next month.
</P>
<P>
   Though a steadfast Democrat, Breaux cannot be defined by
rankings that label legislators liberal or conservative. In the
last Congress, the National Journal rated him near 50 percent on
both liberal and conservative scales on economic and social issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an extremely sophisticated politician. He manages to go
down the middle,'' said Ed Renwick, director of the Institute of
Politics at Loyola University here. ``Breaux wheels and deals with
business, labor, all the power centers. He's very inclusive, and
that's difficult to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaux is so far ahead of his Republican opponent, state
Representative Jim Donelon, that no one has bothered to take a poll
since March, when Breaux was more than 40 points in front of any
rival.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux says Clinton's problems ``could make a difference'' in a
few contests, but not in Louisiana, where the Democratic Party has
remained strong because of a solid base of blacks and a
French-Catholic influence that makes moderate politics more
palatable than the harder-edged conservatism of the Protestant
right.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the South, there are only two closely contested
Senate races. Hollings holds a slight lead over his Republican
challenger, US Representative Bob Inglis, in the latest polls from
South Carolina. In North Carolina, Senator Lauch Faircloth, a
one-term Republican incumbent, is in a tough fight with John
Edwards, a trial lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Incumbents are expected to waltz to reelection in the other
Southern races. Senator Richard Shelby, who renounced the
Democratic Party and joined the GOP after Republicans gained
control of the Senate in 1994, is expected to win easily in
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Senator Bob Graham is an overwhelming favorite to win
in Florida. In Georgia, Republican Senator Paul Coverdell is
comfortably in front of the Democratic candidate, Michael Coles.
</P>
<P>
   A Democrat is expected to hold the seat in Arkansas being
vacated by Senator Dale Bumpers. Blanche Lambert Lincoln, a popular
former congresswoman who gave up her seat two years ago to give
birth to twins, is running 16 points ahead of Republican state
Senator Fay Boozman in the latest poll.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-16-98 1440EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
