<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1253 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-BOSSTONES-BOS &LR;      10-16 1480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BOSSTONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKA BAND BOSSTONES APPEAR TO BE GOING SOMEWHERE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Let's go back to 1979. Dicky Barrett, growing
up in a western suburb of Boston and in junior high school, has the
Clash's second album, ``Give 'em Enough Rope,'' spinning on his
turntable. The speakers are blasting Joe Strummer's harsh,
righteous vocals. Strummer is singing ``The Last Gang in Town,'' a
defiant, punk-rock-as-group-bonding anthem. Barrett may live an
ocean away from London, but Strummer's speaking to him.
</P>
<P>
   Skip ahead ...
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday at 4 p.m., coinciding with the release of the first
live Bosstones CD, Strummer will be in Boston at Tower Records to
present a ``Walk of Fame'' star to Barrett and the Boston ska-punk
band he fronts, the Mighty Mighty Bosstones.
</P>
<P>
   There is an element of this that is mind-boggling to Barrett.
Could he ever have imagined?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not in a million years,'' says Barrett. ``If I were to go to
one of his concerts _ and I never did _ and was in the third row
and he spat on me, that'd have been exciting!''
</P>
<P>
   A pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe, next week,'' says bassist Joe Gittleman, helpfully and
hopefully.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Barrett and Gittleman _ the two main voices of the seven-member
Bosstones _ are seated at a table set up on the otherwise barren
floor at the Middle East Downstairs, early evening, last Monday.
Rock 'n' roll will happen soon in this club _ and come early
December the Bosstones will host four 18-plus nights of their fifth
annual, sweat-drenched Hometown Throwdown in this very spot (a
fifth show, all ages, will take place at the nearby Greek-American
Club on Green Street) _ but right now Barrett and Gittleman are
discussing the good life, as the warm afterglow of success lingers.
</P>
<P>
   Well, sort of. Certainly, they have no complaints. They've
toured the world and gained friends and fans far and wide. Money
has been made. But the good life is not one of limousines and
country estates. It's more, both say, the simple fact that everyone
actually has their own place to live and no longer has to crash
with Gittleman's mother in Cambridge's Central Square.
</P>
<P>
   The Mighty Mighty Bosstones' 1997 album, ``Let's Face It,''
featuring the hit single, ``The Impression That I Get,'' sold over
a million copies in the United States, over 2 million worldwide.
The Bosstones had been on an upward trajectory for some time, but
this put them in the upper stratum of the alt-rock world and on, or
near, the top of the ska-punk re-revival they almost
single-handedly kick-started back in the early 1980s. It was at
this long-ago point, remember, that the English two-tone ska
revival was on the wane, and a betting person would have said the
plaid-clad Bosstones were waging a futile battle. Ska was passe.
Next trend?
</P>
<P>
   Barrett laughs. ``Oh, yeah, it was over,'' he says. ``Ninety
percent (of our genre) was over. The way people thought the story
was gonna go was these eight guys, whacking away, trying as hard as
they can, doing all the right things, showing up and entertaining
every single time ... and they'd quietly go away and it would be
the best-kept secret. But no. It didn't end up like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Just about any punk-rooted band gets hit with a critical
backlash if success comes a-knocking. Ask the guys in Green Day.
For the Bosstones, there was virtually no backlash. Everybody liked
the Bosstones. Everyone still likes the Bosstones. Even, says
Barrett, Gavin Rossdale. And that was after Barrett got drunk and
dissed Rossdale, the singer from Bush, for being in a derivative
weenie band. A year or so later Rossdale came back and told Barrett
how much he liked the Mighty Mighty Bosstones.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bosstones got what they finally deserved,'' says Barrett.
``I think it's because we work hard, we're nice, and we did make
friends along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Gittleman: ``It was like, after all this time, they deserve
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But success is not about flaunting rock-star status. If a fan
gets the wrong idea and approaches Barrett that way, he says, with
a laugh, that he'll make them run away crying, with Barrett yelling
at them, ``I'm not a rock star!'''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look out my own eyeballs,'' he says, ``I don't think
I'm looking out of a rock star's eyes. I think I'm looking out of
this awkward, creepy Dicky Barrett guy's eyes. ... If someone
treats me differently because of what the band's done, I just stomp
on that immediately and say, `Slow down.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a kid. I've met people (in this role) for a long time
and treat them the best I can. I've always thought that society's
not taking kids seriously and I do and always have.''
</P>
<P>
   What Barrett and the Bosstones are about is creating and
maintaining a sense of community. Is that community solid? Has it
grown? Do the Bosstones still feel the connection deeply?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, yes, and yes,'' answers Barrett. ``Absolutely. And it's
on a national level. We bring people in, guys like Rancid and the
right people in from their coast. And that's extremely important to
us. It's not fun to do it alone. ... We're blessed people, and we
mean that whether the band did well or not. We've got our arms, our
legs, our brains, our friendships, and we live in a time in history
when there's not an amazing amount of pressure on guys our age to
truly do anything like fight wars.''
</P>
<P>
   Gittleman notes that the 30-something Bosstones have likely
advanced past fighting age, anyway. In fact, the Bosstones' dancer,
Ben Carr, even got married recently, the first 'tone to take the
plunge. ``We elected him,'' says Gittleman. ``Somebody had to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It took the heat off a lot of us,'' says Barrett. ``At least
one of us did.''
</P>
<P>
   But one of the keys to the band has been its boys-club (ladies
invited) camaraderie. (Saxophonist Kevin Lenear, who played on the
live album, has left the band, only the group's second personnel
change in its history.) &UR;  &LR; Gittleman and Barrett say that remains as
strong as ever. Perhaps the change, says Barrett, is that even if
they're not together 24-7, ``it just goes without saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the Bosstones release the 21-track ``Live From the
Middle East'' CD, a disc culled from last year's five shows. Live
albums are not the de rigueur career move they used to be. This is
a good thing. Most live recordings fell way below expectations. For
every Rolling Stones ``Get Yer Ya-Ya's Out'' or the Who's ``Live at
Leeds,'' there were a lot of big, flaccid dust-gatherers chucked
out. The Bosstones, however, are one band for whom the live CD
scenario fits the band and its fans. For one thing, the cliche of
``You've got to see them live'' fits and for another, the
translation from sight-and-sound to just sound, somehow, works.
``Live From the Middle East'' feels like flesh and blood rock 'n'
roll, not like an artifact.
</P>
<P>
   One model for the Sean Slade and Paul Kolderie-produced ``Middle
East'' was the first live J. Geils Band album, ``Full House.''
``Most are stale and stiff,'' says Barrett, of the live album
oeuvre. ``They try to fix them too much and take away what was
cool.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bosstones album gets to a higher plane. Part of the reason,
Barrett says, is that the band recorded the shows without planning
to make an album. That notion came after they heard what they'd
captured. (Barrett says if he knew he was chattering on stage for
posterity he'd have aped every live album line he could recall.)
The jumpy rhythms, punchy horns and, especially, the electric
guitar from Nate Albert kick in.
</P>
<P>
   This, says Barrett and Gittleman, is a what you saw is what you
get outing. Gittleman waded through six hours of tapes with Barrett
and the album's producers and patched the work together from all
the shows. ``We were genuinely overexcited,'' says Barrett, of the
shows. ``A huge adrenaline rush, the culmination of the entire
year. It's an exciting night every single night. The people that
are in the room are just as much a part of the show. We spend the
whole night standing among them, hanging among them, partying with
them and I think (as a recording) this is as close as we can
come.''
</P>
<P>
   This is, in the classic live album sense, a stopgap, a reminder
``that we're not dead,'' says Barrett. The band begins work shortly
on its next studio album. One thing they predict is that Albert's
guitar will be featured more prominently _ one strength they took
away from hearing themselves recorded live.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go out and make the sophomore album,'' says
Gittleman, mock philosophically. ``Wait a minute. It's not our
first album, is it now?'' They both laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the beauty of the band,'' says Barrett. ``Even though
it was our most successful album, it's not our first album. We know
how to be the Bosstones; we know how to make Bosstones albums.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
