<HEADLINE>
SUPERSHOT CAMERA BRINGS UP CLOSE   AND PERSONAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Say this for Fox. The network is willing to stretch the limits
of new and existing technology to bring viewers closer to the game
of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The latest innovation for the World Series is the Supershot
camera. It's really a slow-motion camera, but instead of focusing
it on a specific player, Fox plans to have it trained on the ball
to capture all the plays, up close and personal.
</P>
<P>
   In a perfect world, the Supershot would not only show a ball
being hit to the shortstop, for example, but also provide a tighter
shot showing the ball entering his glove and being transferred to
his right hand as he throws to first.
</P>
<P>
   The camera, one of 19 Fox plans to use during its coverage of
the World Series starting tomorrow at 7:30 p.m. when the Padres
visit the Yankees, will be stationed along the third base line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to do tight shots when appropriate,'' said producer
John Filippelli. ``They are what we enjoy in the coverage because
they portray the drama and capture the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Filippelli said, Fox trained its slo-mo camera on
the pitcher. But the Supershot ideally will allow viewers to
determine, for instance, whether a baserunner is safe. Not that the
shot will change an umpire's call.
</P>
<P>
   Fox is still working out agreements with the players involved to
wear the catcher-cam, one of best innovations on television. The
shots from the tiny camera perched on the catcher's mask are
priceless.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Buck, Tim McCarver, and Bob Brenly are calling the Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people assume on paper that this will be a very short
World Series,'' Brenly said. ``But the Padres are a very underrated
team. Their grit was shown during the team's series against the
Houston Astros and Atlanta Braves. They were heavy underdogs in
both of those series but managed to win them. They don't scare
easily. They don't back up. In fact, they move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarver said the Series could be ``a great ending to the best
season baseball we ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
That's his audience
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Andelman just bit the hand that feeds him. He blasted his
talk show callers who don't like Bill Parcells, describing them in
a New York tabloid as ``unsophisticated,'' ``brainwashed,'' and a
``herd of ignoramuses.''
</P>
<P>
   The WEEI talk show host's tirade appeared Wednesday in the New
York Post. Surprisingly, Andelman blamed sports talk radio for
spreading the hatred toward Parcells, the coach who left the
Patriots for the Jets last season. He also claimed he was a
Parcells supporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came, he was paid, he did his job and left,'' Andelman
said. ``Why would I wish any ill will on him?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the people who are buying the $5 beers, betting on the
games, the rowdy guys who don't have enough sophistication to
understand what free agency is,'' he added. ``If Parcells says or
does anything, in order to make him look bad, they'll entrap him
into something to fit their own conditions. Patriots owner Bob
Kraft is very skilled at mass brainwashing. Now he's been the best
owner the Patriots have had, but he has this whoop-it-up mentality
to gather the masses against Parcells. The same thing in this town
that applies to Bill Parcells now applies to Roger Clemens.''
</P>
<P>
   Andelman went on to say that only three things matter in Boston
_ sports, politics, and revenge. ``Love is an emotion and so is
hate,'' he said. ``It's `if our team can't win, let's root against
the Jets.' It's like in baseball: `If the Red Sox can't win, let's
root against the Yankees.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Howard Manly is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
