<SLUG> BC-PARIS-FASHION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN DESIGNERS' CASUAL APPROACHES BUBBLE OVER INTO FRENCH
FASHION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The lighter, more casual approach to women's fashion,
taken in Milan's spring 1999 ready-to-wear collections, is bubbling
over into French fashion, albeit under the hand of foreign
designers.
</P>
<P>
   The first three significant shows of the season were designed by
an Englishman, an American and a Belgian, at Christian Dior, Louis
Vuitton and Hermes, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Galliano for Dior &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Galliano lifted spirits, if not ideologies, in his Dior
presentation in the firm's Avenue Montaigne fitting rooms, reached
after a climb up a dramatic stone staircase. Models marched into
rooms and cubicles, posing in the ``Lost Boys' Room,'' for example,
against a decadent bed of mussed sheets, lacy pillows and cashmere
throws. Fluffy white feathers littered the bed and floor, as if the
boys had just enjoyed a naughty pillow fight.
</P>
<P>
   Galliano's collection, inspired by the Russian Constructivist
movement, was replete with olive green uniform jackets with Red
Army trim, sleeves rolled into epaulettes and most worn over stiff
A-line or sheer crystal-pleated skirts. The pants, perhaps a bit
difficult to wear by any but the tallest women, are gargantuan
pleated affairs gathered with drawstrings at the ankles.
Fortuny-pleated tunics and skirts were fastened Chinese style with
bronze ribbon frogs.
</P>
<P>
   Brassy CD initials and stars marked the high jacket collars, and
slightly faded red Guardian Angel berets set off each outfit, as
the curvy waists and stiff skirts recalled the original Dior's
post-World War II New Look. For those who bemoaned the absence of
good jackets in Milan, Galliano delivered and delivered.
</P>
<P>
   The Dior collection also includes a group of white suits, black
lacquered Aran knits and the simplest ivory dresses, the latter
charmingly displayed on three barefoot models with long blond
tresses in the best Daryl-Hannah-as-mermaid style.
</P>
<P>
   Galliano's tour de force in this collection was not that of
camaraderie, however, but the sensuous and breathtaking evening
gowns of silk charmeuse. With fabric worked on the bias and in
chevrons, dresses began as narrow slips and swept the floor in
voluminous trumpet skirts. They came in white, black or
combinations of blood red, white and black. The same colors also
appeared in graphic designs on stiff organdy coats, tunics and
dresses, graphics in the style of artist Sonia Delaunay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marc Jacobs for Louis Vuitton &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That the roots of French fashion still flourish after some long
years of minimalism is very much because of single-minded designers
such as Galliano. While U.S. designer Marc Jacobs was much improved
in his second collection for Louis Vuitton, his is a totally
different path than that of Galliano.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs' show, in the far 15th ``arrondissement,'' was held in a
glass greenhouse, with the weather cooperating to showcase a blue
sky, fluffy clouds and a green park and fountain setting outdoors.
But just in case, the Vuitton collection was chock-full of
rainproof ponchos. Worn with shorts, they would be perfect for
rainy-day bicycle rides. In sheer fabrics over shiny
paillette-covered tops, they could go out for evening.
</P>
<P>
   A rubberized raincoat sported a stylized design of rain
splatters against a background of white, tan and black graphic
shapes. The tan seen throughout the collection was a play on
Vuitton's traditional tan leather, which Jacobs used to best
advantage in accessories with a clear vinyl embossed with the
familiar LV, diamond and rosette designs.
</P>
<P>
   If a one-world description is needed of the Jacobs designs, it
would be minimalist, but the fabrics are luxurious as well as
modern. The colors _ white, beige, blue, yellow, lilac and a mossy
green _ expanded beyond the black and gray of recent years. And
Jacobs' wit was showcased in velvet and plastic bikinis, pastel
bags and pouches on belts and even a pale yellow motorbike helmet.
</P>
<P>
   The grand tour image that Louis Vuitton has always epitomized is
changing under Jacobs, and perhaps for the better, to one that is
younger and sportier, although still firmly tied to luxury goods.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Margiela for Hermes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hermes, another French leather-goods house that has
traditionally prided itself on furnishings for ladies and gentlemen
traveling or relaxing at home or around their private stables, is
undergoing a change of image. There, designer Margiela, also in his
second season and true to his word, sent out not a totally new
collection but one built on the new classics he established for
this fall and winter.
</P>
<P>
   His ``pea jacket,'' actually a long-sleeved tunic with a deep V
neckline, was translated for spring in fabrics from dusky brown
crepe to beige lambskin. If that appears not a wide range of color,
that was Margiela's intention, branching out only from brown tones
into white, gray, putty and sepia.
</P>
<P>
   The fabrics were much lighter-weight than for fall, with ribbon
knits, cotton jersey and gabardine, wool and twill crepes and linen
in several weaves. Dresses, unadorned and hanging roomily but
straight from the shoulder, were the coolest alternatives, along
with cotton ``pea shirts,'' sporting no buttons but rather the deep
V neckline.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Margiela showed the collection on mature models, who
not only made eye contact with the audience in Faubourg
Saint-Honore showroom but also smiled. While not as young or as
sporty as Jacobs' designs for Vuitton, these looks are a giant leap
forward for Hermes and probably much more in keeping with the
company's customer image.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ennio Capasa for Costume National &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Costume National, shown in the heart of the lovely old Ecole
des Beaux Arts on the Left Bank, the hits were little leather
jackets and flat-front pants. Designer Ennio Capasa chose
tight-fitting designs that might have added a touch of modernity
along with rubberized shirt jackets, but then he flubbed up with
too many gimmicks such as capelets, slits and finally trains that
dragged the runways behind pants. Why?
</P>
<P>
   As in Milan, these French collections are beginning to diverge
in two directions _ that of the modernists, who take their lead
from high-tech fabrics, and the path of luxury, also dependent on
materials but more often natural, more costly ones. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
