<HEADER>
A1256 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-16 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG CONNECTION BETWEEN GOAL SETTING, ACCOMPLISHING GOALS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lots of us agonize over what kind of floor covering we'd like in
our kitchen or what kind of paint color would look good in our
living room.
</P>
<P>
   We may spend hours going from one tile store to another
comparing nearly identical blocks of stone or examining paint
samples under a variety of lighting conditions yet we seldom spend
as much time planning our own careers.
</P>
<P>
   We're so busy tending to our daily responsibilities or juggling
family responsibilities or crossing off the ``to do'' things on our
daily list that we never sit back and decide where we really want
to go.
</P>
<P>
   It's a matter of being the author of your own life, said
Nicholas Lore, the author of ``The Pathfinder: How to Choose or
Change Your Career for a Lifetime of Satisfaction and Success''
(Simon &AMP; Schuster). Most people are so caught up in living their
lives that they don't think of sitting down and deciding what they
want to do in life.
</P>
<P>
   Lore believes there is a strong connection between goal setting
and accomplishing the goals.
</P>
<P>
   People who write their goals down and revisit them often _ about
every three months _ tend to fulfill their goals, said Lore, who is
director of the Rockport Institute, a career planning consulting
firm in Rockville, Md. Conversely, people who don't write them down
and have no formal structure to complete their goals tend not to
fulfill them.
</P>
<P>
   Goals give us something to shoot for, said Rory Aplanalp,
president of StarQuest, a consulting firm in Houston that teaches
goal setting. If you don't know where you're going, how will you
know when you get there?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary vs. extraordinary &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Setting goals is adventurous, Lore said. It means the difference
between an ordinary life and an extraordinary one.
</P>
<P>
   Lore said he has a friend who sat down at the age of 15 and made
a list of 127 things he wanted to do in his life. Some of the goals
sound crazy like retracing the travels of Marco Polo and Alexander
the Great or farfetched like watching a cremation ceremony in Bali
or nearly impossible like building his own telescope.
</P>
<P>
   But by carefully planning a way to accomplish his goals, Lore
said his friend has completed most of them, including the ones
listed above. (However, he still hasn't read the entire
Encyclopedia Britannica or appeared in a Tarzan movie.)
</P>
<P>
   While goal setting is kind of a no-brainer, why do so many
people not do it?
</P>
<P>
   Lore said it's because humans feel comfortable at equilibrium.
We like things to stay on a even keel and when things get thrown
off, we struggle to get back to that comfort zone.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to get off your duff is to realize you're in
equilibrium and that you're unwilling to stay there, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes that's caused by a crisis. Other times, circumstances
build up over time at work and reach a point when you don't want to
put up with things any more, he said.
</P>
<P>
   People either go toward pleasure or away from discomfort, he
said. Either way, there has to be a commitment to become the master
of your life.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're perfectly happy to sit with your feet up with a
brewski and open a bag of chips, then you're never going to
change,'' Lore said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Method for creating goals &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aplanalp has a five-step method for creating goals. The most
important is to set a goal based on what you value, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Aplanalp said he strives to be the best father and
husband he can be so he made a goal of taking his family, including
his eight children, on a Hawaiian vacation. It took six years of
planning and saving but the group went last Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   A goal also must have a deadline: year, month and day, and it
also must be specific, he said. For Aplanalp, that meant deciding
which islands to visit and how long they'd stay in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   It's also important to anticipate obstacles and finally, be
realistic.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Lane believes that writing down her goals has helped her
achieve many of her dreams. She dusts them off annually, about the
same time she celebrates the anniversary of her company,
Association Services Team.
</P>
<P>
   Lane, who had been a human resource executive, used goal setting
to chose a new career. She kept a journal and continually evaluated
what she wanted in life and settled on a career of managing
professional associations.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, setting goals and writing them down keeps Lane
highly focused on her plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave my life control at a time when I didn't feel that I
had any control,'' she said. ``Now I feel as if I have a roadmap.''
</P>
<P>
   Send e-mail to lm.sixel at chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
