<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
  
 AEROSMITH COMES ROCKING BACK ON LIVE ALBUM
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   &UR; gfcdrop &LR; Aerosmith has evoked both praise and criticism for the
slickness of its recent hit, ``I Don't Miss a Thing,'' a Diane
Warren-penned tune from the ``Armaggedon'' soundtrack that became
the band's first No.1 song. But no such argument should accompany
Aerosmith's new twin-CD live set, ``A Little South of Sanity,''
which rocks as hard as any live record in memory. Forget the
slickness.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real live record,'' says Aerosmith drummer Joey
Kramer, on the phone from New York. ``It's the band playing live on
stage and there's no going back into the studio and redoing stuff
and making it sound all pretty. It's the band on stage, mistakes
and all. What you hear is what you get.''
</P>
<P>
   And what you hear is excellent, even by Aerosmith's lofty stage
standards. The recordings are taken from various shows from
Boston's FleetCenter to venues across the world during the band's
``Nine Lives'' and ``Get a Grip'' tours of the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The album is really up-to-date,'' says Kramer, who returns
with his mates to the FleetCenter Dec. 31 and the Worcester Centrum
Centre Jan. 2. ``There might be four or five songs from the `Get a
Grip' tour, but the rest of it is all from `Nine Lives.'''
</P>
<P>
   The new live set, which comes out Tuesday, follows the general
song list of Aerosmith's latter-year shows, starting with a
whomping Steven Tyler/Joe Perry-driven ``Eat the Rich.'' Tyler also
launches wild screams on the drug-exorcising ``Monkey on My Back''
and, in another feverish moment, dedicates ``Mama Kin'' to the
Boston club the band owns by that name. ``To the people that go to
Mama Kin and work at Mama Kin and hang at Mama Kin,'' Tyler shouts.
</P>
<P>
   The live set actually represents a contractual obligation to
Aerosmith's former label, Geffen Records. Aerosmith switched to
Sony for the last studio album, ``Nine Lives,'' but as part of the
negotiation to leave Geffen, the band promised Geffen a live set
that would include the first two singles from the Sony deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're going to be a little sorry they let us go,''
Kramer says of Geffen.
</P>
<P>
   The band could have put out a lackluster disc, as many bands do
when they're leaving a label, but Aerosmith made a heightened
return to rock 'n' roll. That was supplied in part by the
reappearance of the band's former producer, Jack Douglas, who mixed
the new record. ``We had a lot of fun with Jack back in the old
days,'' says Kramer. ``And it was a good idea to have him mix the
live stuff, because if there's anybody who knows how the band is
supposed to sound, it's Jack.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Aerosmith seems to be firing on all cylinders these
days. Tyler is back in the saddle after injuring his knee this
summer with a twirling microphone. And Kramer is back after
suffering second-degree burns when his Ferrari caught fire at a
Scituate gas station. Kramer intends to file a lawsuit contending
that the automatic shut-off valve at the pump failed to work,
though he does acknowledge that he failed to turn off the engine
before it shot up in flames and destroyed the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard way to get the summer off, but it kind of
refreshed everybody,'' says Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   As for the recent hit single, which went from idea to conception
in just 10 days, Aerosmith doesn't mind taking heat for it from
core fans. ``Well, I guess enough people like it if it became a
No.1 song,'' says Kramer. ``And because of the hit single, our
shows have been pretty much sold out.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Kramer's burns: ``They've healed up very well and I've
got no scars,'' he says. As for future plans, he adds that
Aerosmith will start writing another record in the spring, then
maybe release it next fall. ``But we're going to pretty much stay
on the road for a while now,'' he notes. ``We're going to stay out
there and pound the boards a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufnoterule &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Instant gratification: &LR;  The increasingly important, locally
produced Instant magazine celebrates its third anniversary with two
upcoming shows. The first is a Bill's Bar soiree tomorrow with Chin
Ho!, Betty Goo, and Missing Joe. Then comes an Oct. 30 bash with
the Math (formerly Sameasyou), Canine, and Hummer. Call Instant at
781-438-3931.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufnoterule &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Another battle of the bands:  &LR; Four Boston bands _ Mindflow,
Canine, Ape Hangers, and Static _ are among six groups chosen from
those around the country for a battle of the bands sponsored by
Entertainment Weekly and All Campus Media. The three bands that get
the most votes via the Internet from now until Sunday will perform
a later show in Boston to determine the winner. Votes can be cast
at www.allcampus.com/bands; interested parties can download one
song from each band.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufnoterule &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sinead sparkles: &LR;  Sinead Lohan, the latest pride and joy from
Ireland, is building an audience fast in Boston. A few months ago
she played before a handful of folks at the Kendall Cafe. Last
week, she headlined two sold-out shows at the Lansdowne Playhouse.
She revealed a hypnotic voice that lies somewhere between that of
Sinead O'Connor and Sandy Denny, combined with a lyrical grace that
mixed street realism and spirituality. Her stage show doesn't yet
rival the shimmer of her recent debut album, ``No Mermaid,'' but
it's getting there.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufnoterule &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bits and pieces: &LR;  Pearl Jam will release a live album Nov. 24
... Cake will play Avalon Nov. 10 in an 18-plus show. Tickets on
sale today at noon through NEXT. And Ratdog stops at the Orpheum
Nov. 23 with opener Alana Davis. Tix on sale tomorrow at 11 a.m.
through NEXT ... Tickets remain for Depeche Mode's Worcester
Centrum Centre show Oct. 27. ... ... Get ready: Little Richard at
Foxwoods on Halloween ... No, that was not Alanis Morissette
shopping at Louis the other day, as one local paper reported. But
Morissette will be at Avalon Wedneday for a sold-out club gig in
preparation for a new album release Nov. 3. ... The International
(at 184 High St.) is now booking live music in its 300-capacity
upstairs club. Barrence Whitfield performs tonight. ... Jon Easley,
singer of the early '80s band Sorry, died Sept. 22 in Atlanta at
the age of 32. There will be a memorial service for friends and
fans at T.T. the Bear's this Sunday at 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Guilty Pleasures Coffeehouse in Roslindale Square has, alas,
closed. ... Incubus, Reveille, Entrain, Neon Jesus, and other acts
perform at the Rocktober Fest tomorrow and Sunday at Winter Island
in Salem. Call 617-720-0080. ... Tonight: Mudhens at Karma Club;
Grits get down at Toad; Silver Star and Jukebox Angels glam it up
at the Kirkland Cafe; Combustible Edison has a CD release party at
the Chau Chow City Ballroom (81 Essex St.) at 8 p.m. with Electric
Logs and Pineapple Ranch Hands; Bruce Katz Band at the new Sean
O'Toole's in Plymouth; Kevin So and Carl Cacho at the Black and
White Theatre in Middleborough; Little Brother at Backstage in
Haverhill; and Talking to Animals, Laurie Geltman, Charlie
Chesterman, and the Kickbacks at T.T. the Bear's ... Tomorrow:
Martin Sexton at Mama Kin, the Gravel Pit at T.T.'s ... Sunday:
Sister Soleil at the Middle East, Jabe at Club Passim ... Monday:
Dale Watson and Jimmie Dale Gilmore at the House of Blues,
Semisonic at Avalon.
</P>
