<HEADLINE>
WINDOWS FIND FUNCTION CAN TURN INTO A SHORTCUT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I use the Find feature on Windows 98 quite a bit. But instead
of going through all the various menus _ Start, Find, Files or
Folders _ can one place ``Files or folders'' be a shortcut on the
desktop?
</P>
<P>
   A. Sure. This is a nifty, hidden feature of Windows that gets
little attention, but if you use the Find function a lot it makes
your life easier.
</P>
<P>
   Bring up Find as you indicated, via the Start menu. Then Click
on File, Save Search. This will create an icon on your desktop most
likely called All Files.
</P>
<P>
   If you search for the same thing over and over _ say, files with
a DOC extension _ you can fill in the blanks for that kind of
search, and use the File/Save Search command. You can also tell the
Find feature to look only in specific places _ a set of folders, a
single drive, etc. _ and save those. Create a folder on your
desktop, call it Search and move all these icons in there for quick
access to the things you search most often.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have Norton Antivirus, which automatically updates with
downloads, always at a preset time on Fridays. Recently, I happened
by the computer when the download was taking place. I didn't recall
being logged on to the Net, so I picked up the phone to hear what
was happening. I got a dial tone. Can you explain how Norton logs
on to my machine silently and without interrupting the phone
service? When one reads about hackers breaking into computers, do
they use similar technology to do it?
</P>
<P>
   A. Don't worry. Norton Antivirus wasn't making a stealth
connection _ though it can be set up to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Many programs are now designed to make automatic checks for
updated components, including Windows 98 itself. What you saw in
this case was Norton Antivirus launching its LiveUpdate feature,
but just churning its wheels, looking for an Internet connection.
You get the same screen whether you are online or not, so it can
appear as though you are downloading something even though that's
not the case.
</P>
<P>
   You can control when most of these auto-downloading components
check for updates, or turn off the automated feature, via each
program's settings. Some, however, use Windows 95's System Agent _
called the Task Scheduler in Windows 98 _ to schedule updates.
Check the manual for the product in question to find out how it's
done.
</P>
<P>
   If your computer had been so configured, your Norton Antivirus
could have made the connection, downloaded the component and
disconnected without your intervention.
</P>
<P>
   To do this, set up Norton Antivirus to dial directly into its
server, rather than going over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I recently spilled a Coke in my keyboard, which ruined it. I
had to throw it away and get a new one. Then, a friend told me
there is a way to fix it by using a can of compressed air and
letting it dry. Is this true?
</P>
<P>
   A. If you spill plain water in a keyboard, you might be able to
salvage it by first getting as much water out of it as possible.
Turn it upside down, shake it, then leave it upside down overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, take the back off the keyboard and remove the
plate that holds the keys. Use compressed air to blow as much
moisture as you can out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Wait another day, or dry it with a hair dryer. Then, plug it in
and cross your fingers.
</P>
<P>
   With sugary sodas and coffee, you have the additional problem of
the sticky sweet substance. I'm not familiar with any way to remove
this stuff. If any hardware gurus out there have suggestions,
e-mail them to me.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Got a question about your computer? Send e-mail to
dwight.silverman at chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
