<HEADLINE>
56K MODEMS RUNNING INTO SPEED LIMITS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the new v.90 standard for 56K modems was approved earlier
this year, both users and manufacturers breathed a sigh of relief.
Burdened for months by competing 56K standards, buyers were
confused and held off upgrading to the faster devices.
</P>
<P>
   With the arrival of v.90, there's now just one way to get to
56K. While there are some Internet service providers out there
still using the X2 or K56flex schemes, their numbers are dwindling.
</P>
<P>
   However, there remain some asterisks, caveats and footnotes.
Despite the fact that these modems are capable of connecting at
56,000 bits a second, federal regulations regarding phone-line
voltage hold them to a maximum of 53K.
</P>
<P>
   And most folks seldom get that close to the top speed, thanks to
the varying quality of home or business phone wiring; the link to
the phone company's switching equipment; the quality of that
equipment; and the link from there to an Internet provider.
</P>
<P>
   Connections for most users of 56K modems seem to fall in the
40K-48K range, with some poking along at 28.8K or 33.6K.
</P>
<P>
   Different modems will also give different results. I tried out
models from three different manufacturers, and found that, despite
a common standard, their performance was far from uniform.
</P>
<P>
   I tested them in several ways _ connecting to a slower, 28.8K
modem through an older phone-company switch; making a v.90
connection at a major Houston Internet service provider;
downloading a 17-megabyte file using Netscape Navigator 4.07; and
dialing in to a v.90 connection at America Online.
</P>
<P>
   All three were internal models and were tested in a Dell
Dimension PC with a 200-megahertz Pentium MMX chip and 64 megabytes
of memory.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Robotics 56K Faxmodem _ $129, 3Com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; I've been a happy user of U.S. Robotics modems for some time,
as are many others. This is the best-selling line of consumer
modem, and with good reason _ they are reliable, affordable, speedy
and easy to install. This is the next generation of the line
previously known as the Sportster.
</P>
<P>
   The 56K Faxmodem I tried installed easily, giving Windows 98's
Plug and Play capabilities no problems at all.
</P>
<P>
   When connecting to the older, 28.8K modem, I routinely got
either 24K or 26.4K connections, the same speeds achieved with the
older, 33.6K U.S. Robotics Sportster modem that came with my Dell
system.
</P>
<P>
   However, when I dialed up my Internet provider _ which just
recently upgraded from K56flex to v.90 _ I got a blistering 52K
connection, the fastest of the three I tried. With AOL, I only
managed to get 37.3K.
</P>
<P>
   Downloading the 17-megabyte file via my Internet provider was
slower than with the other modems, averaging about 32.8K a second.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Supra Express 56K _ $100, Diamond Multimedia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Diamond's Supra Express is an excellent modem, a midrange
product that's fast and reliable. At least, once I got it installed
in my computer.
</P>
<P>
   First, it installed to the wrong communications port, grabbing
COM1 away from the serial port in my machine. I had to fiddle with
my Dell's BIOS settings to set things straight.
</P>
<P>
   Windows also wanted to randomly reinstall the drivers for the
Supra on bootup, as though I just plugged it into my machine.
Eventually I got this behavior to stop by downloading Diamond's
latest drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The Supra made 24K and 26.4K connections to the older modem, and
50K connections to my Internet provider. It's interesting that the
Supra did not do as well as the U.S. Robotics modem, because my
provider upgraded from the K56flex standard, which the Supra
supports, while the U.S. Robotics mode supports X2.
</P>
<P>
   When connecting to AOL, the Supra achieved 44K. And the Supra
was the downloading champion, with speeds of 37.6K.
</P>
<P>
   This was the only modem I tried that came with built-in
voice-mail capabilities. The voice software that comes with it is
rudimentary _ a better choice is the latest version of TalkWorks
from Symantec.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Accura Internal Data/Fax v.90 _ $119, Hayes Microcomputer
Products. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; It's been 20 years since Hayes designed the PC modem still in
use today, but the company has fallen on hard times. It recently
filed for its second bankruptcy in five years.
</P>
<P>
   For purely sentimental reasons, I was really pulling for the
Accura to kick some kilobutt, but alas, it turned in the worst
performance of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Supra, the Accura gave me problems with installation.
Windows tried to redetect it several times before finally settling
down.
</P>
<P>
   The Accura could only connect to the 28.8K modem at 19.2K,
sometimes ekeing out a piddling 16.8K. It connected to both my
Internet service provider and AOL at 44K, but its download speed
was 36.8K, placing second behind the Supra.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that there are many variables to modem performance
and that these results should serve only as a basic guide. Putting
the same cards in your computer and connecting to different
Internet providers could have dramatically different results.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Got a comment or question about computing? Send e-mail to
dwight.silverman at chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
