<HEADLINE>
INTERESTING, GRIM, NOT ENTIRELY SUCCESSFUL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WUTHERING HEIGHTS Starring: Robert Cavanah, Orla Brady On: PBS,
Ch. 2 Time: Sunday at 9 p.m. Rated: TVPG
</P>
<P>
   The unadulterated passion of Emily Bronte's prose, along with
the astute direction of William Wyler, inspired one of the most
full-bodied performances of Laurence Olivier's long career. As the
passionate Heathcliff in Wyler's 1939 adaptation of ``Wuthering
Heights,'' Olivier managed to be as stormy and lovely and desolate
as the Yorkshire moors he wandered. His perverse scowl, the ghostly
fire in his eyes, his noble aspect, all projected the movie's
hugely romantic mood.
</P>
<P>
   The latest version of the Bronte classic, presented on
``Masterpiece Theatre'' Sunday night at 9, is far less
traditionally romantic, with a Heathcliff whose anger and fixation
have a decidedly ugly aspect. As played by Robert Cavanah, this
Heathcliff is not just brooding and desperate about a love doomed
to find its satisfaction only in death. He is thornier and more
complicated, by turns amoral, vindictive, violent, and withholding,
and at moments physically unattractive in his twisted contempt for
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Cavanah's unappealing Heathcliff helps to make this ``Wuthering
Heights'' an interestingly grim, if not entirely successful,
adaptation. He's a compellingly dark hero to watch, although you
don't quite feel his tragedy. While the movie contains all the
hyped-up melodrama you'd expect from Bronte's story, with lots of
crying out about the heart and the soul, and with Cathy making
pronouncements like ``I am Heathcliff,' it has very little of the
greatness and righteousness you hope to find in a portrait of a
love bursting at the seams. No one appears to like, never mind
love, anyone else, and even the critical, central relationship
between Cathy and Heathcliff is never fully established before they
are pulled apart. It's assumed. It doesn't help that Orla Brady
never quite captures Cathy's fragility.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Masterpiece Theatre'' adaptation is also unusual in its
loyalty to the plotting of the novel, with the Cathy-Heathcliff
story giving way to the drama of their children. This
multigenerational aspect adds a sense of welcome resolution to the
story, even if it feels a little crammed into the two-hour time
slot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
