<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-AUTHOR-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR OF BREAST-CANCER BOOK SAYS REDUCING RISKS BEGINS AT DINNER
TABLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BARBARA KARKABI 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Bob Arnot, chief medical correspondent for NBC News, likes
to describe himself as a ``knowledge engineer'' _ someone who finds
cutting-edge research that has immediate benefit on people's lives.
</P>
<P>
   It's a role he relishes and enjoys.
</P>
<P>
   But when his mother-in-law developed breast cancer and his wife
asked him what she could do to keep from getting breast cancer, the
ever-genial Arnot was at a loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her the standard risk factors, like early periods and
late menopause, the age you have children,'' he said. ``Of course,
I reminded her about breast self-exams and mammograms for early
detection. But beyond that, I thought, there was nothing else she
could really do.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not the answer that Courtney Arnot wanted to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife told me: `Is that all you have to say? You don't have
any idea? Look, you are a medical reporter, you are a doctor,
figure it out.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Her challenge sent Arnot on a journey of discovery that resulted
in his latest book, ``The Breast Cancer Prevention Diet: The
Powerful Foods, Supplements and Drugs That Can Save Your Life''
(Little Brown and Co., $24).
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect to find that much, I thought I would putter
around,'' Arnot said. ``And then I found literally thousands of
articles on soy, for instance, and other foods and how they can be
used to help prevent breast cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough in ``chemoprevention'' _ treating cancer by
preventing it from forming in the first place _ came last spring,
Arnot said, when the drug tamoxifen was shown to cut the risk of
developing breast cancer in high-risk women by 45 percent. Less
than a month later, he said, the drug raloxifene was shown to
decrease the risk by 79 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The total amount of estrogen you are exposed to over a
lifetime is associated with the greatest risk,'' Arnot said. ``We
see estrogen as the fuel that causes breast cancer to grow. We
don't know what causes it or what triggers it. But we do know that
the breast is loaded with estrogen receptors and when too much
estrogen reaches these receptors, the potentially cancerous cells
can grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Tamoxifen and raloxifene are successful because they can block
estrogen from reaching the breast, Arnot said. But both have side
effects, though raloxifene's appear to be less, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the women I interviewed for the book and most I run
into tell me, `Look, those are the drugs and that's nice to have
them, but I'm not going to take them,' '' he said. ``Their attitude
was: `I'm young and I don't have the breast cancer gene. I don't
want to take drugs _ what else can I do?' ''
</P>
<P>
   For those not taking the drugs or those who want to do more, the
good news is that there are specific foods that also can block the
estrogen pathway, Arnot said. Among them are soy and flaxseed.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics show Chinese women, who eat more soy in their diet
than American women, have 80 percent less breast cancer than
Americans. Arnot and his family now start their day with a soy
shake, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Flaxseeds can be ground and added to orange juice, yogurt and
salads. The recommended doses are 35 to 60 grams of soy or 25 grams
of flaxseed a day.
</P>
<P>
   Other recommendations Arnot makes in his book:
</P>
<P>
   Eat healthier fats. Avoid omega-6 fats or the polyunsaturated
fats found in most vegetable oil or minerals. A recent study
reported that polyunsaturated fats increase a woman's risk of
breast cancer by 69 percent. Include small amounts of ``healthy''
fats in your diet such as omega-3 fats, found in fish, and omega-9
fats, found in olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Eat cruciferous vegetables, like broccoli, cabbage and
cauliflower.
</P>
<P>
   Decrease upper-body obesity by losing weight.
</P>
<P>
   Eat more fiber. Fiber interrupts most steps of the estrogen
pathway, he said. Strive for 35-60 grams of fiber a day _ beans and
high fiber cereals are good sources, but increase fiber slowly, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Limit alcohol consumption.
</P>
<P>
   Exercise four hours a week. Try to get within 12 pounds of your
ideal weight.
</P>
<P>
   Arnot recommends different approaches for premenopausal and
postmenopausal women and breast cancer survivors. His book also
includes sample meal plans from Asian and Mediterrean diets, both
of which have demonstrated effectiveness in preventing breast
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a changing strategy as your risk changes and your age
changes,'' Arnot said. ``Any time you go from diet as a supplement
or diet with specific foods as medicine, you should go over it
carefully with your doctor or someone in a cancer-prevention center
to make sure you are making the right moves.''
</P>
<P>
   Sally Scroggs, a registered dietitian and nutrition counselor in
Houston, agrees that individual counseling is important.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot coming out on diet and prevention and it's an
exciting place to be,'' said Scroggs, who works with the University
of Texas M.D. Anderson Cancer Center's department of clinical
cancer prevention. ``I would love to work with people so they can
interpret from the book what is appropriate for their needs. The
latest research shows that 33 percent to 50 percent of breast
cancer is preventable by diet.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnot said his basic strategy is: If it's something you can do
now as part of a preventive-health program, why not?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know it's not going to hurt you, and there's some pretty
strong evidence that it could help,'' he said. ``It may be 10-15
years before someone has done all the soy studies and fish-oil
studies and so on. But we have a lot of good, safe data. It's a bet
we're making at our house.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
