<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-MODULATIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HUMANIZING LOOK AT MUSIC OF MACHINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MODULATIONS
</P>
<P>
   A documentary by: Iara Lee
</P>
<P>
   At: Kendall Square
</P>
<P>
   Unrated
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen ninety-seven was the year the mainstream music press
decided to anoint electronica as the next big thing, and despite
success by Prodigy, Chemical Brothers, and Crystal Method, most
people reacted with a shrug. But it didn't matter _ not to the
scores of beat-crazy club kids or the turntable messiahs who find
religion in the uncommon rhythms generated when man lays hands on
machine.
</P>
<P>
   Electronica _ that already-tired catchall label _ existed long
before magazines decided to make Prodigy's Keith Flint a cover boy.
This particular art of noise is celebrated in Iara Lee's
fascinating ``Modulations,'' which traces the evolution of
electronic music from Luigi Russolo's promotion of industrial noise
in 1913 to the modern sounds of ambient, techno, and house cranking
it up in clubs from San Francisco to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic music pioneer John Cage is featured in archival
footage, but the film concentrates on technology's influence on pop
music from disco to hip-hop to jazz. It won't matter if you can't
tell nasty ghetto house from Detroit techno or ambient, a naked
penguin scratch from a crab scratch. Lee's film should appeal to
tech-heads and neophytes alike, as she makes the point that
electronic music has always been with us and continues to be one of
the most creative forces in music today.
</P>
<P>
   For the purveyors of electronic music, every sounds pulses with
rhythmic potential. Electronic producer Tetsu Inoue records a host
of sounds, from those of washing a glass to the hum of a microwave,
all to use on later productions. Writer David Toop says electronic
music is ``a direct reflection of the environment,'' and Lee's film
proves he's right.
</P>
<P>
   But the film is more than just a scientific dissection of the
music. It explores convincingly, say, how techno, the beat-heavy
dance music popularized in the late 1980s and early 1990s, became
the sound of Detroit. The city's black youth, still struggling with
the 1960s legacy of riots and unrest, sought to create music that
recalled the unrest, even as the blips and beeps elevated the music
to a type of space symphony.
</P>
<P>
   Lee also captures the energy of the music and its devotees. It's
impossible not to get swept into the moment as Afrika Bambaataa's
classic ``Planet Rock,'' which borrowed from and deconstructed the
work of German electronic music pioneers Kraftwerk, pumps into a
packed dance club.
</P>
<P>
   And the film hails Robert Moog, inventor of the Moog
synthesizer, and Giorgio Moroder, whose work with Donna Summer in
the 1970s, particularly on her hypnotic hit, ``I Feel Love,''
revolutionized and realized the potential of music made with
machines.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the film's greatest asset is giving electronica its
rightful place in the music pantheon, proving that music made with
machines is not necessarily devoid of human passions or spiritual
release.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
