<P>
   CONGRESS-RECORD _ WASHINGTON _ This 105th Congress has been
compared to the ``Do-Nothing'' 85th Congress excoriated by
President Harry Truman in 1948. But as it leaves town, the 105th
Congress left behind a record of major decisions that most
Americans liked. The five-year budget-balancing agreement and the
gigantic tax-cut package adopted by this Congress in 1997 seem to
be working. This year, Congress overwhelmingly adopted legislation
overhauling the IRS, providing multi-year funding for highways and
mass transit, and making major repairs in two troubled programs --
low-income housing and job-training. Perhaps its least-noticed
accomplishment will be restraint: It passed fewer laws than any
Congress in recent history and avoided divisive party-line splits
during this year's preparations for next year's efforts to repair
Social Security. (Mollison, Cox News Service 700).
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-MAJORITY _ WASHINGTON _ If Republicans increase their
Senate majority to 60 seats in the 106th Congress, President
Clinton could find himself under more pressure to use his veto
power even as he defends himself in an impeachment trial. Without
the 41 votes needed to sustain a Senate filibuster, the Democrats'
ability to block legislation or force compromises would be
weakened. History shows that such situations can lead to a high
number of presidential vetoes. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
