<DOCNO> NYT19981016.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 15:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1285 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-SETTLERS-1017     10-16 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SETTLERS-1017-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAELI SETTLERS KEEP THE HEAT ON NETANYAHU, U.S.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Through protests here and calls on their American
friends, Israeli settler leaders are attempting to make sure Israel
takes a tough stand in the talks this weekend at Maryland's Wye
Plantation.
</P>
<P>
   Long opposed to the Oslo peace process and controversial in
their own country, settler leaders do not want the land around
their neighborhoods turned over to Yasser Arafat's Palestinian
National Authority. If it must be, they say, Arafat must step up
his fight against terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all due respect to the American policy, we are not
willing to sit here and pay the price in blood . . . to boost
President Clinton's standing in American politics,'' Yehudit Tayar,
spokeswoman for the settler association, YESHA, said from her
Washington hotel Friday.
</P>
<P>
   YESHA spent three days meeting with American supporters and
sympathetic officials in U.S. Congress ahead of the Middle East
summit.
</P>
<P>
   Currently in Maryland, Clinton wants Netanyahu to withdraw
Israeli troops from another 13 percent of the West Bank, a
Palestinian area captured by Israel since the Six Day War of 1967.
American officials have also pleaded, along with Arafat, that
Israel stop settlement expansion.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Arafat is being asked to agree to a tight schedule of
steps for fighting anti-Israeli terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   A newspaper poll this Friday showed that 57 percent of Israelis
favor the 13 percent plan. But, the hard-line settlers are among
the best organized and vocal of Israeli interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   Settlers backed Netanyahu, who himself used to oppose Oslo.
Together, they have been successful in slowing down the Oslo
process. Now, the settlers threaten to topple him if he concedes
too much in what they see as an American political show.
</P>
<P>
   They look to members of Congress, especially Republicans, who
have often supported both the settlers and Netanyahu in their tense
relations with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Settlers fear that their neighborhoods, many resembling
condominium developments with with schools and stores, could end up
isolated if Arafat gets more land. Israel has already pulled out of
Palestinian population centers.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, settlers blocked a West Bank road in protest after
Palestinian police reportedly beat two settlement security guards
who had chased rock-throwing youth into Palestinian territory.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1967, Israeli leaders have authorized the construction of
more than 140 settlements, housing about 170,000 people, in the
West Bank. They are spread in a pattern that makes it impossible
for the Palestinians to get a solid block of territory.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Israeli group, Peace Now, about 3,000 new
housing units have been started in the last 17 months, even while
nearly as many units are already vacant.
</P>
<P>
   The Geneva Convention says countries should not move their
population into occupied territories unless it is necessary for
security.
</P>
<P>
   Settlers say their neighborhoods provide a buffer between Israel
and hostile neighbors, but others here say many provide no security
benefit. The Israeli government provides tax breaks and other
benefits to settlers.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. President George Bush withheld loans to Israel when
he suspected American aid was used to finance settlement
construction.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
