<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLOT-NAME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATE MIFFED THAT HER CHINESE NAME WAS OMITTED FROM BALLOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A candidate for president of the Board of
Supervisors criticized election officials for omitting her Chinese
name from absentee ballots, claiming it could cost her thousands of
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Mabel Teng's Chinese name, as well as the
transliterated Chinese names of six other candidates for local
offices, were omitted from thousands of absentee ballots already
sent out citywide. All other local candidates had their names
properly translated into Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Teng's campaign manager threatened to sue the election officials
if corrected ballots were not sent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the only Chinese incumbent running for re-election. How
can my (Chinese) name be missing from the ballot?'' Teng said
Thursday during a news conference in Chinatown.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi Nishioka, director of the Department of Elections, said
the omission was not an error. Although Chinese and Spanish
translation of occupations and other designations on the ballot is
required, translation of names is an optional service offered by
her department. The only other time it was done was the 1995
mayoral race.
</P>
<P>
   She said Teng's campaign was called twice to ask whether the
candidate wanted her name printed in Chinese on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone from my staff called her again and said, `Are you sure
you don't want your name translated because most of the other
candidates are doing it,''' Nishioka said. ``We were told by her
campaign managers that they didn't wish to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   John Whitehurst, Teng's campaign manager, said it was thought
the question referred to the candidate statement in the voter
information pamphlet, not the ballot itself.
</P>
<P>
   Teng demanded that new absentee booklets be printed and sent out
with a corrective letter to those who have received the faulty
ones. Whitehurst said a lawsuit would be filed if proper steps were
not taken to remedy the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Every vote is critical in an election where Teng is seen as
running neck-and-neck with Supervisor Tom Ammiano for board
presidency. Past races for the board presidency have hinged on just
a few hundred votes.
</P>
<P>
   Nishioka said it was too late to reprint booklets; 100,000 have
been printed and 47,000 have been sent out. However, she said
Chinese voter information pamphlets, which are requested by 13,000
voters, would contain the Chinese names.
</P>
<P>
   But Teng said her concern was not merely political.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this situation is not corrected by the Department of
Elections, Chinese voters _ many of them new immigrants, many
registered for the first time _ will be disenfranchised,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
