<HEADER>
A1315 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JETS-MARTIN-BOS &LR;      10-16 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JETS-MARTIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURTIS MARTIN SAYS HE HAS NO SECOND THOUGHTS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ The memories are of Curtis Martin sitting by
his locker, next to Jimmy Hitchcock or Corwin Brown or Sam Gash,
sitting in the Patriots' locker room, always willing to talk in
that soft and gentle voice. In time, especially if the crowd around
him was small, Martin would open up.
</P>
<P>
   But now it all looked and felt and seemed so strange. There was
Martin sitting in the small media room at Hofstra University, a
microphone in front of him, banks of videocams focused on his face
... and most of all, that Jets cap on his head. This was not a
setting to draw out the inner feelings of a football player;
details were few from Martin's mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said Martin. ``I definitely have no second thoughts
about leaving (the Patriots). I'm very appreciative and grateful
for where I'm at, and that's my attitude. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   No, not a ``period,'' definitely not. This situation, and
whatever is said about it _ whether the Jets or the Patriots are
better off since Martin left New England for New York as a
restricted free agent _ can be followed only by a question mark.
Even if the first answers will be coming Monday night when the
teams meet at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a lot of excitement,'' said Martin when
asked what he expects when he trots onto the Foxboro Stadium turf
for the first time in a Jets uniform. ``It'll be a lot of fun. It's
definitely something that I'm looking forward to. Of course,
there's more feeling and emotional meaning to it because of the
rivalry that has developed.''
</P>
<P>
   The ground rules for the mass interview were laid down by the
Jets. No questions about injuries. So Martin could not be asked
about his strained quadriceps or the 30 or so times he carried the
ball after letting his coaches know he had been nicked in the first
quarter of the Miami game two weeks ago. Martin remained in the
game but missed last week's game against St. Louis. He most likely
will play against New England.
</P>
<P>
   When the New York media asked Bill Parcells after the Miami game
if he were concerned about preserving Martin's body for the
duration of the season, the coach gave a most Parcellsian response:
``I'm not in the preservation business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of expect all of that,'' replied Martin when asked if
he figured New England fans would cheer him, boo him, or throw
things at him. ``I don't know whether they'll cheer or boo. That's
not going to be my focus. I'm going there to play ball.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the fans do, said Martin, just being on the oh so
familiar Foxboro turf will be comfortable since ``you know you're
used to running on that field. You're used to that crowd. It's
definitely somewhere where I'm used to playing. But it'll be
playing as the ... uh ... enemy ... versus being on that side.''
</P>
<P>
   Did he think the Foxborough fans might be as rough on him as
they were last year when Parcells made his first return and heard a
mixture of cheers and boos?
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I said, I don't know ... I don't know exactly how it'll
be,'' said Martin. ``I'm expecting all different kinds of things.
But I'm not really worried about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's mother, Rochella, already is on record as saying that
she had a mother-son chat about Martin's getting booed in
Foxborough. ``It's not going to affect Curt,'' Rochella Martin told
the New York Daily News, ``but I'm not going to lie to you. I'm
going to be fired up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets running back, of course, was one of the more beloved
Patriots, both by the fans in the stands and his teammates in the
locker room. Martin did concede that playing against New England
``will be a good thing; it'll be like playing against a lot of your
friends. That's always something that gets you extra pumped up,
playing against people that you know ... personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, personally.
</P>
<P>
   Few fans in New England need to be reminded that the owner of
the New England Patriots and the coach of the New York Jets are
obsessed with each other. Parcells thought he had weakened the
Patriots considerably by stealing Martin from New England in free
agency, then sending last year's solid running back, Adrian
Murrell, to the Cardinals with the proviso that Arizona would not
send Murrell to New England.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots countered by using the draft pick the Jets had to
give up for signing Martin to select running back Robert Edwards in
the draft. Five games into one season do not provide an accurate
gauge of those moves by the Jets and the Patriots _ only years will
tell the full story _ but so far, it is owner Bob Kraft and the New
England coaches wearing the wide smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a gaping void at running back with the loss of the
elusive Martin, the Patriots have a different style with Edwards _
an aggressive power runner who has been delivering more and more in
each game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a different take when you're on the outside
looking in versus being in the situation,'' said Martin when asked
about his move from Foxborough to New York. ``It's your decision.
You have to realize it's your life. It's not everyone else's life
for me to live. You know, I have to live my life and do what I have
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's mother also told the Daily News that it was she, not
her son, who lobbied for Martin to leave the Patriots. ``It was
time to take another route and I told him to go,'' Martin's mother
said. ``I made the decision; I'm sure it was a tossup for him, but
we sat down and thought about it, and the best choice was for him
to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to elaborate on why he left the Patriots, Martin said, ``I
just felt it was a great situation for myself. Bill and the
coaching staff here ... (running backs coach) Maurice Carthon ...
it was definitely a great opportunity for me to be back with the
coaches I came into the NFL with. That played a great role in it.
That influenced me more than any other situation would have.''
</P>
<P>
   With no dominant quarterback, the expectations for Martin here
were that he might carry much of the offense. That was never his
role with the Patriots _ the New England passing and running games
were true complements _ and his effectiveness in New York will be
directly related to whether the Jets ever get their QB situation
settled and put together a threatening passing game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the type of player that no matter what, no matter if I was
having my best year ever, would think it was good enough right
now,'' said Martin. ``But being that's not the case so far, that's
definitely not good enough for me. I believe _ and hopefully, it'll
happen _ that things will get much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially Monday night. For Martin remembers the circus and
hoopla and hype from Tuna Bowl I in Foxborough last year ``when I
had that feeling that it was like playing against your brother.
Parcells was the coach and many of us liked him, but when he came
(back to New England), many of us wanted to make sure we'd win.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin did so, gaining 199 yards to save the Patriots from
themselves in a 27-24 overtime victory.
</P>
<P>
   And now Martin will be the centerpiece of Monday's revival of
the New York-New England jihad. ``You're pumped up for every game,
but there are certain games ... there are certain situations where
it's different,'' said Martin. ``Such as this game. It has formed
into a rivalry. I've been talking to some of the guys (on the
Patriots) and I've been saying, `It's been fun to play with you and
now it'll be fun to play against you.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
