<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-MIGHTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``MIGHTY'' BOND BETWEEN UNLIKELY FRIENDS INSPIRES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE MIGHTY &QC; 
Directed by: Peter Chelsom &QC; 
Screenplay by: Charles Leavitt (based on Rodman Philbrick's novel,
``Freak the Mighty'') &QC; 
Starring: Sharon Stone, Gena Rowlands, Harry Dean Stanton, Gillian
Anderson, James Gandolfini, Kieran Culkin, Eldon Henson, Meat Loaf,
Joe Perrino, Jennifer Lewis &QC; 
Running time: 107 minutes &QC; 
Rated: PG-13 (elements of violence and peril) &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufbitelabel &LR; MovieReview
</P>
<P>
   A screenful of offbeat elements come together soaringly in ``The
Mighty,'' a film that rides the simpatico chemistry of its two
young stars _ El-H den Henson's schoolboy hulk, hiding a sensitive,
traumatized soul beneath a numbed exterior, and Kieran Culkin's
bold, brainy spirit in a body crunched and twisted by a bone
disorder known as Morquio syndrome. They meet and bond after the
bright little kid is assigned to tutor and improve the reading
skills of the slow, inhibited bigger kid next door.
</P>
<P>
   It's a short jump from their joint traversal of the legend of
King Arthur and the Knights of the Round Table to their
idealistically setting forth on a round of noble adventures in
their shabby south Cincinnati neighborhood and in even shabbier
Covington, Ky., just across the Ohio River. With Culkin's Kevin
sitting atop the shoulders of Hen-H son's Max, supplying ideas and
direction while Max supplies the strength and legs, they settle for
taming bullies instead of slaying dragons, and re- turning a stolen
purse in lieu of rescuing a lady in distress.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -------------------- &LR;  Director Peter Chelsom expands upon the
originality he displayed in ``Funny Bones'' and ``Hear My Song,''
making the most of the novelty of the Cincinnati setting, then
exchanging gritty realism for magic realism, with inserts of the
imaginary knights momentarily appearing in vi- sionary ways.
Culkin, sparrow-bright beneath his spectacles, easily convinces us
he has long ago ac- quired the knack of using his mind to propel
him- self out of his hammered little body, while the bulky,
buzz-cut Henson is convincingly gentle.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Stone takes a back seat to the spotlit boys as Kevin's
fiercely loving, hardscrabble sin- gle mother. But she makes every
moment of her  &UR; -------------------- &LR;  screen time count in a smart,
edgy, feeling perfor- mance worthy of a best supporting actress
Oscar, not only touching us with what we see in her eyes and never
is verbalized, but supplying in every gesture the socioeconomic
underpinning the story needs to anchor it and keep it from seeming
sus- pended in a nebulous realm of fable. Deglamor-H ized and
scoured clean of all vestiges of her femme fatale roles, Stone
convinces as a woman who has spent her life in worn-out places, and
has taken more than her share of hits, but isn't about to give up.
</P>
<P>
   Gena Rowlands and Harry Dean Stanton are rock-solid as Max's
kindly American Gothic L grandparents, James Gandolfini delivers
the kind of lowlife menace as Max's psychopathic escaped jailbird
dad that reinforces the film's Huck-Tom dimension, and Gillian
Armstrong neatly sidesteps the pitfalls of her heart-of-gold broken
blossom role. Only at the end does sentimental manipulati-H veness
spill over into obviousness. Even so, ``The Mighty'' earns its
responses and will get to a wide range of moviegoers, much as the
underrated but similar and similarly affecting ``Simon Birch'' has.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el3 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This is an expanded version of the review pub- lished here when
this film premiered at the Boston Film Festival.
</P>
