<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1327 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT17-COX     10-16 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT TRIAL HOLDS HUGE STAKES FOR INDUSTRY, CONSUMERS
 &HT;    900&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's being called the antitrust trial of the
decade, pitting the Justice Department and 20 state attorneys
general against Microsoft Corp., the world's leading software
company.
</P>
<P>
   When the Microsoft trial opens here Monday, in the same federal
courthouse where a grand jury probing the White House sex scandal
still sits, the stakes for the future of the computer industry
could prove every bit as large as the impeachment trauma facing
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   While predictions are risky in the fast-paced digital age, a
Microsoft victory would likely further tighten the software giant's
grip on the personal computer world. But if the government lawsuit
succeeds, both businesses and consumers could end up with many more
individual choices on their desktops as Microsoft's vast powers
wane.
</P>
<P>
   The government charges that Microsoft has leveraged its Windows
operating system monopoly into new markets by outbidding the
competition for third-party takeovers, by taking over the
competition directly, by giving away products the competition
sought to sell for a profit, and by hiring away the competition's
best minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than competing legitimately and on the merits,
Microsoft has resorted to predatory and anticompetitive agreements
and conduct,'' the prosecutors wrote in a pre-trial summary of the
case.
</P>
<P>
   On an NBC news special about Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates that
aired in 1995, the company's president, Steve Ballmer, voiced the
firm's take-no-prisoners approach toward its rivals _ an approach
the prosecution plans to highlight in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys can be taken,'' Ballmer said. ``'But the only way
we're going to take them is by studying them. Know what they know.
Do what they do. Watch them, watch them, watch them. Look for every
angle. Stay on their shoulders. Clone them. Take every one of their
good ideas and make it one of our good ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   The government's brief cites a comment by Ruthann Quindlen, a
Silicon Valley venture capitalist who helped take Microsoft public
in 1986. After learning of the areas that Microsoft regards as
off-limits to other innovators, she noted at a recent investment
forum: ``I guess that leaves us washing machines or toasters.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Justice brought its case in May, the appeals court
found that U.S. District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson had
erred in an earlier related case that revolved around Windows 95.
In that case, the higher court said Jackson should not have
second-guessed Microsoft's decision to bundle its Internet Explorer
browser within Windows.
</P>
<P>
   With that ruling in mind, the prosecutors restructured their
brief away from the firm's alleged mistreatment of Netscape
Communications Corp. to allege _ based on an 1890 statute _ that
Microsoft had engaged in a broad series of illegal acts to protect
its Windows monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Each side is limited to 14 witnesses in the case, which is
expected to last eight weeks. The government plans to call key
players at Apple Computer Co., America Online Inc., IBM, Intel
Corp., Intuit Corp. and Sun Microsystems Inc. The star witness for
the prosecution, however, will be James Barksdale, president and
chairman of Netscape, Microsoft's longstanding rival in the browser
wars.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's briefs, however, argue that it was Netscape's poor
strategic policies that have caused its recent fiscal woes. With
the case virtually certain to be appealed clear to the Supreme
Court, the defense team will seek to establish a factual record
that Microsoft had never sought to persuade Netscape to ``divide
the market'' for Web browsing software.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the 12 initial defense witnesses are key Microsoft
employees. Before the trial concludes, Jackson, who will try the
case without a jury, will hear testimony from two further defense
witnesses whose identities have not been disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft does not plan to call Gates. But videotaped pretrial
testimony by the firm's co-founder and the world's richest man will
likely be injected into the trial.
</P>
<P>
   John Rose, a senior vice president and group general manager for
</P>
<P>
   enterprise computing at Compaq, will also testify on behalf of
the software giant. Houston-based Compaq is known in the trade as
an OEM, or original equipment manufacturer, and it sells units
pre-loaded with Microsoft's browser, initially programmed to pop up
as the users' first screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's curious that the government hasn't called an OEM
if they think OEMs have been unduly harmed and influenced,'' said
Jonathan Zuck, executive director of the Association for
Competitive Technology in Washington. The association, an advocacy
group of about 200 computer-related companies, argues that the
computer industry is best left unregulated.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors, however, want Microsoft to grant OEM's unfettered
control of what should appear on a buyer's first screen. They also
want Microsoft to sever its exclusionary contracts with Internet
content and service providers.
</P>
<P>
   At a midweek meeting of key Microsoft purchasers in Orlando,
Gates said the case has had little effect on his company so far.
``There's no change in what we are doing in terms of the focus _
the product design or any of that _ that has been brought about by
that matter,'' Gates said.
</P>
<P>
   And he predicted that his company's aggressive business
practices would survive the antitrust scrutiny. ``We are very
confident _ particularly with the clear criteria that the appeals
court has laid down (in an earlier case) _ that that kind of
innovation is a great thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Which side prevails in this stage of the legal battle may rest
on how Jackson weighs Microsoft's intent.
</P>
<P>
   What motivated Microsoft to incorporate its Internet Explorer
browser into the Windows 95 operating system, and Windows 98, its
successor? Were these true business decisions, rooted in the notion
that the firm's customers sought an integrated product? Or were
they aimed at harming Netscape?
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers recognize that, under the antitrust laws, the same set
of actions could be deemed legal or illegal, depending on
underlying motives.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, current Windows code, used in 97 per cent of
personal computers currently being shipped, is so tightly
interwoven with the browser that the operating system would fail if
they were to be pulled apart.
</P>
<P>
   So software engineers recognize that any adverse legal outcome
for Microsoft would not easily lend itself to a quick fix _ short
of spinning Windows off into a regulated digital utility, a drastic
remedy that the government has so far rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it hard to believe you can have a case where a company
is found to have violated the law, but there's nothing you can do
about it,'' says Robert Bork, a former federal appeals' court judge
who serves as a consultant to Netscape for the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Microsoft wins this case,'' says William Kovacic of George
Mason University Law School, ``you're going to see a major retreat
in the Justice Department's willingness to bring future antitrust
cases.''
</P>
<P>
   In the run-up to the trial, the government has argued that,
should it prevail, Microsoft could be forced to include the
Netscape browser in Windows. But Kovacic believes that even such an
outcome would, in the end, serve only to further bolster Microsoft.
``It will be seen as delivering magic beans for the cow,'' he
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
