<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL SHOWS LIBERAL DEMOCRAT LOSING GROUND IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a race so tight it may not be decided until
the last votes are counted, a survey released Friday shows Sen.
Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., losing by a razor-thin margin to state
Treasurer Matt Fong.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, commissioned by the San Francisco Examiner KTVU-TV,
shows that for the first time in the campaign more voters view
Boxer negatively than positively. Political analysts say that could
be an electoral kiss of death for the liberal incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the voters are saying is, they don't like you
personally,'' said Del Ali of Mason-Dixon Political/Media Research
of Columbia, Md., which conducted the poll.
</P>
<P>
   Ali said there was little chance voters would change their view
on Boxer, who served in the House before her election to the Senate
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But the poll showed a race still too close to call. Fong, a
Republican, was favored among likely voters 46 percent to 44
percent _ a statistical dead heat because of the poll's margin of
error of plus or minus 3.5 percentage points. Ten percent of those
surveyed were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also showed that Boxer is favored by more women. The
gender gap, however, was much less pronounced than Boxer's 1992
campaign, when 60 percent of women voters cast ballots for her.
</P>
<P>
   Fong and Boxer were running neck-and-neck in the Los Angeles
metro area, a traditional Democratic stronghold. Boxer remains
strong in the liberal San Francisco Bay area, but Fong led in the
Central Valley, the San Diego area and Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   Despite two debates and increasing media coverage of the race,
one-third of voters still have no opinion about Fong. Still, the
poll shows Fong has the support of 81 percent of Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone poll of 820 registered California voters was
conducted Oct. 11-13. All who were questioned said they regularly
vote in state elections.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Democratic political consultant Gale Kaufman said the numbers,
while not encouraging for Boxer, did not signal the race was over.
She said Fong's rise in support was the result of Republicans
finally lining up behind the lesser-known candidate before the Nov.
3 election.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a traditional hardening of positions before the
election,'' Kaufman said. ``I don't think this is the end of the
world. As in any race, the critical weeks are now.''
</P>
<P>
   But the poll shows the momentum belongs to Fong.
</P>
<P>
   In an Examiner poll in February, Boxer had a nine-point edge in
a match against Fong. By May, it was a five-point edge. By July, a
three-point lead. The last poll, taken in September, showed the
race tied. The new poll marks the first time Fong has moved ahead.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, political observers have described the election as
less a battle with Fong than a referendum on Boxer. Indeed, the
poll cast doubts on Boxer's popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-three percent of those surveyed had an unfavorable opinion
of her, while 42 percent viewed her favorably.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Crigler, director of the Jesse Unruh School of Politics at
the University of Southern California, said Boxer's unfavorable
rating is the result of several factors, including her advertising
campaign that attacks Fong.
</P>
<P>
   ``For one, the race is coming closer to conclusion and people
are making up their minds'' about the candidates, Crigler said.
``Also, she's seen as in the Clinton camp and that may be rubbing
off on her. And part of it is that she's running negative ads. When
people run negative ads, their negatives also go up with their
opponents'.''
</P>
<P>
   Fong, however, has avoided attack ads and has promoted a
moderate image.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Fong has needed to do is to wake up, smile, shake hands
with people and say as little as possible,'' said Allan Hoffenblum,
a Republican political consultant in Los Angeles. ``The results are
paying off very nicely.''
</P>
</TEXT>
