</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981016.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1373 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEX-OFFENDERS-3TAKES-     10-16 1791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-OFFENDERS-3TAKES-ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    SEX-OFFENDERS-3TAKES-$ADV18 
 
ONE CRIME, TWO BROKEN AND RUINED 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 18) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.A. DYER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   The names in this story have been changed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Conner was 9 years old, an insecure kid with dyslexia, when
a teacher offered him the most powerful words in the English
language: I love you.
</P>
<P>
   Then he reached for the boy's crotch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `Stop, it's nasty,' '' recalled the boy. ``Mr. O
said, `Oh, come on' and just kept doing it. I just thought he is an
older person, and I have to do what he says.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan was sexually assaulted by 59-year-old Richard O'Leary over
the course of several months in 1989 and 1990. Eventually, the
teacher confessed to the crime and was given a 10-year probationary
sentence. As part of that, O'Leary underwent years of therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, Ryan Conner remains horribly scarred: He
believes the assaults affected his views on sex, women and
authority figures. And he says that justice has not been done, that
O'Leary deserved long imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, O'Leary expresses tortured remorse for his
crimes, but says counseling has taught him self-control. He says
his punishment was correct. Never again, O'Leary insists, will he
harm another child.
</P>
<P>
   This crime, and tens of thousands like it, raise tough,
emotional questions. Should neighbors be alerted when a sex
offender moves next door? Should offenders be kept in jail for as
long as possible? Is the answer therapy, as O'Leary believes?
</P>
<P>
   The story of Conner and O'Leary _ the story of one crime, but
two damaged people _ can provide a human reference point for those
who consider such questions. For any answer carries a human toll:
for the pubic, for the abused, even for the offender.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1986, O'Leary began work at one of Houston's more
popular private elementary schools, where he taught science,
history and physical education. It was there _ during the early
part of the 1989 school year, probably during a climbing-wall class
_ that he met and became fixated on Conner.
</P>
<P>
   On the evening of March 12, 1991, about a year after O'Leary
left the school, three patrol officers came to his door, read him
his rights and led him away in handcuffs. He was panicked and
sobbing. The charges: two counts of aggravated sexual assault of a
minor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked, scared, crying, humiliated,'' O'Leary recalled.
``I don't know, I was just so afraid. But there was also this sense
of relief, like this is going to trigger an end to all this, one
way or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   After his arrest, O'Leary confessed to assaulting Conner, to
similarly abusing another boy years earlier and to acting
inappropriately with 11 other children since puberty. But the
statute of limitations had expired on these other acts, so O'Leary
was prosecuted only in Conner's case.
</P>
<P>
   The strictest sex offender registration and notification laws
would not have prevented these assaults, and O'Leary may never have
been arrested if Conner had not alerted his mother. The admission
came Feb. 25, 1991, a year after the assaults ended, in his
mother's car, as she drove Conner home from his therapist's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that he didn't want to tell me since I would probably
cry,'' recalled his mother. ``(Conner) had numerous nightmares that
night, waking me about every 15 to 30 minutes to tell me that he
was dreaming that Mr. (O'Leary) was going to kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   Through therapy, O'Leary says he has gained a better
understanding of his sexual compulsions. He described some of those
conclusions, and much of his life story, during hours of interviews
at his home in one of Houston's upscale enclave cities.
</P>
<P>
   Through most of it, O'Leary sat in an easy chair, his legs
crossed at the ankles. He generally spoke in soft, even tones _
except on a few occasions when he wept, or on another occasion,
when his voice rose perceptibly after acknowledging a contradiction
in his account.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary is thin, but not too tall, and walks with a shuffling
grace. With his graying hair, long face and soft voice, he reminds
one of television's Mr. Rogers. He speaks easily, rarely fumbling
with words, even at awkward moments.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary graduated from Rice University in Houston in 1953 with a
degree in philosophy and later received a theology degree from New
York's Union Theological Seminary, one of the country's best. He is
an ordained minister and worked as a minister and youth director at
two Methodist churches for the first 15 years of his career. Later,
he worked at various private schools in the Houston area.
</P>
<P>
   He is married and has four adult children (none say they were
ever victimized by their father) and six grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary said he agreed to tell his story to show that he and
others like him are not necessarily monsters.
</P>
<P>
   He can look a person in the eye, and without turning away, say,
``I'm a child molester.'' What may be even more difficult for
people to hear is this: Richard O'Leary also says he's a human
being.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my mother and father met and married, my father had just
gotten out of World War I,'' O'Leary began, choosing his words
carefully. ``But he told her he had a serious war injury and that
they could not have any sexual contact until the injury was
corrected.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary's father, however, had lied. There was no war injury.
Instead, he had syphilis, presumably contracted overseas. Although
O'Leary's mother did not divorce her husband, she nonetheless was
repulsed by him. And O'Leary's father, who eventually was cured of
syphilis, remained sexually frustrated throughout the marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so that was the home I was born into,'' said O'Leary,
recounting a story told to him by his mother shortly before her
death. ``I remember violent fights, a cold aloof woman _ repulsed
by her husband _ and those terrifying fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember going to bed at night and hearing them fight
and hearing her wail and cry and remembering hearing that he was
throwing stuff across the room _ probably at her. We were
terrified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, my father's anger and frustration would focus on my
brother and I. We got whipped by his hand, by his belt, and we got
kicked. I remember getting kicked _ that was probably the worst
punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary also said his mother could not console him _ ``There
were never any hugs and kisses'' _ and that the only love he
received was from his brother, Raymond. About a year his senior,
Raymond also was terrified by their father's frightful rages.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there was this one time I felt my father loved me,'' said
O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was about 5 years old, playfully wrestling with his
father. But as they rolled around on the bed _ laughing happily _
the play turned sexual, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a clue what was going on,'' said O'Leary. ``I
couldn't compare his behavior with any other sexual behavior,
because I didn't have any other sexual behavior to compare it with.
I didn't think it was abnormal behavior, because I didn't know what
normal was.
</P>
<P>
   ``And in my mind, I linked a man playing with a little boy _
being sexual with a little boy _ with a man loving a little boy. It
was so much better than being kicked and demeaned and whipped and
beaten with a belt. I thought my dad was loving me.''
</P>
<P>
   After that single incident _ for O'Leary recalled no other
sexual encounter with his father _ he began to ``act out sexually''
with his brother. As the family couldn't afford a big house, the
two brothers slept in the same room, in the same bed. That's where
it happened, night after night, for about five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I loved my brother, and that's the way you show
love: sexually,'' said O'Leary. ``I never forgot those sexual
experiences I had with my father and my brother. But somehow or the
other, I didn't link that with pedophile tendencies. It's odd in
retrospect.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Conner doesn't buy it. O'Leary's whole story about the
brother _ the one who witnessed this abuse first-hand, the one with
whom O'Leary supposedly engaged in incest for five years _ where is
he now? Conveniently dead. O'Leary's older brother can neither
confirm nor dispute the story because he was killed in a hunting
accident about 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And what does O'Leary's other brother _ a younger sibling still
living in Texas _ have to say? In a sworn affidavit, he says he
knows nothing of O'Leary's early childhood because he was born
seven years after his brother.
</P>
<P>
   To Conner, O'Leary is an intelligent and well-spoken con man.
How else to explain the high regard to which he was held by parents
and teachers? How else to explain the probationary sentence? And,
especially, how else to explain O'Leary's popularity with all the
little boys at the school, the boys who idolized O'Leary?
</P>
<P>
   To them, said Conner, Mr. O'Leary was like a god.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. O in that school was the man,'' he said. ``He always did
stuff that boys liked, like he would make explosions happen and he
showed us how to climb rocks. But (he wasn't popular) with the
girls so much, because the girls didn't care about seeing something
explode on the table when you mixed two chemicals together.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would even bad-mouth the girls, in front of the guys. He
would try to make himself seem like one of the guys and would try
to keep the girls away, saying this was a `guys only' lesson. Or
he'd say, `We're going to be blowing things up here, and you can't
be around.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Conner is grown now: 18 years old, ruddy good looks, thin but
athletic. He works outdoors as a boat mechanic and so has grease
beneath his nails and hair that has gone blonde from the sun. For a
youth with so many problems _ he said that he hardly left his house
for years after the sexual assaults _ Conner speaks with
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   The dyslexia that keeps him from writing clearly has not
prevented him from gaining a command of language. He can succinctly
describe his violent attacks on a classmate, or punching his fist
through a window pane, or becoming sick with anxiety upon being
called to testify against O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   He speaks of it all with lively twang, with drawn-out Texas
vowels and ``yeps'' and ``uh huhs,'' and with a bit of profanity
here and there.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one elementary school, I remember that I had a female
teacher that tried to make me do my work, and so I'd pick up
furniture _ you know, the little chairs _ and I'd throw them around
the room,'' he said, recalling the months after the assaults. ``And
at recess, if anybody tried to do anything to me, like try to take
the ball away from me, I'd end up pounding their face into the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was doing all this stuff on auto-pilot. I didn't know why I
was doing it, I just knew that I was angry. I remember being really
mad at everything, being really mad at everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Conner now attributes that anger, as well as many of his
prejudices and phobias, to O'Leary. For instance, Conner said that
O'Leary often spoke poorly of other teachers, Conner's mother
(O'Leary supposedly said she was stupid) and women in general. For
many years afterward, Conner shared those views.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, I had this weird idea that females were just
useless things and that's what (O'Leary) had instilled in me,''
Conner said. ``He gave me the impression that women were good for
one thing and one thing only (sex), and the rest of the time they
could just be locked up in the closet. You'd just pull them out
once in awhile, do your things to them, and then put them back in
the closet.''
</P>
<P>
   Conner failed the fourth grade three times, was expelled from
various schools, and for years after the assault was terrified of
removing his clothes or using public bathrooms. Even taking a bath
would sometimes prompt panic attacks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As Conner thinks back _ as he remembers the lies and the
manipulation and as he remembers O'Leary's big con _ the anger
returns. But Conner is an adult now, and he has words for his
feelings. This is what he now says about Richard O'Leary: ``I hate
him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When it snapped in my head that he was a sick, perverted wacko
_ you know, after a bunch of therapy _ and after I sat around and
thought about what the hell he was doing, and how it was totally
not normal, and how he totally violated me and other people, well,
I just didn't want to just kill him. I wanted to torture him first.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now, you know, I don't want to kill him and I don't want
to torture him. I'd still kind of like to go kick his ass a little
bit _ but I don't want to kill him. You know, I believe that
everybody has their place in this world, even if they're really
sick and twisted and disgusting. I believe they should have a
chance to make themselves better.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the alternative was years in prison, O'Leary said
deferred adjudication _ the sort of probation he received, the sort
of probation that leaves no record of conviction _ has been quite
strict.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, O'Leary is subject to the state's notification
and registration laws: He must go to police headquarters once a
year to have his photo taken and must provide his address and other
personal information to authorities every three months. Much of
that information is available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   He said the process is stressful and that if the state
institutes more restrictive notification and registration rules, he
may move when his probation ends in three years. O'Leary also said
that in his case, the public notification requirements are somewhat
irrelevant, as he already informed his friends and neighbors of the
sexual assaults.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, as a requirement of his probation, O'Leary must attend
therapy. If he misses sessions or fails to cooperate with his
therapist, he could face a long prison sentence, which he believes
would only leave him further damaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's good punishment because it covers such a long
period of time and because there are a lot of restrictions _ like
travel restrictions and constant monitoring and lie detector
tests,'' said O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   ``This also allows a person to get their own rehabilitation, to
seek very good help and to pay for it. None of my rehabilitation
has been at taxpayers' expense, and it has cost me over $30,000. I
think that's good. I don't think the taxpayers should pay for the
rehabilitation.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the origins of his own compulsions were always a
mystery. But thanks to his weekly sessions at the Baylor College of
Medicine's Sexual Abuse Treatment Program, O'Leary believes that
he's finally gained an understanding of his compulsions and how to
avoid situations that could trigger them.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary said that, perhaps every seven years or so, he would
find himself sexually attracted to a young boy. He said those boys
were always between the ages of 5 and 10 and were always children
he knew well, children with whom he had developed a rapport over
several months. He said he has had contact with more than 150,000
children in the course of his 30-year career, but made an emotional
connection with only a small number.
</P>
<P>
   What drove that, said O'Leary, was a sense that his victims were
experiencing troubled childhoods similar to his own. O'Leary said
his two victims expressed longing for their fathers' affection _ as
O'Leary had as a young child _ as well as a sense that their
mothers were in some ways emotionally absent, generally because
they were obliged to work long hours.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Leary described another trigger _ a sense that the child
already has been sexually molested by someone else. He described
the resulting compulsion not just in sexual terms, but in emotional
ones: It was as if he became jealous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like this other guy had loved him, and I knew that I
loved him,'' said O'Leary, describing his feelings upon hearing
that his victims already had been sexually assaulted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a completely deranged, sick thinking that I couldn't
explain. And when I would become aware that I had sexual feelings
for children _ whenever that awareness came about _ it was
humiliating and degrading. It was the low point in my life. I felt
horrible, strange, different from other people. I felt alone.''
</P>
<P>
   The first case _ an assault that occurred about 20 years ago _
involved a boy whose parents were divorced. The boy ``loved his
father and missed his father and wanted his father's love and
respect ... and so my heart went out to the kid,'' O'Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then, one day, we were together, and he was talking to me,
and he started relating to me about this high school kid that
molested him ... and BANG _ I knew I had to do the same thing to
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't happen immediately, but in my mind the stage was set
and the die was cast. I felt like I had to love that little boy
like I was loved by my father. I thought, `I do love him.' You
know, I felt so close to him, and I was empathetic for him, and so
I had to express my love for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the sick feeling in my head.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary said he repeated the same behavior 10 years later, when
he established an emotional connection with Conner. Again, he said,
the sexual assaults began only after Conner spoke of being molested
by someone else.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Ryan Conner said he was never molested by anyone
other than Richard O'Leary. Conner acknowledged that he once told
O'Leary of being sexually assaulted by his mother's ex-boyfriend,
but insisted that story was a lie. Conner said he never liked the
ex-boyfriend and probably lied to hurt him. Or maybe he made up the
story because he thought that was what O'Leary wanted to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a little kid, you tell weird things to weird people,''
said Conner.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, Conner said, O'Leary had been acting indecently
months before hearing the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was, like, showing me his penis, and touching me through my
clothes and stuff like that,'' said Conner. ``But, yeah, when I
told him (of being sexually assaulted), that was when he started
getting very into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Conner recalled that he first met the teacher in an after-school
program, during a climbing-wall class that O'Leary organized.
There, said Conner, the teacher would touch him through his
clothing while fitting him with a climbing harness. Conner, who
said the inappropriate touching began from almost the first day of
the class, assumed that O'Leary touched other children.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary then started grabbing the boy's genitals during games of
flag football, said Conner. According to the youth, O'Leary told
the children that such touching was normal among adult football
players.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, O'Leary would expose his genitals to Conner or
attempt to fondle the boy in his office, behind a locked door.
Conner also said O'Leary began speaking graphically about sex _ and
encouraged the 9-year-old to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Conner recalled one such occasion when the two were alone in the
school's Chevrolet Suburban, as O'Leary was driving to drop off
various recyclable materials from the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how it came up,'' said Conner. ``I was just there
and we were talking about how much money we were going to get on
the recyclables, and then it would jump into what women did wrong,
and women were good for only one thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it was bizarre. I didn't get it. He talked about one of
my teachers that way _ that she was just a whore, and that he bet
she was good in bed, that he bet she was noisy.''
</P>
<P>
   Conner said O'Leary's compulsion continued to escalate, until he
would perform oral sex and other sex acts on the boy. O'Leary also
asked the boy to perform such acts on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the time that all this was going on, Mr. O was
constantly calling my house,'' Conner stated in a court affidavit.
``After my mom told him to stay away from me, he started sending me
letters and cards. He gave me toys and money, too. When Mr. O would
call me on the phone, he would say sexual things about what he was
going to do to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The court record indicates that several of the assaults occurred
during overnight camping trips or at hotels. Conner said that on
one such trip, Mr. O'Leary wanted to sleep alone with him in the
hotel bed. In another, O'Leary took revealing photographs of him
with a Polaroid camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was sick about the whole thing was that it was like you
were his lover or something,'' said Conner. ``And then you'd be
with him for about a year, and you got too old for him and he'd get
bored with you. I remember one time he even said, `I don't think we
should see each other anymore.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Conner recalled on one occasion, he joined O'Leary and his wife
for a day at the beach. Although O'Leary did not behave
inappropriately during the excursion, Conner wondered why O'Leary's
wife never suspected the truth. How could she be so blind?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' said Conner, ``I was over at their house a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his arrest, O'Leary and his wife had been married
about 30 years. For much of that time, they resided in the same
house with the same neighbors. They raised four kids.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. O'Leary, who also asked that her real name not be used,
said in all that time, she suspected something was amiss only once.
It was years and years before O'Leary's arrest, after she found
some photographs _ including nude photographs _ of one of O'Leary's
young students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I confronted (my husband) when I first saw them, and he
explained that the boy had been molested by one of his neighbors,
and that he (her husband) had been shocked and horrified,''
O'Leary's wife said, haltingly.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, she said, claimed that the photos helped the child
explain, physically, how the molestation took place. But instead of
turning the photos over to the police, O'Leary burned them. It was
then that she insisted her husband see a psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the psychiatrist said to me, point blank, `Can't you
handle that your husband has a mistress?' '' said Mrs. O'Leary,
explaining that the psychiatrist misinterpreted her husband's
behavior as signs of an affair. ``In those days, they didn't really
understand sexual addiction.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And what of the strong bonds her husband would sometimes form
with prepubescent boys? What about Conner's visits to the house, or
the attention her husband sometimes lavished on other children _
often to the exclusion of his own? She witnessed all that behavior,
but insists she never suspected her husband was a pedophile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that (my husband) had a strange upbringing _ I knew how
his parents were cold and indifferent with him, and I knew that his
father had a very volatile personality,'' she said. ``And I knew
that he was very, very close to his brother, Raymond. My
interpretation of things was that he just related better to
children because the best relationship in his life was with his
brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the other thing was that this didn't go on all the time.
He had thousands of relationships with kids that were healthy. And
it never happened in front of me. It's like you have a picture of
reality, about what your life is all about _ and then this happens.
I just never dreamed that anything like this was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, Conner's mother also was fooled by the teacher. Her
son was dyslexic and she perceived O'Leary's attention as that of a
concerned teacher. But as the months wore on, she began to see
O'Leary's attention as a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, she told the school of her concerns. It was then,
according to court documents, that school officials acknowledged
that they also had noted O'Leary's unusual attention to the boy and
already had attempted to separate the two. School officials told
Conner's mother that they had opened an internal investigation into
O'Leary and found that former employers at other private schools
had expressed similar concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Conner's mother demanded that O'Leary cease all contact with her
son. School officials agreed, and the following year declined to
renew his contract _ citing differences in educational
philosophies.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Conner said nothing about the assaults, although he
expressed dismay that his mother had separated him from O'Leary. He
also continued to display increasingly bizarre behavior. Conner's
mother recalled how the child refused to remove his baseball cap,
denim jacket and pants, even in bed. Sometimes he would even wear
several layers of clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would tear things up for no reason; he was very
destructive,'' she recalled. ``I found pictures of (my son) where
he had stabbed through himself with knives and things. He would
sometimes go into fits of crying, and he would ask me to spank him,
for no reason. He'd say, `I'm a bad kid, I'm a bad kid.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In desperation, his mother sent young Ryan to a therapist. It
was after one such session, as he and his mother were driving home,
that the boy finally told his mother the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``What made me tell was the therapy,'' recalled Conner. ``I
finally thought this was stupid, and I'll just go ahead and tell
her. This was like two years after it had gone on.''
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't Conner speak out earlier? Conner said there probably
are several reasons. For one, Conner said, O'Leary was able to
manipulate his dwindling self-esteem. Because of his dyslexia,
Conner was already having difficulties in school and he said being
singled out by O'Leary _ ``a god'' among the boys there _ made him
feel special.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, O'Leary would repeatedly tell Conner that what they
were doing wasn't wrong, although others wouldn't understand it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like I was being brainwashed _ thinking that it's all
normal, and it's all in guy fun, and this was what was cool,''
recalled Conner. ``He was, like, `You know, if your dad was around,
he would be doing this, and so I'll do it for you, because I feel
like your dad.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Conner also said O'Leary used his position to make him feel
guilty about the activity and warned Conner that if his mother
found out, she probably would abandon him.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the simplest reason for maintaining his silence,
said Conner, was that O'Leary told him to.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Don't tell' and said, `If you do tell, bad things
would happen,' '' recalled Conner. ``He said it all the time. He
said it a lot. I got the impression that (if I told) he was going
to come and beat my door in, and beat me up, and kill my mom.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary claims to be a man on the mend _ a man who accepts the
reality of what he's done. ``Honesty,'' he said, ``is the only way
to deal with this.'' And yet one wonders.
</P>
<P>
   For instance his story in some regards did not match that of
Conner's, and on one occasion, O'Leary even contradicted himself.
While the former teacher repeatedly expressed remorse for his
attacks, he often seemed more upset about his own plight. At one
point, he began sobbing as he spoke of growing up in dysfunctional
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why bring an innocent child into that? I'm living proof of
what happens,'' he said, his tear-strewn face contorted with
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 10 years into therapy, O'Leary continues to insist that
he never encouraged Conner to keep the sexual activity a secret. He
said he never told any of his victims to keep it a secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I didn't think I'd get in trouble,'' said O'Leary.
``My thinking was so screwed up in that area of my life, that I
didn't have the normal fears that normal people have.''
</P>
<P>
   But Conner said O'Leary told him, over and over, not to tell a
soul.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, O'Leary said he spent 30 years of his life working
with kids. Tens of thousands of kids. And yet, he said, he never
requested that work. He said supervisors at the various private
schools and churches would note that he related well with children
and would assign him those jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But later, O'Leary acknowledged that one after-school program he
operated was created at his suggestion. After hours of questioning,
he acknowledged that it probably wasn't pure happenstance that the
children eligible for that program were exactly of those ages that
he found sexually appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, after going through years of therapy, I can see my
problem figured into a lot of what I did,'' O'Leary conceded, his
voice rising in momentary annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary _ who said he was so remorseful that he considered
suicide _ voluntarily confessed to his various friends and
neighbors after his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   But was he prompted more by self-interest? His image was already
broadcast across every major Houston television station and in
major newspapers. And after telling acquaintances of the assaults _
and explaining ``his problem'' _ O'Leary requested that they submit
letters to the court on his behalf. It may have been those letters
that saved O'Leary from a long prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary insists he is working hard toward recovery _ and many
around him agree. His children, for instance, were among those who
wrote letters on his behalf. They spoke of a distant man who
perhaps never showed them enough love, but who didn't abuse them
either _ and how that man was changed by his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (now) is an open book and would tell us even more than we
are comfortable knowing about his problem,'' wrote one daughter in
a court document. ``He has immersed himself in treatment and is
doing everything he can to become whole and functioning again.
There is a stack of at least 25 books which sits next to his bed,
and when he is not in therapy, he is reading one of these.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first he seemed destroyed and he still has a lot of hard
days. But his determination never dies, and I have no doubt that
for the rest of his life, he will fight with all that he has to
break the cycle of abuse which he fell victim to and which he
continued by victimizing others.''
</P>
<P>
   Conner also has worked hard toward recovery. His challenges have
been many: Besides living with dyslexia, he has dealt with several
relocations, the divorce of his mother and with his hatred for at
least one of her boyfriends. At 18, after repeated arguments with
his mother, Conner left home. He now shares a house with his
girlfriend _ his very first _ and her family.
</P>
<P>
   He said his former teacher damaged him in a way that seems
permanent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ruined my life!'' the young man blurted out in a moment of
anger.
</P>
<P>
   But Conner is a youth of keen intelligence _ his knowledge of
computers, for instance, is nothing short of astounding. Despite
O'Leary's assaults, Conner believes his own future is bright. He
said he wants to open his own business, maybe rent boats and teach
water skiing.
</P>
<P>
   If O'Leary didn't ruin his life, it was only because Conner
wouldn't let him. He said he no longer is a defenseless boy. Now
he's strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, you know, I would have liked to have had friends in high
school and go to parties and games and all the stuff normal high
school kids do,'' he said. ``So I can't sit here and imagine that
it never happened. It's all part of my life now.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
