A1390 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEDBUD-EMERGENCY17-CO     10-16 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEDBUD-EMERGENCY17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'EMERGENCY' LABEL PROVIDES A WAY AROUND BUDGET CAPS
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The coming of the year 2000 is hardly unexpected,
but money to fix the computer Millennium Bug is one of several
``emergency'' expenses totaling $20 billion in the new federal
budget agreement between the White House and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   And while it has been known for months that U.S. troops in
Bosnia would require funds, since they have been there since 1995
and have no departure date, the spending accord puts $1.9 billion
for their operations in the same ``emergency'' package.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, once Congress and the president agree that a
program is an emergency, ordinary spending limits don't apply. But
this year's expansion of the category has some experts warning of a
breakdown in the fiscal discipline that helped deliver the first
budget surplus in three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Congress passes supplemental spending bills every year, but the
most recent version is almost quadruple the size of last year's.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the computer and Bosnia provisions, the emergency
package includes $7 billion that Republicans added for military
readiness and anti-missile defense, plus $1.8 billion to strengthen
security at U.S. embassies abroad and $6 billion in disaster aid
for farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost everything in this emergency bill fits the definition
of 'We couldn't afford it in the regular bill so we're doing it
this way,' `` said Martha Phillips, executive director of the
Concord Coalition, a non-partisan group that urges budget
restraint.
</P>
<P>
   For example, she said, Congress added more military spending
because they had overstuffed the regular Pentagon budget with pet
projects such as weapons built in their districts. ``Then you don't
have money for the basic bread and butter, meat and potato stuff
you have to do,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Phillips argued that the federal government routinely
fails to plan for disasters such as the current farm crisis by
setting aside an adequate contingency fund.
</P>
<P>
   Charles L. Schultze, an economist at Washington's Brookings
Institution who was an adviser in the Carter administration,
concurred. ``They're fudging the concept of emergency,'' he said.
``It's bad budgeting and it's a way to get around the budget
limits.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's emergency package is the largest since 1991 and
1992, when Congress paid the bills for the Persian Gulf war. Since
then, spending in this category has been relatively modest, with
the exception of the $13 billion bill in 1994, when the country was
hit by several natural disasters, including the Los Angeles
earthquake, Hurricane Andrew and Midwest flooding.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency appropriations in recent years include $5.5 billion
for fiscal 1998, $9.2 billion for 1997, $5 billion for 1996 and
$7.7 billion for 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
