<HEADER>
A1406 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDUCATION-TX-POLITICS     10-16 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-TX-POLITICS-2TAKES-$AD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDUCATION-TX-POLITICS-2TAKES-$ADV18 
 
EDUCATION BECOMES LEAD ISSUE FOR TEXAS POLITICIANS 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 18) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ With Texas' crime rate down and voters not yet
concerned about the economy, candidates in this year's statewide
election are running like it's a contest for local school board.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats alike in the contests for governor,
lieutenant governor, comptroller and land commissioner have
emphasized their role in obtaining educational excellence in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The debate has ranged from property tax relief to classroom
construction; from teacher pay raises to audits of public schools;
from private school vouchers to state-paid college scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   The debate in the governor's race between incumbent Republican
George W. Bush and Democratic challenger Garry Mauro has focused
mostly on education spending.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush wants to spend more, he also wants to deliver a $2
billion school property tax cut. Mauro wants to take advantage of
the state's good economy to bring teacher pay up to the national
average, and he wants to take a 30-year, $2 billion loan from the
state's education trust fund for school renovation and classroom
construction.
</P>
<P>
   In the contest to replace retiring Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, the
campaign fire has been over using tax dollars for private school
vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Rick Perry supports a voucher test program for
children in low-performing public schools. Democratic John Sharp
has not ruled out such a program, but he accuses Perry of actually
seeking a full-scale voucher program for all children as a way of
repaying his financial backers.
</P>
<P>
   In the race for state comptroller, Republican Carole Rylander is
borrowing a page from Sharp's successful 1990 campaign by
describing herself as an ``education watchdog'' who will audit
school districts. Sharp has conducted financial audits of numerous
districts, including Houston and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic comptroller candidate Paul Hobby wants to use half
the state's lottery money for incentive bonuses for schools that
improve their education performance. Both candidates support
teacher pay raises.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas land commissioner manages state mineral leases to
raise money for public education, which has opened the door for
Democrat Richard Raymond and Republican David Dewhurst to debate a
wide range of education issues that have little connection to the
land office. But both promise to improve education by raising more
money for it.
</P>
<P>
   All four candidates for governor and lieutenant governor appear
to be moving in the same general direction toward creating a
college scholarship program for Texas students.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp originally made the issue a cornerstone of his campaign
when he announced for lieutenant governor last year, but Mauro
quickly moved to back it. And last week Bush and Perry both
described it as ``an interesting idea,'' with Perry predicting some
form of a scholarship program will pass the Legislature next year.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp's proposal is based on a program called Hope Scholars
adopted by Georgia. Sharp calls his plan Lone Star Scholars and
proposes having the state pay for the tuition, fees and books of
any Texas student who maintains a B average in college. This would
include the state's private universities and technical schools as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``What that has done in Georgia ... is it has completely changed
the dynamics in the first grade classes,'' Sharp said.
</P>
<P>
   ``First graders who weren't talking about college because their
parents weren't sure they could foot this bill 10 or 12 years from
now suddenly they're all wearing Georgia and Georgia Tech T-shirts
and they're talking about college.''
</P>
<P>
   The program would cost about $485 million a year, but Sharp says
that could be paid for with half the state's lottery income or
about half the budget cuts he plans to propose to the Legislature
next year. Sharp said the economic payback to Texas would be
enormous.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you doubled the price of oil today, that would bring in
$16.5 billion (to the state's economy) over the next five years,''
Sharp said. ``If you increase your college graduates by 5 percent,
it brings in $26 billion over the next five years. That is the
difference between what a high school graduate makes and a college
graduate makes.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans last year greeted Sharp's program cautiously,
calling it a new ``entitlement'' program. Sharp said college is no
more of an entitlement to future generations than a high school
diploma was for his father's generation.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spoke favorably of the plan last week and said he has not
endorsed it because he has other education spending priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't taken a position on it yet because I want to make
sure my budget is sound and whole,'' Bush said, but noted: ``It
deserves debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry said he does not want to give Sharp credit for an idea
conceived in Georgia, but he predicted some form of the program
likely will pass the Legislature next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be some technical changes that we would want to see,
raising the standards,'' Perry said. ``We will see some type of
substantial scholarship program debated and most likely passed.''
</P>
<P>
   When the debate turns to secondary education, there is far less
harmony.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has established the primary Republican position on public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I set the most profound goal that I'll probably ever set as
governor, and that is: Every single child should be reading and
comprehending at grade level by the third grade and remain at
appropriate grade level throughout their entire public school
career,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has promised to end the practice of ``social promotion,''
the automatic promotion of students who cannot pass the Texas
Assessment of Academic Skills. Mauro has complained that the
decision should be based on teacher assessments, not a standardized
test.
</P>
<P>
   If the program had been in place last year, about 250,000
students would have been held back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad news is we've got many children who need help,'' Bush
said. ``My fear is if we don't do something about it, we will be
passing illiterate children through the system.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under Bush's plan, students who fail the test would be given
remedial after-school and summer school help and be given a second
chance to pass the test. A major portion of his budget proposal
goes to a reading initiative to prepare students for when the
social promotion program takes effect in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wants to give $2 billion of the state surplus to public
school districts so they can cut their local property taxes by a
like amount. Bush also wants to give districts $1 billion they can
spend as they please on classroom instruction.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to spend $203 million on the reading initiative
linked to his social promotion plan; $166 million for textbooks;
and $25 million for after-school programs in neighborhoods where
the children are at risk of dropping out or joining gangs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he also wants to spend $200 million on school facility
construction. He said by paying the interest and principal on
school bonds, that money can be leveraged into about $3 billion in
school construction.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro argues that Bush's budget plan is missing a golden
opportunity to make up for shortcomings in the state's education
finance system. He says budget surpluses can be used to improve the
system.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro said that in 1984, the state committed to improve
education by reducing class size to 22 students for every teacher;
bringing teacher pay to the national average; and holding schools
accountable for educational excellence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then because money ran out, we spent the next 10 years, the
next 15 years talking only about accountability,'' Mauro said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stopped doing anything at the state level to do anything
about class size and we gave minimal pay raises. So we're right
back to where we started in 1984.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro wants the state to borrow $2 billion from the Permanent
School Fund to pay for public school construction and renovation.
At present, only interest earnings from the education trust fund
can be used.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has called Mauro's plan a ``raid'' on the state's education
trust, but Mauro proposes passing a constitutional amendment to
borrow from the body of the fund and then repay it with principal
and interest over 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro said Bush's school construction plan does not come close
to his because Bush is wrong about what costs are covered in the
school facility construction program. Mauro said it just pays for
the interest on school construction bonds and thus finances far
less construction than Bush claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he (Bush) knows what he's talking about because
the current program only pays interest,'' Mauro said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Texas Education Agency rules for the program
clearly shows Bush is correct _ ``debt service shall include
payments of principal and interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro also proposes giving public school teachers a $6,000 a
year pay raise, and a $5,000 signing bonus for college graduates
who commit to teaching in public schools for three years.
</P>
<P>
   He said the average Texas teacher pay right now is about $32,000
a year while the national average is about $38,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our teachers aren't being paid enough and now we're having a
teacher shortage,'' Mauro said.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro said Bush's plan does not guarantee teacher pay raises by
leaving that decision up to local school districts.
</P>
<P>
   In the lieutenant governor's race, Perry supports most of Bush's
initiatives. But he also is pushing his own plan for master reading
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers under Perry's plan would take specialized courses on
the teaching of reading. Once they had passed a skills test, they
would be eligible for a $5,000 a year increase in pay, with another
$2,000 if they agreed to teach in a low-performing public school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes sense to us to very quickly, as soon as we can, to do
the same thing for math teachers, science teachers, social science
teachers and other teachers,'' Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp has promoted a plan to increase state funding to public
schools by about $1.4 billion over the next two years to ease the
burden that the so-called Robin Hood school finance plan places on
wealthy school districts. The plan also would trigger a pay raise
for most teachers.
</P>
<P>
   But Sharp and Perry have clashed over vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Perry is pushing a plan to adopt a pilot project to give
students in low-performing schools a voucher that they can use to
transfer to another public school, a private school or a religious
school.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp says Perry has received more than $300,000 in campaign
money from people who want a full-scale, $2 billion-a-year voucher
program and that he is using the pilot as a first step.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp said public schools should be forced to accept students
from low-performing schools and those low-performing schools should
pay for the student's transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about a pilot project. This is about a bunch of
folks who want to get into the private school business, people in
state and out who want to get into the for-profit school
business,'' Sharp said.
</P>
<P>
   ``John claims a lot of things about Rick Perry that are not
true,'' Perry replied.
</P>
<P>
   Perry said the competition of private school vouchers will force
districts to improve low-performing schools. If not, then it gives
the students an option for getting out.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are children who don't have a choice. Their parents
can't send them to another school,'' Perry said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-16-98 1555EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
