<HEADER>
A1408 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CHILDREN-1017-     10-16 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHILDREN-1017-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN KOSOVO, THE TOLL IS SHOWING ON THE CHILDREN
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ International aid workers are expressing
grave concern about the thousands of children, particularly babies,
among Kosovo's ethnic Albanian refugees displaced by months of
fighting here.
</P>
<P>
   Children examined by health workers are showing signs of decline
because of malnutrition, diarrhea and respiratory infections,
conditions likely to worsen when cold weather comes, doctors and
aid workers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things don't change, my feeling is that there will be a
high rate of morbidity and mortality among children,'' said Paula
Silverman, an American pediatrician who is in the preliminary
stages of assessing the needs of children for aid groups.
</P>
<P>
   In visits to refugees this week, Silverman said many children
have little or no access to the kind of consistent medical care
needed to keep these problems from becoming life-threatening. She
expressed particular concern about dehydration, a by-product of
diarrhea that can be fatal if not treated properly. ``These
children need access to get some rehydration solution very soon,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Months of village-to-village fighting between the ethnic
Albanian Kosovar separatists and Serb military and police forces
have forced thousands of civilians from their homes. Many houses
were leveled or severely damaged in the fighting, and an estimated
50,000 refugees remain outside as the temperatures drop.
</P>
<P>
   Since estimates of the number of refugees vary from 250,000 to
more than 450,000, there also is uncertainty about the number of
small children among the refugees. Relief agencies estimate the
number of children a year old and younger to be at least 15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors at Kinderberg, a German relief group that specializes in
caring for children, are particularly concerned about new mothers
who cease breastfeeding because of the extremely stressful
circumstances. The women lose their milk quickly, creating a
potential crisis for babies because of poor access to baby formula
or cow's milk, said Bajram Maxhuni, a doctor working with
Kinderberg.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the scarcity of medical facilities, pregnant women
are delivering babies in the open or in unsanitary conditions
without disinfectants or even clean water, said Maxhuni, who added
that many of the newborns die. Their mothers get serious infections
from the deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   Education also is a concern. While the studies of many children
have been suspended, others drift in to classrooms in schools that
remain open. In the refugee community of 1,800 near the village of
Kisnareka, refugees have erected a makeshift school built largely
of plastic sheeting. The school has two classrooms for 30 children,
who sit on logs for two hours of lessons each day.
</P>
<P>
   After an interruption in aid deliveries of several days caused
by the uncertainty over NATO airstrikes, relief trucks have been
rolling to isolated villages and other places where people
displaced by the fighting have congregated. The convoys, organized
by the Pristina office of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees,
are targeting priority areas each day, carrying basic food,
medical, shelter and other supplies. Convoys destined for two
villages are scheduled for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers stress that they believe the refugees would be
better off returning to their homes, even if they were severely
damaged in the fighting. But refugees express reluctance to return
home because they fear Serb police and military forces who remain
in the area. Additionally, they are unnerved by the occasional
gunfire and shelling that continues in the countryside despite the
U.S.-brokered peace deal, which averted the NATO airstrikes in
exchange for a Serb police pullback and end to violence in the
Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
   These fears also are keeping them from seeking medical care in
field clinics being provided by aid groups. ``The reality is that
they will have no access to medical care if they are not willing to
go get it,'' Silverman said.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers also worry about the psychological damage inflicted
on children. ``We are seeing a lot of trauma with what they have
been through,'' said Iliriana Loxha of Kinderberg. ``These problems
will last a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
