u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONOR-KILLINGS-$ADV18     10-16 1558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONOR-KILLINGS-$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONOR-KILLINGS-$ADV18 
 
JORDANIAN REPORTER HAS MISSION TO END FAMILY `HONOR KILLING' 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 18) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ Four years ago, a 16-year-old Jordanian girl
named Kifaya was tied to a chair and told to recite an Islamic
prayer. As neighbors listened to her plead for her life, her
brother slit her throat.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, bloody knife in hand, the brother went into the
street shouting that he had cleansed his family's honor of the
shame of Kifaya's ``immoral behavior``: Kifaya had been raped by
another brother and forced to get an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   When a crime reporter for the English-language Jordan Times went
to Amman's poor, crowded neighborhood of Hashemi Ashmali to find
out the details, the girl's uncles defended the killing and
suggested Kifaya had seduced her brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them that maybe the brother who had raped her should
have been killed,'' the reporter, Rana Husseini, recalled. ``They
thought about it for a second and then said `No, the right person
was killed.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The incident, hardly noted otherwise in the media, was a
watershed moment for Husseini, a Jordanian of Palestinian origin
who has worked Jordan's crime beat since 1993. ``This was when I
realized that our society tends to blame women for everything,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, she has crusaded to keep a spotlight on an age-old
practice that is usually shrouded in secrecy. Jordanians call the
crime an honor killing. They occur when a woman is killed by a
relative for a real or imagined sexual transgression that might
tarnish the family's name.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever an honor killing occurred, Husseini, a 6-foot-tall,
athletically built 31-year-old, would appear at the scene wearing
jeans and tennis shoes in case she needed to escape angry relatives
and start asking questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women in this culture belong to their families,'' said
Husseini. ``If they do something wrong, it's as if they have
tarnished their whole family. I'm just trying to fight for their
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Her vigilance has paid off. Last May, Jordan's ministry of
social development announced plans to build the country's first
shelter for battered women, including those in danger of being
murdered by family members. The shelter would become home to some
50 women now held in prison for their own protection.
</P>
<P>
   She says she has received quiet encouragement from the royal
family. Earlier this year, she won the Reebok Award for Human
Rights for uncovering honor killings. Farah Daghistani, the
daughter of King Hussein's sister, nominated her; Queen Noor called
to congratulate her.
</P>
<P>
   The king, in 1994, described violence against women as a
``flagrant contradiction to our ongoing calls to preserve human
dignity and all human rights'' _ words widely interpreted as
directed against honor killings.
</P>
<P>
   But the royal family's opposition to the practice has not
changed traditional Jordanian notions of honor linked to the
virginity of a family's unmarried women.
</P>
<P>
   Royal opposition has not reduced the number of honor killings.
Every year, about 30 such slayings occur here. They account for
about one-third of all murders.
</P>
<P>
   And the king's words have not altered laws that seem to condone
honor killings by meting out light prison sentences to the
murderers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any man convicted of killing his female relatives for honor
reasons, the verdict will be reduced by half,'' said Asma Khader, a
human rights lawyer and former president of the Jordanian Women's
Union. ``Sometimes they get as little as six months or maybe one
year.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kifaya's case _ Husseini does not publish last names _ a
21-year-old brother raped her and then tried to kill her after she
told her parents that she was pregnant. Her family forced her to
undergo an abortion and then to marry a man 35 years her senior.
Six months later, the man divorced her. On the day of the divorce,
her 30-year-old brother killed her.
</P>
<P>
   The younger brother received 15 years for rape and attempted
murder. The older brother, her killer, got 15 years, but a court
cut the sentence to seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court views it as a crime of passion and makes excuses
because the woman has ruined the reputation of the family,'' said
Khader.
</P>
<P>
   Khader says these attitudes shape other areas of law dealing
with women, including inheritance, property rights and child
custody. In Jordan, a woman cannot get a passport or travel outside
the country without the consent of her ``wali,'' a husband or
closest male relative.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `wali' decides everything,'' said Khader. ``It leads to
crazy situations. We have had female ministers and members of
Parliament, and they can't travel without the permission of their
`wali.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Khader and other Jordanian feminists have campaigned to change
the laws without success. In 1989, Husseini was part of a 60-person
team _ and one of four women _ appointed by the king to draft a new
National Charter. The document affirmed sexual equality, but it was
not legally binding.
</P>
<P>
   Khader says she does not expect a bill calling for stricter
sentencing for men who commit honor crimes, which she helped draft,
to be considered by the Parliament any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Even attempts to raise the legal age of marriage for women to 18
from 15 have met heavy resistance from traditional-minded members
of Parliament, most of whom are men. Of 40 members of the upper
house, only three are women. Among the 80 members of the lower
house, none are women.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say, `We are an eastern, conservative society.' If we
encourage women this way, this will lead to breaking the unity of
the family,'' said Khader. ``They say, `We are different from the
foreigners, the Westerners. We don't want to import their values of
sexual freedom, which leads to AIDS and single motherhood.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Husseini, has weathered a barrage of criticism since she began
covering honor killings _ and not just from men. Once, an Arab
woman living in the United States called her newspaper to complain
that Husseini's stories were painting a negative picture of Arabs
in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Twice, while reporting on a story in Amman's poorer
neighborhoods, where most honor killings take place, Husseini fled
the scene because she felt unsafe around men who clearly viewed her
presence, and her Western dress, as an intrusion.
</P>
<P>
   On occasion, she has been verbally attacked for dressing in
Western clothing, being single at an age considered old in her
culture and having studied at an American university.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think I'm doing this to encourage (premarital)
sex or to tarnish the image of our country,'' said Husseini, who
studied at
 &UR;  &LR; Oklahoma City University &UR;  &LR; for six years and received bachelors and
master's degrees in mass communications. ``It's not true. There is
something wrong and I just feel like it should be fixed.''
</P>
<P>
   Husseini goes out of her way to stress that honor killings are
embedded in tradition, not religion. Christian Arabs, she says, as
well as Muslim may commit crimes of honor. And Arab culture is not
alone in honor killing. They also happen in Turkey, Pakistan and
Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the criticism, Husseini continued to cover honor
killings, publishing an expos in The Jordan Times titled ``Murder
in the Name of Honor'' for which she received the an award.
</P>
<P>
   In four years, she has written about dozens of such cases. There
was the 31-year-old man who killed his 39-year-old aunt because she
often left the house without the knowledge of her family. There was
the court ruling reducing the sentence of a 22-year-old man who
killed his sister because ``the victim provoked the defendant by
telling him that she was free to do as she wished.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there was case of the 21-year-old man who murdered his
24-year-old sister and a man acquitted of raping her. The woman was
killed after she spent four years in protective prison custody. Her
family had signed a guarantee with the court vouching for her
safety.
</P>
<P>
   Husseini found that in many cases, the plea of ``honor killing''
was designed to cover up crimes of incest or rape. And she says she
found that innuendoes of sexual misconduct were often false.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court views the killers as victims also, victims of
circumstances,'' said Husseini. Over the years, she has come to
agree. ``Their families pushed them,'' she says. ``They say,
`You're responsible for the family honor.' They offer rewards, a
piece of land or to pay for a wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often they choose someone who is under 18 to do the killing so
that he will not have a record when he gets out of prison.''
</P>
<P>
   She hopes that her reporting will crack the silence that
surrounds honor killings, when family members, neighbors and even
the police conspire to cover up such a crime in order to hide the
shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any case, I will not stop (reporting),'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Husseini says she is willing to risk public censure if it means
ending honor killings and helping these women lead normal lives.
Keeping the problem under wraps will not make it go away, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our society and we have to face it,'' she said.
``These women can do something with themselves. Instead, they are
wasting their lives in fear or in prison.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
