A1540 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-TOWNE-TEX     10-16 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TOWNE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT TOWNE PUSHES THE `LIMITS' OF WORK AND OBSESSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Towne manages to be sanguine about the Peter Biskind book
``Easy Riders, Raging Bulls,'' which revels in the seamy,
self-obsessed side of the moviemaking generation that came to power
in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me put it to you'' this way, Towne responds, in his
reassuring murmur. ``If you were happily married to your wife for
20 years, and you had one knock-down, drag-out fight and then
someone wrote about only that one fight, of course you'd look bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, if we'd all been such terrible people, why would
anybody have made movies with us?''
</P>
<P>
   And Towne _ who made his reputation as a script doctor,
repairing such pictures as ``Bonnie &AMP; Clyde'' and ``The Godfather''
before becoming a legend as a writer with ``The Last Detail,
Shampoo'' and ``Chinatown'' _ is still making movies. His latest,
``Without Limits,'' the story of Olympic long-distance runner Steve
Prefontaine, opened last week, with Billy Crudup in the title role.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second film about Prefontaine, whose career was cut
tragically short by an auto accident not long after the 1972
Olympics; ``Prefontaine,'' with Jared Leto, made little impression
with critics or audiences last year. Still, Towne was fascinated by
the man affectionately known as Pre, who was a media icon in the
world of track and field. ``It was the last amateur moment in track
in this country,'' Towne says, ``where a star in that field was
doing it not for the love of money, since he was making only $3 a
day. So he was doing it for the love of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pushing your own limits, which is what I think an artist does.
And Steve actually did say, `I consider a race to be a work of
art,' so it's not hard to see how I could identify with that. For
him, his race was something he held to a higher standard than
simple victory. So the story of a front-runner who's more concerned
with pushing himself to the very limits of consciousness is
intriguing to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Several threads can be found in Towne's writing; one is that he
details the lives of those who are wedded to their work. ``I've
always written about protagonists who are obsessive about their
work. You think about the obsessive private detective in
`Chinatown,' the hairdresser in `Shampoo,' the athletes in
`Personal Best' and now in `Without Limits,' the obsessive drug
dealer. It has always struck (me) that men who (are) defined by
what they do are inherently dramatic, and there's always that
possibility of tension between their dedication to their work, and
anything personal that might interfere with it. I guess it's just
another wrinkle on that oldest conflict in drama, the conflict
between love and duty.''
</P>
<P>
   Towne's concentration on defining his character by their
professions, and that overwhelming attachment to work, is
specifically American. How does that come to him? ``Well,'' he
says, sighing, ``the nearest that I can tell, is that it probably
comes from watching Disney cartoons.''
</P>
<P>
   Pardon?
</P>
<P>
   He laughs. ``Look, when I grew up and you went to the movies,
there was always a little cartoon, a Disney cartoon. And it was
Mickey and Donald's moving day, or Mickey and Donald window washing
on the skyscrapers. Or Mickey and Donald as ghostbusters. So, the
first lesson I learned as a 5-year-old is that people have to
figure out what they want to do. Right away!
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, for the animators,'' Towne observes, ``it was a great way
of showing movement. If you're a kid, that makes a great
impression.The thing that a good mouse and duck do, is figure out
what to do with their lives, how they're gonna make a living. And
coming out of the Depression, that was an ongoing concern of
everyone's.''
</P>
<P>
   Like his other work as a writer-director, ``Without Limits'' is
about competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's just a way of hardening the target. And
competition and emphasis on competition is a very American
preoccupation, being a winner. In the end, I don't know how you
reconcile that, because in the end, the competition is between you
and you.''
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7614. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
