<HEADER>
A1544 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAINTRIP-ROCKIES-TEX     10-16 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAINTRIP-ROCKIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FATHER AND SON, THERE'S NOTHING LIKE A TRAIN TRIP THROUGH THE
ROCKIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLORADO and NEW MEXICO _ I like the way our vacation pictures
turned out.
</P>
<P>
   There's Patrick, my 7-year-old son, smiling out the window of
our passenger car as the vintage steam engine chugs along in the
background. Next picture: Patrick again, in the open flat car at
the end of the train, grinning up at the camera as rails disappear
into the mountains behind him. Next: Black clouds of smoke
billowing from two locomotives as they climb through the aspens;
then the deep, craggy face of Toltec Gorge as seen from hundreds of
feet above, on the thin ribbon of rail.
</P>
<P>
   It had been a day for my boy, who is a train nut. But the photos
remind of the rustling aspens, the mountains all around, the deep
gorges, trestles over mountain streams, inky tunnels, a doe on the
hill, the brisk air. If this jaunt through the Rocky Mountains on
the Cumbres and Toltec Scenic Railroad was kid stuff, then I was
glad to be a boy again, too.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Chama, N.M., is a three-hour drive northwest from our cabin in
the Sangre De Cristo Mountains near Angel Fire, so my wife, Patrick
and I leave at 6 a.m. to make our midmorning departure. Past Taos,
there is flatness and desert, sweet-smelling sagebrush spreading to
the horizon. Then mountains again, great orange vistas in the
morning sun.
</P>
<P>
   The little town of Chama, a few miles south of the Colorado
border, seems to exist only to serve the historic railroad and the
roughly 60,000 riders the Cumbres and Toltec attracts from mid-May
until the riding season ends in mid-October. Restaurants, hotels
and souvenir shops line the street up the hill from a rustic rail
station, which includes an old-time blacksmith shop and tall heaps
of coal waiting for steam-engine boilers.
</P>
<P>
   The Chama station dates from the 1880s, when the 64-mile route
between the town and Antonito, Colo., was one spur of the Denver
and Rio Grande Railroad built to service mining camps and logging
operations in the San Juan Mountains. Until area highways were
upgraded during World War II, the railroad was the only means of
travel through the rugged, remote territory.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1960s, mining had petered out, the automobile was
king, and mountain railroads like this one had become obsolete.
Were it not for some persistent rail buffs, the tracks we rode that
day in August would have been long abandoned _ rusting mountain
relics like the tumbledown shacks seen here and there along the
mountain line.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, in 1970, after lobbying by railroad lovers, New Mexico
and Colorado jointly purchased the 64-mile track between Chama and
Antonito, and a thriving tourist enterprise was born.
</P>
<P>
   Thus on a sunny mountain morning nearly three decades later, we
board one of several full passenger cars as two locomotives huff
from Chama station at the head of our train. The extra oomph is
necessary for the long, 4-degree incline toward Cumbres Pass, which
at 10,015 feet is the highest pass on any scheduled passenger train
in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Even with two engines, the task sometimes seems too much. We
wonder whether the gritty old machines will conk out and send us
rolling back down through the mountains. To ride the Cumbres and
Toltec is to gain new appreciation for the Little Engine That
Could. But we lumber on _ at only 10 mph most of the time, but up
we go.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the tracks cross roads or highways, cars, pickups and
semi-trailers stop, and smiling, waving people emerge from their
vehicles to stand near the tracks with cameras, capturing a little
of the romance.
</P>
<P>
   Farther on, cattle graze in high pastures that are inaccessible
by car or pickup. Several brown-and-white horses dash from one end
of a fenced pasture to another when the train nears. Two fly
fishermen stand knee deep in a stream below us. One turns and
waves. We notice our hair and clothes are flecked by coal dust. The
train whistle howls, echoing off the mountains. On the trip to
Antonito, we cross back and forth from New Mexico to Colorado 11
times.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway to our destination, the train pull into a depot built in
remote range land, and the hundreds of passengers file off for
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The best scenery comes shortly after our journey resumes. Toltec
Gorge falls off to the right, its jagged face plummeting to the Rio
de Los Pinos, which means River of the Pines in Spanish. The river
is running fast, and even from our rail perch 600 feet up, we see
white water.
</P>
<P>
   The locomotive _ only one now since lunch because most of the
trip is downhill _ enters the trip's first tunnel _ 360 feet
chiseled through a mountain. We emerge from the blackness into the
sunlight, and tower above the river for several crooked miles. Far
below, cabins with red roofs dot the land along the river. They are
only summer homes, says brakeman Felipe Romero. In winter, those
homes are buried beneath 15 feet of snow, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Romero worked in a mine before getting laid off and has been
with the railroad for eight years. He never grows tired of his job,
he says, because of the scenery and the people he meets from around
the world. He agrees that the second half of the trip is much
prettier than the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you ought to see it in the fall,'' he says. ``By
mid-September the aspens are changing color, yellows, reds,
oranges. That's the best time to ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Closer to Antonito, the land levels out and we return to desert.
By now, after more than five hours on the rails, the trip has
become a bit grueling. Weary adults bump along in their seats,
sleeping children bouncing along in their laps. It seems to take an
hour to get from the Antonito town limits to the station.
</P>
<P>
   Most passengers are ready for the trip to end. We gratefully
shuffle from the train onto waiting, air-conditioned buses supplied
by the railroad for the ride back to our cars in Chama. That trip
takes less than an hour. The buses are decorated in Southwestern
colors, have television screens above the seats and tinted windows,
an instructive contrast to our previous mode of travel.
</P>
<P>
   It is very late by the time we reach the cabin back in Angel
Fire. We are bone-tired, a reality that overshadows some of the
day's pleasures. But then we return to Texas, where the grass is
brown and the air is 100 degrees. We get our photos back after a
few days. I see my son's happy face, and the mountains and the
locomotives and remember the feel of the cool alpine air.
</P>
<P>
   And I'm glad that Patrick loves trains.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   If you go
</P>
<P>
   Fares range from $34 to $52 for adults, and $17 to $27 for
children under 11. A variety of trip packages are available. For
more information, call Cumbres and Toltec Scenic Railroad at the
Chama Station, (505) 756-2151; or the Antonito Station, (719)
376-5483.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
