<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DEAD MAN WALKING' AUTHOR FINDS ATTITUDES ABOUT EXECUTION CHANGING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sister Helen Prejean, the author of ``Dead Man Walking,'' is
full of life. The spirited Roman Catholic nun's smiles and hugs won
her audience long before she began speaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking my case to the American people,'' said Prejean, who
munched a sandwich as she greeted old and new acquaintances and
signed autographs before speaking out against the death penalty
last week at St. Rita Catholic Church in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Since actress Susan Sarandon won an Academy Award for her
portrayal of Prejean in the acclaimed movie version of ``Dead Man
Walking,'' the nun has been much in demand and her audiences are
larger.
</P>
<P>
   Prejean, who wore a simple silver cross and street clothes,
noted that her book about her ministry to men on Louisiana's Death
Row is also being made into a play and an opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm especially excited about the play, because I can see it
being performed on university campuses and in community theaters,''
Prejean said.
</P>
<P>
   What she likes most about her bigger crowds, she said, is that
she has the chance to speak to backers and opponents of the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the movie came out, my audiences would be about 100
people, and 98 of them would already be against the death
penalty,'' she said. Now she often draws more than 1,000, and last
week she spoke to about 700 at her Fort Worth stop.
</P>
<P>
   Also, sales of her book increased dramatically after the movie.
Her book was on the bestseller list for 31 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   She has no misconceptions that the death penalty will be
abolished right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we are just solidly locked into the death
penalty,'' she said. ``There's not a politician running for office
who says they are not for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Prejean noted that some good, decent people support the death
penalty because of their outrage over crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm outraged, too,'' she said. ``And we have to talk about
that outrage, and what we as a society are going to do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she believes many grassroots Americans are beginning to
change their minds about the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of surface support for the death penalty, but
right below that surface, people are ambivalent,'' she said. ``And
it just shows me that people are good and decent, and they've been
manipulated into this thing. Give them information and they reject
it _ including the people of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People see we are doing the death penalty left and right, and
there is still horrible crime,'' she said. ``More people are
asking, `Do we have to keep doing this? Or is there an
alternative?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Prejean believes that the death penalty violates Christian
teaching about the sanctity of human life. She also argues that it
is unfairly administered _ that only those with a less skillful
lawyer are sentenced to die, and that it is applied in a racist
manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty-five percent of people who go to Death Row are there
because they've killed white people,'' she said. ``When people of
color are killed, or homeless people or poor people are killed,
there's not a shrug of the shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   Prejean travels internationally and last year met with Pope John
Paul II, who has led the Catholic Church to oppose capital
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot is happening internationally, because more and more
countries are voting to abolish the death penalty,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In March she was in Geneva during a meeting of the U.N.
Commission on Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``A majority of the countries voted for a moratorium on the
death penalty, moving toward abolition,'' she said. ``But the
United States voted against it, along with Iran, Iraq, China and
Saudi Arabia.''
</P>
<P>
   Prejean believes that international pressure will eventually
lead to abolishing the death penalty in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it won't happen by 9 o'clock tomorrow morning,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or write:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
