<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORMEL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE WEIGHS RESUBMITTING HORMEL BID FOR AMBASSADOR POST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: UPDATES 2d graf, saying Congress is expected to adjourn
Tuesday instead of ``in the next few days.'')   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the wake of the apparent failure of the Senate
to approve the nomination of gay rights advocate James C. Hormel to
be ambassador to Luxembourg, the White House is considering whether
to resubmit his bid next year.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Socarides, special assistant to the president, said
Friday that if Congress adjourns Tuesday _ as expected _ without
acting on Hormel's nomination, ``the president will weigh what
options he has.''
</P>
<P>
   Socarides added that ``a recess appointment is an option, a post
that doesn't require Senate confirmation is an option, or the
president would resubmit his name next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The aide, who said the White House will consult with Hormel to
see what he wants, added: ``The president has used his recess
appointment power very sparingly. Resubmitting the nomination is
always a more likely scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   Socarides stressed that the administration ``is deeply
disappointed that Mr. Hormel's nomination has not been acted on
simply because he is gay. We have a commitment to him that we are
going to do everything we can to see that someone who is as
qualified and distinguished as Mr. Hormel can make the contribution
he has so graciously offered to make to this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., a leading advocate for Hormel,
has urged President Clinton ``to use his constitutional authority
to make a recess appointment of Hormel,'' according to her press
secretary, Jim Hock.
</P>
<P>
   He said Feinstein believes that ``the failure to vote on his
nomination is really quite incomprehensible. She believes he's been
denied the constitutionally delineated due process of a Senate vote
and debate simply because he is gay.''
</P>
<P>
   Hock said Feinstein, who has known Hormel for more than two
decades, deems him ``a man of decency and honor and the type of
person who should be encouraged to be in public service.''
</P>
<P>
   Hormel's nomination has been blocked by Senate Republicans for
nearly a year. Conservatives, including Sens. James M. Inhofe,
R-Okla., Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark., and Robert C. Smith, R-N.H., used
a parliamentary maneuver known as a ``hold'' to stymie a floor
vote.
</P>
<P>
   The opponents said a gay activist would be an inappropriate
choice for the job because Luxembourg is a predominantly Catholic
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., likened
homosexuality to kleptomania, alcoholism and sex addiction. He has
refused to bring Hormel's nomination to the Senate floor for a vote
since it was approved 16 to 2 last November by the Foreign
Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Hormel, a San Francisco philanthropist, is a Democratic Party
donor, former dean at the University of Chicago Law School and heir
to the Hormel meat packing fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Winnie Stachelberg, political director for the Human Rights
Campaign, the nation's largest gay and lesbian organization which
Hormel helped found, called the Republican stalling on Hormel's
nomination ``another example of anti-gay bias.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Hormel ``surely would have won'' if his nomination had
come up for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   She also said the nomination was failing because ``he is honest
and open about who he is. Unfortunately, there are people in the
U.S. Senate who think it's okay to discriminate against gay people
simply because of their sexual orientation. It sends a signal not
only to Jim Hormel but to an entire community of people that just
because of their sexual orientation they can't hold certain jobs. I
would have thought that our country was beyond that. It's clear to
me that we have a long way to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
