<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1598 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-MAURO-PROFILE-$     10-16 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-MAURO-PROFILE-$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARRY MAURO: DARKHORSE DEMOCRAT KEEPS HIS EYE ON THE PRIZE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 18)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It is crunch time on the campaign trail, and on
this particular day, Garry Mauro is munching on popcorn for lunch
before catching a flight to San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The polls are against him, the money isn't flowing his way and
even some stalwarts in his own party have forsaken him for his
opponent, but Mauro doesn't act like a man headed for a predicted
major defeat.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Democratic challenger to Republican Gov. George W.
Bush seems energized and even a little cocky as he heads into the
frenzied final days of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   No, he is not a political Don Quixote. He has just been the
underdog before _ and won.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real comfortable with who I am,'' Mauro, 50, says
confidently as talks about why he would make a good governor.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the past five governor's races, he says he has reason to
be optimistic about the Nov. 3 election. In those races, the
challengers were never ahead of the incumbent in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only poll they ever won was on Election Day,'' Mauro
notes. ``If I were George Bush, I'd be worried right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the political tide is running against Mauro and threatens
to sweep him off the map on Election Day. In Bush, Mauro faces a
well-funded, popular son of a former president who himself is
considered prime presidential timber for the 2000 race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm worried. I don't want to lose,'' Mauro concedes at
one point in an interview last week.
</P>
<P>
   But Mauro, the Texas land commissioner for the past 16 years,
would rather spend his time talking about his ideas, his
qualifications, his background and his vision for Texas than the
polls _ which show him trailing Bush by some 50 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the polls say, he has no regrets about getting
into this uphill race.
</P>
<P>
   ``There comes a precise moment in time when a state or a
generation can make a decision that will really make a
difference,'' Mauro says. ``I think we have the opportunity of a
lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro wants to take advantage of the state's robust economy and
an expected $6 billion cash surplus to, among other things, give
teachers a big raise, build more schools and make schools adhere to
limits on the number of students per class.
</P>
<P>
   ``This state is in such a good position to lay a real foundation
for the 21st century,'' he notes. ``And I think George Bush is
complacent. I don't think he has a sense of urgency about anything
... I don't wait. I don't hang back.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro is quick to list his experience in explaining why he
qualifies for the state's top job. And he voices some frustration
over the name recognition Bush gets from his politically famous
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``You bring a set of life experiences to any job, and I'm
surprised people haven't been more interested in going beyond my 16
years as land commissioner,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of Bush's biggest strengths is that he is a decent man
from a decent family,'' Mauro says. ``But I'm surprised people
haven't been more interested in my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro's Italian family includes a great-grandfather who was a
tenant farmer in Tabor who never learned to speak English, and a
father, now dead, who was the first person in his family to get a
college degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just as proud of my family as I imagine George is of
his.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Bryan, Mauro later attended Reicher High School, a
private Catholic school in Waco. He played on the high school's
state championship football team.
</P>
<P>
   After graduation, Mauro went to Texas A&AMP;M, where he was a
freshman football player and later a yell leader. Still a die-hard
Aggie, he recently took a few hours off from his grueling campaign
schedule to catch an A&AMP;M football game.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, he worked on the attempted comeback campaign of former
Sen. Ralph Yarborough, who lost the Democratic primary. After that,
he finished law school at the University of Texas and worked in
private practice.
</P>
<P>
   But his heart belonged to politics. He worked on several
campaigns before announcing his first candidacy, running and
winning the land commissioner's race at age 34 in 1982. He was
re-elected three times.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro says he also learned a lot about state government as a
deputy to then-Comptroller Bob Bullock.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock, a Democrat who is retiring from politics when his term
as lieutenant governor expires next year, is the godfather of one
of Mauro's children. But Bullock shocked political circles when he
endorsed Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro says he still considers Bullock a friend, but he adds that
the two don't talk anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``What am I going to talk to him about right now?'' he asks
candidly. ``All I'm doing right now is running for governor.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Mauro was first elected land commissioner, the Democrats
swept the statewide offices. Now, he's the last Democrat elected in
that sweep who is still in office, and it is the Republicans who
have their eye on taking it all this time.
</P>
<P>
   As land commissioner, Mauro notes, he established the state's
successful Adopt-A-Beach program; boosted income from leases of
state lands that went to schools; fought oil spills; and worked to
improve veterans' benefits that come from the land commission
office.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure, Mauro ran President Clinton's Texas campaigns
in 1992 and 1996. The two are old friends, and Clinton recently was
in San Antonio and Houston to help Mauro raise money.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro has remained supportive of Clinton, saying he can't defend
the president's actions in the Monica Lewinsky affair, but does
forgive him.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro's days in office also have been marked with some
controversy. He filed for personal bankruptcy and apologized for
making more than 200 telephone calls from his state office to
Clinton's campaign headquarters in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer of 1997, Mauro toured Texas promoting his book
``Beaches, Bureaucrats and Big Oil,'' and thought about whether he
wanted to run for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats thought about it as well but decided to skip the
chance of being beaten by a strong incumbent. Mauro decided to run.
</P>
<P>
   He went home to his old neighborhood in Bryan to announce his
campaign for governor. Then he went to Waco, where he announced his
candidacy on the steps of the McLellan County Courthouse. He worked
there briefly more than 40 years ago for $1 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was an elevator operator at age 14 at the McLellan
County Courthouse, I never dreamed I was going to come back to that
same courthouse and announce for governor,'' he says, munching on
more popcorn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
