u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-BUSH-PROFILE-$A     10-16 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-BUSH-PROFILE-$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE W. BUSH: POPULAR INCUMBENT CAN'T ESCAPE THE `P' WORD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 18)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPLE, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush and company find themselves
in a rare downpour as they journey to this Central Texas town to
promote the Republican ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Republican candidates traveling with Bush are eager to be seen
with the popular governor. But the rain has dampened turnout, and
only about 50 people show up to greet them.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, ever the ice-breaker, is undaunted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to announce our drought relief plan is working,'' he
quips, and the crowd laughs its approval.
</P>
<P>
   They are off to a good start.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of hours later in Abilene, Bush is riding in a trolley
to the West Texas Fair and Rodeo when he spies a group of
motorcyclists parked at the entrance and asks the driver to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Grinning a crooked smile, he heads into the crowd and happily
shakes hands and poses for pictures with the bikers, who thank him
for supporting a repeal of the mandatory helmet law.
</P>
<P>
   Bush the candidate is affable and approachable. He easily makes
a joke and takes one as well. He makes ``Joe Q Citizen'' feel like
the only person in a crowded room, if just for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like my job here. I love Texas,'' he says one day.
</P>
<P>
   His easygoing style has served him well so far in his quest to
become the first governor re-elected to consecutive four-year terms
in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But as Bush talks about Texas, it seems Texans have something
else on their minds _ the presidential race in 2000. Bush is
confronted with the question at almost every stop.
</P>
<P>
   A placard in Abilene reads: ``Bush 4 President.'' Many people
who get their photos snapped with him boast that they had their
picture taken ``with the next president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   With the polls titling Bush's way and an awesome campaign fund
on hand, many Texans seem to think the governor's race is a
foregone conclusion. They want to know what Bush will do next and
when he's going to announce it.
</P>
<P>
   Bush insists he is focused solely on the Nov. 3 election and
won't make up his mind about a presidential bid until early next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I wasn't interested in running for president, I would've
said so,'' the governor said recently at a stop in San Antonio.
``And I told the truth nearly a year ago when I said I don't know
whether I will or will not run for the presidency _ and people are
going to have to factor that in when they get to the voting
booth.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, 52, is not sure if wants to commit his wife, Laura, and
twin 16-year-old girls ``to the Washington, D.C., lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is ever a time when Bush gets visibly emotional, it is
when he discusses his father's 1992 presidential campaign and the
agony he endured ``watching someone you love go down in flames.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that his own life was scrutinized when his father was in
office, and against during the 1994 race for governor, Bush says he
can pass another round of attention, should he decide to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was young and irresponsible, I was young and
irresponsible,'' he says, declining to provide any specifics except
that he drank too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Now) I'm a devoted father, a loyal husband and I've upheld
the integrity of this office.''
</P>
<P>
   His opponent, Democratic Land Commissioner Garry Mauro, has
criticized Bush for not giving Texans a definite answer on the
presidential question. Yet Bush's refusal to say one way or the
other doesn't seem to have hurt him politically.
</P>
<P>
   First things are first, and Bush has to get re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are campaigning like there's no tomorrow,'' Bush said at
the Temple stop. ``The only poll that matters is on Election Day.
All this talk about the polls makes me nervous. It's not over.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He speaks from experience. Four years ago, Bush was the underdog
who pulled off a shocker by beating another popular incumbent
governor, Democrat Ann Richards.
</P>
<P>
   Richards' loss has been blamed in part on her failure to lay out
a new agenda. In this campaign, Bush points to his record, but he
also has outlined plans for the next term.
</P>
<P>
   During his first legislative session, he says, he made good on
his campaign promises to reform welfare, toughen juvenile justice
laws, increase local control of schools and reform civil
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, however, complain that Bush took on a set of goals that
already were on the legislative radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1997 session, Bush wanted to cut school property
taxes by some $4 billion by shifting the tax burden to other areas.
Unable to persuade the Texas Senate _ where his own party holds a
majority _ to approve the deal, he had to settle for a $1 billion
tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   And there have been some controversial decisions he had to make
alone.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Bush refused to halt the execution of pick-ax
killer Karla Faye Tucker, despite pleas from supporters that she
deserved mercy because she had undergone a religious conversion and
was a changed woman. Bush refused to intervene, and she became the
first woman executed in Texas since the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, he commuted the death sentence of Henry Lee
Lucas, who had confessed to numerous murders but then recanted
almost all of them. Bush accepted the Board of Pardons and Paroles'
recommendation to commute Lucas' only death sentence because there
was no evidence linking him to the crime except his recanted
confession.
</P>
<P>
   If he is re-elected, Bush says, he will seek to lower school
property taxes by $2 billion by tapping some of the state's
anticipated $6 billion surplus. He also has proposed eliminating
the sales tax on over-the-counter medicines, suspending the sales
tax on some school items before classes start every year, and
exempting 176,000 small businesses from the state's franchise tax.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the nuts-and-bolts issues, Bush often talks about
ushering in ``a new era of responsibility.'' He urges young people
not to drink, abuse drugs or alcohol and to refrain from having sex
until they are married.
</P>
<P>
   Bush admits to drinking too much earlier in his life and says he
is glad he quit the day after his 40th birthday. He says it isn't
hypocritical for an ex-drinker to tell others not to use alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, did you learn from your mistakes? Are you a
grownup,'' Bush says. ``Yes, I am.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
