<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SHORT TERM, THESE RESULTS ARE DISHEARTENING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am a conservative retiree, 69 years old. Attached is a
schedule of my investments, and I hope you can tell me if my broker
is giving me good advice and what changes, if any, I should make to
give me better, but safe, returns. I am not interested in the stock
market. I'm especially concerned about the Smith Barney Premium
Total Return fund, which the broker tells me is paying 4 percent,
but which rate doesn't show up on my monthly statement. As you can
see, the position lost $5,000 during the month of August. Also, the
Smith Barney Large Cap Blend fund looks suspicious, with only a .77
percent yield. The overall situation looks pretty good, with a
total funding of $430,282 in 1996, withdrawals of $56,662, and a
current balance remaining a credible $461,158. So the investments
must be doing something right.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  J.G., Vidor, Texas
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The reason you didn't see a yield figure for Smith Barney
Premium Total Return on your last statement is because it pays its
dividends quarterly, rather than monthly as do most of the
investments on this portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Your broker was probably right at the time you were told the
fund had a 4 percent return, although the figure had dropped to 3.4
percent by the time of the latest Morningstar Mutual Funds report.
That's still a high payout level for a stock fund, which this one
manages by maintaining a portfolio of companies with above-average
payouts, and also by habitually selling call-covered options. The
latter practice reduces the fund's upside potential in bull
markets, but it also reduces overall risk and increases income.
Morningstar rates it above-average, with a low risk score and
average returns.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on Smith Barney Large-Cap Blend (presuming you have
class B shares) is lower because of its more aggressive investment
stance.
</P>
<P>
   Lipper Analytical Services lists the 12-month yield at .92
percent in its Oct. 8 report, slightly below the 1.07 percent
average for growth and income funds. (Morningstar doesn't track
this fund.) Now, when you combine these two positions, they
represent 14.8 percent of the total portfolio, which is a pretty
small number for the typical investor of your age, but perhaps a
large number for a person who is not ``interested in the stock
market.'' All I can suggest is that such funds have doubtless
played a good part in the overall portfolio performance with which
you seem to be satisfied. Yes, both are in the red so far this
year, with Smith Barney Premium Total Return showing a negative
total return of 7.35 percent through Oct. 8, and with its Large-Cap
Blend fund off 12.36 percent in the same period. But think back to
last year, when Premium Total Return delivered 24.55 percent and
Smith Barney Large Cap Blend fund (then called Smith Barney Growth
and Income fund) returned 22.06 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously the short-term results from these two funds are
disheartening, but I suggest you view them as a small part of a
conservatively balanced portfolio and stick with them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are ages 35 and 34 respectively. We have no
debt and rent a house and have joint annual income of approximately
$70,000 _ $35,000 each. I have a $50,000 CD at 5.34 percent, and my
wife has a $37,000 CD with the same terms. We would like to use
most of this money for a down payment on a house. We began IRAs in
January with 1997 contributions, and have switched them to Roth
accounts. Each has $2,000 in Vanguard Wellington, and for this year
we plan to put $2,000 each into Vanguard Balanced Index. We then
decided to take advantage of a 403(b) program offered through our
employer (we work at the same place). I'm not enthusiastic about
the plan, but it is tax deferred. I feel the charges _ management
fees, mortality fees and so forth _ are astronomical, but I don't
see any alternative. Do you have any suggestions for an
alternative? Our employer says it's the only plan. Couldn't we use
a Vanguard variable annuity and avoid at least the mortality fees?
We have both made the same investment choices, putting 50 percent
of our money in Fidelity Asset Manager and the rest in Fidelity
Equity Income. We each contribute 30 percent of our income. I
enclose the list of investment options; I realize that with our
time horizon being 30 years our allocations may seem a bit
conservative _ I was a bit nervous in January. Would you suggest a
different investment mix?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  M.D., San Diego
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. To start with the idea of using a variable annuity instead of
a 403(b), the big problem is that while money that goes into a
variable annuity account grows on a tax-deferred basis, the
contributions come from after-tax income. The advantage of funding
retirement accounts with pretax dollars, as you are doing through
your 403(b) accounts, is substantial, and would outweigh the lower
fees associated with the variable annuities. All I can suggest is
that you continue to lobby your employer for a 403(b) plan with
better terms.
</P>
<P>
   On your investment choices, I do think you're being much too
conservative. You should think of these plans as 360-month
dollar-cost averaging programs, and thus be willing to disregard
the short-term condition of the market. Fidelity Asset Manager,
which typically holds about 40 percent of its portfolio in cash and
bonds, should prove a serious drag on your returns over the long
haul. Among the 17 options available to you is a stock index fund,
and it offers the highest historical returns of all of the options.
I suggest you move your entire Asset Manager balance and 50 percent
of ongoing contributions there. Since both the index fund and
Fidelity Equity Income fund focus on large-cap stocks, I would then
reduce that concentration a bit by cutting the Equity Income
contributions to 30 percent, putting 10 percent each in the Janus
Mid-Cap and T. Rowe Price Small-Cap Growth options.
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly true that a portfolio such as I suggest will be
more dangerous in bear markets, but the point is that you have a
very long time, and through your program of regular monthly
investments, you will be buying in markets high and low, and while
short-term risks in the market can be considerable, you have too
much time to do anything but take the more aggressive course.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker will answer investors' questions. Send letters,
including your name, address, and telephone number, to: Kenneth
Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
