<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO CLEAN SEPTIC TANK PLUGGED WITH GREASE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. A cleaning of my septic tank revealed that drainage holes
were plugged with a hard, greasy substance, possibly from soap. Is
there a soap that would not create that buildup? Would a grease
remover be advisable?
</P>
<P>
   FRANK BERNARD, Spooner, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. A high-pressure stream from a hose when the tank is pumped
out should knock off those greasy buildups. There are several
things you can do to prevent their returning. Use a detergent, not
a soap, and do not put cooking fats and grease in the tank. A
grease remover is not recommended; such chemicals may dissolve
grease but can kill microorganisms essential to the operation of
the system.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing you should add to your system is baking soda,
which helps brings the sewage into the proper pH level (neutral,
neither acid nor base) to allow bacteria to digest the sewage. Pour
a cup of baking soda down any drain once a week. Nothing else is
needed to add to the system other than what normally goes into it
from drains in house.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am looking for closet poles that will span distances of
four to eight feet in several closets. I think wood would be too
light for the longer spans, even with a center support. What
material would be better: wood or metal?
</P>
<P>
   MIA LAEB, Jonesport, Maine
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Wood (1 1/2 to 2 inches in diameter) is good up to spans of
four to six feet. For longer spans, use a steel rod; you might need
a center support on an eight-foot span.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there a difference in the quality of outdoor light
fixtures, and how do you know the difference? Our four-year-old
house had all brass-plated outdoor fixtures, and all have lost the
shine, are etched and wretched looking. Some that were protected on
the front stoop also need replacing. Does anyone make a quality of
brass that resists the elements? How do you evaluate the quality? I
don't want to replace fixtures every three-four years.
</P>
<P>
   B. SPARKS, Somewhere in the U.S.A.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You are the victim of the ``Save money in a house by
installing cheap fixtures and other accessories'' syndrome.
Contractors have to save money in building any house, and do it by
putting in cheap accessories; by the time they deteriorate, the
house is out of warranty and the owner is left holding the junk,
such as inferior lamps, bathroom fixtures, and hardware, and so-so
kitchen cabinetry. This junk, unfortunately, is within code.
</P>
<P>
   There are quality light fixtures at building supply and lighting
stores, all expensive. If you like brass, specify solid brass; you
can determine that by putting a magnet on the brass; if the magnet
does not stick, it is solid brass; if it sticks, it is brass
plated, something to avoid. Sometimes aluminum is brass plated,
another thing to avoid. But even solid brass will tarnish and
corrode; it is the nature of brass to do this, and outdoors it is
best left tarnished. Some brass is lacquered, to make it stay
shiny, but this does not work well outdoors, and when the lacquer
peels or wears off, the fixture looks worse than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Other quality fixtures are cast iron, black painted aluminum, or
copper, which will also corrode and turn to that familiar green
patina, which is good. Sometimes brass or aluminum is painted
black, which is also OK.
</P>
<P>
   Expect to pay anywhere from $60 or so to hundreds of dollars for
quality fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufpibox &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Remember Attilio Ceraldi's question about a high-pitched hum in
his refrigerator? The handyman gave a long explanation of how to
reduce it by lining the refrigerator enclosure with acoustical
tiles.
</P>
<P>
   That might have helped, but Sharon Rogers (no town listed) wrote
to tell us what she did about her humming refrigerator. ``I had the
same problem, and a friend also had the problem with a fairly new
refrigerator. With both our refrigerators it turned out that the
drip pan was left loosely taped in place after delivery. Once the
drip pan was pulled out, the shipping tape removed, the pan cleaned
and put back into place, the noise stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such a simple solution to a very annoying problem!''
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, Sharon Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufpibox &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Here's a question on a roof that has not been answered, so
far. I have lichen all over the roof. How can I remove it?
</P>
<P>
   H.S., North Andover
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Ah, lichen; or rather, my goodness, lichen! It is a
combination of a fungus and algae, is light green or gray, grows on
many surfaces and, in the handyman's experience, is virtually
impossible to remove. It is impervious to bleach. A wire brush
might remove it, but will also destroy the shingles. A reader once
wrote that she removed lichen with a bristle scrub brush, but that,
too, could ruin asphalt shingles.
</P>
<P>
   So, the handyman asks, is there anyone out there who knows how
to remove lichen safely from asphalt shingles? H.S. of North
Andover and the handyman would love to find out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Call in your questions on 617-929-2930. Globe Handyman on Call
Peter Hotton is available on Tuesdays from 1 p.m. to 6 p.m. to
answer telephone questions on house repair. Hotton will chat on
line about house matters Thursdays, 1-2 p.m. To participate, point
your Internet browser to http://www.boston.com and use keyword:
chat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
