<HEADLINE>
A SOGGY SAGA OF HERSHEY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R. WHITE 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HERSHEY, Pa. _ Sometimes life is just a wash-out. First it was
the annual International Motor Press Association Test Day that got
rained out at Pocono Raceway in Pennsylvania's eastern hills _
barely time to look at a couple of vehicles. Then it was the annual
Hershey regional meet of the Antique Automobile Club of America, a
monster auto show and flea market on the grounds of Hershey Foods
Co. (the folks who make the cocoa and candy bars) where the
monsoons struck.
</P>
<P>
   To the regulars in the old-car hobby who flock here every
October, the event is simply known as ``Hershey.'' It is difficult
to comprehend the immensity of this rite of autumn where Hershey
Park, a vast complex of stadium, amusement park, factory store, and
even vaster grassy fields separated by roads is turned into a tent
city of 28,000 souls overnight. Suddenly this pretty little company
town is home to a sprawling refugee camp cum junkyard wherein you
may find parts for obscure autos, whole vehicles, automobilia, and
such diverse offerings as musical instruments, boats, pedal cars,
cameras, lamps, gas pumps, an occasional boat _ once an airplane.
It was reliably reported that 10,225 vendor spots were rented, each
with a 10-foot frontage on a ``street,'' usually a grassy path. All
in a row, that would be 19.36 miles of commerce.
</P>
<P>
   It used to start on Wednesday; now the setup begins on Monday
and the wheeling and dealing continues through Saturday, the day of
the huge antique car show in the stadium parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional beginning for many of us is the Wednesday night
gathering of writers, collectors, publishers, editors, and auto
industry types at Harry's Tavern, a neighborhood establishment in,
to put it kindly, a rundown section of Harrisburg. A thinking
person wouldn't go there without police escort _ a lot of the
residents seem to have frequent police escorts of the custodial
type. Yet in 25 years of this tradition, nothing untoward has
happened _ except to Harry's, which has changed hands a couple of
times largely because of the robbery rate.
</P>
<P>
   Once, when Harry's was between administrations, so to speak, the
group switched to a hotel in Hummelstown. This Wednesday, a call to
Harry's elicits the information that the telephone has been
disconnected _ ``no further information.'' Harry's is kaput. John
Lawlor of WBZ and NPR has joined me this year, his first trip,
primed for Harry's; in disappointment, we head for Hummels-town _
eventually 15 of the group, most of whom have found Harry's boarded
up, home in on Hummels-town for the tradition. There is joy in
mudville again _ and the steaks are better here. But it's raining.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning we hitch a ride with a vendor to the Green
Field, a major duchy in the flea market empire, and begin trudging
the lanes in search of ... in my case a column or two. I find a
couple of battered baritone horns, a trombone, and a three-bell
bugle among the oddities. The Eastwood tent is busy where John
``The Bankman'' is eyeballing the miniature truck banks. But most
everything is buttoned up against the downpour. Even with
umbrellas, we are soaked.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, we head for the car corral where hundreds of
antique cars are on view, on sale _ a better show than the
scheduled show. At least it's paved; the grassy paths are now
sticky, sodden, clay morasses. Here I find an appropriate vehicle,
a 1964 Amphicar, apparently in very good condition (19K miles,
$15,500). I wander back to the Green Field, soaked, then discover
my notebook is in a pocket full of water, now blue-stained mush _ I
should have heeded the advice of the late Doug Crocket and brought
a pencil.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the rain continues and the White Field is virtually
impassable, but business is booming anyway _ desperation has set
in. The dealers in paper goods are suffering. The price of plastic
ponchos, $1.50 yesterday, has inched up to $3.50 today. Today I
bring the van, the Honda Odyssey, with a change of clothes for the
Society of Auto Historians' dinner in the evening and slog the
Chocolate Field in search of copy. I talk to people selling things
but nothing really odd, such as last year's phony Stradivarius or
the hearse trader. Lawlor is eyeing a Cadillac, laboring under a
pile of stuff for his grandchildren. In the afternoon, sopping wet,
boots caked with mud the consistency of hardened concrete, I head
for the van parked in a field a mile away. The field is a soggy
mess; hours later I arrive at the dinner site much too late to
participate.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, it is back with the van, drop Lawlor at the Harrisburg
airport, then back to Hershey to find a parking spot _ that field
again. Here, slicker-clad traffic directors with official airport
batons direct the Honda into a hog wallow, certain to mire it until
spring. They push, they grunt, finally announce they will send for
a tractor, and move off to direct others into the mud. I wait,
listening to the radio; in a half hour the wheels are dry, the mud
is caked, and I ease the Odyssey into reverse, gently move it until
it slips, then brake the wheels to a complete stop, ease into
first. After three or four repeats of this, the Odyssey finds firm
ground and I head for a parking spot. The baton man is in front of
me again, wig-wagging me toward what looks like another wallow. I
am going to park where he is standing and, when he finally figures
that out, he has barely time to leap out of my way.
</P>
<P>
   At the stadium auto show, many slots are vacant; the
participants and their cars are mired somewhere in the fields. But
it is a wonderful array of old iron nonetheless. I gravitate to
where a crowd has gathered to find a familiar face, Frank Hix of
Estes Park, Colo., explaining the charms of steam power as the
onlookers admire his 1916 Stanley Roadster.
</P>
<P>
   The rain has let up and area farmers are busy supplying tractor
power to free vendor vehicles from the grip of Hershey mud. So far
all I have accomplished today is a bad lunch and wet feet. I head
home.
</P>
<P>
   It is 12:30 a.m. Sunday, raining, on Route 290 in Worcester, and
I find out how good the Odyssey really is when a young woman in a
Detroit barge slides into my lane doing about 80. I avoid her but
the Chevy in front of me isn't so lucky. She hits it twice, caroms
over to the retaining wall, blows a tire and grinds off the other
side of the car on the wall, bounces back onto the road _ and hits
the gas. Twice more she nails the Chevy, then spins in front of it,
back up the other side and she's heading for me again. She has hit
everything but the brakes. The Odyssey responds, everybody parks.
The woman is distraught, the Chevy owner furious, the State Police
quick to arrive and take charge.
</P>
<P>
   I am home two hours later _ wide awake, contemplating my
problem: How does one explain ``washout'' to his editor while
submitting an expense account?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
