u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDUFF-BODIES-$ADV18-     10-16 1985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDUFF-BODIES-$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCDUFF-BODIES-$ADV18 
 
CONVICTED KILLER MCDUFF MANIPULATED SYSTEM, LEFT HOMETOWN IN
TERROR 
 
EDITORS, PLEASE NOTE: FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 18 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSEBUD, Texas _ He didn't just kill his victims, he savaged
them in unspeakable ways.
</P>
<P>
   He raped them with a measure of sadism that made grizzled cops
cringe. He blew their faces off at close range. He slashed and
stabbed with knives and bludgeoned with clubs and crushed their
necks with broom sticks.
</P>
<P>
   He preyed on the relatively defenseless. A couple of his victims
were young boys. Most were young women. ``Killing a woman's like
killing a chicken,'' he once told an accomplice. ``They both
squawk.''
</P>
<P>
   Tall, dour and icy-eyed, Kenneth Allen McDuff is the hometown
boy this small town southeast of Waco would like to forget, but
can't.
</P>
<P>
   He keeps coming back, usually in bad memories, sometimes in the
flesh, sometimes in chilling rumor. He's been scattering corpses
around Central Texas _ no one knows how many, but estimates have
ranged upwards of 15 _ since he was a teen-ager. He's now 52 and
still awaiting the ultimate punishment, still haunting his home
town.
</P>
<P>
   He is under two death sentences but may not live long enough to
be executed. His liver is being destroyed by Hepatitis C and
cirrhosis. But among his former neighbors, there are jittery
confessions of an irrational fear _ that somehow, McDuff, who has
slipped through the cracks of the judicial and penal systems with
mindboggling alacrity, will do it again and will come home once
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are actually afraid that he'll get out somehow and
come back here,'' said a retired schoolteacher who asked that her
name not be used.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really sad,'' said Glen Stock, a Rosebud, Texas, city
councilman and former classmate of McDuff's. ``It's been a long
time and he's still going on. He has worked the legal system better
than anybody I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Those fears were fueled by an unusual series of events in the
past three weeks. McDuff was scheduled to be executed Wednesday for
the murders of two young women in 1991 and 1992, crimes he
committed while on parole from a life sentence for a triple
homicide in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   The body of one of those women, Colleen Reed, had never been
found. Neither had the bodies of several others McDuff was believed
to have killed. As his execution neared, state and federal
appellate courts regularly were refusing to hear his case or were
ruling against him.
</P>
<P>
   Then, late in September, federal district judges in Austin and
Waco, Texas, granted stays of execution. Almost immediately, the
U.S. attorney's office and Texas Rangers, acting on information
from an informant they declined to identify, unearthed two of
McDuff's alleged victims in McLennan County near Waco. A third,
Colleen Reed, was found buried beside the Brazos River in a grassy
area that had been a popular fishing and partying spot for the
teen-agers of Rosebud when McDuff was growing up.
</P>
<P>
   No one here doubted that McDuff was the anonymous informant. Who
else could have pinpointed the bodies so precisely, they asked. An
electric rumor crackled on the streets: McDuff had come back in a
black limousine to point out the bodies. It was denied by lawmen,
but it was affirmation of what the townsfolk think McDuff is
capable of doing. At the least, they suspected he had made a deal:
the bodies in exchange for a little more time to beat the
executioner.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Johnston, the assistant U.S. attorney in Waco, said they
were wrong, but they were not persuaded. They knew Kenneth McDuff
too well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always did sort of what he wanted to,'' said James Hudson,
a banker who went to school with McDuff. ``If he got in trouble,
he'd run home and hide and his mother would bail him out.''
</P>
<P>
   His father was a cement contractor who worked hard and earned a
good living. The family lived in a two-story house, across the
street from a coin-operated laundry, which his mother ran when she
wasn't defending her son, which was often.
</P>
<P>
   Addie McDuff was known around town as ``Pistol-Packing Mama''
because she usually carried a .45 and, according to Rosebud legend,
once toted it to school to confront a teacher who had disciplined
Kenneth. Another story, passed around for decades, has it that she
used the gun to flag down and dress down a school bus driver who
had ejected her son for fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Though she had another son and four daughters, she doted on
Kenneth, a slow learner, who, by most accounts, began his criminal
career in the sixth grade and dropped out of school in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was overprotective and excused everything he did,'' said
the former teacher. ``He stole a billfold with $100 from a woman at
the Washateria. His mother argued with the woman and denied that
Kenneth took it. Well, the woman called the sheriff and Kenneth
handed over the billfold.''
</P>
<P>
   She dressed him in nice clothes, provided him a generous
allowance and made certain that in material possessions he was
always a step ahead of the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us used to have these little motor scooters, the ones
with the small engines that you didn't have to have a license to
ride,'' said Stock. ``He had a Harley Davidson. He wasn't big
enough to kick-start it, so his brother would start it for him in
the morning so he could ride the two blocks to school. Then, he had
to push it home.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he drove new cars and wrecked them as fast as his mother
could pay for them, according to Mike Baca, another former
schoolmate. ``I don't know how many cars he tore up. He tore up so
many the Ford dealer quit selling to him,'' Baca grinned.
</P>
<P>
   Because he made no effort to succeed in school, he had been held
back and was older than the others in his class, and bigger. He
bullied, insulted them and took their lunch money. Until the eighth
grade when Tommy Sammon, a popular athlete, accepted his challenge
and met him in a drainage ditch after school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took about 30 seconds for Tommy to take care of him,'' Baca
said. ``Kenneth never bothered anybody again.''
</P>
<P>
   Except his teachers.
</P>
<P>
   In his sophomore year, the principal sent him home for
disrupting a class. His older brother, Lonnie, who had a speech
impediment and referred to himself as ``Wuff, tuff Wonnie McDuff,''
went to the school with a knife. While some students watched from
their classroom, he bounded up the stairs to where D.L. Mayo, a
college football All-American before he was a school principal, was
bending over a drinking fountain. Mayo saw Lonnie from the corner
of his eye, spun around, disarmed him, lifted him off his feet and
tossed him back down the stairs. Kenneth never returned to school.
</P>
<P>
   Many years later, Lonnie would be shot to death by the
ex-husband of his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1994, we were planning our 30-year class reunion,'' said
Stock. ``Most of us in that class have done pretty well, but
Kenneth's the only one who made national news. I suggested that we
invite him to be our speaker.''
</P>
<P>
   McDuff became as famous for cheating the system as for his
crimes. He wiggled out of arrests for burglary, theft or robbery
until, at the age of 18, he was nailed for a string of burglaries
in Falls, Bell and Milam counties in Texas. McDuff could have
received sentences totaling more than 50 years. He got four and was
out in 10 months.
</P>
<P>
   While on parole and working in his father's concrete business,
he and a running buddy named Roy Dale Green finished work one
Saturday night in the summer of 1966 and drove to Fort Worth
looking for action.
</P>
<P>
   At a baseball field, they spotted three teen-agers _ two boys
and a girl, ages 15, 16 and 17. McDuff took a .38 pistol from under
the seat of his car, the new Dodge Charger he received from his
mother when he was paroled, and robbed them.
</P>
<P>
   He ordered them into the trunk of their own car and drove it to
a field outside of town. Green followed in the Charger. McDuff took
the girl out of the trunk, shot the two boys twice in the face,
then lifted one of them by the hair and shot him again.
</P>
<P>
   Forcing the girl to undress, they drove her to another location
and repeatedly raped her. McDuff dragged the girl out of the car
and threw her naked into the middle of the road. While Green held
her legs, McDuff crushed her throat with a broomstick.
</P>
<P>
   For reporting the crimes and cooperating with the police, Green
got five years. McDuff was sentenced to die in the electric chair.
</P>
<P>
   Addie McDuff attended every day of the trial and refused to
accept her son's guilt. During one recess, she said Kenneth had
actually been with a girl from his church the night of the murders,
but was keeping quiet to protect her reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's too good for his own good,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it seemed that the courts and the prisons were as
protective of him as his mother had been. After six years on death
row, his sentence was commuted to life when the U.S. Supreme Court
banned capital punishment in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   That meant he could, one day, be paroled again and events
conspired to help him toward that goal. Federal court mandates to
ease prison overcrowding in the 1970s and 1980s created a
precipitous turnover in the prison population and McDuff tried to
speed his own release by offering a deal he thought a parole board
member couldn't refuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get me out of this pen,'' he told Glenn Heckman in
1981, ``I guarantee that $10,000 will be left in the glove
compartment of your car. My family's got the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Being convicted of bribery would have made him a three-time
loser under the habitual criminal act that existed then, and he
could have received another life sentence _ forestalling any
possibility of parole. Instead, a confused jury returned a two-year
sentence, which, in effect was no sentence at all. He had already
earned that much good time.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the pressures to thin the prison population led to
his release _ in late 1989 _ and he went back to Rosebud. Along the
relaxed streets of the community of 1,600, doors were suddenly kept
locked. Women who had once taken evening walks for exercise stayed
indoors. Some carried knives or large scissors on the front seats
of their cars.
</P>
<P>
   But McDuff didn't stay long. He accosted three young black men
in a park. He shouted a racial slur at them and chased them down an
alley with a knife. It was enough to cause his parole to be
revoked, but not enough to keep him behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   Charges of ``making terroristic threats'' were not prosecuted
because the three victims were too frightened to testify. Two
months later, his parole was reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   He settled this time in Waco to attend a technical school and
almost immediately young women in the area _ many believed to be
prostitutes _ began disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   When he became a suspect, McDuff fled to Kansas City where he
was arrested after his picture appeared on the television show
``America's Most Wanted.'' He went back to prison under Texas' new
death penalty law.
</P>
<P>
   Though other charges were filed, only two were prosecuted _ the
murder of Melissa Northrup, a 22-year-old pregnant mother of two,
whom he abducted from a Waco convenience store, and that of Colleen
Reed, a 21-year-old accountant who was kidnapped from an Austin car
wash.
</P>
<P>
   When Reed's body and two others were found recently, there was
speculation that perhaps instead of a deal, Kenneth McDuff, facing
imminent death, had found his conscience and it drove him to
surrender the victims' remains.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Ranger Matt Cawthon laughed when he heard that theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is evil, evil incarnate,'' Cawthon said. ``The things he
did to other human beings were unconscionable.''
</P>
<P>
   His advice to Rosebud? Relax. Kenneth McDuff isn't coming home
again.
</P>
<P>
   A new execution date is set for Nov. 17. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
