<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-JUDGE-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT JUDGE REGARDED AS TOUGH BUT FAIR
 &HT;    With MICROSOFT-BIOBOX. Moving in (w) Washington and (f)
financial categories for release Monday, Oct. 19.
 &HT;    A black and white file photo of Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson
photo is available in the National folder on the Cox server.
 &HT;    By MARY BETH REGAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Last December, when Microsoft Corp. insisted that
the Windows 95 operating system wouldn't work without its Internet
browser, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson decided to
find out for himself.
</P>
<P>
   With help from a courtroom technician, the judge was able to
``uninstall'' his own Explorer Internet browser in about 90
seconds. With that, Jackson ordered the software giant to begin
selling Windows 95 separate from its browser.
</P>
<P>
   While that order was overturned on appeal _ leading eventually
to the new Justice Department suit against Microsoft based on the
Windows 98 software that goes to trial Monday _ Jackson's dive into
the technical aspects of the case is indicative of his approach to
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom calls it like he sees it,'' says James Schaller, his
former law partner at Jackson &AMP; Campbell in Washington. ``That's
his signature. Most people respect him for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, 61, will be presiding over what has been billed as the
antitrust lawsuit of the decade. The suit pits the Justice
Department and the attorneys general of 20 states against
Microsoft, the world's leading software company. At issue: Whether
Microsoft has used its dominance in the market for personal
computer operating systems to stifle competition in application
markets such as Internet browsers.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is no newcomer to the national spotlight. The burly
white-haired judge was appointed to the bench in 1982 by President
Reagan. In 1991, he sent Washington Mayor Marion Barry to jail for
cocaine possession. Three years later, he ordered former Sen. Bob
Packwood, R-Ore., to turn over sex-filled diary entries to a Senate
Ethics Committee. And last year, he fined Reagan's former aide
Michael Deaver $100,000 for lying about lobbying activities.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's Washington roots run deep. He grew up in the city's
affluent suburbs, attending the exclusive St. Alban's School. He
sang for the Washington Cathedral Choir.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to Dartmouth College. Upon graduation, he joined the
U.S. Navy as a line officer, spending three years aboard a
destroyer in the Atlantic and Mediterranean. He returned to Harvard
University Law School, graduating in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to Washington, Jackson worked with his father, Thomas
Searing Jackson, a well-known Washington lawyer, at a predecessor
firm to Jackson &AMP; Campbell. The father of two grown daughters, he
loves sailing and spends weekends in St. Mary's County, Md.
</P>
<P>
   In the hallways of the U.S. District Court, prosecutors and
defense attorneys say Jackson is an affable, able judge who runs a
tight ship. A former litigator, he's considerate of the time
pressures on overworked lawyers. Also, he's been known to show
compassion for those sentenced. One defense attorney recalls
Jackson using flexibility in sentencing a former military medic who
served in Panama. The reason: The man had served his country during
war without a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Jackson is not without critics. The gossipy
Washingtonian magazine lambasted him in 1996, calling him one of
Washington's worst lawyers. In 1995, the trade publication Legal
Times took him to task for moving slowly and calling long lunch
breaks. A 1993 Legal Times analysis, however, showed that his
reversal rate was about 18 percent. And former clerks describe the
judge as a warm, mentoring boss who takes a personal interest in
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   No one denies he has a tough side. Jackson repeatedly has gone
head-to-head with Microsoft. Following the browser incident, he
threatened the company's lawyers with contempt sanctions because he
said they defamed a court-appointed expert, Lawrence Lessig. Lessig
is no longer serving as the court's special master in the Microsoft
case.
</P>
<P>
   In the trial, Jackson is expected to show his signature
tenacity, digging deep into the technical merits of the case. He's
unlikely to stray beyond established law.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very fair,'' said Michael Volkov, an assistant U.S.
Attorney in Washington. ``But he'll enjoy a hard-fought trial.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
