<HEADER>
A1681 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-16 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN KENNETH GALBRAITH: A VOICE WORTH HEEDING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ For John Kenneth Galbraith, this life has
been a 90-year run of merry adventure and diligent, breezily
intellectual reflection.
</P>
<P>
   What he has stood for is a staunch, historically derived,
politically battle-tested and cleverly argued liberalism. His
liberalism realistically appraises human nature, rigorously defends
legitimate aspirations, and gleefully attacks the greedy cant spun
off like mud from the spinning wheels of runaway capitalism. You
simply cannot argue political economy and fail to take Galbraith
into account.
</P>
<P>
   The birthday of Harvard's famous and prolific professor was
celebrated Thursday night at the school named for his most prized
associate, John F. Kennedy, by that iconic figure's brother (Ted),
son (John) and the surviving galaxy of American liberalism. Coming
off the Ontario farm, Galbraith decided early to work with his head
rather than his hands, that the brain, not the back, was the muscle
he favored, and that judicious courting of power was the way to go.
That he's been very good at it was amply demonstrated.
</P>
<P>
   The turnout was top-shelf, and the video tribute (narrator:
Walter Cronkite) featured encomiums from Clinton &AMP; Gore. Harvard
runs lots of shindigs with intellectual candlepower on parade, but
this one featured warmth as well as light for a scholar who's
chowed at the Faculty Club for 65 years. Ted Kennedy ignited the
drumroll, recalling how Galbraith's father, a prairie liberal, once
addressed a farm gathering from atop a manure pile, declaring he
was ``standing on the Conservative Party platform.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean Joe Nye and Marin Kalb of the K School presided; Willian
vanden Heuvel bestowed a $25,000 prize upon the canny
Scots-Canadian economist. Nader Darehshori, Galbraith's publisher
at Houghton Mifflin, where the lanky professor enjoys a 46-year
run, was co-host, and highlighted the truly astonishing appeal of a
graceful writer who's produced 40-odd books on serious subjects
elaborated light-heartedly.
</P>
<P>
   In an advance copy of ``Between Friends,'' a collection of
essays on Galraith by 16 notables, the great man himself counsels:
``All authors should seek to establish a relationship of warmth,
affection and mutual mistrust with their publishers in the hope
that the uncertainty will add, however marginally, to
compensation.'' More hints to writers: Rewrite ruthlessly so ``the
product improves,'' and get to be a regular book reviewer. Why? It
``causes other reviewers, contemplating the reception of their own
books, to be marginally more judicious.''
</P>
<P>
   President Neil Rudenstine positioned Galbraith generously in the
Harvard constellation, alluding eliptically to Galbraith's lifelong
habit of volunteering advice on weighty subjects, in this case
Harvard's recent erosion in the endowment's bottom line. John F.
Kennedy Jr. showed again why he is the best public speaker of the
whole Kennedy food chain, for voice, manner, looks, self-possession
and modesty; his sang froid simply sizzles.
</P>
<P>
   Galbraith's three sons and his wife of 61 years, the widely
revered Kitty, were represented by a short and graceful toast from
son James, a boffin at University of Texas, who located his old
man's place in the pantheon of philosopher-economists alongside
such as John Stuart Mill, John Maynard Keynes and Marx (Karl, not
Groucho).
</P>
<P>
   William F. Buckley Jr., for decades the opposite bookend to
Galbraith's secure placement on the Lively Left, contributed his
patented barbs-dressed-as-irony. These two have long played
straight man to the other's ideological polarity, and their
affection is as durable as it is apparent. Arthur Schlesinger and
Gloria Steinem unveiled the new Galbraith Fund for fellowships
devoted to ``public service and humane ideals,'' jump-started with
over $600,000 in initial donations.
</P>
<P>
   The birthday cake was rolled forth in front of a kilted
bagpiper. No one was having a better time than the Birthday Boy,
who asked the piper: ``Do you know `The Campbells Are Coming?'''
Galbraith's remarks were brief, witty, and expansive. He is a man
who enjoys life, revels in a happy family situation, is more
cautious with his wealth than with his advice, and never loses
sight of the fact that life is a lot better for a lot more folks at
the end of this century than at the beginning, which is where he
came in.
</P>
<P>
   He looked forward gaily to his next big bash, at his 95th, and
there was no one present who did not wish to make that party as
well. Associates from a long public life toasted his health: George
McGovern, Kitty Dukakis, Katherine Graham, Tom Winship, John
Silber, Profs. Carl Kaysen and Nathan Glazer, and `formers' like
ex-Labor Secretary Robert Reich, and ex-Sen. Alan Simpson of
Wyoming. Roy Jenkins, the British politician now out of office long
enough to be called a statesman and be introduced as Lord Jenkins
of Hillhead, flew from Oxford with his wife to pronounce Galbraith
an international treasure.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts never got to vote for Galbraith. He wrote in
``Letters to Kennedy,'' his correspondence with JFK, that when
Kennedy offered him the ambassadorship to India, Galbraith asked
Kennedy: ``Would that be more useful than the Senate with the
prospect of bringing some decency back to Massachusetts Democratic
politics?'' He said yes, `by a factor of five to one.' Freshman
senators are not very useful; did I really want to spend my time
with Massachusetts politicians whom he described amiably as `that
gang of thieves.' I told him I would not raise the matter again.''
</P>
<P>
   That book is a goldmine for political sophisticates. In one
letter to Kennedy, Galbraith counseled there are three
qualifications for appointing office-holders: ``ability, political
acceptability and personal loyalty.'' He added: ``I have difficulty
in appreciating your use of Dean Acheson (Truman's Secretary of
State, then advising JFK). He is able. He has reestablished himself
politically with the right. But I cannot think he is capable of
loyalty. He will be a source of trouble for he wants the policy
that serves his ego, not your needs.''
</P>
<P>
   In that same letter from India in 1961, Galbraith warned Kennedy
that the situation in ``South Vietnam is exceedingly bad. I hope,
incidentally, that your information from there is good and I have
an uneasy feeling that what comes in regular channels is very bad.
Unless I am mistaken Diem has alienated his people to a far greater
extent than we allow ourselves to know. This is our old mistake. We
take the ruler's word and that of our own people who have become
committed to him... But I fear that we have one more government
which, on present form, no one will support.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be 14 years, and 55,000 American soldiers dead, and a
million Vietnamese lives wasted in war, before that letter's gloomy
forecast was apparent to Washington. Then, as now, Galbraith's was
a voice worth heeding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
