<HEADER>
A1694 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHORS-BARRETT-SPI &LR;      10-16 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHORS-BARRETT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARRETT BUOYED BY ACCLAIM FOR `VOYAGE OF THE NARWHAL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andrea Barrett had toiled for three years on her first novel,
revising the manuscript six times while supporting herself doing
various menial jobs, everything from dental-surgery assistant to
greenhouse technician to tax-form typist.
</P>
<P>
   Then Barrett finally summoned enough courage to attend her first
writers conference, lugging her manuscript along with her hopes.
One of the teachers there was intrigued enough to read it and offer
his appraisal: Forget it. Move on to something else. Too much has
been done to this for it ever to amount to much of anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was right,'' confirmed Barrett, winner of the 1996 National
Book Award for fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett's own reaction was much different 14 years ago when
writing teacher Nicholas Delbanco offered his assessment of her
first novel. She spent an entire day in tears, then five more days
in a disheartened rereading of the manuscript until she finally
consigned it to the wastebasket. She later did the same with her
second novel, since it seemed to suffer from the same problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad they're (the novels) both gone; they were both so
terrible,'' Barrett added in an interview during a tour to promote
her excellent new novel, ``The Voyage of the Narwhal'' (W.W.
Norton, 399 pages, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   Becoming a writer of literary fiction these days, as Barrett's
example shows, often is a test of resolve and nerve perhaps as much
as of writing talent. And even with those attributes, it all can
come to naught. There is too much competition, too few readers, too
little criticism, too many skittish publishers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, every once in a while, a worthy literary writer such as
Barrett will emerge, often as a result of some major prize or some
other stroke of good fortune, and to no one's surprise more than
the writer's.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett had written four well-received, but slow-selling novels
before ``Ship Fever,'' a collection of stories and a novella for
which she had no great expectations beyond her past work. Indeed, a
collection seemed even more chancy than a novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a very real chance it would not be published,
especially since I had such a bad track record with sales of my
four novels,'' Barrett said. ``So when my publisher, Norton, did a
beautiful book and it got some nice reviews and went on to sell
6,500 copies, I was pleased. If it had all stopped right there, I
would have been a very happy woman.''
</P>
<P>
   But it did not stop there. ``Ship Fever'' was named finalist for
the National Book Award, the second-most prestigious prize in
American publishing after the Pulitzer, and Barrett soon found
herself in the audience for the gala ceremony at the
Waldorf-Astoria Hotel in New York City, her first black-tie event.
</P>
<P>
   She had been persuaded to draft some comments in the event she
won, as all finalists are, but Barrett was so certain she would not
need them that she did not bring her reading glasses in her tiny
evening purse. Then her name was called as the winner and she was
so stunned she thought she might be sick to her stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Barrett is still stunned as she reaps more
rewards from the National Book Award.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Voyage of the Narwhal'' is receiving the sort of prominent
and serious reviews that only works by the most notable writers are
accorded and it is nearing best-seller status.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett has almost finished her first book tour, a cross-country
hopscotch through 17 cities, where she has been facing a series of
interviewers and a host of her readers, meeting more people in the
past two weeks than the intensely private writer used to meet in a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I literally can't believe it on some days,'' she admitted.
``In the middle of a reading, I'll sometimes realize what I'm doing
and I get so startled that my voice will freeze up. I have to force
myself not to be conscious that people are actually listening to me
because it seems such madness.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett's refreshing honesty is only one of her appealing traits
in the still-unexpected glare of attention. The 43-year-old writer
from Rochester, N.Y., comes across as bright, earnest, modest and
thoughtful. There is about her a certain elegance and reserve, too,
traits that, in these Jerry Springer days, seem oddly 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   That is not a coincidence. Barrett has been fascinated with the
19th century since girlhood when her love of reading led her into
the fiction of that time and the accounts of its arctic explorers,
those compelling true sagas of life and death and solitude in the
white world of ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ship Fever'' and now ``The Voyage of Narwhal'' reflect that
19th-century fascination, with their focus on the bygone era's
sense of wonder and restraint, plus a writing style to reflect that
time.
</P>
<P>
   As Barrett explained, ``I attempt to emulate 19th-century
restraint in writing and in talking of personal issues because I
value restraint. I like prose that is cleaner; I like fiction that
hints more subtly than shrieks when dealing with emotion. Not
everybody likes that, I recognize. Some people find me too quiet in
person; some find my books too quiet, too. But that's OK. I am
quiet and so are my books.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Voyage of Narwhal'' showcases Barrett's remarkable
talents, her poetic descriptions, her measured plotting, her
masterful grasp of science, her marvelous depictions of landscape,
both physical and mental.
</P>
<P>
   But this novel of an ill-fated arctic expedition in the 1850s is
not a mere photocopy of what might have been written back then.
Barrett infuses her novel with concerns of the 20th century, the
power of celebrity, the dangers of obsession, the drawbacks of
``progress,'' the mistreatment of indigenous peoples, the
distortions of ``truth,'' the aftermath of fame.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett's novel shows the distinct benefits of her own
background in science _ she majored in biology in college and once
expected to become a scientist (as are many of her friends and her
husband). It also shows the depth of her immersion in the accounts
of 19th-century ex plorers.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett admitted she read 350 books about those explorers for
her novel, more than necessary perhaps, but also indicative of the
breadth of her mind and the nature of her approach to her work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a belief amounting to a superstition about the need to
throw myself into a swimming pool filled with the books of a period
in order that, by some strange osmosis, it will enter my writing
through my unconscious,'' she said. ``I believe that the only way
to write historical fiction that is alive is for me to sink so
deeply into a period that I know it as well as I know now. Besides,
I'm a slow learner and not an economical writer. I will sometimes
spend a year reading 100 books for a 20-page short story, as I did
for `Rare Bird' in `Ship Fever.'''
</P>
<P>
   This might lead some observers to infer that Barrett is a
glutton for literary punishment, subjecting herself to too many
weighty volumes. She strongly counters that notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not onerous work for me _ I love it,'' she stressed.
``I do this not because I'm some virtuous creature; I do this for
me. It's play for me and I can't believe that anybody lets me get
away with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
