<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SMITH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE JOY OF WORK' _ DILBERT SHARES SOME FUN-LOVING TIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scott Adams can afford to skewer corporate America. He doesn't
work there anymore.
</P>
<P>
   But the creator of the Dilbert comic strip hasn't forgotten the
millions who do, and who rely on his wicked renderings of life in
cubicle-ville to make their days more bearable.
</P>
<P>
   That's why he wrote ``The Joy of Work _ Dilbert's Guide to
Finding Happiness at the Expense of your Co-workers'' (Harper
Business, 1998, $22).
</P>
<P>
   Adams considers himself a workplace expert of sorts, even though
he quit his engineering job several years ago and now operates from
a home office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get hundreds of messages a day,'' said Adams, who solicits
e-mail on the strip. ``Plus, every time I go out the door, I get
stopped by people who want to tell me their own stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the well of business stupidity runs deep and Adams said
he's nowhere close to running out of inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   The workplace seems to breed bad ideas, he said. ``Whenever you
get three smart people together, they get stupid collectively.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be bad for people at work, but it's great fun for
Adams, who said there's no danger Dilbert will become a
telecommuter in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   His cast of characters includes his alter ego, the endlessly
deadpan Dilbert, as well as Catbert, the evil human resources
director; Dogbert, the maniacal adviser; Ratbert, the hapless temp
with low self-esteem; Wally, the woefully stupid co-worker; and the
always illustrious pointy-haired boss.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ongoing workplace traumas of his characters, Adams
said the real workers of America have reason to hope.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, workers were cringing under their desks for fear
of downsizing, he said. With unemployment at all-time lows, they
have more clout today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good time to get your revenge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And revenge is one of Adams' main areas of expertise, according
to his latest management tome.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few suggested activities for improving your own
morale at the expense of others.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fun with phones. ``If you have at least two co-workers you
don't like, that's all you need for phone fun,'' he writes. ``Sneak
into the cubicle of one of them and forward the phone to the other.
This is especially effective if they dislike each other as much as
you dislike them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Dress codes. ``Create an update to the employee dress code.
For realism, make sure it has no basis in common sense,'' he said.
For example, as a helpful transition to ``casual Fridays,''
institute a ``stained Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In your memo, point out that this is the sort of management
change that creates winning companies,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Multishirking. All you need for this is a hands-free headset
for your telephone, he writes. ``Once you're properly equipped, you
can make personal phone calls while simultaneously using your
computer for personal entertainment. ... Multishirking is not only
fun, it doubles the odds that an observer will think you're doing
at least one work-related activity.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has other helpful tips.
</P>
<P>
   For example, on the joy of sarcasm, he writes: ``Sarcasm can get
you fired if your boss realizes you aren't being a team player. But
that risk is low. Your sarcasm will go safely undetected if you
simply use your boss's own words. This is obviously the easiest
form of sarcasm to master, since it requires no creativity. It
doesn't even have to make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   In his book, Adams quotes from real e-mails readers have sent
him. One reader recounted how he borrowed a line from Wally's
weekly activity report for his own performance review.
</P>
<P>
   In his review he wrote, ``I streamlined my business processess
while honing my participatory style and my proactive attitude, all
while valuing diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Commenting to Adams, the reader noted, ``My pointy-haired boss
either didn't see the humor in it or didn't read it at all, and it
is now part of my permanent record as an employee.''
</P>
<P>
   This is an effective use of sarcasm, Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Adams has absorbed a few of his own corporate values
along the way. He admits he writes books for money.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I hope people get out of the book is a deep emotional
need to buy the sequel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And there will be plenty more of those.
</P>
<P>
   The only threat he sees to Dilbert's universe is if managers
across America suddenly get a clue and start acting rationally, he
said. ``But what we're betting on is whether people will get much
smarter in the next few years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And evolution doesn't work that quickly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
