<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1703 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-WALKER-COLUMN1018     10-16 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-WALKER-COLUMN1018 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Trying to keep a peaceful place away from a murder
 &HT;    Ana Pecina Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can you hate someone you have never met?
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the news broke that the body of a victim of one of
Texas' most feared killers had been discovered on the peaceful
banks of the Brazos River in Falls County, my home.
</P>
<P>
   Colleen Reed, 28, mother of a 13-year-old girl, had been
kidnapped from an Austin car wash and tortured before she was slain
and buried on the banks of the Falls on the Brazos some seven years
ago, police said.
</P>
<P>
   When I read the news, I called home. ``Where was it?'' I
demanded of my older sister.
</P>
<P>
   You see, if you grew up in Marlin, you knew the Brazos, from
Rock Dam Roadto below the Falls, a spot where Native Americans used
to cross Texas'
</P>
<P>
   longest river. And chances are, if you know that river, your
memories of it are good ones.
</P>
<P>
   My sister gave the answer I didn't want to hear. It was right
there, she said, right near where we used to go.
</P>
<P>
   On many a summer Sunday afternoon, my mom would put sandwiches
in a cooler
</P>
<P>
   and my three sisters and me in the car, and we'd go to my dad's
gas station.
</P>
<P>
   There, he and I would proceed to fill the cooler with sodas from
his
</P>
<P>
   machine. I liked to be in charge of the selection: so many Big
Reds, so many
</P>
<P>
   Sun Tang Oranges and so many Cokes. His soft drink machine only
had three
</P>
<P>
   selections.
</P>
<P>
   Off we would head down Highway 6 to the Falls. More often than
not, aunts,
</P>
<P>
   uncles, cousins or neighbors would join us.
</P>
<P>
   The bridge that now spans the Falls did not exist then. Instead,
we would cross on a concrete slab which lay in the river. How it
got there or who put it there, I don't know, but it served its
purpose. I don't think it was wide enough to accommodate two cars
passing each other, but it always had severalinches of water
flowing over it, depending on the season. It could be a scary ride
for a small child. After all, we were in the middle of a river in
our car, but such are the experiences that build the unshakable
trust of a little girl in her father. He always got us there
safely.
</P>
<P>
   The reason to cross was the beach on the west bank. The east
bank, closest to Marlin, was steep and covered with vegetation, a
great place to fish, but
</P>
<P>
   not to swim.
</P>
<P>
   Kids wanted to swim and did we ever, but always under watchful
grown-up eyes. Part of the swimming area, clear water flowing over
a rock bottom, could be slippery but provided a primitive preview
of today's water park slides.
</P>
<P>
   Those days were filled with laughter, camaraderie and just plain
fun: the stuff happy childhoods are made of. In fact, it was one of
the first places I showed my future husband when I finally took him
home.
</P>
<P>
   Then last week, I learned a monster had been there, and I hated
him.
</P>
<P>
   I told my sister during our phone call. She understood but she
said her overridingm memory of the spot was still ``baloney
sandwiches and Big Red.''
</P>
<P>
   She told me she often crosses the river in her daily travels and
that one recent day, after the discovery of the body, she saw a car
parked there and several people standing nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wondered if it was her family, and I started to stop. I
wanted to see if I could help,'' she said. ``But then I figured
they wanted their privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   So she drove on and the next time she passed, she saw flowers at
the spot.
</P>
<P>
   I knew she was trying to comfort me when she said, ``It was a
real pretty place.''
</P>
<P>
   Then I re-read a quote from the victim's sister, Lori Bible.
``It was some solace for me to know that Colleen has rested in a
pretty place for seven years.''
</P>
<P>
   By no means do I dare compare my anger at the intrusion on my
wonderful memories to the terrible loss experienced by Ms. Reed's
family.
</P>
<P>
   But after hearing from those two sisters, I decided to replace
hate with hope, hope that the horror that happened on those banks
could somehow be softened by the happiness that thrived there years
earlier. Happiness which still lightens my heart.
</P>
<P>
   A foolish wish, perhaps. But it's also a symbol of my refusal to
allow the mindless act of serial killer Kenneth Allen McDuff, a man
I have never met, to obliterate the joys of a happy life.
</P>
<P>
   My hope is the same for Ms. Reed's family.
</P>
<P>
   Ana Pecina Walker is managing editor of the Longview
News-Journal, P.O. Box
</P>
<P>
   1792, Longview TX 75606. Telephone: 903-237-7744. E-mail awalker
</P>
<P>
   (at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
