r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     10-16 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE GIRL NEXT DOOR' AN EYE-OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Annie, the insecure, emotionally thin heroine at the center
of ``The Girl Next Door,'' is rescued from a woman-beating creep by
a charming police officer, she has no idea she's about to enter an
even darker world. Officer Craig Mitchell isn't what he seems, a
revelation disclosed early on in this surprisingly watchable drama.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell slides into Annie's life effortlessly and efficiently,
gaining her trust and her tortured heart, even though he's married,
with no intention of severing ties with his two energetic children.
</P>
<P>
   Annie is convinced he'll leave his wife for her, and midway
through this two-hour movie, he decides to do just that. But he
needs help. He needs Annie to don a black mask, point a revolver at
his wife's chest, and fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a police officer,'' Craig assures his new love. ``I know
how these things work.''
</P>
<P>
   He does. The murder is pulled off perfectly: Annie emerges from
the shadows of what looks like a warehouse, saying nothing before
pulling the trigger four times, hitting the wife twice in the
chest, once each in the stomach and arm. She leaves no evidence, so
it goes in the books as a botched robbery attempt. All's well. Or
is it?
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Girl Next Door,'' (8 p.m. CDT Tuesday, CBS), writer Mel
Frohman and director David Greene have caught the enraptured
impotence of psychological gloom and turned it up a notch. The
high-minded will cringe at this, but ``Girl Next Door'' is actually
what last week's snobbish ``Crime and Punishment'' wanted to be.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ``Crime,'' which misfired in its attempts to put us
``inside'' the mind of its murderous lead, ``Girl Next Door'' hangs
back, and, surprisingly for a made-for-network movie, actually
provides insight into guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, Annie, played by Tracey Gold (another surprise,
huh?) is a complete wreck. She has moved into the home of the woman
she killed. Sleeping in her bed, rifling through her closets,
seeing the dead woman's framed photos, looking into the eyes of the
woman's offspring. ``My mom was killed,'' the little boy says to
Annie at one point. ``Did you know that?''
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder that ``Girl Next Door'' actually begins with
Annie dashing into a police station to turn herself in? She
eventually talks with Gayle, a police psychologist (Sharon Gless of
``Cagney &AMP; Lacey'' fame, who sleepwalks through this
just-a-paycheck-role), and the story unfolds in flashback.
</P>
<P>
   By confessing, Annie begins to come to grips with her own
identity, and ``Girl Next Door'' fleshes out yet another element,
that of a lonely woman who was a basket case to begin with. ``I
don't like the part of me, the part that's way down,'' Annie
confides to Gayle. ``The part that says I'm not pretty enough or
clever enough, and afraid of being alone in this world.''
</P>
<P>
   Gold, whose acting career (''Growing Pains'') floundered because
of anorexia prompted by her insecurities, acts with a defiant force
and desperation, playing Annie as a highly vulnerable woman who
defined herself by her men. She couldn't feel complete unless she
was in a relationship, even a bad one.
</P>
<P>
   As she asks a friend before falling into bed with Craig, ``Why
don't guys like me?''
</P>
<P>
   In one eerie scene, in fact, Annie's resolve is broken and she
tells Craig (Tom Irwin) that, OK, she'll kill his wife. Sobbing,
she keeps asking him to say, ``I love you.'' He does, giving her
all the reassurance she needs to kill.
</P>
<P>
   This week in TV:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A Will of Their Own'' (7 p.m. CDT Sunday and 8 p.m. Monday,
NBC): What a waste. Over five hours, this miniseries looking at the
changing roles of women in America _ as seen through the eyes of
six generations of an American family_ is an empty, sappy,
melodramatic mess.
</P>
<P>
   The star is Lea Thompson, who ages from teen to wise old lady,
looking out of place as both. Daughters are born in the family
(sons simply disappear), cut up as teens, then turn their lives
around after witnessing some momentous event.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, they say things like, ``It's terrible to feel
like you have to give up one part of your soul to keep the rest!''
and ``Life is what you make of it. It's not what it makes of you!''
Oh, boy.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Emma's Wish'' (8 p.m. CDT Sunday, CBS): Joanna Kerns is a
75-year-old who gets her birthday wish to be 35 and clean up her
daughter's life, along with their relationship. A shallow, though
relatively harmless fantasy tale that also features Della Reese
delivering her usual motherly shtick.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Stranger in Town'' (8 p.m. CDT, Showtime): A talented Trevor
Blumas, along with his 13-year-old buddies, tries to solve a murder
mystery involving a mysterious drifter played by Harry Hamlin in
full cable mode _ the grungy, sexy type. For a suspenseful mystery,
it's a bit thin on suspense and, well, mystery.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The New Addams Family'' (6:30 p.m. CDT Monday, Fox Family
Channel): This new version of the '60s series that won't die is a
lot like a copy of a copy of a copy. It's quite faded. And it's on
every weeknight, no less.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``NYPD Blue'' (9 p.m. CDT Tuesday, ABC): Arriving fashionably
late, as usual, is the emotional cop series that needs (and will
get) a shot in the arm. The story arc opening the door for Jimmy
Smits' departure begins; replacement Rick Schroder is on deck.
Executive producer Steven Bochco insists that Schroder ``blew us
away,'' and was ``by far the best candidate'' to be partnered with
Dennis Franz's Andy Sipowicz. We'll see.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Discovery News'' (9 p.m. CDT Saturday, Discovery): This news
program devotes an hour to U.S. Sen. John Glenn, scheduled to
return to orbit next week at age 77. Might not be a bad time to
revisit ``The Right Stuff'' (11 a.m. Saturday, TNT), the film about
the seven original astronauts aboard that 1962 mission; here, Glenn
is played by Ed Harris.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
