s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV18-NYT &LR;      10-16 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Oct. 18)  
(JT) 
 &HT;     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Budget With a Surplus: Late, but No Shutdown &LR;
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Congress reached agreement, only 16 days
late and without a government shutdown, on a $1.7 trillion budget
for fiscal 1999 that is the first since the late 1960s not to
include deficit spending. The deal included an industry-backed
increase in visa quotas for foreign workers with technology skills,
a sharp increase in military spending, aid for farmers and new
money for the International Monetary Fund, but no general tax cuts.
Projects to combat global warming and farm runoff won financing; so
did plans to step up logging on public lands in the West and
Alaska. A bankruptcy overhaul passed by Congress but disliked by
the White House was omitted from the deal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Once Again, Drug Giants Can't Get Along &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Any doctor or pharmacist knows the importance of checking for
harmful cross-reactions before putting together two drugs, but the
idea appears to be lost on drug-company bosses. For the third time
this year, an announced merger of pharmaceutical giants fell apart,
largely because the chief executives of the two companies could not
agree on sharing power. Last week it was American Home Products and
Monsanto calling the whole thing off, following bust-ups between
SmithKline Beecham and Glaxo Wellcome in February and Smithkline
and American Home in January.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Headache, Thy Name Is `Hedge Fund' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica said it would eat $372 million of a $1.3 billion
unsecured loan to D.E. Shaw &AMP; Co., a hedge-fund manager, and would
take over and liquidate Shaw's entire $20 billion bond portfolio in
hopes of recouping the rest. The bank's bum hedge-fund loan, rotten
trading results, write-downs on a mortgage-servicing portfolio and
merger-related charges hammered third-quarter earnings down 80
percent from a year earlier ... Another hedge fund, Ellington
Capital Management, dumped a huge position in mortgage-backed
securities to cover margin calls from its lenders and stave off
insolvency ... Merrill Lynch demoted the executive in charge of
managing the firm's financial risk-taking, two days after reporting
a steep quarterly loss related to market turmoil and saying it
would lay off 5 percent of its staff.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Earnings Smiles and Scowls &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Companies reporting happy surprises in a heavy week for
quarterly earnings reports included Apple Computer, back from the
dead thanks to its red-hot iMac computer, as well as Chrysler,
Delta Air Lines, Intel and Johnson &AMP; Johnson. Disappointers
included General Motors, whose results were savaged by an
eight-week strike, along with Caterpillar, Eastman Kodak, Pfizer
and several brokerage firms, including Bear Stearns, Paine Webber
and Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Notes &LR;  ...
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor jumped back into the auction to buy Korea's
debt-hobbled Kia Motors and its sister, Asia Motors ... Two top
executives of Triarc bid to take the beverage company private ...
The two largest compilers of Internet ``audience'' statistics,
Media Matrix and Relevant Knowledge, agreed to merge. ... A
battered Cendant abandoned its planned to buy American Bankers
Insurance. ... Primestar scrapped a plan to buy the
direct-broadcast satellite venture of the News Corp. and MCI
Worldcom ... A $517 billion package of bank rescue measures was
approved by Japan's legislature ... Retail sales rose only modestly
in September, despite strong demand and higher prices for cars.
Over all, consumer prices were unchanged. Producer prices rose more
than expected, but analysts called it a blip; industrial production
weakened ... Columbia/HCA, under investigation for Medicare billing
fraud, sued one of its former top executives, accusing him of
conspiring with vendors to defraud the hospital chain.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SO TO SPEAK &LR;  ...
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Beating the Rush &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the mail comes an alarming-looking card featuring a tight
close-up of a clock reading two minutes to midnight. Black stripes
slash across the garish yellow clock face, asking in computerish
type, ``Concerned about the millennium bug?'' and listing a Web
site to contact. A fire-red stripe says ``Every minute counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the addressee has been worrying about the Year 2000
problem, in which computers that think of years in two digits may
be faked out to deleterious effect when '99 becomes '00. Perhaps
the mailing offers a consultant's smart prevention strategies or a
software house's handy diagnostic tools.
</P>
<P>
   Curiosity whetted, the recipient flips open the card to discover
that it is from . . . a law firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the turn of the century is not yet upon us,'' the
card allows, the New York firm of Bernstein Litowitz Berger &AMP;
Grossman has a Year 2000 Practice Group ``ready to assist our
clients in their efforts to vindicate their legal rights with
respect to defective products infected by the Millennium Bug.'' The
firm already has several big class-action lawsuits contending Year
2000 software flaws, including suits against Intuit and the Medical
Manager Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   The card's implicit message: Never mind that any harm the
dawning of 2000 may do remains 63 weeks in the future. It's never
too soon to sue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
