<HEADER>
A1743 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-GOV-HNS &LR;      10-16 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GOV-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS, LUNGREN DEBATE HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY and ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As his campaign for governor struggles to
attract moderate Democrats and independent voters, Republican Dan
Lungren has wrapped himself in the legacy of Ronald Reagan while
remaining unapologetic about a conservative record his opponent
says is more Gingrich than the Gipper.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren's extensive record after a decade in Congress during the
Reagan years, and eight more as California attorney general, became
the centerpiece of the fourth and final debate Thursday with Lt.
Gov. Gray Davis, the Democratic candidate for governor.
</P>
<P>
   The forum at San Francisco State University was punctuated by
dozens of death-penalty protesters outside and the arrest inside of
Peace and Freedom candidate Gloria La Riva, who rushed the stage to
participate in the ``rich men's debating club.'' La Riva was
charged with disturbing the peace and resisting arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The debate also had Lungren take a slap at San Francisco's
decade-old program to provide condoms to prisoners in the county
jail _ an AIDS-prevention measure Sheriff Michael Hennessey
defended as ``a critical way'' to prevent the spread of the deadly
disease.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly the debate was about Lungren and Davis bringing up
positions, statements and votes from 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of people have moved to California since the
Mediterranean fruit fly caused a panic in the early 1980s, but
Lungren made sure to mention that Davis was then-Gov. Jerry Brown's
chief of staff at the time. And Davis was ready with dozens of
votes Lungren cast in Congress between 1979 and 1989, when Lungren
sometimes found himself aligned with the most extreme
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Slightly behind in the polls with less than three weeks before
the election, Lungren said he was proud of his votes in Congress
and questioned whether Davis even had a record. The politically
cautious Davis, Lungren and his staff say, was ``boldly neutral''
on a securities reform initiative fiercely opposed in the Silicon
Valley and didn't even take a position on the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was proud when I was in Congress to be the single, strongest
supporter of Ronald Reagan,'' Lungren said. ``We took the road less
traveled for less government, less spending, lower taxes and
restoring pride in America.''
</P>
<P>
   But Davis had a powerful weapon against Lungren's attempt to
show himself as a Reagan Republican: The congressional record.
Lungren, Davis pointed out during the debate, was one of only 21
members of the House of Representatives to vote in 1986 against the
Safe Drinking Water Act, a measure eventually signed by Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan Lungren isn't a bad person, but he is a bad choice to lead
California,'' Davis said. ``He's simply out of step on too many
important issues. He would take us backwards on a woman's right to
choose, backwards on education, backwards on the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   When Lungren tried to defend his vote against the Safe Drinking
Water Act as an attempt to balance the national budget, Davis shot
back, ``Which is it? Is Reagan leading the revolution or are you
leading your own little rogue effort over here?''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's hourlong debate is certain to be the last between
Lungren and Davis, who have faced each other four times this year.
The forum was not broadcast in the state's largest media market,
Los Angeles, and the two candidates have reneged on their agreement
to debate there before the election.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lungren's strategy to invoke Reagan led him to talk about the
economy. Both of his questions to Davis concerned taxes and
``job-killer'' measures he says Davis either supported or didn't
actively oppose. Once again, Lungren questioned why Davis did not
fight against Proposition 211, a 1996 initiative that would have
allowed class-action lawsuits over stock fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative was opposed by Silicon Valley, but supported by a
major Davis campaign contributor _ class-action lawyer Bill Lerach.
President Clinton and Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., opposed the
initiative, but Davis never took a position.
</P>
<P>
   Davis gave his weakest explanation of the night when he said he
didn't think he was under any obligation to take a position on
every initiative on the ballot, and that he wasn't an expert on the
securities reform issue.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren sarcastically praised Davis for his modesty: ``I am
overwhelmed by your humility on this one, Gray, to say you have no
expertise on 211. You have better relations with the liberal trial
attorneys than anyone in California.''
</P>
<P>
   Lungren and Davis also clashed over the distribution of condoms
in schools, leading Lungren to an unexpected slap at San
Francisco's program to distribute condoms in the county lockup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I disagree with the sheriff of San Francisco,'' Lungren said,
``who happens to allow condoms to be distributed in the jail here
and then tells them (prisoners) not to use it and if they use it,
they can be prosecuted for a felony but they can always bring back
a used one and get a second or third one. ... We go crazy with
distribution of some of these things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
