   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHILDREN _ PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Humanitarian aid
officials estimate that 25,000 to 30,000 children of the Kosovar
refugees all facing all types of ailments: from diarrhea to
respiratory infections. Most troublesome is the lack of nourishment
being shown by newborns because their mothers have stopped
breastfeeding during the escalating violence. Developing.
(Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-SETTLERS _ JERUSALEM _ The group most directly
threatened by any concessions in West Bank land by Israel are the
settlers who live in the area. They are keeping the heat on Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, warning him not to give away too
much or they will try to bring down his government. Friday, they
were noting the beating Thursday night of two Israeli security
officers (alleged) by Palestinian officers as another example of
how the Palestinians should not be trusted. Recapping some of the
settler issues. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CNN _ BEIJING Chinese authorities have once again set up
electronic barriers on the internet aimed at blocking the 1 million
web users in China from accessing the CNN and British Broadcasting
Company websites. The spokesman of China's ruling State Council
declined to answer a written query on why average netsurfers in
Beijing could no longer dial up CNN website. ``It's not an easy
question to handle,'' said an official in the State Council's
information office. During the glow of openness before and during
President Bill Clinton's visit to China three months ago, both the
CNN and BBC websites were freely accessable to Chinese computer
users, as China appeared to be paring down its list of ``banned''
sites. But then this week, the BBC said the main state controlled
internet service provider ChinaNet was ``believed to be blocking
access'' to its main London-based site called bbc.co.uk. As a
result, the BBC said, web surfers in China were unable to access
the BBC's new web-based Mandarin language broadcast and transcript
service. CNN has made no similar announcement. (Kunstel/Albright,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECONOMY _ MIAMI _ The next near-death experience for
world financial markets may occur in Brazil. With the world's
ninth-largest economy, a recession or devaluation in Brazil would
spread throughout Latin America and bring the global financial
crisis to America's doorstep. President Fernando Cardoso hopes to
unveil an austerity package to stave off a crisis by Oct. 20. With
a pool of 164 million consumers, companies like Coca-Cola and IBM
have a major stake in Brazil's future. In addition, Brazil is
Florida's biggest trading partner. Despite reassurances from the
International Monetary Fund and World Bank that relief will be
provided, economists -- and more importantly, banks and investors
-- have become increasingly pessimistic. (Emling, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-PRIMER _ A primer box on Brazil's economic and political
situation. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
