<HEADER>
A1807 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOBEL-MURAD-2NDWRITET     10-16 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOBEL-MURAD-2NDWRITETHRU-$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOBEL-MURAD-2NDWRITETHRU-2TAKES-$ADV18 
 
EDITORS: THIS UPDATED STORY IS NEW THROUGH OUT 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 18) 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RUTH SoRELLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ After Dr. Ferid Murad learned he had won the Nobel
Prize for medicine Monday morning, he still set aside 30 minutes to
meet with the trainees and scientists in his lab to discuss some
``fantastic data'' that one had uncovered over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Those close to him say it is a mark of the man that he would
take time on such a day for the younger scientists he is training.
It also is proof of his wife's assertion that the Nobel will not
change him or divert him from his single-minded pursuit of what he
loves _ science.
</P>
<P>
   Murad, 62, put it more simply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a data freak,'' he confessed. ``I can't go a day without
hearing good new data.''
</P>
<P>
   The dogged pursuit of new information characterizes Murad and
his success, capped last week by science's most prestigious award.
Friends describe him as competitive, brilliant, unassuming and
mild. His wife calls him a ``regular guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Willerson, chairman of medicine at the University of
Texas Medical School at Houston, said he pushed for Murad's
recruitment as chairman of the school's new integrative biology
department because of that love of ``data'' _ particularly in his
field, dealing with biologic effects of a chemical called nitric
oxide.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Murad spent most of his adult life pursuing the mystery of the
colorless, odorless gas best known as an air pollutant. Although
most living creatures produce nitric oxide (not to be confused with
the dentist's nitrous oxide, or laughing gas), Murad and co-winners
Robert F. Furchgott and Louis J. Ignarro proved its fundamental
role in cells throughout the body.
</P>
<P>
   Their research showed how it can help unclog arteries and reduce
blood pressure, among other benefits. In small doses, nitric oxide
opens up the constricted pulmonary arteries in extremely premature
babies and allows their blood to be more fully oxygenated.
</P>
<P>
   Little remains controversial about it today. But for 18 years,
Murad fought for recognition of the tiny molecule's importance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unexpected that a free radical would work like this,''
said Murad, who maintained his work and studies despite the world
of medicine's indifference to his efforts.
</P>
<P>
   That is typical of him, said a lifelong friend, Ronald Delismon
of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were playing chess with him and he was losing, he never
gave up,'' said Delismon. ``He made you beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1990s, nitric oxide's importance became clear. In
1992, the journal Science named it molecule of the year. In 1996,
Furchgott and Murad received the Lasker Award, often dubbed the
American Nobel.
</P>
<P>
   Murad, new to Houston and UT, hopes his new celebrity will bring
grants and top-notch younger researchers to the school. But he
hopes the Nobel will not change him.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Murad, his wife of nearly 40 years, is confident it won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will go on doing the things he loves,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The money from his share of the $978,000 prize will go toward
educating his five grandchildren and maybe to Indiana's DePauw
University, where he went on a full scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   One area of Murad's expertise that is ignored frequently is his
skill as a physician, his wife said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won the prize for the `Art and Practice of Medicine' when
he was in medical school'' at Cleveland's Case Western University,
she said. ``In 1976, when I had a pulmonary embolism (a blood clot
in the lungs), he diagnosed it before anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   His concern for patients was evident last week as he talked to
24-year-old Sharon Jones as she cradled her prematurely born baby,
James Michael, on her chest in the Turner Neonatal Intensive Care
Unit at Hermann Children's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Although its use is relatively new, nitric oxide is helping
save lives in such units across the country. In very premature
newborns, it can help reduce a life-threatening condition known as
pulmonary hypertension.
</P>
<P>
   Little Michael, born weighing 1 pound, 7.6 ounces, has not yet
had to have nitric oxide treatments. But his mother and father
drive in regularly from Splendora to cuddle the infant born three
months early at a hospital in Humble.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Murad's big body, hugged by the yellow cotton gown
required in such nurseries, dwarfed the young mother as she cradled
her infant.
</P>
<P>
   But he leaned forward to catch her soft words, and he was
cautiously encouraging as he elicited the story about how Sharon
Jones had dropped out of college when her baby was born, and now
spent hours each day holding him close. His father takes the
weekend duty, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got married when I was 19,'' she said. ``We wanted to wait
a few years to have children, but ...''
</P>
<P>
   Even though a medical school planning committee was awaiting
Murad's appearance downstairs, he seemed in no hurry as he talked
to Jones and toured the unit with Dr. John Sparks, chairman of UT's
Pediatrics Department.
</P>
<P>
   Murad's enthusiasm for the treatment options offered by nitric
oxide is almost boundless, but his face and voice soften when he
talks about the use in keeping newborns healthy and whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been a real shot in the arm for the school,'' said
Sparks. Already, Murad has been working with pediatric researchers
like Dr. Michael Fant and Dr. Bruce Alpert, whose interests in
infant development and care of critically ill children overlaps
that of Murad.
</P>
<P>
   His interest is not limited to children, but as the father of
five, he has been necessarily involved with the younger generation.
</P>
<P>
   All his youngsters are grown and gone, but Monday morning's
first hours were spent tracking them down and telling them about
his Nobel.
</P>
<P>
   Another of those early communications was with Delismon, a
retired Boeing engineer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so excited when I heard it on television,'' said
Delismon. ``I didn't even stay upstairs to hear the whole thing. I
ran downstairs and e-mailed him my congratulations.''
</P>
<P>
   The two grew up in Whiting, Ind., a town of 10,000 south of
Chicago. Their high school had only about 120 students in the
senior class.
</P>
<P>
   But the teachers were wonderful, said Delismon. ``They really
took an interest in us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Delismon, who describes his youthful self as 6 feet tall and 125
pounds, managed the swimming and football teams. Murad, he said,
lettered in track and football. Both were members of the men's glee
club and took roles in school and local operettas and musical
productions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always smooth,'' said Delismon. ``He was voted best
dressed in high school. The dress then was slacks and sweaters.''
</P>
<P>
   At lunch, the pair would eat at a small restaurant run by
Murad's parents, John and Josephine, Delismon said. It was a
favorite with teachers and students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just a bunch of gunky kids 16 and 17 years old,'' he
said. ``But they went out of their way to take an interest in us.
It was absolutely amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Murad's father had emigrated from Albania when he was 16. His
wife was from St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they were living today, they would be so proud,'' said
Delismon. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
