<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981016.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1809 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOBEL-MURAD-2NDWRITET     10-16 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOBEL-MURAD-2NDWRITETHRU-$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOBEL-MURAD-2NDWRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-$ADV18 
 
EDITORS: THIS UPDATED STORY IS NEW THROUGH OUT 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 18) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  HOUSTON: said Delismon.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Neither Murad nor Delismon were valedictorian or salutatorian,
but ``we were up there,'' said Delismon. They competed mercilessly.
If one got a 95 on a test, the other got a 100. After graduation,
many of the students took a college algebra course from Indiana
University, Delismon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was another competition,'' he said. ``Did you get a hundred
on the exam? What? Only a 99? You dummy!
</P>
<P>
   ``We aced that class, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought his friend would win the Nobel Prize,
Delismon said, ``Never.''
</P>
<P>
   When Murad first made his nitric oxide discovery almost 20 years
ago, he told Delismon that it was important and might lead to some
kinds of awards. His friend remembers what he told Murad later.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were the only one who thought this work was important,''
said Delismon. ``You never give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Murad's interest in nitric oxide began early in his career, and
he continued to work in the field even when others thought his
pursuit fruitless because nitric oxide acted contrary to what was
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Because it has one electron free, nitric oxide is known as a
free radical. It readily combines with other chemicals in the body,
and exists in a pure state no longer than 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But those crucial 10 seconds allow the gas produced by one cell
to penetrate the outer membrane and regulate the function of
another cell. It was the first time that a gas had been found to
act as a ``signaling'' molecule that turns on the functions of
other cells.
</P>
<P>
   Further work in the field showed that this so-called
second-message molecule provides crucial signals in the
cardiovascular and nervous systems. It fights infections, regulates
blood pressure and governs the flow of blood to different organs.
</P>
<P>
   Delismon understands the basics of his friend's work, but Murad
laughs when asked about Delismon's.
</P>
<P>
   Most of it was top-secret for the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd say, `I would tell you about it, but then I'd have to
kill you,' '' Murad said.
</P>
<P>
   Delismon said he knows what Murad will say when they meet next:
``I'm ahead, one Nobel to nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The two parted ways when they went to college. Murad went to
DePauw, Delismon to the University of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   After getting his bachelor's degree, Murad was almost ready to
go Washington University in St. Louis when a fraternity brother
told him about an M.D.-Ph.D. program at Case Western. He obtained
both his medical degree and a doctorate in pharmacology there.
</P>
<P>
   At the prestigious Massachusetts General Hospital, where he did
his internship and residency with Willerson, he also worked with
future Nobel laureate Dr. Joseph Goldstein of UT Southwestern
Medical School in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very bright and hard working,'' said Willerson. ``He is
committed to doing everything well. He wants everything around him
to be done at a high level. He is ambitious for the Health Science
Center and the Texas Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at the same time, he is unassuming and shy.''
</P>
<P>
   And he is a regular guy, said wife Carol. Most people call him
``Fred'' rather than Ferid, an Albanian name his father gave him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And how many doctors do you know who have a radial saw in the
garage?'' asked his wife.
</P>
<P>
   He always has some kind building project, she said. He built a
garage at their Lake Tahoe home, she said, and a three-car garage
at their former place in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   He taught his son to build and fix the family cars. ``And,'' she
said, ``my oldest daughter can do a mean wallboard.''
</P>
<P>
   None of Murad's four daughters nor his son went into medicine,
although one is a medical editor and another a respiratory
therapist. ``I guess I scared them off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like many in the medical field, he has bounced from medical
school to medical school and even done a stint in the
pharmaceutical industry.
</P>
<P>
   He was at the University of Virginia in Charlottesville and at
Stanford University in California. In the early 1990s, he was vice
president for pharmaceutical research and development for Abbott
Laboratories in Illinois. ``Then I decided to create a biotech
company at the wrong time,'' he said. ``I spent most of my time
raising money.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not what he liked to do, and he left Molecular Geriatrics
Corp. in Lake Bluff, Ill., to return to academia where he could do
what he likes best _ research and teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really get my jollies when I go to the blackboard with my
trainees,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There they plan new experiments and mull over old ones. They
brainstorm new work that could take a couple of months or a couple
of years.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, his trainees are a new generation of Ferid Murad, just
as he is a product of the laboratories in which he was trained.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look on my trainees as scientific offspring,'' he said. ``I
follow what they are doing, and many have done well. They are
scattered around the globe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very likely that he will grow his own Nobel Prize
winners here,'' said Dr. M. David Low, president of the UT Health
Science Center. ``It is one of our challenges to make sure that all
the conditions are there so he can.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
