u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POLITICS-HNS &LR;      10-16 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLITICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOLSTERED BY VICTORIES, CLINTON LAUNCHES INTO UNCERTAIN DEMOCRATIC
CAMPAIGN SEASON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Bolstered by victories at home and abroad, President
Clinton decried Republican partisanship Friday as he launched into
an uncertain campaign season for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Congress comes to a close next week with the president
having defied the pundits by not only remaining in office, albeit
under threat of impeachment, but being emboldened by a week of
successes and favorable polls.
</P>
<P>
   Only a week ago, the Republican-led House voted to begin an
impeachment inquiry of Clinton stemming from his extramarital
affair with Monica Lewinsky and his efforts to keep it secret.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, it was Clinton who was on the offensive: agreeing
to a budget deal with Congress, helping to head off a military
conflict in Kosovo and bringing together the Israeli and
Palestinian leaders for peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight days of progress cannot totally erase eight months of
partisanship,'' Clinton said in a Rose Garden appearance with
Democrats from Capitol Hill at his side.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know that in those eight months of partisanship, too
many dreams of too many families were deferred. The Republican
majority is now leaving town to campaign, but they're also leaving
a lot of America's business unfinished,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said his first legislative priority in 1999 will be
passage of a patients' bill of rights measure killed by Congress.
He also pledged to fight for other issues rejected by Republicans
such as a school construction measure, minimum wage increase,
campaign finance reform and anti-tobacco legislation.
</P>
<P>
   With a historic low turnout being predicted, Clinton exhorted
voters to take ``a trip to the ballot box.''
</P>
<P>
   The president himself left the capital immediately after his
statement, flying here to raise money for an embattled Democrat,
Illinois Sen. Carol Moseley-Braun.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, greeted outside the event by scores of demonstrators
calling for his impeachment, told Mosely-Braun's supporters that
the new budget deal pending in Congress looks like it was crafted
by Democrats. He claimed credit for the increases in education,
payments to the International Monetary Fund and protections for the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a dizzying week, but a wonderful week for our
country,'' Clinton said, citing the budget, Kosovo, the Middle East
and the Nobel Peace Prize for the key players in the Northern
Ireland peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton canceled a second fund-raising event in St. Louis to
return to Washington to huddle again with Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian Authority Chairman Yasser
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tendency in the press to overwrite how much trouble
he's in or how well he's doing,'' said Doug Sosnik, a presidential
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Sosnik recounted the half dozen times in the past six years that
Clinton has been declared politically dead: from the lost battle to
reform health care in 1994 to speculation early this yea that he
would be impeached by Labor Day over the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the hallmarks of his presidency is the desire of his
enemies and some members of the press to declare his presidency
over,'' Sosnik said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Buchanan, a political science professor at the University
of Texas at Austin, said, ``It is fair to say, it's probably true,
that people expected more of a weakening as a consequence of the
Lewinsky matter than there actually was.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan noted Clinton remained able to use the bully pulpit,
repeating his education agenda ``250 times'' in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, whether Clinton's momentum can transfer to Democrats on
Nov. 3 Election Day remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably still too early to tell whether it affects the
base Democratic vote,'' said Rep. Gene Green, D-Texas. He noted the
Republican base vote, their core constituents, are ready to go to
the polls while Democrats ``have to really be motivated to turn
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats can take heart in nationwide surveys indicating public
is becoming increasingly dismayed with Republicans' handling of the
impeachment issue.
</P>
<P>
   Green said Republican impeachment inquiry debate was ``not
fact-finding as much as it's political and the American people are
reflecting that.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said Clinton's momentum could potentially help
Democrats because of a renewed focus on the agenda favored by the
president and his party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the president's problems this year, people forgot
what they already knew: A). Republicans are out of the mainstream,
and B). they've not been able to demonstrate an ability to govern
since they took over (Congress),'' Sosnik said.
</P>
<P>
   With the election less than three weeks away, Clinton still has
an incredibly light campaign schedule. He will travel to California
next week for a two-day swing to help struggling Democratic Sen.
Barbara Boxer. And, he will attend fund-raising events in New York
and Florida before the election.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the campaign appearances on behalf of Democratic
candidates are being performed by first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
and Vice President Al Gore. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
