<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDGET VOTE POSTPONED FOR REVIEW BEFORE MIDWEEK VOTE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress postponed until next week a vote on its
final 1999 spending agreement with President Clinton to allow time
to have the massive bill printed and to give members a chance to
review it.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders in the House and Senate said Friday a vote
would be taken Tuesday or Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Congress approved another short-term funding
measure to keep the government running through early next week. The
stopgap bill, the fifth that Congress has passed since the start of
the new fiscal year on Oct. 1, replaces another interim funding
measure that expired Friday at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Republican and Democratic leaders predicted that the final
spending bill, worth nearly $600 billion, would pass with
overwhelming support. But some Republicans expressed concern that
angry fiscal conservatives in the GOP might revolt. They say the
bill is filled with pork-barrel projects and drains more than $19
billion from projected surpluses of about $131 billion over this
year and next.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of disappointed members,'' said one Republican
official. ``I think the more they read through this thing, the less
likely they are to vote for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were less worried about defections, since the
agreement contains an increase in education funding earmarked for
hiring new teachers. The Democrats have sought to make the
modernization of the public school system a key theme in this
year's congressional campaigns. They believe the extra $1.2 billion
designated as seed money for the president's plan to hire 100,000
more teachers could help them.
</P>
<P>
   In a Rose Garden ceremony Friday, Democratic lawmakers gathered
with Clinton to celebrate what they called the ``hard-won gains''
for education and other programs they hope to turn to their
advantage in the Nov. 3 election. They used the event to play up
the Republicans' refusal to go along with the administration's
request for more money to help build up to 5,000 new schools.
</P>
<P>
   After laying out disagreements over issues ranging from
education and health care, Clinton called on voters not to abandon
the Democrats, who are expected to lose to Republicans in many of
the close races around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Staying home is not an option when so much is riding on a trip
to the ballot box,'' Clinton admonished Democratic supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans also tried to cast the agreement as an
election-year victory for their members. In a speech on the House
floor, House Speaker Newt Gingrich outlined some of the reasons
that GOP lawmakers ought to vote for the bill and defend it as they
campaign for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   He touted the nearly $10 billion included in the bill for extra
defense-related spending as ``the first real increase'' in Pentagon
funding since 1985. He emphasized that Republican negotiators
insisted that the new teacher hiring money in the agreement be
controlled by local officials rather than the federal Education
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is going to win everything they want,'' Gingrich said.
But he called the budget deal ``the best agreement you can get when
you have a conservative Congress and a liberal president....I think
we can be very proud of this budget and I hope on Tuesday we have a
resounding vote of support for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote next week on the budget agreement will be the last
remaining business for the 105th Congress, unless it's called into
special session. Although Congress technically will be in
adjournment, the House Judiciary Committee will convene after the
Nov. 3 election to begin its impeachment inquiry against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But it's unlikely the whole House would have to return to
Washington to take any action related to the inquiry unless the
panel recommends that a vote be held on whether to impeach the
president. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
