<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-TAMAULIPAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL SHOWS PRI CANDIDATE FAVORED IN TAMAULIPAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Results of a poll released here Friday show
Mexico's ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, is
virtually assured of retaining the governor's seat in this month's
elections in the northeastern state of Tamaulipas.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI's Tomas Yarrington Ruvalcaba was favored by 56 percent
of those polled, while 18 percent said they support Gustavo
Cardenas Gutierrez of the center-right National Action Party (PAN).
Joaquin Hernandez Correa, of the center-left Democratic Revolution
Party (PRD), was favored 11 percent of those surveyed, said Jesus
Flores Aguilar.
</P>
<P>
   Flores is executive adviser to the University of Guadalajara's
Center of Opinion Studies, which conducted the poll on Oct. 10 and
11. The sampling of 1,400 voters has a margin of error of plus or
minus 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Results were virtually identical to a survey one month ago,
Flores said. The election is Oct. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Antonio Trujeque, a political analyst at the Colegio de la
Frontera Norte in Matamoros, said that despite a general decline
across the rest of Mexico, the PRI's strong showing in Tamaulipas
is not surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI built its strength over the years with the guaranteed
loyalty of the labor and peasant votes,'' Trujeque said.
</P>
<P>
   ``While that loyalty is now slipping away in other parts of the
country, it is still strong here in Tamaulipas, and especially so
at state election time,'' he said of the state that skirts the
Texas border.
</P>
<P>
   Following a stunning victory by PAN in state elections in
neighboring Nuevo Leon last year, PRI members in Tamaulipas
realized they needed to work harder than ever to ensure victory,
Trujeque said.
</P>
<P>
   Yarrington has proven a strong candidate, with the support of
current PRI Gov. Manuel Cavazos Lerma, and has unified the state
party, which appeared bitterly divided after Yarrington defeated
another candidate favored by President Ernesto Zedillo in a primary
two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas, the former mayor of the state capital, Ciudad
Victoria, and the son of Jorge Cardenas, who in 1980 became the
first opposition mayor ever elected in Matamoros, was expected to
run stronger, Trujeque said.
</P>
<P>
   But organizational problems within his campaign and a somewhat
undependable middle-class base for PAN weakened his effort.
</P>
<P>
   While Hernandez has strong name recognition in the southern port
cities of Ciudad Madero and Tampico, the PRD is just getting
started in Tamaulipas and has not offered a strong campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Trujeque said Yarrington's coattails seem broad and could result
in a near clean-sweep of mayoral races across the state.
</P>
<P>
   PAN now holds the mayoralty of Matamoros and Tampico, while the
PRD has won in Ciudad Madero twice in the past six years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
