<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981016.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1911 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS17-CO     10-16 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR CLINTON, A GREAT WEEK ENDING A TERRIBLE YEAR
 &HT;    950&AMP;insert.
 &HT;    With CONGRESS-RECORD.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton mixed the powers of the bully
pulpit this week with his remarkable resilience in the polls to win
substantial portions of his populist agenda from an adversarial
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   On issues as varied as funding for international economic
bailouts, hiring elementary school teachers and expanding aid to
farmers, Clinton managed to pry a host of concessions from a
Republican-led Congress, even as he worked to end bloodshed in
Kosovo and broker an accord for peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   He even managed _ with the help of Republican infighting and the
threat of a presidential veto _ to turn back a House effort to cut
taxes in an election year, which Clinton said would squander tens
of billions of dollars of the first federal budget surplus in 29
years.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad, some might say, for a man who just the week before
became the third president in American history to become the
subject of a formal impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly, this has been a very good week for the president,''
said political scientist Stephen Wayne, a Georgetown University
professor. ''He testified to his vitality and relevance as
president. He's still the president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as measured against the bold vision Clinton outlined
for the country in January, this has been largely a year of lost
opportunities for the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco legislation, campaign finance reform, health care
reforms and a hike in the minimum wage _ four popular, if
controversial, priorities that Clinton pledged to fight for in his
State of the Union address nine months ago _ were killed on Capitol
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's vow to deny Iraq the ability to build weapons of mass
destruction simply melted away after President Saddam Hussein first
dodged the threat of U.S. air strikes, then later asserted that he
would no longer submit to United Nations weapons inspections
mandated under the terms of Baghdad's Persian Gulf War surrender.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton's quest for so-called ''fast track'' trade
negotiating authority was never seriously taken up in a Congress
deeply divided over the broad issues of economic globalization.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, as Clinton assembled his party's congressional
leadership for a round of election-year congratulations in the
sun-dappled Rose Garden, the victory was decidedly bittersweet.
</P>
<P>
   Between his personal troubles over Monica Lewinsky and his
political difficulties on Capitol Hill, Clinton is approaching the
midpoint of his second term at risk of having to settle for
comparatively small gains instead of the big-picture changes he
once hoped might frame his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's really sacrificed any kind of larger vision to the
politics of the ad hoc, the bargain, the transaction,'' said Erwin
Hargrove, a presidential scholar at Vanderbilt University in
Nashville. ''He hasn't been able to really capture people's
imagination about big things he wants to do.''
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Last January, the week after allegations first surfaced that he
had an affair with Lewinsky, Clinton delivered a stirring State of
the Union address in which he outlined a bold vision of the
country's future and laid out an ambitious Democratic road map to
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Key pillars included legislation:
</P>
<P>
   _ To spike cigarette taxes in a deal that Democrats hoped would
bring in some $25 billion a year in new revenues.
</P>
<P>
   _ To end perceived abuses in campaign financing.
</P>
<P>
   _ To raise by $1 the $5.15-an-hour minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   _ To provide new health care guarantees for more than 50 million
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The agenda would have been ambitious at any time. Indeed,
Clinton's troubles with Lewinsky made it politically imperative
that the speech appear as visionary as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ''All at once, the purpose of the State of the Union message was
to contrast Clinton as president with Clinton's personal
behavior,'' said Wayne. ''It served, in a sense, a different
purpose for him.''
</P>
<P>
   It would have been difficult, during the best of times, for
Clinton to lead his party to victory in those areas against a
Republican-led Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The question haunting the White House is how much better his
chances might have been if Clinton had not been hog-tied by
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly he had no political capital with which to push those
goals,'' said Wayne. ''Had the Lewinsky thing not broken, he might
have.''
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   What Clinton demonstrated in the past week, though, was that
he's neither crippled by scandal nor prepared to live out the rest
of his term in a state of political atonement and personal shame.
</P>
<P>
   He retains all of the constitutionally endowed powers of his
office, including the authority to veto spending bills and other
legislation that makes its way to his desk.
</P>
<P>
   His Republican foes may have the upper hand on Capitol Hill, but
unless they confound all expectations to win veto-proof majorities
in November elections, they'll continue to have to bargain with
Clinton and the party he represents.
</P>
<P>
   A modern president, however, governs largely from the podium,
using the presidency and the unlimited store of props the office
provides as a stage for pressing his agenda and selling his
programs to the public, all the better to influence balky members
of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''A president's powers are basically powers of persuasion,''
said retiring Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind. ''His powers of persuasion
with Republicans, to a large number of them at least, are
reduced.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Clinton _ whose job approval ratings have remained
above 60 percent for most of the year _ has been able to use the
voice of public opinion to amplify his own message to reluctant
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he's riding high,'' Hamilton said, ''the politicians in the
Congress respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   If they don't respect it, Clinton challenged them this week to
fear it.
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks away from midterm elections _ in which all 435
House seats and one-third of the 100-seat Senate are up for grabs _
Clinton is arguing hard that each defeat handed to him by
Republicans was a net loss for the country.
</P>
<P>
   ''Partisanship killed the Patients' Bill of Rights,'' Clinton
said on Friday. ''Partisanship killed our efforts to help students
stuck in crumbled and overcrowded school rooms,'' he said,
referring to the defeat of a White House proposal for $5 billion
over the next five years for elementary school construction and
repair.
</P>
<P>
   ''Republican partisanship killed an increase in the minimum
wage,'' he continued, ''partisanship killed our best chance at
bipartisan campaign finance reform ...and finally, let me say that
partisanship killed the comprehensive anti-tobacco legislation,
which would have saved millions of young Americans from painful and
premature
</P>
<P>
   death.''
</P>
<P>
   In a preview of what already promises to be a central theme of
his next State of the Union message this January, Clinton vowed to
fight hard, to restore those priorities to the agenda he means to
place before the incoming Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''By that time,'' said Vanderbilt's Hargrove, ''impeachment
politics will either be over, or we'll all be in a hell of a
mess.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
