u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-CHINA-BEETLES-     10-16 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-CHINA-BEETLES-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;    
 &HT;      CHINESE OFFICIALS BUGGED BY NEW TRADE RULE
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Ronald F. Eckstein  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Oct. 16 -- The damage Asian longhorn beetles are
doing to Chicago-area trees may be heartbreaking, but the U.S.
Department of Agriculture's plan to stem the destruction really
bugs Chinese trade officials.
</P>
<P>
   Effective December 17, all shipments to the United States from
China containing solid wood packing materials must be accompanied
by official certification noting the wood has been treated to kill
any six-legged stowaways.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic response to the rule was positive Friday morning, as
the USDA held the first of three public hearings on the subject.
Representatives from packaging companies and wood products
associations applauded the wisdom of not banning wooden packaging
of imports, and a manufacturer of plastic packing materials offered
to sell his wares to Chinese exporters.
</P>
<P>
   But Chinese officials used the forum to express their
displeasure with the imminent rule. Xia Hongmin, Director General
of the Department of Animal and Plant Inspection and Quarantine for
the People's Republic of China, and his six-person entourage were
in Washington to negotiate with American agriculture and trade
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Through a translator, Hongmin called the rule ``discriminatory
and unfair.'' He said Asian longhorn beetles have also been
discovered in packages from Japan and Korea. And 72 percent of
wood-boring pests intercepted at American ports came from European
packing materials, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Hongmin claimed the rule will seriously hinder trade between the
United States and China.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more than 1 million shipments exported to the USA
from China annually and 33 to 50 percent of the total shipments are
packed with wood materials,'' he said. ``It is very difficult for
China to implement and supervise the treatments on time due to the
lack of methyl bromide, infrastructures and skillful fumigators and
limitation of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the treatments are not carried out on time, the shipments
will not export normally, or cause delay of the shipments. The cost
of the shipments will rise ... It will seriously impact the
bilateral trade between China and the USA.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, he predicted, the price of Chinese imports to the
U.S. will rise dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   But USDA officials said Chinese fears are overstated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interim rule has been crafted in a way that will have the
least possible impact on trade with China,'' said Michael V. Dunn,
assistant secretary of agriculture, marketing and regulatory
programs at USDA.
</P>
<P>
   The last two public hearings on the rule will be held in
Seattle, Wash. and Long Beach, Calif. in early November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
