u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-LMAY17-COX     10-16 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-LMAY17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Onion blooms provide sweet lessons of life
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLUE RIDGE, Ga._Pregnant onion. The name, at least that common
name, is truly descriptive. I'd never had one of these houseplants
until a few months ago when I got one from Pat Sublett, owner of
Misty Mountain Gifts, which sells plants and garden accessories.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the cabin, I put the ornamental onion in a sunny window,
where its strap leaves, more than two feet long, stream down to the
floor. Demonstrating how it got its name, it continues to produce
little offsets about the size of peas under the skin of the mother
bulb that sits above the soil. Each baby can sprout and become a
mother when it touches dirt.
</P>
<P>
   My mother plant, now a bit bigger than a golf ball, surprised me
recently; in a weeks-long process it bloomed, producing a
foot-long, leafless flower stalk with a lot of little star-shaped
flowers at its end.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed fitting to take the blooming onion back to Misty
Mountain for a celebration. This I did when the flowering was at
its zenith, on a recent night, after the shop had closed.
</P>
<P>
   In a world so filled with man-made razzle-dazzle, high
technology and automation, such celebrations comfort, reaffirming
the importance of simple, natural beauty. To be with friends and
watch the opening of an iris or a night-blooming cereus, to admire
the bloom of a pregnant onion, is to understand that nature rules.
Nothing we can manufacture can do what plants do. No machine can
make blossoms. Or produce the color of autumn leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Pat, Dianne Lee, co-owner of a custom gift basket business
called The Basket Case of Blue Ridge, and I pulled up seats, sipped
wine, nibbled light hors d'oeuvres and talked, while the onion sat
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   As we admired it, Pat said, ``You ought to see the mama,''
explaining that the mama, her first pregnant onion, has grown
zaftig during the 15 years they've been together, producing many
little onions.
</P>
<P>
   Pat, who used to be senior buyer at Pike Family Nurseries, where
she worked from 1970 until 1995, opened her own business here last
year, selling onion babies harvested from the mother plant at home.
``I kept every one of them and stuck them in the soil,'' she said.
``I don't like to throw away anything.''
</P>
<P>
   So now, little onions grow among the herbs, perennial flowers,
containers and other items at Misty Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, my onion, in its little clay pot, stayed for
about an hour before I put it on the front seat of my car and
headed back through the sharp mountain air toward the cabin in
McCaysville, some 10 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   The celebration did wonders. Like all such times when we stop
doing the ordinary things we have to do and experience something at
once as simple, yet profound, as staring at a bloom, we relax
profoundly.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the celebration focused attention on blooms beyond the
onion's, making me think of many others I've known, all those I
have yet to see and appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   So much from such a little plant. One with such a big botanical
name: Ornithogalum caudatum. As much as I have gotten from this
plant, I know it wouldn't be nearly as appealing if I had to call
it Ornithogalum caudatum.
</P>
<P>
   No, pregnant onion works. It is bulging again, pregnant with
several little balls. Pregnant with nature's lessons. With the
beautiful miracle of growth. This is the sweetest onion I know.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: leemay(at)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
