<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1959 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAINT-COX     10-16 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAINT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coordinating paint, plant colors makes homes inviting
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a good-looking guy or girl turns your head 180 degrees, you
immediately know why. Those eyes. The smile. That bod. They all
come together to grab your attention.
</P>
<P>
   And when a beautiful house and yard make you do a double take,
chances are the home's architecture, materials and colors are in
sync with its landscaping.
</P>
<P>
   ``So often, people miss the boat on their homes because they
don't understand that if the structure complements the garden, and
vice versa, they've got themselves some major curb appeal,'' said
Kenneth Charbonneau, a color marketing consultant for Benjamin
Moore &AMP; Co. paints. ``For most of us, a home is our biggest
investment, so why wouldn't you want to safeguard that?''
</P>
<P>
   Professional designers know how to coordinate a structure with a
landscape. But most do-it-yourselfers need help learning how the
various components of a facade and yard come together to create
harmony, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's as simple as planting a few flowering annuals
near the entrance with the same color of the front door or
shutters. ``If someone is putting his home up for sale or just
looking for the personal gratification in increasing its curb
appeal, a lot of times seasonal colors can draw the eye to certain
areas, such as the entrance, to make it more inviting,'' said
Phillip Cates of Lifescapes landscaping company in Canton, Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   But more often, creating curb appeal requires a look at the big
picture, starting with your home's architecture.
</P>
<P>
   A Victorian style house might lend itself to an English cottage
garden, with colorful perennials and roses spilling loosely over
fences and beds instead of a manicured lawn and foundation shrubs.
``For a contemporary house with lots of glass, you think of a
California type of landscape, which tends to be simpler in style
with lots of tropical plants, like banana trees and sago palms,''
said Mark Schisler of Legacy Landscapes in Marietta. ``It doesn't
hurt to have your house associated with a villa on the beach.''
</P>
<P>
   A simpler way for integrating the home and garden is to think in
terms of formality.
</P>
<P>
   If the facade is formal, such as Georgian style, with a
symmetrical design _ a centered door balanced by an equal number of
windows _ that feel should be extended to the yard, Cates said.
Boxwoods or other stiff, structured shrubs might flank the doorway,
with a straight walkway extending to the street and plantings on
either side that mirror each other.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, if the facade is informal, such as most ranch
styles, with an asymmetrical design (a door off center and possibly
an odd configuration of windows), what works best is an informal
landscape. A small ornamental tree, such as a Japanese maple with
its red leaves, planted at one side of the entry could draw
attention to the door, while a curving walkway would make for a
casual setting. Less-structured plants, such as ornamental grasses
and trailing vines, also can enhance an informal look.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, the landscaping should be planned as the house is being
designed in order to coordinate the two; typically, though, the
yard ends up being designed around the house, making the options
more limited. But even small touches, such as containers or garden
ornaments of a style appropriate for the architecture, can be
placed near the entrance to help put the house and land in harmony.
</P>
<P>
   An equally important tool is color.
</P>
<P>
   Charbonneau recommends selecting up to four exterior paint
colors for accenting the home's various architectural details.
Think of a house as a man's wardrobe, he said. ``The siding should
be like the man's suit. The trim is like a dress shirt. The punch
of color you put on the front door is the tie _ your own little
social statement _ and the shutters are like your socks, or the
accent color,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, play off those colors with your plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more neutral the house color, the more variety you can do
with plants,'' Schisler said. ``Annuals are always effective.''
</P>
<P>
   To draw attention to the door, paint it a color that's different
from all others on the house and repeat that color in plants beside
the entry. A purple door could be complemented by purple pansies in
fall and winter, for example, and purple petunias in spring and
summer. Yellow shutters work well with yellow lantana in summer,
yellow mums in fall.
</P>
<P>
   If the house contains natural materials, such as stone, slate or
brick, choose plants that have flowers or foliage that will
complement them. ``Natural stone is a joy for us to work with, such
as perennials with crab orchard stone,'' Cates said.
</P>
<P>
   That's why light earth tones, such as gray, beige and cream make
dramatic backdrops for rich green foliage. Darker shades make a
house blend into the landscape, while white makes the structure
stand out. Avoid green, especially medium to dark shades, because
it can clash with the landscaping.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran expert who advises product manufacturers and companies
throughout the country on color, he said one of the worst examples
of curb appeal he's seen was a house in New Jersey painted cottage
red and surrounded by purple-blooming azaleas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like fingernails on a blackboard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
