</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAINT-TIPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tips for exterior decorating
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- When choosing exterior paint, remember that colors intensify
and look brighter in daylight than they do on the color card in the
store. Buy quarts and test the colors on the outside of the house.
</P>
<P>
   -- Keep in mind that today's color combinations are softer in
contrast, with tones of one color or similar colors. Twenty years
ago, it was light siding and dark trim, or vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   -- Remember that color can be skewed by its surroundings. If a
yellow house is surrounded by a lot of trees in summer, the foliage
will make the house appear a yellow-green.
</P>
<P>
   -- Look for architectural details that can be accented with a
paint color different from the rest of the house. One popular
accent color is teal, which works well with flowers that are pink
and white, purple and violet, yellow and white or orange and gold.
</P>
<P>
   -- When coordinating plants with exterior colors, don't overlook
the roof, because shingles aren't something you replace very often.
Play off a red roof with red-blooming annuals or trees with red
foliage.
</P>
<P>
   -- Be kind to your neighbors. Choose colors that will increase
your curb appeal but avoid ones that will make your house scream
above others on your block.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
