<HEADLINE>
``BAYWATCH'' MEETS ``BONANZA'' IN HAWAII
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Wind on Water''
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Bo Derek, Lee Horsley, William Gregory Lee, Brian
Gross, Jacinda Barrett, Shawn Christian &QL; 
On: NBC, Ch. 7 &QL; 
Time: Saturday at 8 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Wind on Water,'' a series premiering Saturday on NBC is set on
a very picturesque Hawaii, where the waves are totally tubular and
the babes _ male and female _ are totally toned. There's lots and
lots of water around Hawaii, of course, which means there's lots
and lots of swimming and surfing, which means there's lots and lots
of bathing suits, which means there's lots and lots of flesh, which
of course is the raison d'etre for the show. Let's hope no one at
the network had high hopes regarding the dramatic elements of this
hybrid of ``Baywatch'' and ``Bonanza,'' which ranges from the
merely cliched to the obvious, the turgid, and the silly.
</P>
<P>
   The show follows the fortunes of the Connolly family, as their
very evil and wealthy neighbor tries to buy out their cattle range
to turn it into a resort. The Connolly sons, Cole and Kelly, happen
to be world-class surfers, and they just might be able to save the
day in an important competition that might (I don't want to give
anything away) require Cole to ride the biggest wave ever ridden.
The Connolly matriarch is played by Bo Derek, the actress who is
best known for being 10 on a scale of 10, although the top rating
is certainly not for her acting. To be fair, Derek is doomed by the
script, which requires her all-knowing earth-mother character to
deliver gems like ``Follow your dreams where they take you.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bad guy on ``Wind on Water'' is played with 100 percent
nefariousness by Lee Horsley, who was TV's ``Matt Houston'' in the
1980s. The show's curiosity factor is slightly upped by the fact
that his daughter, who is smitten with the Connolly boys in a
little ``Romeo and Juliet'' twist, is played by a former cast
member of MTV's ``The Real World'' named Jacinda Barrett. That's
not much of a leap, though, since this great-looking, vapid hour
isn't too far a cry from those endless MTV beach parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-16-98 1902EDT &QL; 
