<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOYOTA MAKES AN ENTRY INTO THE TOUGH TRUCK CATEGORY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 bY JOHN R. WHITE 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toyota, dropping the kid gloves in the truck market, unveiled a
new weapon for a fresh assault on full-size pickup market share for
the New England Motor Press Association this week. The truck,
dubbed Tundra, is to be a no-nonsense competitor with a
245-horsepower (315 ft/lb torque), 32-valve, double overhead cam
low-emissions V-8 under the hood, a one-ton load capacity, and the
ability to tow 7,200 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   And, while maybe it won't qualify as an all-American vehicle, it
is to be assembled in a new factory near Princeton, Ind. Tundra,
Toyota said, is to be available in rear-drive or four-wheel-drive
with either a regular two-door cab with an eight-foot bed or the
four-door Access version with a 6.5-foot bed. Toyota said the
Tundras would also come with dual 12-volt outlets and achieve
something of a breakthrough in cupholders for pickups.
</P>
<P>
   The Tundra came as the capstone of an automotive history lecture
by Toyota's Wade Hoyt, who detailed the birth and growth of the
mini-truck phenomenon in America.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New England International Auto Show blows into town two
weeks from today for a nine-day stay at Bayside Exposition Center.
While it has not achieved the size and stature of the Detroit and
New York shows just yet, it has become a major event for the motor
industry where new models debut and are hailed with full-blown
press conferences. And it is the first of the major shows.
</P>
<P>
   What began as an Auto Show/New England Motor Press Association
lunch is now Press Preview Day with major unveilings scheduled
Friday, Oct. 30, the day before the show opens to the public. This
year, the keynote speaker is Mark Hutchins, president of Lincoln
Mercury and a vice president of Ford Motor Co. New models to be
seen for the first time in Boston are the 1999 Acura 3.5 RL, the
Saab 9-5 wagon, Saturn's new 3-door coupe, the Mercedes-Benz C230
Kompressor, and the BMW 5 Series Sport Wagon.
</P>
<P>
   The show promises to be of more than casual interest to car
buyers and car buffs _ in addition to new models, exotics and
concept vehicles, a new marque debuts: Korea's Kia will have its
line on view.
</P>
<P>
   Show hours are 10 a.m. to 10 p.m. Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 7 p.m.
Sundays, 2 p.m. to 9 p.m. Monday and Tuesday, 2 p.m. to 10 p.m.
Wednesday, Thursday, and Friday. Admission is $8 for adults, $4 for
children 6-12, free to children under 6. Discount coupons are
available at car dealers and in the Tuesday, Nov. 5, edition of The
Boston Globe.
</P>
<P>
   The show is sponsored by the Massachusetts State Automobile
Dealers Association and The Globe _ which means that your humble
scribe will be on hand at the Globe booth most show days for a
couple of hours to answer questions and take comments.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the course of recent travels, rain has been a plague. It
started with the annual International Motor Press Association Test
Day at Pocono Raceway in the hills of eastern Pennsylvania, an
event in which auto and truck manufacturers bring their wares to
the track where members of the press (and a whole lot of other
people, it seems) drive their wares on a course, including a
section of the high-speed raceway and a paved infield roadway, to
sense the handling.
</P>
<P>
   Off-road-capable vehicles have a separate course through unpaved
sections _ but not this year. In the rain, the first thing to go is
the off-road course, despite the fact these vehicles are designed
for just such work. No, the manufacturers are not leery of getting
mud on the new machines _ they risk more than that just handing
over all those keys. It is the guardians of the track facility who
frown on tearing up the grass.
</P>
<P>
   The turnout was light this year, it seemed, most likely because
of the widespread knowledge that Pocono is undergoing major
construction _ the kitchen and lunchroom were gone and the sanitary
facilities had been replaced for the moment with those portable
things. Not pretty. Yet with all the hardships, the lunch was
spectacular compared to previous years.
</P>
<P>
   The rain dampened the track and the speeds for most drivers.
Before the downpour got too extreme, I did manage to compare an
Audi A4 and an Audi A6 _ these cars look alike but there are small
but significant differences, aside from price and power. The A4 is
a nimble little car that, with a Quattro option, takes on just
about any road in any weather, but its back seat is cramped and it
still has that idiotic stalk serving as a headlight switch. With
that stalk sitting, as it does, atop the signal stalk, it's a
simple matter to make a really bad move at night and find yourself
in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   The A6 has more room in the rear _ the A6 Avant wagon is the
superior version, I believe _ and the stalk has given way to a real
headlight switch. Both cars still feature red dash illumination, a
drawback for the color-perception challenged, but that will change
next year in the A6 at least. With the all-wheel-drive Quattro
option, a rain-slicked roadway proved no hazard in an Avant.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in many a moon, I got behind the wheel of a
GMC truck, the new model for 1999, and found it a pleasant beast,
roomy, powerful, very manageable on the track in the rain despite
the speedsters who insist everybody drive like Buck Rogers. General
Motors has been at war with the motor press and makes it extremely
difficult for some to sample their cars, impossible for others.
</P>
<P>
   The rain increased in ferocity, slowing things considerably, but
some of us began to fret about the exuberance being displayed by a
few _ but it was a professional driver for Porsche, not a member of
the press or an automotive wannabe who signaled an end to the
misery by spinning a new Porsche into the wall. Injuries were a
bruise to the passenger's arm and severe damage to the driver's
ego.
</P>
<P>
   The consolations of the soggy day were to be found in
conversation with colleagues and an early start to supper at Arlene
&AMP; Tom's in Port Jervis, N.Y., but that doesn't mean much when
you're paid to drive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-16-98 1909EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
