<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1998 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CATERPILLAR-EARNINGS-     10-16 0314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATERPILLAR-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIRD-QUARTER PROFITS DOWN 12.7 PERCENT AT CATERPILLAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Caterpillar Inc., the world's largest manufacturer of
construction and earth-moving equipment, said Friday that
third-quarter profits fell 12.7 percent because of weaker sales in
Asia and greater competitive pressures that forced the company to
lower prices around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The results, which were well below Wall Street's expectations,
helped deepen the gloom surrounding Caterpillar and other companies
that continue to suffer from a global economic crisis that is
slowing worldwide demand for farm and earth-moving equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Caterpillar, which is based in Peoria, Ill., fell $1,
or 2.1 percent, to $47 in trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly looks like the competitive landscape has gotten
worse,'' said David Bleustein, an analyst at Paine Webber. ``There
is much more pricing pressure than there was three months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Caterpillar said, however, that revenue growth was strong, with
sales of $5.17 billion in the third quarter, up 12.5 percent from a
year ago, largely because of rising sales spurred by lower prices,
huge discounts and strong demand for its equipment in the United
States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Profits for the quarter were $336 million, down from $385
million a year ago. That translated into 92 cents a diluted share,
down 9 percent from $1.01 a share a year ago. Wall Street analysts
had forecast earnings of $1 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Slowing demand for farm and construction equipment in Asia and
Latin America and Caterpillar's acquisition of Perkins Engines in
February cut into profits. Caterpillar was also hurt by its foreign
currency exposure, because of the strong dollar, and by a heavier
sales mix of equipment that had lower profit margins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
