<HEADLINE>
TXREFUGE-DEBATE-$ADV18 
 
RIO GRANDE VALLEY LAND DEBATE ERUPTS OVER EFFORT TO PRESERVE
ENDANGERED WILDCAT SPECIES 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 18) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ISABEL, Texas _ Trying to help an endangered wildcat make a
comeback while preserving a delicate ecosystem of sand dunes, tidal
flats and grassy marshes, the federal government is offering to buy
a large amount of land in the Rio Grande Valley in South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan to expand the Laguna Atascosa National Wildlife
refuge by 172,000 acres _ including the upper half of South Padre
Island near the southern tip of Texas _ is being fought by area
cities that want to leave open the chance for future resort
development, and by communities fearing curtailed beach access.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Givens, who lives near the existing refuge, warns that
when added to the Padre Island National Seashore to the north and
holdings along the Rio Grande to the south, the refuge expansion
would place long stretches of the Texas coast and borderlands in
government hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest concern is this is part of a huge land grab in
South Texas, and the federal government is hiding from the people
of Texas what they are doing,'' said Givens, a retired Army colonel
living in Los Fresnos.
</P>
<P>
   The cities of South Padre Island, Bayview and Los Fresnos have
also voiced their opposition to the refuge expansion, and they are
gaining support from beachgoers who for decades have enjoyed free,
unfettered access to Valley beaches for surf fishing, shell
hunting, picnicking _ even nude sunbathing.
</P>
<P>
   Bayview Mayor Bob Middleton said his main concern is that if the
federal government owns the land, it could eventually restrict
fishing in the area. ``That's just too much land for them to be
tying up forever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Austin, a longtime fishing guide, agrees something needs to
be done to preserve the Valley's pristine beaches but also is
concerned about beach access.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see it (expanded), but then again I know what's
going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will lose the right to use it. There is no doubt in my
mind the federal government is going to curtail traditional uses as
we know it.''
</P>
<P>
   But refuge manager Steve Labuda promises that access will
continue under the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service's
multimillion-dollar plan to buy or lease land and more than
quadruple the refuge's acreage.
</P>
<P>
   The existing refuge, 47,000 acres across the Laguna Madre Bay
from South Padre Island, serves as an important wintering stop for
migratory birds that draw thousands of eco-tourists to the Valley
every year.
</P>
<P>
   The new acreage would provide additional habitat for a number of
endangered species, including 30 to 35 ocelots _ the country's
largest remaining wild population of the reclusive wildcat, which
makes its home in the brushy thickets of the refuge. Federal
biologists hope the small ocelot population, which is showing signs
of inbreeding, would be able to migrate off the refuge and into an
adjacent wildlife corridor that the government is slowly stringing
together along the banks of the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, this plan will allow them to expand southward and
all up and down the river as far as Laredo, if they want, to find
other ocelots,'' Labuda said.
</P>
<P>
   Labuda, a native Texan, biologist and avid hunter and fisherman,
understands residents' concerns, but he is hopeful he can gain
their trust.
</P>
<P>
   He notes that, as it has done in the past, the federal
government will only buy or lease land from willing sellers, and it
will compensate the surrounding counties for lost property taxes.
(This year, the wildlife service gave Cameron County $139,900 to
make up for lost taxes on existing lands in the refuge, and future
payments could reach $400,000 a year.)
</P>
<P>
   Labuda also points out that no tax dollars will be used to
purchase or lease land. Instead, Fish and Wildlife will tap
proceeds from federal duck stamps as well as revenue from offshore
oil leases and from grazing and timber harvesting on public lands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect people to necessarily take me at my word when I
tell them they're going to have free access to the beaches,
improved hunting, more access to (government) lands in the Valley
as a result of this program,'' Labuda said. ``But I hope to prove
(it) to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the wildlife agency's goal to expand the refuge has
been hindered by a 57-page draft issued in August, which in part
seems to contradict promises made by Labuda and local refuge
officials. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Opponents of the expansion, including Givens, are using the
flawed document to claim government officials will promise Valley
residents one thing, and do another. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``I think in the future, some starry-eyed beauty from New York
City, who doesn't appreciate hunting and fishing, could be assigned
to manage the refuge and she could use the stuff in this document
to deny fishing on the lower Laguna Madre,'' Givens said. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Meanwhile, Valley farmers say there is concern that an expanded
refuge _ inhabited by growing numbers Aplomado falcons, ocelots and
other endangered species _ could lead to restrictions on certain
pesticides and agricultural chemicals, curtailing ability to raise
certain crops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big fear that agriculture has is they'll get 20,000 or
30,000 (more) acres in the county, and they'll declare a five-mile
buffer zone around that and then list the chemicals you can't
use,'' said one Valley farmer. ``If they do that, they've
effectively taken your land without paying for it.''
</P>
<P>
   When endangered Aplomado falcons were released on the refuge in
1985, farmers and conservationists met with federal biologists and
reached a deal on the use of pesticides and other chemicals near
the refuge. The compromise allowed farming next to the refuge while
protecting the small falcon, which vanished from Texas in the 1940s
because of habitat loss and pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agricultural community in Texas needs to have some sort of
program that says we will not be inhibited from doing what is legal
on our land just because wildlife habitat has moved next door to
us,'' said Wayne Halbert, manager of a Harlingen irrigation
district who worked on the falcon compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more ocelots killed on highways than anywhere else,
and farmers should not be at risk of being fined or put in jail for
using a licensed pesticide in a legal manner, any more than a
motorist is at risk for running over an ocelot that runs out in
front of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Labuda acknowledged that part of the uproar over the expansion
plan is that the first draft was misleading and ``not real
well-written.''
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to correct any errors in the next draft, expected by
year end, to ease residents' concerns. He said if he succeeds in
acquiring the land, he will seek to keep it open for the same
public uses as today.
</P>
<P>
   Local suspicions about beach closure were heightened last summer
when the state highway department barricaded the only paved road
leading beyond the town of South Padre Island, preventing cars from
driving on the beach through a number of breaks in sand dunes.
Instead, visitors had little choice but to pay to drive onto the
beach through two toll booths on county-owned land.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government, however, plans no fees to drive on the
northern part of the island, Labuda said. He added that many Valley
families could not afford a $2 entrance fee to get to the beach and
hopes to improve access so more people can enjoy the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the opposition, the expansion has some ardent
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make those arrangements so we will have at least
one part of the world, or South Texas, that still is in its natural
state, wildlife in its natural habitat,'' said Ralph Cowan, a
Brownsville car dealer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
