</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FURNITURE-MUSUEM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Famed museum inspires elegant designs
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIGH POINT, N.C. _ The last thing you probably want is for your
living room to look like a museum.
</P>
<P>
   But the pieces that the John Widdicomb furniture company has
selected to reproduce from London's famed Victoria &AMP; Albert Museum
are not only elegant but inviting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is English furniture from a period that's comfortable,''
said the company's Hugh Griffith, as he unveiled the Victoria &AMP;
Albert Collection this week at the International Home Furnishings
Market, which continues through Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The museum was founded in 1852 to encourage excellence in
design. It houses nearly 5 million objects, including the finest
furniture from every period and culture.
</P>
<P>
   Widdicomb has interpreted 14 pieces, mainly from England's
traditional Georgian and Regency eras. The designs, including
Chippendales and Hepplewhites, include an elegant inlaid rosewood
table decorated with a geometric band of parquetry in walnut and
burl. A gold upholstered camelback sofa with high scrolled arms is
embellished with plush cushions. A gilt console table has a marble
top and intricate moldings.
</P>
<P>
   The pieces are expected to retail for $5,400 to $23,000,
Griffith said.
</P>
<P>
   Because the museum holds extensive archives, companies licensed
to design reproductions are granted access to a wealth of furniture
drawings.
</P>
<P>
   And given the Victoria &AMP; Albert's mission to inspire exceptional
design, it's possible, said Michelle Alfandari of V&AMP;A Enterprises,
the museum's commercial arm, that even today's pieces could someday
find a home in a museum.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
