<P>
   CLINTON-POLITICS (Chicago) _ President Clinton, feeling a
rebound from the long focus on the White House sex scandal, embarks
on political trip to help Democratic congressional candidates. By
NANCY MATHIS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-BUDGET (Washington) _ The House and Senate delay until
Tuesday a vote on $500 billion spending package that emerged from
arduous negotiations with the White House. Leaders of the
Republican-run Congress, postponing again their election-year
adjournment, say the delay was needed so lawmakers could review the
budget deal. By GREG McDONALD. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TERRORISM-OFFICE (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno
announces the creation of a new office that will focus on domestic
terrorism. By STEVE LASH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   HORMEL (Washington) _ In the wake of the apparent failure of the
Senate to approve gay rights advocate James C. Hormel as ambassador
to Luxembourg, the Clinton administration is considering whether to
resubmit the nomination next year. By JUDY HOLLAND.
(1stld-writethru filed.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-TAMAULIPAS (Mexico City) _ Results of a new poll show
Mexico's ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, is
virtually assured of retaining the governor's seat in this month's
elections in the northeastern state of Tamaulipas. By PHILIP TRUE.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M (Waco, Texas) _ No. 10 ranked Texas A&AMP;M, coming
off one of the biggest victories in school history, will try to
extend its mastery over Baylor Saturday night. By TERRY BLOUNT.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-TEXAS-TECH (Boulder, Colo.) _ Undefeated Texas Tech puts its
No. 22 ranking on the line against Colorado in a Big 12 battle of
nationally ranked teams. By JEROME SOLOMON.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ANTHRAX-VACCINE (Washington) _ Ten months after the Pentagon
announced plans to inoculate 2.4 million troops against the deadly
anthrax disease, the military is combating widespread anxiety that
the vaccine might cause sterility, cancer or the mysterious Gulf
War syndrome. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-MAURO-PROFILE (Austin, Texas) _ The polls are against him,
the money isn't flowing his way and even some stalwarts in his own
party have forsaken him for his opponent, but Garry Mauro doesn't
act like a man headed for a predicted major defeat. He seems
energized and even a little cocky as he heads into the final days
of the campaign for governor of Texas. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-BUSH-PROFILE (Temple, Texas) _ Gov. George W. Bush and
company find themselves in a rare downpour as they journey to
Central Texas to promote the Republican ticket. Bush, ever the
ice-breaker, is undaunted by the rain. ``I'm happy to announce our
drought relief plan is working,'' he quips, the crowd laughing its
approval. We profile the incumbent. By LAURA TOLLEY. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-TX-POLITICS (Austin, Texas) _ With Texas' crime rate
down and voters not yet concerned about the economy, candidates in
this year's statewide election are running like it's a contest for
local school board. Republicans and Democrats alike have emphasized
their role in obtaining educational excellence in Texas. By R.G.
RADCLIFFE. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-TOWN (Jacumba, Calif.) _ Imagine that you have friends
and family across the street, but you have to make a circuitous
drive a couple hours out of your way to visit them. That's the
reality for the residents of Jacumba, Calif., and Jacume, Mexico.
Operation Gatekeeper, the highly touted border crackdown, pushed
thousands of illegal immigrants from San Diego east into Jacume,
followed by a fence straddling these two border towns. By KIM COBB.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NOBEL-MURAD-PROFILE (Houston) _ The son of an Albanian
immigrant, Dr. Ferid Murad may be the only Nobel winner in the
world who owns his own radial saw and builds his own garages. We
profile Murad, whose pioneering work with nitric oxide is saving
the lives of premature babies who likely would have died just a few
years ago. By RUTH SoRELLE. (2ndl-writethru filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NOBEL-PRESTIGE (Houston) _ A Nobel prize can do wonders for your
self-esteem. Just ask people at the Baylor College of Medicine,
which has one on display. By RUTH SoRELLE. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   McDUFF-BODIES (Undated) _ Three bodies have been dug up in
Central Texas _ all of them women who were slain by Kenneth McDuff
in 1991-92. The 52-year-old killer is the only inmate on Texas'
death row to be paroled and later sentenced to death again for
another capital murder. He recently was granted a stay of his Oct.
21 execution date for Colleen Reed's slaying. By THADDEUS
HENDERSON. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SEX-OFFENDER (Undated) _ Ryan Conner was an insecure kid with
dyslexia when a teacher offered him some powerful words: I love
you. Then he reached for the boy's crotch. ``I told him, `Stop,
it's nasty,''' the boy recalled. ``Mr. O said, `Oh, come on' and
just kept doing it. I just thought he is an older person, and I
have to do what he says.'' By R.A. DYER. (2ndld-writethru filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TXREFUGE-DEBATE (Port Isabel, Texas) _ The federal government's
plan to expand the Laguna Atascosa National Wildlife refuge by
172,000 acres _ including the upper half of South Padre Island near
the southern tip of Texas _ is being fought by cities that want to
leave open the chance for future resort development, and by
communities fearing curtailed beach access. By JAMES PINKERTON.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HONOR-KILLINGS (Amman, Jordan) _ Four years ago, a 16-year-old
Jordanian girl named Kifaya was tied to a chair and told to recite
an Islamic prayer. As neighbors listened to her plead for her life,
her brother slit her throat to cleanse his family's honor of the
shame of Kifaya's ``immoral behavior'': she had been raped by
another brother and forced to get an abortion. By DEBORAH HORAN.
(Already filed.)
</P>
