<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS CONTINUE TO CLIMB FOLLOWING RATE CUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Confidence stemming from the Federal Reserve Board's
second interest rate cut in three weeks spread further through
financial markets Friday, as stock prices registered strong gains
in heavy trading and bond yields fell.
</P>
<P>
   By the close of trading, the Dow Jones industrial average, which
soared more than 330 points Thursday in an enthusiastic response to
the rate reductions orchestrated by Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan,
advanced another 117.40, or 1.41 percent, to 8,416.76. For the
week, the blue-chip index was up 6.55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Broader market averages also posted healthy gains.
</P>
<P>
   Capping its best week in 14 years, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index rose 8.93 points, or nine-tenths of 1 percent to 1,056.42.
For the week, the index gained 7.31 percent, its best showing since
the week of Sept. 3, 1984, according to Birinyi &AMP; Associates.
</P>
<P>
   And the Nasdaq composite index concluded its best week in 24
years, rising 9.94 points, or six-tenths of 1 percent, to 1,620.95.
For the week, the Nasdaq, home of many fast-growing technology
companies, soared 8.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The benefit of what Mr. Greenspan did for stocks on Thursday
is not so much an indication that the Fed will provide liquidity to
the system, but to instill a sense of confidence in the system
again,'' said Jonathan Olesky, head of block trading at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some degree, things have shut down in financial markets,
due to a loss of confidence,'' Olesky said, referring to what has
happened since Russia defaulted on its sovereign debt in August.
``You don't have to look very far now to realize that people are
much more constructive on the market.''
</P>
<P>
   The gains left all three major indexes in positive territory for
the year. Since the first day of trading in January, the Dow is up
6.4 percent, the S&AMP;P 500 is up 8.9 percent and the Nasdaq composite
is up 3.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of small companies, which have been battered so far this
year, also finished with strong gains.
</P>
<P>
   Two stocks rose for every one that fell in price. The Russell
2000 index of smaller-company shares gained 8.06 points, or 2.4
percent, to 342.87. At more than 1 billion shares, volume on the
New York Stock Exchange was the fourth-busiest in the history of
the Big Board.
</P>
<P>
   In large measure, the interest rate cuts by the Fed have
generated hope among investors that the central bank will do all it
can to avert a downturn in the American economy by cutting interest
rates further.
</P>
<P>
   The sense that the Fed is prepared to cut the overnight Federal
funds rate, currently at 5 percent, still further is readily
apparent in the credit markets.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although yields on 30-year Treasury bonds rose marginally, to
4.98 percent from 4.97 Thursday, the rate on three-month Treasury
bills, the rate most sensitive to changes in the overnight Federal
funds rate, fell by 30 basis points, to a bond equivalent yield of
3.61 percent. It was the biggest one-day drop in the three-month
bill rate since the summer of 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to get more rate cuts, maybe at the next Fed
meeting in November,'' said Alfred Goldman, chief market strategist
at A.G. Edwards in St. Louis. ``The Fed is our friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Short-term rates were also responding Friday to continued rumors
that a big bank or other financial institution is near failure.
</P>
<P>
   As they often have in recent days, the rumors focused on the
health of Bankers Trust, which is expected to release its
third-quarter earnings report next week.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Bankers Trust came under heavy selling pressure in the
stock market, losing 5 9/16, to 51 5/16, on a day when most
financial stocks posted good gains.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, prices of regional bank stocks, which have lost about
one-third of their value since July, were among the market's
leaders Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Bank One gained 2 13/16, to 47 15/16. Keycorp climbed 2 15/16,
to 31 1/8. U.S. Bancorp rose 1 3/8, to 40 15/16. And SunTrust
gained 1 1/8, to 68 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation stocks, led by airlines, roared ahead. The Dow
Jones transportation index jumped 116.59 points, or 4.4 percent, to
close at 2780.87.
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest gainers were Delta Air Lines, which rose 4
1/2, to 98. AMR, parent of American Airlines, gained 1 7/8, to 56
3/8. And US Airways Group gained 4 5/16, to 54 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes that the Fed might be able to stave off a recession helped
to lift cyclical stocks Friday, as prices of automobile, steel and
chemical companies all rose.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors gained 2 15/16, to 59. Ford Motor was up 2 1/16,
to 50 13/16. And USX gained 1 3/8, to 23 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dow is up almost 1,000 points since its close on Oct. 8,''
Goldman said. ``We are not going to just sail from here, but I
think we saw the lows on Aug. 31.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
