<HEADLINE>
WHAT MORE CAN WE DO TO PROTECT THREATENED WOMEN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One Quincy woman is dead, another is presumed to be. One husband
is in custody, another is under suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic violence is back in the headlines with the fatal
shooting of Elizabeth Holland in her Dysart Street home this week
and the disappearance of Katherine Leonard Romano from her Huntress
Street home three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Once again we are reciting the same old cliche: ``A restraining
order is just a piece of paper It can't save women.'' Once more, we
are asking the same old question: ``Can we ever protect women from
violence in their own homes?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer from Quincy District Court Judge Charles Black and
Norfolk County District Attorney Jeffrey Locke seems to be that we
can't. At least, not always. At least, not this time.
</P>
<P>
   Locke insists that Liz Holland did everything right, that the
Quincy police did everything right, that the courts did everything
right in their combined efforts to protect the 31-year-old
operating room technician from an abusive spouse. How is it then
that on Wednesday morning, 8-year-old Patrick Holland found his
mother's battered, bullet-ridden body in a pool of blood in a
corner of an upstairs bedroom?
</P>
<P>
   It is not as though ``the system'' that Locke extols was unaware
of Daniel Holland's penchant for violence toward his wife. Liz
Holland obtained her first court order of protection against him in
1993 from the Quincy District Court, renewed it many times, and
received her last one on Feb. 16 of this year from the Norfolk
County Probate Court.
</P>
<P>
   In an affidavit filed last winter, Holland outlined the pattern
of violence that defined her marriage. ``In the last week he
knocked me down on the kitchen floor, telling me he was going to
smash my face in, chased me through the house yelling and throwing
things at me,'' she wrote of her estranged husband, a man she was
in the process of divorcing. ``He threw a glass at my head,
shattering it, and overturned a table. All this occurred with
Patrick, age 8, in the immediate area. He threw me to the ground,
pulled me back by the hair when I tried to get up, screamed
obscenites at me and threatened to kill me if I `did anything
stupid.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I have tried to leave the immediate area to allow him to cool
off and he chases me. Once I got as far as the car and he pulled me
out through the window. We have gone to counseling, mediation and,
while it gets better at times, the threat is always'' there.
</P>
<P>
   The threat was there last June when young Patrick handed his
mother the gun he found under a sofa cushion in the living room.
Liz Holland called the police. Violation of a restraining order is
a criminal offense. Her husband denied the gun was his. His denial
was good enough for the officers, who decided there was no probable
cause to arrest Daniel Holland for violating the court's order of
protection.
</P>
<P>
   The court disagreed and issued a criminal complaint. But the
system moved forward none too urgently: Prosecutors did not arraign
Daniel Holland for violating the restraining order until September,
three months after the incident. Judge Black said the district
attorney did not ask for bail, so he set a trial date of Dec. 7 and
let Holland go.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later, Liz Holland is dead and Daniel Holland is
charged with first degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   It is always easier to assign blame after the fact than to
prevent tragedies before they occur. It is always easier to talk
about saving battered women than to address the legitimate tension
that exists between protecting the lives of victims and preserving
the rights of defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a case like this, I don't know that anything more could
have been done,'' Judge Black said yesterday. ``The Quincy police
are superb on these cases. They had a close call on probable cause
in the gun incident. The prosecutor could have requested bail, but
should he have? I don't know. We fast-tracked this case to get it
to trial in December. I ask myself what more we could have done to
change the result and, sadly, I don't think there is anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Locke, who handled Holland's arraignment personally this week,
noted that on Tuesday night Liz Holland's killer trapped her
between a wall and a bed while he shot her and beat her with the
rifle butt. ``It appears she did everything she could to get away
without diving out a window,'' Locke said. ``It looks like
Elizabeth Holland was in a state of terror for some period.''
</P>
<P>
   That period of terror did not begin on Tuesday night, Mr. Locke;
that's just when it ended. Elizabeth Holland did do everything she
could do to save herself. Did we?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
