<HEADLINE>
POWERFUL `AFRICANS IN AMERICA' IS MUST VIEWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several times during the six hours of ``Africans in America,''
the camera moves reverently over a list of names that were
scrupulously entered into the record by an American owner of
slaves.
</P>
<P>
   Davy Sr. Davy Jr. Fanny. Ellen. Jenny. Dolly. Isaac. Israel.
James.
</P>
<P>
   Cretia. Lilly. Lilburn. Matilda. Lovila. Nancy. Jupiter. Amy.
Joe.
</P>
<P>
   From these names, inscribed neatly in black ink on white paper,
it's easy to imagine the inhumanity: the horror of families ripped
apart, of human liberties abridged, of personal integrity subsumed
by the profit motive.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the most effective devices Orlando Bagwell's
production team uses in this fine PBS documentary _ a film every
American should see at least once, because it's not likely many of
us have spent much time with the subject, no matter how tightly it
is woven into the fabric of this country.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell's work is exhaustive but never tiresome, and it stands
alongside Ken Burns' ``The Civil War'' as one of the great
historical documentaries of this generation.
</P>
<P>
   Airing on four consecutive nights next week on PBS, ``Africans
in America'' is a troubling story of a nation dedicated to
principles of personal liberty yet built on the most egregious
violations of those principles.
</P>
<P>
   In part one Monday, ``The Terrible Transformation'' tells of
``the largest forced migration in recorded history,'' which began
innocently enough with the unplanned arrival of 20 Africans at
Jamestown, Va., aboard a mystery ship in 1619. The crew of the ship
had pirated the Africans from a Spanish vessel and sold them to
Virginia colonists in exchange for food.
</P>
<P>
   Those first African Americans were not slaves. They might have
become indentured servants, the same as white Europeans who signed
agreements with their Virginia employers in exchange for passage to
the New World and a chance to start out on their own at the
termination of their service contracts. Records show that some
black servants, upon satisfying the terms of their indenture,
became prominent landowners, living in harmony alongside their
white neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   In 1640, however, when three servants ran away from a Virginia
plantation, the climate began to change. Upon their capture, two of
the servants, both white Europeans, were indentured for an
additional year. The third, an African named John Punch, was
sentenced to serve ``his master'' for the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Massachusetts became the first American colony to
make slavery legal. One century after that, 31 slaves were either
burned at the stake or hanged in New York City amid rising fears of
an insurrection by slaves.
</P>
<P>
   How had colonial America gone from a nation that was essentially
color blind to one that subjugated an entire race?
</P>
<P>
   It was the economy. As American planters sought to expand, first
in the production of tobacco, and eventually in cotton and rice,
they needed cheap _ or better yet, free _ labor. Thomas Jefferson,
author of ``all men are created equal,'' admitted that slaveholders
would someday have to pay for their transgressions. His shame,
though, was not sufficient to free the slaves who kept him and his
family comfortable at Monticello.
</P>
<P>
   Parts two, three and four are ``Revolution'' (1750-1805),
``Brotherly Love'' (1776-1834) and ``Judgment Day'' (1831-1861).
With rich narration by Angela Bassett and the voices of such actors
as Avery Brooks, Andre Braugher, William Hurt and Carl Lumbly
bringing words of the era to life, each installment is an
invaluable guide to what ``Africans in America'' calls ``America's
journey through slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   Africans in America. Four-part, six-hour documentary on the
history of slavery in America. Narrated by Angela Bassett. Monday
through Thursday on PBS. Check local listings. Parental guideline
rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
