<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S REALITY, AND THEN THERE'S HOLLYWOOD'S CONCEPTION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ?????  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The show lasted just four episodes. Not even
Southie chic could rescue ``Costello,'' with a concept too tiny and
a kitchen too big. This sitcom family chowed down in something like
the hoop court at the South Boston Boys and Girls Club or the
parade ground at Castle Island.
</P>
<P>
   The Fox network, under the spiritual guidance of Rupert Murdoch,
is the Lower End of programming, seldom fussy about authenticity or
amiability. Many new programs hope to resurrect working-class
nostalgia. Ralph Kramden begat Archie Bunker, who begat Roseanne,
whose heirlooms are high ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Reality has bleached that blue collar into cluelessness. The
scripts for the latest washout placed the beguiling heroine, Sue
Costello, in impossible situations. She pesters Pop for a ride to
City Point to visit her therapist. A ride? To City Point? To see a
therapist? Another character threatens Sue with trouble ``at the
DMV.'' In Massachusetts, it's the Registry of Motor Vehicles, if
the California writers had checked.
</P>
<P>
   South Boston's kitchens are small, but its heart is big.
Overall, the show was not flattering to that patch of heaven, zip
code 02127. Southie must be content with the afterglow of ``Good
Will Hunting,'' even as Greater Boston remains a giant sound stage
for movies and television.
</P>
<P>
   Some television touches stretch credulity, making area code 617
a fantasy island of verisimilitude. Why does the scruffy lead
lawyer in ``The Practice'' boycott Southie's biggest employer? Some
jurors might work for Gillette. Ally McBeal's confusion may be
related to geography. Her office is on Beacon Street,near the State
House, but her view is of Faneuil Hall. In Hollywood, one
gold-domed pile of bricks is as good as another.
</P>
<P>
   Verisimilitude can affect a city's reputation. Here in San
Francisco, the city was becoming cloyingly precious in the 1970s
before Clint Eastwood made those gritty ``Dirty Harry'' movies. On
television, Karl Malden and Michael Douglas rode the squad cars and
public sympathy for police, making cops look good in ``The Streets
of San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   The city of Baltimore is the real star of ``Homicide: Life on
the Street,'' but authenticity isn't everything. In the latest
police show filmed here, ``Nash Bridges,'' the scenery is stunning,
but the plots and characters are preposterous. ``Dharma and Greg''
is filmed in a studio, but the characters evoke everyday life in
Haight-Ashbury and Nob Hill.
</P>
<P>
   In the final episode of ``Costello,'' Sue meets a student at
Harvard Dental School. Harvard has no dental school, but Tufts
does. Tufts plays a starring role in an ABC comedy about two guys,
a pizza, and unfunny dialogue. In one wildly improbable plot turn,
someone is scalping tickets to a Tufts homecoming game. The noble
Jumbos should have it so good. Also, the team seems to be playing
UCLA in a stadium bigger than Sue Costello's kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   In verisimilitude, size matters. Those bush pilots in ``Wings''
lived in houses on Nantucket that Fortune 500 tycoons couldn't
afford.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the television characters in ersatz Hub settings affect
a post-Seinfeldian edge that favors nasty over zany. It's witless
class warfare, making the gang at ``Cheers'' seem as distant and
quaint as characters in a Henry James novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheers'' took place in Ward Five, but recent movies still
celebrate the less glamorous precincts of Boston. ``Next Stop,
Wonderland'' asks the question: Will the suspicious woman from the
South End finally meet the earnest fellow from Eastie? ``Monument
Ave.'' wonders whether Charlestown is still Charlestown and whether
Townies are still Townies.
</P>
<P>
   Boston is cinematic hot property, good news for the many guys I
know who seldom travel beyond Neponset Circle. Hollywood is now on
a talent hunt in what Jack Kennedy called ``a city where they
pronounce the words the way they are spelled.'' These barstool
Barry-mores could soon be dialect coaches. Is America a great
country or what?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
