<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CAMPAIGN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOULD CLINTON CAMPAIGN FOR THOSE WHO WILL SIT IN JUDGMENT?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's President Clinton's modus operandi as a
prodigious fund-raiser _ using his appeal to raise big bucks for
Democratic allies, including those on Capitol Hill, in the final
push before an election.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, shadowed by impeachment clouds, there is concern
that Clinton's fund-raising on behalf of Senate candidates is
inappropriate and should cease because the full Senate would sit in
judgment of the president if he is impeached by the House.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and congressional watchdog groups are warning that
with a constitutional process now in play, such fund-raising
activities have the appearance of a conflict of interest,
particularly when support from Democrats is so crucial to whether
Clinton stays in office.
</P>
<P>
   The concern surfaced earlier this week when the president went
to New York and raised $1.1 million for Representative Charles E.
Schumer, a Senate candidate and member of the House Judiciary
Committee. Clinton also raised eyebrows when he made a reference to
Schumer as ``voting right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The president owes it to the public not to do anything at all,
particularly in the case of the Senate, that creates the appearance
of witness tampering or jury tampering,'' said Gary Ruskin,
director of the Congressional Accountability Project, a
congressional reform group tied to consumer advocate Ralph Nader.
``Whether or not it's an actual conflict is one thing, but the
appearance is bad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But is it reasonable to expect Clinton to sit on his hands and
not help elect members of his own party, including Senate
candidates? And is it reasonable to expect those who benefit from
his financial support to not be influenced?
</P>
<P>
   Friday, after a Rose Garden ceremony celebrating the budget
deal, Clinton flew to Chicago for a $2,500-a-plate luncheon to help
Senator Carol Moseley-Braun, who is locked in an tough battle to
retain her seat.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, it's Senator Barbara Boxer's turn. The president is
scheduled to travel to California Tuesday _ for the second time in
three weeks _ to help fatten her campaign coffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The support of every Democratic senator is utterly essential
to Bill Clinton,'' said Charles Lewis, executive director of the
Center for Public Integrity. ``Their judgment has to somehow remain
objective even though he may have saved their neck financially in
terms of the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis added: ``This is particularly bizarre and wild, and an
almost unprecedented historic occurence that we are stumbling into
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Grossman, a Massachusetts native and chairman of the
Democratic National Committee, said, ``I have no doubt that any
Democratic member of the Senate will exercise his or her
responsibility in an entirely appropriate and dignified way.''
</P>
<P>
   The potential conflict for Clinton did not present itself, most
analysts agree, until last month, when independent counsel Kenneth
W. Starr sent his report to Congress outlining possible impeachable
offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Before then, Clinton had attended fund-raisers that benefited
some members of the House Judiciary Committee, which will conduct
an impeachment inquiry starting next month, including an August
event that raised $300,000 for California Representative Maxine
Waters.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, White House and Democratic Party officials scoffed at
the notion that Clinton's fund-raising for Senate Democrats is
improper and said the pace has not increased since Starr issued his
report.
</P>
<P>
   They compared Clinton's situation to House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, saying Gingrich did not refrain from campaigning for
fellow Republicans when he was under an ethics investigation by the
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the speaker isn't the subject of an impeachment inquiry,''
retorted Patricia Harrison, who co-chairs the Republican National
Committee. She said the White House and its allies were comparing
``apples to dump trucks.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Barry Toiv said that using Harrison's
logic, Clinton would not be able to campaign for any member of
Congress ``since at some point they could all conceivably have to
sit in judgment of him. Frankly, that's exactly what the
Republicans would like, but there is no reason for him not to and
he will continue to campaign for Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the Democrats who benefit from Clinton's
fund-raisers would be unlikely to vote for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Cathie Levine, Schumer's press secretary, said Schumer does not
think the allegations against Clinton are worthy of impeachment.
``Chuck has made it very clear that he believes what the president
did was wrong, and while it warrants punishment, it does not rise
to the level of impeachment,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton has raised money for Schumer, his Republican
opponent, Senator Alfonse D'Amato, ``went down to Atlanta and
raised money from Newt Gingrich,'' Levine said.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman described the criticism of Clinton as ``political
gamesmanship. They are attempting to obscure the fact that ... the
Republican Party is adrift and without an agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   But others cited the fund-raising as part of Senator Robert
Byrd's warning to Clinton. The veteran Democrat from West Virginia
took to the Senate floor last week to tell the White House, ``don't
tamper with this jury,'' after Clinton aides tried to get 34
signatures from senators to prejudge a House impeachment inquiry as
moot.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case of potential jury tampering and votes for
sale,'' said the GOP's Harrison. ``We are part of a very serious
initiative here. We are Americans first, not Democrats and
Republicans, and the Constitution trumps all of this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
