<HEADLINE>
MIDDLE EAST LEADERS SPEND A DAY TALKING PEACE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Wearing casual clothes and listening to
exhortations from US mediators, Israeli and Palestinian leaders
entered their first full day of peace talks in a Maryland retreat
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   While four working groups discussed security and other issues,
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian President
Yasser Arafat sat with an interpreter on a deck overlooking the
bank of the Wye River for about an hour. They then joined Secretary
of State Madeleine K. Albright for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James P. Rubin described a day full
of meetings, phone calls, and ``cross-pollination.'' But he refused
to talk about the progress of the talks, which are expected to
conclude tomorrow or Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the pace of the work, the seriousness of the
work, the pragmatism that the delegations are bringing to bear, the
constructive approach, is there,'' Rubin said. ``Whether that will
be enough is still an open question.''
</P>
<P>
   A Palestinian indicated to reporters that Clinton had given the
negotators a firm deadline of Tuesday to come up with a plan for an
Israeli withdrawal from 13 percent more of the West Bank.
Otherwise, the US government will abandon its role as mediator, the
aide said.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, Albright has hinted that Washington is
tiring of negotiating without solid results. Asked about an exact
deadline, Rubin said. ``I never heard anyone suggesting such a
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Many experts who have talked to both delegations expect some
agreement about a pullout to be reached by the end of the weekend,
although thorny issues about Palestinians' rights to travel and
plans for a Palestinian airport are still being discussed. Even
tougher matters, such as the boundaries of Jerusalem and water
rights, await other rounds of talks.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and Arab-language newspapers and television stations
have given conflicting accounts of the progress of talks leading up
to the summit and during the initial conversations Thursday at the
White House and the Wye plantation. Several experts said top CIA
officials are present to talk with Palestinians about
anti-terrorist measures demanded by the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Both delegations also have lawyers to discuss the different
phases of the next West Bank withdrawal, which is expected to take
several months.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made a political appearance in Chicago but talked to
Albright on route. He is expected at the Wye River retreat today
for informal discussions with both sides. Albright also spoke with
Jordan's King Hussein, who is serving as a long-distance
mediator-emeritus from a cancer clinic in Rochester, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   The king met Friday with Israel's foreign minister, Ariel
Sharon, who was on his way to the summit.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai also is expected this
weekend. A spokesman told Reuters that Mordechai had remained in
Israel during the week because of threats of ``Hamas terrorist
attacks aimed at undermining the negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   The talks halted at sundown in honor of the Jewish Sabbath.
Netanyahu dined with his advisers while the Americans and
Palestinians gathered for a dinner. Because the Sabbath does not
end till sundown tonight, the Americans cautioned that very little
progress is likely today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect people to talk to each other, but as far as
formal work or note-taking or formal travel, I wouldn't expect
that, but we'll have to see,'' Rubin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
