<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILLINOIS-CAMPAIGN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY DOES CAROL MOSELEY-BRAUN LOOK LIKE A LOSER?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVANSTON, Ill. _ In a charming Victorian parlor on a broad,
tree-lined boulevard _ the suburban equivalent of a legendary
Chicago smoke-filled room _ the new Democratic kingmakers sipped
bottled water and wondered how things had gone so terribly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Less than three weeks before the election, US Senator Carol
Moseley-Braun, the political nobody these affluent, activist women
of Evanston helped turn into a historic somebody six years ago,
looks like a loser on Nov. 3. Though leading Democrats are mounting
a rescue operation _ Hillary Rodham Clinton will campaign with her
today, President Clinton was at her side Friday _ she trails her
Republican opponent, state Senator Peter Fitzgerald, by 13 points
in the latest Chicago Tribune poll.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, this parlor was full of promise and high hopes
for Moseley-Braun, the nation's first black woman senator. Today,
her backers are frustrated at Moseley-Braun's many missteps and
bitter that the soccer moms and stalwart Democratic men who elected
her aren't inclined to give her a second chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``God help a woman candidate who strays,'' said Joan Levin, who
was in Moseley-Braun's law school class at the University of
Chicago. ``Everybody makes mistakes, but somehow people hold women
officials to a higher standard and have expectations for them that
they don't have for men.''
</P>
<P>
   If 1992 was the Year of the Woman, when a record number of
female candidates soared into office, 1998 looks like the Year of
the Endangered Woman. First-term women senators are fighting for
survival in California and Washington state, but neither seems as
desperate as Moseley-Braun, who in a statewide TV ad this week
admitted to Illinois voters that she had let her backers down.
</P>
<P>
   ``My tenure hasn't been without rocks and blemishes. I've
stumbled and made mistakes,'' Moseley-Braun told her friends last
weekend in Evanston. ``But I've kept the faith, and I've worked
hard. It's a big job, and bigger when you look like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics don't buy the argument that Moseley-Braun, 51, is
disadvantaged by her race or gender. This contest, they say, is a
referendum on the senator's character and integrity, qualities that
are magnified this year by President Clinton's affair with Monica
S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   John McGovern, spokesman for Fitzgerald, points out that
Moseley-Braun has been investigated for several scandals of her
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1992, a lot of women voters, particularly Republican women,
were intrigued by the symbolism of Moseley-Braun's candidacy, but
now that they have learned all about the scandal and the
controversy, they are the first to desert her, based on ethics
alone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   First there was the $28,000 inheritance she and her siblings
divided before being forced to reimburse Medicaid for their
mother's nursing-home bills. Next came a secret trip _ the first of
seven _ to Nigeria, where Moseley-Braun met with General Sani
Abacha, the late dictator despised by human-rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   There were sexual harassment allegations made against Kgosie
Matthews, her former fiance and 1992 campaign manager. And both the
Federal Election Commission and the Internal Revenue Service
investigated the senator and Matthews for allegedly spending
campaign funds on clothes, jewelry, and personal travel. No formal
charges were brought in those cases.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Moseley-Braun created a stir when she lost her
cool before the cameras and blasted conservative commentator George
Will for writing what she believed was a racist column. She
referred to herself with a racial slur and suggested Will could be
a Ku Klux Klansman. ``Will can just take his hood and go back to
wherever he came from,'' she said. Moseley-Braun had to retract her
words and apologize to Will.
</P>
<P>
   ``She simply has blown it with the dumb things she does,'' said
Kenneth Janda, a professor of political science at Northwestern
University in Evanston. ``She had an opportunity for a long career
in Washington but instead showed by her behavior that she was not a
very able individual and that she is out of her league.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Lehner, an Evanston homemaker and mother of three, voted
for Moseley-Braun in 1992 but says she is unlikely to support her
again. ``Why should I, when she hasn't done much in six years?''
Lehner asked. ``I'd like to vote for `none of the above.'''
</P>
<P>
   Moseley-Braun says she has ``produced and been accountable.'' In
her first term she has championed affirmative action, abortion
rights, and gun control, supported free-trade treaties, farm
relief, and a balanced budget, and sponsored legislation to rebuild
schools and mandate pension equity for women.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the refrain in Illinois is that Moseley-Braun was an
``accidental senator.'' A former state legislator and a protege of
former Chicago Mayor Harold Washington, Moseley-Braun was recruited
in 1992 by women outraged over Supreme Court Justice Clarence
Thomas's confirmation hearings. She was the only Democrat left
standing in a nasty, three-way primary fight that ousted incumbent
Senator Alan Dixon, and she easily beat a weak GOP candidate to win
the seat.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Alexis of Evanston, a lawyer who coaxed Moseley-Braun into
the 1992 race and helped her raise money, said state Democratic
leaders _ mostly male and white _ are still chafing over Dixon's
defeat and have done little to bolster Moseley-Braun. ``They're
trying to teach us a lesson about what happens when women and
African-Americans get too uppity,'' she said. ``I hope they wake up
before it's too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Time is running out. Odds now are on a victory by Republican
Fitzgerald, a 37-year-old multimillionaire with a degree in the
classics from Dartmouth College. His voting record is so
conservative that party elders recruited the state comptroller, a
centrist woman, to run against him in the March primary.
</P>
<P>
   In the state Senate, Fitzgerald opposed any new taxes and urged
using the budget surplus to cut taxes instead. He is against
abortion except to save the life of the mother and opposes
homosexuals in the military. He supports school vouchers, and he
recently dropped his opposition to legislation barring people from
carrying concealed handguns.
</P>
<P>
   Though he doesn't fit the progressive profile of past Illinois
senators, Fitzgerald is far ahead in the polls. According to the
Tribune poll published Sunday, Fitzgerald leads Moseley-Braun 49 to
36 percent among all voters, 46 to 35 percent among women, and 58
to 28 percent among suburban white women. In 1992, the gender gap
was reversed; Moseley-Braun led her GOP opponent by 16 points among
women voters. (The latest poll, taken Oct. 3-6, has a margin of
error of 3 points.)
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Fitzgerald is so popular. Only one-third of the
voters have a favorable impression of him, and half don't agree
with his positions on gun control and abortion. But he isn't the
issue. Almost half the electorate has an unfavorable impression of
Moseley-Braun, and only 19 percent believe she is more trustworthy
than her opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Moseley-Braun's high negatives are being reinforced by
Fitzgerald's $400,000 a week in television advertising. Fitzgerald,
who spent $7 million of his own money to win the primary, has been
dubbed the ``stealth candidate'' by the Chicago media because he
makes few public appearances around the city and provides only rare
opportunities for interviews, debates, or speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Celinda Lake, Moseley-Braun's pollster, says she believes the
race is tighter than polls indicate and will narrow more as the
senator pounds her opponent's politics and woos women on issues
they care about, particularly education, health care, and Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the state party is pumping money into Moseley-Braun
ads on television, and today the National Organization for Women
and other liberal interest groups are to launch a ``Women's Votes
Count Campaign'' aimed at increasing turnout in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Democrat Ann Richards, the tart-tongued former
governor of Texas, joined Moseley-Braun for the Evanston meeting.
She urged the women to open their wallets so the senator could
``compete with this rich yahoo on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not since Adam said `Eve made me do it' has a man blamed a
woman for so much that's gone wrong,'' Richards said. ``I say
voters should get over it, move on, and reelect Carol
Moseley-Braun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-16-98 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
