u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMORY-APPRECIATION-BO     10-16 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMORY-APPRECIATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUSADER FOR ANIMALS DIDN'T SHY AWAY FROM FIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was known to many as the archly hilarious author of ``The
Proper Bostonians,'' and to many more as an acerbic writer and
social commentator for the ``Today'' show, ``CBS Morning News,''
the Saturday Review, TV Guide, and Parade magazine.
</P>
<P>
   To those closest to him, he was a charming, kind friend. But to
animal lovers, Cleveland Amory, who died in his sleep at 81 in his
New York apartment Wednesday night, will be remembered best as the
tireless if curmudgeonly crusader for creatures in need.
</P>
<P>
   With his formidable intellect and wit, Amory was like a force of
nature in any cause he took on. And he was never afraid to pick a
fight. In his early years, the Harvard-educated social historian
became known as a traitor to his class with his anthropological hit
on proper Bostonians. Published in 1947, the book is now in its
29th printing. Even the elite eventually had to laugh at his
scorchingly accurate portraits.
</P>
<P>
   He had the ability to make his enemies smile (sort of). And
enemies he made. Throughout his life, he battled any force that
harmed animals.
</P>
<P>
   As a young man writing for the Arizona Daily Star, he was sent
to Nogales, Mexico, to cover a festival that included a bullfight.
Amory often said that he had never witnessed anything as despicable
as the treatment of the bull. In an interview with me in 1997, he
said that the animal had been blinded and his horns shortened. ``A
cross goose could have killed him,'' Amory said, growing angry even
then at the memory.
</P>
<P>
   While the crowd was focused on cheering the matador, Amory, in a
rage, made his way down to the ring, carrying a rain-sodden cushion
from the stands. ``Then I made my prayers to the Almighty. He
hadn't listened to me about the Red Sox,'' Amory said, but he asked
for divine guidance anyway, then hurled the heavy pad at the
smiling matador. It hit him hard in the neck. ``I've had a lot of
great feelings in my life,'' Amory whispered, as an angelic look
passed over his face, ``but this was the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides assaulting matadors, Amory was proud to have protested,
exposed, and sued people, institutions, and government agencies
(including the powerful federal Bureau of Land Management, which he
called ``one of the most despicable agencies in the entire history
of the federal government'').
</P>
<P>
   For the past 30 years, he served, without pay, as president of
the Fund for Animals, a nonprofit animal welfare organization.
Despite his deteriorating health, he insisted on working at the
fund's Manhattan offices every day _ making his way there with the
aid of two canes.
</P>
<P>
   Though often in pain, Amory maintained his dignity and wit. He
was at once both frail and imposing _ a big man with a rakish shock
of gray hair.
</P>
<P>
   Amory begrudgingly revealed his sweet side in three nationally
best-selling cat books: ``The Cat Who Came for Christmas,'' ``The
Cat and the Curmudgeon,'' and ``The Best Cat Ever,'' all centered
on his dear companion, Polar Bear, a big white cat as set in his
ways as his owner.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Amory wrote ``Ranch of Dreams,'' the story of
Black Beauty Ranch, an animal sanctuary he created in Texas.
Through the ranch, he was able to rescue 5,000 burros slated for
slaughter on government land, 4,000 goats in the way of the US Navy
on San Clemente Island, a chimpanzee from a biomedical lab, and
abused elephants and horses.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was born in Nahant to an old New England family, the
genealogical connection that made Amory proudest was his
great-uncle, George Thorndike Angell, founder of the Massachusetts
Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals and the man
responsible for introducing the classic book ``Black Beauty'' to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Anna Sewell's novel about a horse's adventures so profoundly
affected young ``Clippie'' Amory that he dedicated his life to
protecting animals, and he named his sanctuary after it.
</P>
<P>
   Amory's ashes will be buried at the sanctuary, next to the
remains of his beloved Polar Bear. Inscribed nearby, at the gates
of the sanctuary, are some words from ``Black Beauty'' that could
serve as an epitaph: ``I have nothing to fear, and here my story
ends. My troubles are over, and I am home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
