<SLUG> BC-HUNGER-RUSSIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA THREATENED WITH WIDESPREAD HUNGER THIS WINTER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A human chocolate bar merrily bounced through the
crowded hall past the friendly elves in straw hats dishing out
yogurt and fruit juices. Plump butchers proudly displayed salami
mountains, while a large butterfly fashioned from cold cuts and a
beaming young woman surrounded by clusters of balloons dispensed
Eskimo ice cream bars.
</P>
<P>
   This festive cornucopia of Russian food products appeared Friday
in Moscow's central exhibition hall. It was an odd sight as the
poorest harvest in decades and the worst economic crisis in years
threatened Russia with what could be a harsh winter of widespread
hunger and shortages.
</P>
<P>
   Stranger still was the upbeat mood among the food show's
predominantly Russian participants, including producers from some
of the remote far north regions where international relief agencies
fear millions of people could go without basic foodstuffs this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Russians have a saying to explain this apparent contradiction _
``net khuda bez dobra:'' ``There is nothing bad that is not
accompanied by something good.''
</P>
<P>
   One side effect of Russia's financial crisis, during which the
ruble has lost 60 percent of its value, is that imports providing
half of the diet of Russia's large cities became prohibitively
expensive. As a result, domestic food producers suddenly feel
wanted again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say we haven't suffered, and we have even won in
the sense that now our prices no longer look so bad compared with
imports,'' said Nikolai Buldyldin, a top trade official with the
Yamal-Nenets region, a desolate stretch of tundra along the Kara
Sea shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   The region produces the delicious white salmon that Buldydldin
describes as ``an elite fish.'' It has been impossible buy in any
Moscow store because until now, imports from Europe were cheaper.
The outdated distribution system that dogs the entire post-Soviet
food industry made it harder to get fish from Yamal-Nenets to
Moscow than from Norway.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the loss of Soviet-era subsidies made it impossible
for the Yamal-Nenets fish business, like most Russian companies, to
survive without resorting to barter and mutual debt writeoffs. As
with most firms in the food industry, production has plummeted as
the country turned increasingly to imports.
</P>
<P>
   But overall imports to Russia plunged 45 percent in September
because most people can no longer afford them, the government
conceded last week. The flow of imported food has slowed to a
trickle, because no one wants to buy it or distribute it in a
country where the ruble, which has been stable at around 15 to the
dollar for weeks, could return into freefall at any time.
</P>
<P>
   Although no one in Russia wants to appear happy about the
crisis, northern fish factories and other domestic food producers
now find that they can ship their product affordably by using
special rail rates introduced by the government to ease the flow of
foodstuffs during the hard times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fish is full of calories and vitamins so you don't starve,
with enough fat to keep you from freezing to death,'' said Ivan
Zakharov of the far northern region of Tyumen, another fish
wholesaler whose products have become popular in the crisis. Behind
him, as he displayed an array of pungent dried and pickled fish
products soon to hit Moscow's markets, was his firms' slogan: ``The
taste you know from your youth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can live through the winter and hopefully make it to the
next harvest,'' Zakharov said.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, it is hard to reconcile this optimism with the
gloomy assessment produced by western diplomats, relief agencies
and even a Russian parliamentary commission that has recommended
evacuating over a million people from places like Zakharov's Tyumen
homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Red Cross launched an emergency $15 million
appeal to help poor, elderly and disabled Russians hit hard by the
economic crisis. ``We can't exclude the possibility of mass
starvation if the situation continues to deteriorate,'' Borje
Sjokvist, head of the Moscow delegation of the International
Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies, said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Some 12 million people who reside in the hostile climates of
Russia's Far North, the human legacy of the failed Soviet dream to
conquer the resource-rich Arctic, face a winter of hunger due to
the breakdown of supply networks. Many of these people live in
cities that have no growing season and can only be supplied by ship
or river barge during the short summer season.
</P>
<P>
   The whole country may suffer shortages of meat, vegetable oil
and butter starting in January, a private agriculture think-tank
headed by former Agriculture Minister Viktor Khlystun predicted in
a report announced Friday in the Russian media.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a disaster in the making, and there doesn't seem to be
any way to avoid it,'' said one Western diplomat, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov said his bankrupt
government had found $600 million to create an emergency food
reserve that will last two weeks and cover one-third of Russia's
148 million residents. Russia has also asked for food and medicine
from the European Union to survive the winter, and has been
conducting talks with the United States on receiving grain and
other foods on long-term credit and as humanitarian aid.
</P>
<P>
   Such plans are at odds with the words of Deputy Prime Minister
Gennady Kulik, who this week declared: ``Russian producers are
capable of feeding the country by themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   But years, even decades, or shortage and crisis have left
Russians unflappable in the face of disaster. Here, the bar is
higher on suffering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone used to a stable, logical or predictable situation can
easily find himself shocked by our daily life,'' commented Viktor
Dobrostosky, a senior Russian Agricultural Ministry official.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people are used to living within their means and getting
by,'' added Lena Cherdashina, marketing manager for Mistral, a
Russian company that sells smartly packaged rice products. ``Rice
is one of the things people are buying.''
</P>
<P>
   And many Russians just like winter, no matter what it brings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever seen the Russian winter?,'' asked Olga Tolstik,
marketing manager from an ice-cream maker in the Urals capital of
Yekaterinburg, her eyes dancing with the reflection of hundreds of
Eskimo ice cream bars in their bright wrappers. ``It's all snow and
delicious cold and endless, clean white, like Russian ice cream.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
