<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITALS-FOR-SALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC GROUP MAKES DEAL FOR EIGHT SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA HOSPITALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- San Francisco-based Catholic Healthcare West will
buy eight Southern California hospitals from Unihealth of suburban
Burbank for an undisclosed sum, the companies announced.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which will make CHW the third-largest hospital
operator in the Los Angeles market, includes Northridge Hospital
Medical Center, Glendale Memorial Hospital and six others in Los
Angeles and Orange counties.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at CHW said the purchase should be approved by state
regulators within 60 days and, when complete, will give the chain
greater leverage in contracting with physicians and managed care
companies. CHW now owns six hospitals in Southern California,
including St. Vincent Medical Center in Los Angeles. Both CHW and
Unihealth are nonprofit organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Yoshioka, president of Unihealth's medical centers division,
characterized the sale as a merger because half of the hospitals'
existing board members will remain, while half will be new
appointees from CHW. Yoshioka said Unihealth is exiting the Los
Angeles market because of a lack of market share.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look around Southern California, we don't have any
critical mass anywhere in terms of number of hospitals,'' he said.
``This combo is a good strategic fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Unihealth last year sold its CareAmerica managed care and life
insurance divisions to Blue Shield of California for $175 million.
The company will continue to operate a physician management network
in California.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Lott, a vice president at the Healthcare Association of
Southern California hospital trade group, said consolidation of
hospital ownership is increasingly common in California and will
likely accelerate in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We envision throughout California having eight to 12
(hospital) systems dominate the market within the next 10 to 15
years,'' Lott said. ``We see that as the only way to effectively
compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott said that using similar leverage, managed care firms have
wrangled unsustainably low prices from hospitals and other health
care providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we hope will happen is that some of the leverage will
return to the provider side of the ledger at the expense of the
payer side of the ledger,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While CHW has said it will continue to provide care at the new
hospitals in the tradition of Unihealth, the chain does plan to
limit the availability of reproductive health care, including
in-vitro fertilization and abortion-on-demand procedures. The
hospitals will, however, provide abortions when the life of the
mother is at risk, CHW spokeswoman Joyce Hawthorne said.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the Los Angeles chapter of the National
Organization of Women opposes CHW's purchase of the eight
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view this as the major problem of the end of the '90s,''
said Judith Meuli, vice president of L.A. NOW. ``We're unalterably
opposed to any religious organization taking over our health
organizations that do not supply birth control and reproductive
services.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than register its opposition with regulators, however, the
group can do little to stop the sale, she acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshioka said the hospitals will continue to provide
contraceptive services.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
