<HEADLINE>
SMITH SAVORS RUNNING REVIVAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ For much of the past two seasons, critics have
pointed to Soldier Field and the sight of Cowboys running back
Emmitt Smith being carted off on a stretcher as the beginning of
his decline.
</P>
<P>
   Smith will return to Chicago tomorrow for the first time since
that 1996 season opener. And he'll be stoked with the knowledge
that the scary incident _ in which he suffered a bruised neck and
back after diving over a pile in the fourth quarter _ and talk of
his decline are in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to say I told you so,'' Smith said. ``I already knew
what I could do. It's you doubters out there that seem to be
surprised about what's going on. I felt all along that things were
going to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   And better they have gotten. Smith leads the NFC in rushing with
529 yards and is third in the NFL. At this pace, Smith will finish
the season with 1,408 yards, his best since rushing for 1,773 in
1995. His 1,074 yards last season were his lowest output since his
rookie year.
</P>
<P>
   Along with giving credit to the improved offensive line, Smith
said coach Chan Gailey's offense has made a big difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have certain plays that lend to a bunch of options, and you
have plays that are reverse to the way we ran them in the past,''
Smith said. ``The difference is my technique is different, and my
whole thought process is different from what it was in the past.
That right there has allowed me to be a better runner.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said Smith will be better when he understands the offense
fully and starts anticipating where holes are going to be.
</P>
<P>
   Although he wants to add another NFL rushing title to his mantel
(he has four), Smith said that it's early, and that winning is more
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean a hill of beans,'' Smith said. ``If I was
there at the end of the season, it would be different. The most
important goals are team goals. If we reach the playoffs and go to
the Super Bowl, everything is going to be sweet. Once you get to
the Super Bowl, no one really cares whether you won the rushing
title.'' Smith and Davis practice Receiver Billy Davis (sprained
left foot) and Smith (strained left hip) practiced yesterday for
the first time this week, and Gailey expressed confidence that both
might be ready for the Bears game Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Both will be game-time decisions. If Davis plays, it's unlikely
that he will start. Ernie Mills will probably start in Davis' spot
because Mills had more practice time this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
