<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-UVA17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech wants to halt second-half slides
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech hits this stretch every year.
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Jackets have started 4-1 each of the past two seasons
only to fall apart in the second half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a 38-0 loss to Florida State, a 16-13 loss to North
Carolina, followed by a 35-31 loss to Virginia, nearly cost Tech a
bowl bid. In 1996, the Yellow Jackets played Virginia, Clemson and
Florida State in four weeks, lost two of those three and five of
the last six, and missed a bowl trip.
</P>
<P>
   Tech is knee-deep in it again, with _ Boom! N.C. State _ Boom!
Virginia _ Boom! Florida State. But this time it might be
different, both in attitude and result. With a win over then-No. 23
N.C. State last week, Tech has some momentum for No. 7 Virginia
today. The two teams are tied for first in the ACC with 3-0
records.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, Tech gets the two toughest games _ Virginia and FSU _ at
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we can win games we're not supposed to win,'' junior
quarterback Joe Hamilton said. ``Going into the preseason before
Boston College, I think there was a sense of confidence, but I
think it was a false confidence. We weren't as good as we thought
we were. Now, it's a real confidence that we can do things, no
matter who we're playing. My first year here and my second, I don't
think we really believed that. Now, I'm hearing around if we
practice hard we can beat anybody in the conference. We're ready
for this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach George O'Leary has talked about playing 11 one-game
seasons. Five down, one to go. It's cliche, but his players appear
to be buying into the thinking behind it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we were talking about other teams before we should
have,'' senior defensive end Jesse Tarplin said. ``If we don't beat
Virginia, the Florida State game doesn't mean anything.''
</P>
<P>
   More than the words they are using, Tech players might be
feeding off their experience of going through the last two
midseason disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   ``(After a 4-1 start) my sophomore year, we were all talking
about what bowl game we were going to,'' Tarplin said. ``Last year,
we barely made a bowl game. We lost our focus a little bit. This
year, everybody is keeping their focus. There hasn't been any talk
about what bowl we're going to go to, only the next game. As coach
O'Leary says, we've only got one shot at this team.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary said he hasn't been doing much talking about the
importance of the game; he figures his team already knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need to say much,'' he said. ``I think the heat is
turned up a little bit. What good teams do, the heat doesn't bother
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia has dealt with some second-half adversity of its own.
In the 1990s, the Cavaliers have gone 33-7 in the first five games
of the season, 29-25-1 the rest of the way. At 5-0, 3-0 in the ACC,
the Cavaliers are going for their best start since opening 6-0 in
1990. That streak ended with a loss to Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1996, we went down there 4-0 in a similar situation and
they came out with a big win (13-7),'' Virginia All-America safety
Anthony Poindexter said. ``We don't want that same thing this year.
... It's an ACC game, both of us are ranked, both of us are
undefeated in the conference, which makes the game even more
important. The stakes are high.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
