<HEADLINE>
`HURRICANE BOWL' ON UCLA'S AGENDA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UCLA could make college football history this season. The Bruins
could wind up playing in two bowls.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the school announced it has agreed to reschedule its
game at Miami for Dec. 5. The game was originally scheduled for
Sept. 26 but was postponed because of Hurricane Georges.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins coach Bob Toledo joked this week that his team would
refer to the game as the ``Hurricane Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   But for UCLA, the game will be a serious test. Also, it could
provide the final boost into the real bowl that the top teams are
aiming at _ the Fiesta Bowl, site of this season's national
championship on Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   When the UCLA-Miami game was postponed, it appeared that it
might not be rescheduled. UCLA, in particular seemed reluctant to
play a game after its traditional season-ending game with Southern
California. And with Dec. 5 the only available date, the
rescheduled game wreaks havoc with recruiting and academics.
</P>
<P>
   But for Miami, the home game in the Orange Bowl is worth about
$700,000. And the Hurricanes want to play their entire schedule so
that they can enhance their chances at winning the required number
of games to qualify for a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA is ranked second in the nation behind Ohio State. If the
season ends with those teams atop the polls and the Bowl
Championship Series rankings, they'll meet in the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA had no choice but to agree to reschedule the Miami game. If
they had declined to play despite Miami's insistence, it would
appear the Bruins were hiding behind a hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with that extra game, the Bruins are taking a calculated
risk. If they win the rest of their games _ and the Pacific-10
Conference isn't without challengers _ they could take a 10-0
record to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   A loss there could knock them out of the title picture. A
victory could be the final step for a trip to the Fiesta Bowl. Also
on Dec. 5, No. 3 Tennessee figures to be playing in the
Southeastern Conference title game. If not for the trip to Miami,
the Bruins would spend that day sitting at home and fretting over
the Volunteers leapfrogging them in the polls and rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be sitting back in December being mad at
ourselves because the game slipped away and we're in the Rose
Bowl,'' offensive tackle Kris Farris said. ``I never thought the
Rose Bowl would be second-best. But to be that close \Rto the
Fiesta Bowl\S and not obtain our goal is terrifying.''
 &LR; tagtop:Wendell Barnhouse, (817) 390-7238
Rose-colored glasses
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State is No. 1. UCLA is No. 2. If both finish the season
undefeated, they'll play in the Fiesta Bowl on Jan. 4. And if that
happens, everyone will say the Rose Bowl made a bad deal.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Well, if it wasn't for the Rose joining the Bowl
Championship Series, it would have staged its only national
championship party with the Big Ten Conference champion (Ohio
State) facing the Pacific-10 Conference champion (UCLA).
</P>
<P>
   The Rose has been the traditional destination for those two
conference champions. But the last time the game in Pasadena had
No. 1 vs. No. 2 was 1969 (Ohio State vs. Southern California). If
the Fiesta winds up with the Buckeyes vs. the Bruins, the Rose Bowl
committee members will keep a stiff upper lip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some local people will think we made a bad deal,''
said Harriman Cronk, Rose Bowl committee chairman. ``By the same
token, we've given the public what it wants, we've given the
\Rcollege\S presidents what they want and we've given the coaches
from the two conferences what they want. What else can I say?''
</P>
<P>
   As compensation for losing their traditional matchup, the Rose
gets first choice of the available teams. That could mean a Notre
Dame-Nebraska matchup. Or, if Wisconsin and Kansas State finish
unbeaten but are not Fiesta-worthy, the Rose could stage its own
ersatz championship game.
Backup backup plan
</P>
<P>
   There was a 45-minute power outage at Sun Devil Stadium during
last Saturday's Notre Dame-Arizona State game. That's the bad news.
The good news is that the blown transformer provided a wakeup call
for the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the site of the national championship game will be ready if
another blackout occurs on Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it was kind of a fluke thing,'' Fiesta Bowl spokesman
Shawn Schoeffler said. ``We also think it was a wakeup call. We
have now prepared for that for Jan. 4. We have backup plans for
backup plans.''
Curses
</P>
<P>
   Northwestern followed its 10-2 Rose Bowl season in 1995 with a
9-3 record and Citrus Bowl appearance in 1996. But last season, the
Wildcats were 5-7 and they're 2-4 going into today's game with
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   There might be a reasonable explanation for the school's slide.
That is, if you believe in curses and hexes.
</P>
<P>
   Before last season, Northwestern changed the name of its home
field from Dyche Stadium to Ryan Field. The new name honored a
big-bucks contributor whose donations had helped refurbish the
facility.
</P>
<P>
   To protest the name change, George Beres, a Northwestern
graduate and former sports information director at the school, put
a curse on the school. He stood outside the stadium last summer,
plucked the petals off a long-stemmed rose and repeated this
phrase: ``Northwestern will not return to the Rose Bowl until the
name `Dyche Stadium' is reinstated.''
Meaningful victory
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's 26-24 victory against Northwestern had special
meaning for Iowa junior quarterback Randy Reiners. He returned as
the Hawkeyes' starter and passed for 249 yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Reiners, who has overcome major knee surgery, lost the starting
job to Kyle McCann after the second game. At the time, he was
trying to recover from the death of his older sister Natalie. She
died of complications from a brain hemorrhage suffered during a
pickup softball game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear that his mind wasn't completely on football not
too long ago,'' Iowa coach Hayden Fry said.
</P>
<P>
   But his return to the starting lineup and his performance helped
ease some of Reiners' anguish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big boost,'' said Reiners' father, Gary. ``We needed
something positive to happen. For him, too.''
In quotes
</P>
<P>
   Virginia safety Anthony Poindexter on being the homecoming
opponent for today's game at Georgia Tech:
</P>
<P>
   ``You're supposed to schedule a lesser opponent than yourselves,
someone you think you can beat. That just shows a lack of respect.
We'll go down there and earn our respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State quarterback Terrance Bryant is from Miami, Fla. He
played at a San Francisco junior college before going to Oregon
State:
</P>
<P>
   ``I went from Miami where they had hurricanes to the Bay Area
where they had earthquakes. In Corvallis all you have is rain, and
you can survive that.''
</P>
<P>
   Illinois coach Ron Turner after the Illini's fourth consecutive
loss to Ohio State (the scores: 41-3, 48-0, 41-6, 41-0):
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was the owner of a pro team, I'd have about eight scouts
\Rat Ohio State\S right now.''
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska is 11th nationally in rushing, averaging 237.8 yards a
game. The last time the Huskers' season rushing average was in that
range was 1976 when the 9-3-1 team averaged just under 220 a game.
Since then, Nebraska has finished under 300 yards per game twice _
287 in 1993 and 291 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Bowl Championship Series will release its computer-enhanced
standings beginning Oct. 26 and will continue through Dec. 6. The
original plan was to release the rankings starting Nov. 15.
However, BCS officials were being deluged with questions from
commissioners and athletic administrators, so the date was moved
up.
</P>
<P>
   Since throwing six interceptions in a loss to North Carolina
State, Florida State quarterback Chris Weinke has attempted 143
consecutive passes without an interception.
</P>
<P>
   Last year under defensive coordinator Rex Ryan (now at
Oklahoma), Cincinnati allowed 233 points. This year, the Bearcats
are 0-6 and have allowed 300 points. The record for most points
allowed in a season is 553, set last season by Southwestern
Louisiana.
</P>
</TEXT>
