<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-FEATURE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yanks, Padres series promises to be a dramatic World Series
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like the two cities they represent, the Padres and
Yankees seem a continent apart.
</P>
<P>
   But a closer look at this World Series matchup shows, as one New
York daily pointed out in a headline Friday, ``Enough connections
to bridge a continent.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many mini-dramas.
</P>
<P>
   Game 1 Yankees starter David Wells grew up in San Diego. Padres
jack-of-all- trades Jim Leyritz was a Series hero for the Yankees
in 1996.Hideki Irabu refused to play for the Padres, and the
Yankees traded Ruben Rivera to San Diego for him. Greg Vaughn was a
Yankee for several hours last year before failing a physical.
Sterling Hitchcock, the league championship MVP pitched for the
Yankees for three years. Padres reliever Brian Boehringer pitched
for the Yankees, and Shane Spencer grew up outside San Diego, and
Yankees bench coach Don Zimmer managed the Padres and ...
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of good stories out there about these guys,''
Leyritz said. ``It's going to be emotional. I think this is going
to be a special thing for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Special, indeed. Unlike last October, when some fans considered
the Indians-Marlins matchup unappetizing, this series could be a
dandy. Arguably, the two best pitchers in baseball right now _
Kevin Brown and David Wells _ face each other in Game 1. Wells has
helped pile on the hype. On Thursday, his loose tongue predicted
that the Yanks would win in five games. He came back Friday and
said his quotes were taken out of context. ``I told nobody I was
predicting everything,'' he said. ``Whoever wrote it, they had fun
with it. So be it.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Series sets to open at Yankee Stadium, tickets already
are being priced as high as $2,500, and the subways are filled with
trash-talking fans of the Bronx Bomber. The Yankees, with an
AL-record 114 regular-season victories, are making their 35th
Series trip, and they will go down as one of the great teams of all
time if they win.
</P>
<P>
   For the Padres, it is only the club's second trip in its 30-year
history. San Diego lost to Detroit in five games in 1984 after
knocking off the Cubs in the NL Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been underdogs every time (this year),'' Leyritz said,
``and we are still underdogs in this series, and we look forward to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But that underdog tag means nothing now. The Padres have
defeated two clubs _ 100-game winners Houston and Atlanta _ much
handier than the Yankees have knocked off their postseason victims.
The Yankees beat the Rangers and struggled with the Indians. The
Padres also are 4-1 on the road this postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the Padres are a very good club,'' Yankees manager Joe
Torre said. ``They are playing with a lot of confidence. They
overcame a lot of things to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Padres manager Bruce Bochy said, ``Sometimes it is nice going in
as underdogs, because people don't quite expect as much of you.''
</P>
<P>
   The first game of any short series is important, but tonight
seems more important than most. For the Yankees to win the Series,
they probably need Wells to carry them. The same with Brown for the
Padres. ``Look at what they did to Atlanta,'' Wells said about San
Diego. ``Atlanta was supposed to be one of the best teams in
baseball, which I think they are, but they got beat by a team that
they didn't think was going to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, the pressure is all on the Yankees, a 3-to-1 Las Vegas
favorite. They are supposed to win: They are the team that has won
121 games this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as legitimizing our season,'' Torre said, ``I hate to
even think in negative terms, but if San Diego happens to win the
World Series, sure it takes a little bit of luster off what we have
accomplished by getting here.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre says the Series reminds him of 1996, when he was facing
Atlanta, which came in the favorite but lost to the Yankees. Now,
Torre is playing the role of the Braves and the Padres his Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that we had a chance to beat Atlanta in '96,'' he
said, ``and I am sure that is the way the Padres feel right now _
that maybe other people are predicting a lot of them, but I am sure
they are for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   As for that Wells prediction that he now says he never made?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I am going to predict anything, I'd rather predict it in
four, not five,'' he said. ``Why go five?''
</P>
<P>
   Expect it to go longer than that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
