<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TECH FINDS HIDDEN TREASURES IN RESERVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before every home game, members of the Texas Tech football team
follow the Masked Rider onto the playing surface at Jones Stadium.
Dressed in black and cloaked in anonymity, the mounted horseman
also makes celebratory sprints after Tech touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   A school tradition since 1953, the mascot serves as a perfect
symbol for a football team off to its best start in 22 years. Every
week, it seems, a different Red Raiders player steps forward after
an injury to one of the starters.
</P>
<P>
   Cloaked in anonymity, the reserve makes a game-turning play that
lifts the team to victory and causes fans to wonder, ``Who was that
masked man?'' The formula has worked well enough to carry No. 22
Tech (6-0, 3-0) to the top of the Big 12 South Division standings
heading into its 12:30 p.m. battle today against No. 19 Colorado
(5-1, 2-1) in Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, coach Spike Dykes would prefer to stop relying
so heavily on the contributions of his reserves. But he can't
imagine where the Red Raiders would be without them. A 6-0 record,
he suggested, would not have been imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, I'm surprised where we are ... based on all the
different faces we've had in there. Some of those guys have played
above their heads,'' said Dykes, who has seen 11 starters or top
reserves miss a combined 22 games because of injury. ``It's been
one of the most gallant efforts I've seen out of a lot of guys who
haven't played all that much. If they were great players, they'd be
starting. But they're not. They're overachievers, and they've
really lifted this team.''
</P>
<P>
   The most recent example came in last week's 24-17 victory
against Oklahoma State. Dorian Pitts, making his first start at
strong-side linebacker in place of injured Ty Ardoin, blocked a
punt to set up a second-quarter touchdown that gave Tech a 14-10
lead. In the fourth quarter, he returned a fumble 53 yards for the
game-winning score.
</P>
<P>
   Dykes credited Pitts with making ``the biggest plays in the
game.'' Oklahoma State coach Bob Simmons credited him with
something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``The blocked punt changed the momentum of the game,'' Simmons
said. ``We didn't have a breakdown. The Tech player just took more
pride in getting there than our guy did in stopping him.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons' praise landed on the shoulders of Pitts. But his words
could summarize the secret of Tech's success, said offensive guard
Lance Williams, a redshirt freshman from Arlington Bowie High
School.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some depth and everybody can play. We take a lot of
pride in that,'' said Williams, who made his first career start
last week in place of injured Curtis Lowery and is expected to play
against Colorado. ``It makes practices more intense. This week,
Curtis is still hurt, so the rest of us have to step it up. It's
been like that all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Significant contributions have come from unlikely sources. When
quarterback Rob Peters suffered shoulder and thumb injuries in the
season opener, fifth-year senior Matt Tittle rallied the team to a
35-3 victory against UT-El Paso and posted a 4-0 record as a
starter until Peters reclaimed the job. Heading into the season,
Tittle had completed one pass for 7 yards in his college career.
</P>
<P>
   Williams and Justin Collingsworth were among four reserve
offensive linemen who played the brunt of the Baylor game when
injuries felled all starters but left tackle Jonathan Gray. Tech
produced a season-high 538 yards in a 31-29 victory.
</P>
<P>
   With weakside linebacker Kevin McCullar sidelined the past three
weeks by an ankle injury, replacement Tim Duffie has emerged as one
of the team leaders in tackles. Duffie, a junior, has 37 tackles,
one sack, one forced fumble and one fumble recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries have not been the only conduit into the lineup for
newcomers. Freshman Kevin Curtis, the only member of Tech's 1998
signing class who is not being redshirted, has played well enough
in spot duty at free safety (15 tackles, one pass breakup) to allow
starter John Norman to take breathers before and after kick
returns. Norman ranks among the national leaders in kickoff returns
(35.8 yard average) and punt returns (12.6 average).
</P>
<P>
   Joining Norman as starters in the secondary are two former
walk-ons, Reagan Bownds and Oscar Solis. Bownds, who has 44 tackles
and two interceptions, won a starting berth with his solid play at
rover while Keith Cockrum missed three games with injuries. Solis,
a converted running back who played mostly on special teams last
season, has become a fixture at left cornerback, with three pass
breakups and two fumble recoveries.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprise, without question, has been kicker Chris
Birkholz. A walk-on from Temple, Birkholz is not mentioned in
Tech's 1998 media guide. But he is 7-of-9 on field-goal attempts
and 16-of-16 on conversions since replacing Jaret Greaser on Sept.
12 against North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   While kicking into a net on the sideline in anticipation of a
43-yard field-goal attempt, Greaser pulled a groin muscle. The
holder, Jeremy Hernandez, began screaming for Birkholz to take the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even have my shoes on,'' said Birkholz, who scrambled
to ready himself and made the 43-yarder without benefit of a
warmup.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Dykes said Birkholz ``will have to miss one'' before
Greaser gets his job back. Birkholz remains stunned by the
unexpected turn of events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd just fill in for one game, but now I don't know
what to expect,'' Birkholz said. ``So I stay ready all the time.
We've had a lot of that this season. I think it's a real positive
when you have guys play a lot in backup roles and you can still
win. You do that, you know you're doing something right.''
</P>
<P>
   It's something Tech has been doing on a weekly basis throughout
the 1998 season.
Plugging the gaps Texas Tech is 6-0, the team's best start in 22
years, thanks largely to some key contributions from unheralded
players. The group includes: Player, Pos.Comment Matt Tittle, QB
4-0 as starter while Rob Peters nursed injuries. Dorian Pitts, LB
Blocked punt, scored on fumble return vs. OSU. Reagan Bownds, DB
Former walk-on has 44 tackles, 2 INTs. Lance Williams, LG Made
first career start vs. Oklahoma State. Justin Collingsworth, RT
Spelled injured starter Steve McFadden. Chris Birkholz, K Walk-on
is 7-9 on FGs, 16-16 on PATs. Kevin Curtis, FS Incoming freshman
has 15 tackles, 1 Pass breakup. Oscar Solis, CB Former walk-on has
3 PBUs, 2 fumble recoveries. Tim Duffie, WLB Key reserve has 37
tackles, 2 turnovers, 1 sack.
Missing in action Texas Tech has had 11 starters or top reserves
miss a combined 22 games this season because of injury. The list:
Starters, Pos.Games Jaret Greaser, K4 Kevin McCullar, LB3 Keith
Cockrum, DB3 Rob Peters, QB2 Steve McFadden, RT2 Curtis Lowery, LG2
Robert Haddon, C1 Ty Ardoin, LB1 Top reserves Games Tim Baker, WR2
Terry Patton, DT1 Antwan Alexander, CB1
</P>
</TEXT>
