<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jackets can take huge step forward
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Every so often, a program reaches a defining moment _
an opportunity to take a giant step forward in the way it is
perceived on the national level.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech faces such a moment today when No. 6 Virginia comes
to Bobby Dodd Stadium. A victory over the Cavaliers would provide
the Yellow Jackets with an obvious benefit: First place in the ACC
standings, with No. 7 Florida State coming to Atlanta next week.
</P>
<P>
   The not-so-obvious benefit would come in the hype leading up to
the next game with the Seminoles, the preseason choice to win the
ACC title. Georgia Tech would get more national exposure in that
one week than in the previous few seasons combined. No decision has
been made yet, but there are strong hints that if the Yellow
Jackets beat Virginia and Florida State wins at Clemson, ESPN will
bring its College Game Day show to Georgia Tech next Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   You can't buy that kind of exposure, which is the fuel that
drives such powerhouses as Florida State, Nebraska and Ohio State
and keeps them good year after year. Great players want to be at
schools that get national exposure every week, not just once in a
while. The boost to recruiting is immeasurable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tell our guys that with each win the heat gets turned
up a little bit,'' Georgia Tech coach George O'Leary said. ``Then
the question becomes, can you handle the heat in order to get what
you want?''
</P>
<P>
   Next to No. 12 Oregon at No. 2 UCLA, Virginia-Georgia Tech is
the game of the day. Will the Jackets take advantage of it? We'll
find out today at 3:30 p.m. Until then, here are this week's picks:
</P>
<P>
   No. 7 Virginia (5-0) at No. 25 Georgia Tech (4-1), 3:30 p.m.
(Channel 2): Logically, Virginia should win this game because of
its running game (1st in the ACC) and defense (2nd in the ACC).
Tech has lost one of its better backs (Charles Wiley) and young
linebackers (Matt Uremovich). But emotion, not logic, will prevail.
Georgia Tech17, Virginia 16.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt (0-5) at No. 13 Georgia (4-1), 12:30 p.m. (WXIA):
Georgia will have a serious post-Tennessee hangover. Won't matter.
Bulldogs will still roll and start thinking about Tim Couch.
Georgia 45, Vanderbilt 7.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn (1-4) at No. 5 Florida (5-1), 3:30 p.m. (CBS): The Gators
are really banged up after last week's win over LSU. Look for Steve
Spurrier to pull in the reins against Auburn's solid defense.
Florida 24, Auburn 3.
</P>
<P>
   No. 11 Oregon (5-0) at No. 2 UCLA (4-0), 3:30 p.m.: UCLA was
impressive in beating Arizona, but the Bruins haven't seen anything
like the Ducks, who are averaging 50 points. UCLA gets the edge
playing in Pasadena. UCLA 42, Oregon 35 .
</P>
<P>
   Clemson (2-4) at No. 6 Florida State (5-1), 6 p.m. , (ESPN2):
The Seminoles have to keep winning to set up a showdown with the
Georgia Tech-Virginia winner. Clemson's offense picked up last week
but not enough overcome Florida State. Florida State 28, Clemson
14.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue (3-3) at No. 12 Penn State (4-1), 3:30 p.m.: Purdue
quarterback Drew Brees set an NCAA record last week with 83
attempts. He will have to throw a bunch again to have any chance
against a stout defense. Penn State 31, Purdue 21.
</P>
<P>
   No. 22 Texas Tech (6-0) at No. 19 Colorado (5-1), 1:30 p.m.: The
Red Raiders are 6-0 for the first time since 1976. Texas Tech RB
Ricky Williams _ not the one from Texas _ has 1,026 yards. The Red
Raiders in an upset. Texas Tech 24, Colorado 20.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky (4-2) at No. 21 LSU (3-2), 9 p.m. (ESPN2): If LSU's
Kevin Faulk can't control the ball, the Tigers could be in trouble,
because they are going to find it hard to stop Tim Couch. LSU 35,
Kentucky 31.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State (2-3) at No. 4 Kansas State (5-0), 3:30 p.m.:
Kansas State has something Nebraska didn't when it played Oklahoma
St.: A quarterback (Michael Bishop) who can pass over a stacked
defense. Kansas State 28, Oklahoma State 10.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota (3-2) at No. 1 Ohio State (5-0), Noon, ESPN: Minnesota
started 3-0, but times got tough once the Gophers entered
conference play. Ohio State 45, Minnesota 14.
</P>
<P>
   The others
</P>
<P>
   ACC: Wake Forest 24, Maryland 17; N.C. State 28, Duke 17.
</P>
<P>
   SEC: Arkansas 17, South Carolina 7; Miss. State 42, ETSU 21;
Alabama 27, E. Carolina 14.
</P>
<P>
   Top 25: No. 8 Nebraska 42, Kansas 14; No. 9 Wisconsin 35,
Illinois 10; No. 10 Texas A&AMP;M 21, Baylor 10; No. 14 Virginia Tech
31, Temple 0; No. 16 Arizona 21, Oregon State 17.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's record: 13-7.
</P>
<P>
   Season's record: 83-34 (70.9 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
