<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's midterm exam time for Tech
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech flunked its first quiz of the season
Sept. 5 when it was embarrassed by Boston College 41-31.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, professor George O'Leary has put his Yellow Jackets
through a serious tutorial, with notable improvement. Tech has four
victories in a row, including two impressive performances on the
road at North Carolina and N.C. State. At 4-1 (3-0 ACC), the
Jackets have managed to crack the Top 25.
</P>
<P>
   All that is well and good, the professor said. But today his
class faces its midterm exam when No. 7 Virginia (5-0, 3-0) visits
Bobby Dodd Stadium (3:30 p.m., Channel 2)
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made some strides and gotten better, there's no question
about that,'' O'Leary said. ``Against Virginia, we'll see how
much.''
</P>
<P>
   At stake is first place in the ACC standings, with No. 6 Florida
State looming on the horizon. The Seminoles come to Atlanta next
week. Virginia goes to Tallahassee on Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the George Welsh's Cavaliers have the numbers in their
favor. Virginia has the ACC's best running attack and the league's
second-best defense to Florida State. Virginia has had a week off
to get ready, something that usually favors Welsh and his
experienced staff.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, it has not been a good week on the Flats. On Monday,
Tech lost versatile running back Charles Wiley to a knee injury. On
Wednesday, the school suspended talented young linebacker Matt
Uremovich, who was caught taking an NCAA-banned,
performance-enhancing substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things I think we will overcome,'' O'Leary said. ``I've
seen this team react positively to setbacks before. I think we will
again.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary is more worried about a Virginia running game capable of
eating up the clock and keeping quarterback Joe Hamilton and the
Tech offense on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slowing down the run is the key to the game _ for both
teams,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In other games Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   _ Georgia will try to shake off the effects of last week's
disappointing loss to Tennessee when it plays Vanderbilt (0-5) for
Homecoming.
</P>
<P>
   _ First place in the Southern Conference and the No. 1 spot in
the Division I-AA rankings will be on the line when No. 3
Appalachian State (5-0) travels to No. 2 Georgia Southern (6-0).
Previous No. 1 McNeese State lost Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 2 UCLA (4-0) faces a major test at home today against No.
11 Oregon (5-0).
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 5 Florida (5-1) tries to keep its SEC and national
championship hopes alive when it hosts struggling Auburn (1-4).
</P>
<P>
   TODAY'S GAMES
</P>
<P>
   VIRGINIA
</P>
<P>
   VS. GEORGIA TECH
</P>
<P>
   _ When: 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Bobby Dodd Stadium/Grant Field, Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV, radio: WSB, WGST (640 AM, 105.7 FM).
</P>
<P>
   VANDERBILT
</P>
<P>
   VS. GEORGIA
</P>
<P>
   _ When: 12:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Sanford Stadium, Athens.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV, radio: WXIA, WSB (750 AM), WNGC (95.5 FM).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
