<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smith's request to forego fine denied
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Falcons and starting right defensive end
Chuck Smith got some disappointing news Friday, learning the NFL
denied his appeal of a $7,500 fine against Smith for a low hit on
former Carolina QB Kerry Collins in the season opener Sept. 6. All
parties had been under the incorrect impression the matter was
dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a letter from NFL director of game operations Peter
Hadhazy said that because of Smith's track record for this kind of
thing, the next offense of this nature could lead to a suspension.
Smith was fined $25,000 for a more severe hit on Collins in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, his agent, Jimmy Sexton, and Falcons officials had been
led to believe the matter was going to be dropped after
conversations with league finemeister Gene Washington and other
officials in the NFL office.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has a rule that says if a player has an unobstructed
path to a QB, he cannot hit him at or below the knees. Smith and
the Falcons contended that Smith was tripped by Carolina tackle
Blake Brockermeyer, and upon hitting the ground, reached for
Collins who was running toward him.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out those conversations were informal, however. Reeves,
who was not involved in an official capacity in the appeal process,
said he plans to call NFL commissioner Paul Talgiabue, seeking
relief in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket talk
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons (4-1) have distributed about 56,000 tickets for
Sunday's game in the Georgia Dome against the Saints (3-2), and
with strong sales today at ticket outlets and a good walk-up sale
before the game, sales could surpass 60,000 for the first time in
two years.
</P>
<P>
   Roster news
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' four early inactive players are LB Henri Crockett
(dislocated wrist), OL Dave Widell, RB Harold Green, and S Omar
Brown. ... Reserve CB Randy Fuller's strained hamstring is still a
problem, and a game-day decision will be made on his availability.
Meanwhile, CB Darren Anderson, who was signed more two weeks ago
when the team waived CB Juran Bolden, has progressed to a point
where he grasps much of the Falcons' nickel and dime defenses.
Also, reserve CB Michael Booker, who missed the last two games with
a strained thigh muscle, will play.
</P>
<P>
   Colossal Cam
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are wary of big Saints TE Cam Cleeland, who at 6-4,
272 pounds is critical in the running game. The second-round pick
from Washington also is the Saints' leading receiver, with 18
catches for 241 yards (13.4-yard average), and two TDs.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Falcons safety Devin Bush's appeal of the $5,000 fine he got for
a late hit in the 51-23 win over Carolina Oct. 4 could be heard as
early as next week. Bush probably doesn't have much of a chance,
since he was penalized and ejected. ... New Orleans WR Andre
Hastings, a graduate of Morrow High and the University of Georgia,
this week declined multiple interview requests with Georgia media.
... The Falcons elected backup DE John Burrough as alternate
representative to the NFL Players Association. DE Lester Archambeau
is the primary rep. ... Dan Stryzinski has had 10 punts originate
from the opponents' 44-yard line and in. He's averaging 32.7 yards
on those kicks, with an average hang time of 4.58 seconds. On his
20 kicks from the 45 and back, he's averaging 40.2 yards with an
average hang time of 4.4 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Red hot in red zone
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons continue to perform well in the red zone. Defining
red-zone possessions as any that include at least one first down
inside the 20, Atlanta has scored 100 percent of the time, with
seven TDs and six field goals. That's tied with six other teams.
Since joining the Falcons last season, QB Chris Chandler has thrown
15 TDs in the red zone, and no interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
