<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-TUGGLE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Saints series `like high school rivalry'
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No current Atlanta Falcons player or coach has been
through more Saints-Falcons games than middle linebacker Jessie
Tuggle, who has seen this rivalry up close and personal 22 times _
with 10 wins _ since joining the team as an undrafted free agent in
1987.
</P>
<P>
   It started ugly, as the Saints won the first five times, seven
of the first eight, and 10 of the first 13. But Atlanta has won six
in a row, sweeping the seasons series three years consecutively.
</P>
<P>
   Tuggle, a four-time Pro Bowl player from Griffin High School,
has had some great games against the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   He had a season-high 20 tackles in a 27-24 overtime win at New
Orleans in 1995, icing the victory with an end-zone interception
with 1:11 left. In 1993, he recorded his 1,000th career tackle
against the Saints. In 1992, he scored on a 69-yard fumble recovery
in a 10-7 loss at New Orleans. And in 1991, he had a 22-tackle game
against the Saints, second-best in his career.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal-Constitution spoke with Tuggle about the
Saints-Falcons rivalry, which is the top one for each team.
Thirteen of the games have been decided by a TD or less.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What moment among all others in these games will you never
forget?
</P>
<P>
   A: I guess the best memory would be when we beat them (27-20) in
the playoffs (in 1991). That place was sold out, and it was so loud
you couldn't hear yourself talk.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How about the crummiest?
</P>
<P>
   A: Any time you lose down there, you get in the middle of all
that ``Who dat'' stuff (from fans). The worst feeling is if I've
just played as hard as I can, and walking off the field those fans
are still bugging me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What makes this a great rivalry?
</P>
<P>
   A: We're pretty close, and I remember when we would always take
10,000 fans when we went down there, and they would bring 20,000
when they came here. It seems like it didn't matter what the
records were ... it always seemed to go down to the wire.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Falcons kicker Morten Andersen has 25 game-winning kicks in
his career, and in his 13 years with the Saints, six came against
Atlanta. Any stick especially hard in your craw?
</P>
<P>
   A: Aw, man, it seems like there were a million. All I know is I
remember when Morten became a free agent (after the 1994 season),
we picked him up, and I was like, ``They got to be kidding, letting
him go.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is this game any better than the old days, when the Griffin
Bears took on the Newnan Cougars?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's like a high school rivalry. It brings back those Friday
night memories of when you would play in high school and everybody
would get real emotional. In the NFL, you don't get that too much.
That's the feeling I get when I play the New Orleans Saints. You
get butterflies, you want to play well, and you want to win.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
