<SLUG> BC-RAC-DAYTONA-NOTES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Michael Waltrip, Mattei team up
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _
</P>
<P>
   WINSTON CUP
</P>
<P>
   Michael Waltrip has driven for Dick Bahre, Chuck Rider and the
Woods brothers, all without a single visit to a Winston Cup victory
lane in 391 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, he'll try again, with Jim Mattei Motorsports, which
has released Geoff Bodine following this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael has a lot of experience and a great passion for this
sport,'' Mattei said. ``I consider him to be at the beginning of
his career. I believe the kind of equipment we'll have with our
race team, he'll be stepping up to a new level in Winston Cup
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip has agreed to a two-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Mattei obviously is very committed to being successful,''
he said, ``and that type of commitment is what I need.''
</P>
<P>
   GREEN'S SHOT: David Green has been offered the No. 41 Larry
Hedrick Motorsports ride for 1999, but Green has yet to make a
decision. He stepped into the car at Martinsville but didn't
qualify; made the field at Charlotte, but was caught up in the big
wreck and finished last; and didn't qualify last week at Talladega.
``My plans are still up in the air,'' said Green, who was released
earlier this year by Buz McCall's team and returned to the Busch
series.
</P>
<P>
   BRIEFLY: For the first time in Mike Skinner's career, he led the
most laps, 74 in Sunday's Winston 500. Skinner also was the halfway
leader to earn the $10,000 bonus. ... Going into the Pepsi 400,
Bobby Labonte has the best average finish on restrictor-plate
tracks in 1998. His average is 3.0, compared with such notables as
Terry Labonte, 6.67; Jeff Gordon, 7.67; Dale Jarrett, 12.6; Rusty
Wallace, 14.65; Dale Earnhardt, 23.00; and Mark Martin, 33.67.
</P>
<P>
   BUSCH
</P>
<P>
   Testing at AMS
</P>
<P>
   Buckshot Jones put in a little track time recently at Atlanta
Motor Speedway to test his Busch car in preparation for this week's
Gateway 250. He is ninth in points but only seven points from
sixth. ``Atlanta is a smooth track, with more grip than Charlotte
or Texas,'' Jones said. ``I don't have a lot of experience here,
but I'm comfortable with the speed, and I really like the way the
car feels on the track.''
</P>
<P>
   KENSETH'S REVENGE: A year ago, the Gateway Raceway got the best
of Matt Kenseth. ``When we got out of the one lane you could run
on, all the loose asphalt knocked all the engine belts off and
ended our day early.''
</P>
<P>
   BRIEFLY: Dale Earnhardt Jr. carries a 97-point lead over Kenseth
to Gateway. Statistically, Earnhardt is dominating most categories:
Six victories, 1,390 laps led, 15 races led, 1,325.35 miles and
three poles.
</P>
<P>
   CRAFTSMAN TRUCKS
</P>
<P>
   Trucking is tough
</P>
<P>
   Boris Said won his first Craftsman Truck race last week at Sears
Point, winning by 6.549 seconds, the largest margin of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Said led 47 of the 77 laps in the race and proclaimed afterward,
``It wasn't easy winning one of these races.''
</P>
<P>
   That from a racer who has won Le Mans and the 24 Hours of
Daytona.BRIEFLY: Said's victory in the Kragen/Exide 150 made him
the season's sixth first-time winner, one fewer than last year's
record number. His average speed of 72.939 mph was a course record,
eclipsing Joe Ruttman's 70.199 mph. ... With three races remaining,
Jack Sprague's 18-point lead over Ron Hornaday is the smallest in
the tour's history.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
