<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DAYTONA-ADVANCE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jarrett anxious to step up to `plate'
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Dale Jarrett goes for a restrictor-plate
double tonight, hoping to back up last week's Winston 500 victory
with another of its kind, the Pepsi 400 at Daytona International
Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   While most teams would rather do a double-header at Charlotte
than one restrictor plate outing, Jarrett says bring 'em on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm really looking forward to it,'' said Jarrett, who
has won three restrictor-plate races, two Daytona 500s and last
week's Winston 500. ``This is the car with a good chassis that we
had, and put a new body on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd Parrott (crew chief) spent countless hours in the wind
tunnel, and we kind of went back to a different setup at these type
tracks and the car drove just great. That's what I'm gonna need
Saturday night, so I'm looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett isn't alone. Jeff Gordon is no stranger to
restrictor-plate races. He's won three, two at Daytona. He has a
288-point lead over Mark Martin and can win the championship by
finishing 16th or better in the last four races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're in real good shape for Daytona,'' said Gordon,
who starts sixth. ``We've been very fortunate to contend for the
championship the past few years, and I think every year we contend,
we get a little more experience and I think we get smarter and more
confident about what it's going to take.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we were really awesome all year long until the end
of the season, and then we struggled. This year, we came in and
said we're not going to let that happen, and we've done a pretty
good job of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, there's Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wish we didn't have another restrictor-plate race
this week,'' Martin said prior to Thursday's qualifying, where he
was sixth fastest. ``We ran real good, especially with an untested
car. We're pleased with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We qualified good at Talladega, then didn't race very well.
So, we hope we'll race as well as we qualified.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, there are the lights, which got good reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like the track surface was consistent throughout
qualifying,'' said pole winner Bobby Labonte. ``The corners are lit
up real well. It's bright enough where it's not like you have
headlights on and you're going down the road at night. There is a
uniqueness to the track as compared to the sun. I really didn't see
a whole lot of difference.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
