<HEADER>
A2165 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BB0-SERIES-NOTES17-CO     10-16 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB0-SERIES-NOTES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Padres pitching lineup set
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Beyond tonight's matchup between David Wells and
Kevin Brown, the Yankees and Padres put the rest of their pitching
plans in place Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will follow Wells with rookie Orlando Hernandez and
then David Cone and Andy Pettitte. The Padres will go with Andy
Ashby in Game 2 followed by Sterling Hitchcock. In Game 4, the
Padres might turn to righthander Joey Hamilton, but only if they
are not trailing in the series. Otherwise, they will go with Brown
on three days of rest.
</P>
<P>
   The use of Hernandez in Game 2 is a change of thinking for the
Yankees, who against Cleveland pitched Cone after Wells. But it was
``El Duque'' who proved to be the turning point in that series,
winning Game 4 when the Yankees were down 2-1 and earning the
chance for two starts in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   In last year's Series, it was Hernandez's brother Livan who beat
the Braves in Game 5 of the league championship and then won two
games in the Series en route to a Florida world championship.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry leaves hospital
</P>
<P>
   Yankees outfielder Darryl Strawberry, who underwent colon cancer
surgery two weeks ago, left the hospital Friday. ``It's been a
difficult time but now that time is over,'' Strawberry said. ``As
you can see, I've lost a lot of weight. But from my nurses to my
doctors, they told me everything will come back.'' Strawberry
returned to his home in New Jersey and will watch tonight's game on
television.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa pinch-hits for DiMaggio
</P>
<P>
   Yankees great Joe DiMaggio, 83, is being treated for pneumonia
in Hollywood, Fla., and will not attend this weekend's games.
DiMaggio was scheduled to throw out the ceremonial first pitch
tonight. Instead, Sammy Sosa will do the honors. ``He's had
pneumonia three months,'' longtime friend Morris Engelberg said.
``He walked around with it for a couple of months. He couldn't
knock it out. He should be out this coming Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Ticket costs soaring
</P>
<P>
   Scalpers are asking a boatload of money for tickets to games
tonight and Sunday. One ticket agency was asking $2,500 for field
box seats that were $150 at the box office, $550 ($100) for
upper-level box seats and $315 ($40) for bleacher seats. Those
prices will likely go up at least another 25 percent before the
first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   No stadium vote
</P>
<P>
   A referendum on whether a $1 billion stadium should be built for
the Yankess in Manhattan was pulled off the ballot for next month's
election by an appeals court. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is pushing for
the new stadium but would like to do it without putting the issue
to a vote. Others say the general public is opposed to moving the
team from the Bronx to Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Around the horn
</P>
<P>
   Yankees center fielder Bernie Williams is one player who likes
to keep to himself. ``Once you're here in New York, you have your
life kind of dug into a little bit,'' Williams said. ``I've always
taken a lot of pride in keeping my private life private. I don't
see why it shouldn't stay that way.'' ... Pettitte missed Friday's
workout and might not be in uniform for Games 1 and 2. Pettitte,
scheduled to start Game 4, remains with his father, who had heart
bypass surgery. ... San Diego's Jim Leyritz, who played on New
York's1996 World Championship team, is getting a hard time about
his shaved head from his former teammates. ``My wife almost fell
off the table when she saw that,'' right fielder Paul O'Neill said.
``That, we need to talk about.'' ... Brown has a career 12-2 mark
against the Yankees. The next best active mark against New York is
Wells, who was 13-5 against the Yankees when he was with other
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
