<HEADER>
A2167 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SERIES-MATCHUPS17     10-16 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-MATCHUPS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    World Series matchup
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   ROTATION
</P>
<P>
   At the top, both teams have wonderful starting pitching. David
Wells and rookie Orlando Hernandez carried the Yankees last round,
while Kevin Brown, Andy Ashby and Sterling Hitchcock did the same
for San Diego. New York's problems are that David Cone has
struggled and Andy Pettitte got crushed in his one start against
the Indians. Unless they are down 3-0 in the series, the Padres
probably will go with Joey Hamilton, whose inconsistency can drive
a manager crazy. The key here might be Hitchcock. He was fabulous
against the Braves, but the question is whether he can do it
against his former club. Advantage: Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   BULLPEN
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's Trevor Hoffman and Mariano Rivera of the Yankees are
the best closers in the game. But the Padres might have a problem
behind Hoffman, as shown against the Braves. However, San Diego
might have found an answer in Wednesday's clinching game, with long
men Mark Langston and Brian Boehringer in setup roles. The Yankees'
bullpen is strong from top to bottom. Jeff Nelson dominates
right-handed hitting, and left-hander Mike Stanton always has been
a dominant pitcher in the postseason. Advantage: Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   CATCHER
</P>
<P>
   No stars here, just workhorses, as the Yankees use both Joe
Girardi and Jorge Posada, and the Padres go with Carlos Hernandez
and Jim Leyritz. Of the four, Leyritz can be the most damaging at
the plate. None is great defensively, and the Yankees, which led
the majors in stolen bases, are certain to go to their running
game. Advantage: Padres.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST BASE
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, one would think the Yankees have a big edge,
with Tino Martinez over Wally Joyner. Not true. Martinez has hit
just .167 in the postseason. Joyner isn't going to carry any team
on his shoulders, but he's consistent and solid defensively. Still,
Martinez can dominate if he gets hot. Advantage: Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   SECOND BASE
</P>
<P>
   Both players lead off for their teams. The Indians series was a
strange one for Chuck Knoblauch, who already has a love-hate
relationship with the New York fans. Knoblauch is hitting only .167
but does appear to have overcome his Game 2 snafu against the
Indians. Quilvio Veras is not much of an offensive threat, but he
rarely strikes out or makes mistakes in the field. Advantage:
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   SHORTSTOP
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter for the Yankees; Chris Gomez for the Padres. OK,
it's a mismatch on paper, although both were under .200 at the
plate in the last round. Jeter has turned into one of the best
all-around players in the game and is a super No. 2 hitter. Gomez
can be shaky with his glove. Advantage: Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   THIRD BASE
</P>
<P>
   Pick a Yankee MVP from the start of the season, and it just
might be Scott Brosius. Pick a postseason MVP position player MVP
for the Padres, and it's probably Ken Caminiti, who got the two
biggest hits in the series against the Braves, an extra-inning
homer in Game 1 and the single to start the rally to win Game 6.
Brosius makes it awfully tough for opposing pitchers to overlook
the bottom part of the Yankees lineup, while Caminiti will be
helped by the fact that Greg Vaughn should be in the lineup for the
entire series. Advantage: Padres.
</P>
<P>
   LEFT FIELD
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn appears recovered from his quadriceps injury and will be
back for San Diego. Vaughn's presence in the No. 3 spot in the
order should make a San Diego lineup much more dangerous than it
was against the Braves. For the Yankees, this spot was a problem
against the Indians, with four different players _ Shane Spencer,
Chad Curtis, Tim Raines and Ricky Ledee _ starting games. Look for
Curtis to play the most because he is the best defensive player.
Advantage: Padres.
</P>
<P>
   CENTER FIELD
</P>
<P>
   New York's Bernie Williams is a fabulous player although he
hasn't looked it much this month. Still, his World Series in 1996
was one to remember, and very little drops in against him in the
field. The Padres' Steve Finley struggled in the regular season but
was effective against the Braves. Vaughn's return will enable
Finley to bat lower in the lineup. Advantage: Yankees
</P>
<P>
   RIGHT FIELD
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's Tony Gwynn might still be the best pure hitter in
baseball, but he hasn't showed it in the postseason, hitting just
.220. Gwynn also seems to be bothered still by a foot injury. New
York's Paul O'Neill played a major role against the Indians and is
hitting .306 in the postseason. He is one of the toughest outs in
the game, and his intensity keeps the rest of the team on its feet.
Advantage: Yankees
</P>
<P>
   DESIGNATED HITTER
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will go with Chili Davis, while the Padres platoon
the right-handed hitting Leyrtiz and left-handed hitting John
Vander Wal. Leyritz is being called the new Mr. October and would
love nothing more than to beat his old team. Davis, meanwhile,
showed against the Indians that he still has some pop in his bat.
Here, the platoon works better. Advantage: Padres.
</P>
<P>
   BENCH
</P>
<P>
   In the four possible games in New York, it won't be used much,
but on NL turf, no one is a better pinch-hitter than Vander Wal.
Also, the Padres have former Yankee prospect Ruben Rivera, who
filled in admirably for Vaughn against Atlanta. The Yankees also
have a lot to choose from, including deep-threat Spencer.
Advantage: Padres
</P>
<P>
   MANAGER
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's Bruce Bochy did a masterful job against the Braves.
Almost every move was a good one, and even using Brown in Game 5
worked out because Bochy now has him available to pitch three times
in this series. On the other bench is Joe Torre, who has been here
before. Torre has improved over the years at working his bench and
bullpen. Advantage: Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   OVERALL
</P>
<P>
   On paper, New York should win. At their best, no one can stop
the Yankees. But the poor-pitching Indians proved that New York can
be beaten, and the Padres will throw a lot better arms against them
than Cleveland did. Also, when many people thought the Padres were
through after a Game 5 loss to the Braves, they came right out and
did the job. This series might come down to who is better between
Wells and Brown. A hunch here says the Padres are a team of
destiny. San Diego in seven.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-16-98 2107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
