A2189 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT     10-16 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CUT IN U.S. INTEREST RATES HELPS MARKETS RALLY ABROAD
</P>
<P>
   Stock markets in Asia and Europe surged in response to
Thursday's interest rate reduction by the Federal Reserve. Hong
Kong's Hang Seng index jumped 9 percent, to 9,777.01, its highest
level since early May. Shares in Singapore, Bangkok, Jakarta and
Manila all rose more than 5 percent. The Nikkei index of 225 issues
in Tokyo gained 2.19 percent. The German DAX index climbed 1.76
percent, and the main market gauge in London increased 1.38
percent.
</P>
<P>
   REASONS FOR AN INTEREST RATE CUT
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan and the other members of the Federal Reserve were
criticized for not cutting interest rates aggressively to offset
the 1989-1990 credit crunch. Analysts say the chairman of the
central bank does not want to be caught in that situation again,
which is one reason why he pushed to lower interest rates Thursday.
More interest rate reductions are now expected later this year and
possibly into next.
</P>
<P>
   MILD GAIN IN SOCIAL SECURITY BENEFITS
</P>
<P>
   The government said Social Security benefits will rise 1.3
percent next year, the smallest cost-of-living increase since 1987,
because of exceptionally low inflation. More than 44 million
Americans, most of them elderly, receive Social Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET AGREEMENT STILL NEEDS WORK
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans sounded notes of discord over the $1.7 trillion
Federal budget deal, but they also said they would probably vote
for the package because it increased defense spending and provided
aid to farmers. However, no one can vote on the package just yet
because there are still disputes to iron out.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked into the $1.7 trillion federal budget agreement is a
measure that would restrict children's access to pornography on the
Internet. The measure says Internet merchants and others will be in
violation only if they give children access to material that is
``harmful to minors.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION DECLINED LAST MONTH
</P>
<P>
   Output at the nation's factories, mines and utilities fell
three-tenths of 1 percent in September and consumer prices were
unchanged last month for the first time in six months, further
signs that the economy is slowing. A third economic indicator, the
University of Michigan's index of consumer confidence, fell to 98.9
this month, from 100.9 in September.
</P>
<P>
   SHAKE-UP CONTINUES AT MERRILL LYNCH
</P>
<P>
   A shake-up in the executive suite continued at Merrill Lynch.
The leading brokerage firm, led by David H. Komansky, left, named
G. Kelly Martin, 39, as chief of the debt business, replacing Seth
Waugh, who will become Martin's deputy. Waugh had been co-head of
the global debt unit since 1997. The change is the second in two
days. On Thursday, Merrill named Richard A. Dunn to replace Daniel
Napoli as head of its risk management team. Both Mr. Waugh and
Napoli were demoted, but the firm said it was not assigning blame
to them and that both will stay on the job.
</P>
<P>
   HOECHST CALLS OFF SALE OF HERBERTS
</P>
<P>
   The German chemical maker Hoechst has ended talks to sell its
Herberts paint unit to Kohlberg Kravis Roberts. The buyout firm was
offering a price below what Hoechst was willing to accept.
</P>
<P>
   NISSAN MOTOR EXPECTS A NET LOSS
</P>
<P>
   Nissan Motor, Japan's second-largest automaker, said that it
expected to post a net loss of 33 billion yen ($284 million) for
the first half of the current business year because of huge losses
on its securities holdings.
</P>
<P>
   PROFITS DECLINED AT CATERPILLAR
</P>
<P>
   Caterpillar, the manufacturer of construction and earth-moving
equipment, reported that third-quarter profits fell 12.7 percent,
to $336 million, or 92 cents a diluted share. Sales jumped 12.5
percent, to $5.17 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
