<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ONLY ISSUE IN THE CASINOS ELECTION IS FAIRNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kansas City's business community is right to
support the Nov. 3 constitutional initiative that would allow
business to continue as usual for Missouri casinos in man-made
lagoons adjacent to rivers.
</P>
<P>
   The Greater Kansas City Chamber of Commerce is careful not to
champion gambling while coming out for approval of Amendment 9,
which would legalize ``boats in moats.'' The chamber characterizes
its endorsement of the issue as recognition of the unfairness of
changing the rules after casino companies made their investments.
</P>
<P>
   Those who sought loopholes in the law in their effort to destroy
the state's gaming industry have forced the vote by successfully
challenging the legality of building some riverboat casinos outside
the river channel. The casinos so situated were placed away from
the river for reasons involving convenience and safety, but doing
so made them vulnerable to those who would manipulate the law's
language to their advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The need for voter revision of the law turns mostly on the slot
machine trade, which is the life's blood of any casino's
profitability. If the constitutional authorization for casinos
isn't revised to fully cover boats in moats, these operations would
lose their franchise to feature games of chance, of which slots are
the most lucrative.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the casinos present themselves as virtuous, but the
virtue of their position is difficult to discern. Hundreds of
millions of dollars were invested in Missouri in response to what
everyone involved perceived to be a legalization of all forms of
gambling. Clever use of a legal loophole has put the viability of
that investment in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that gambling is objectionable to some doesn't make it
virtuous to attempt to render investment in casinos nearly
worthless. People are certainly free to make their moral judgments
concerning gambling, and to forgo gambling if they consider it
immoral.
</P>
<P>
   However, translating moral qualms about gambling into efforts to
deprive others of the constructive use of their private resources
is an act of questionable morality. Beyond this, it jeopardizes the
bedrock principle on which free-market capitalism rests, which is
the sanctity of private property.
</P>
<P>
   When the United States emerged as a geopolitical entity, it was
unique in the degree of legal protection it provided for private
property. As such, it was one of the few places in the world where
the law protected citizens from the deprivation of the fruits of
their labor by government or monarchal fiat or whim.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over riverboat casinos focuses for the most part on
competing economic claims. The benefits are there for all to see in
the form of jobs, tax revenues, civic contributions and economic
vitality in communities where casinos exist. The alleged
liabilities, though, are mere contentions, not substantially proven
and certainly not obvious. Experts of questionable credentials are
recruited to make the economic case against gambling, but their
claims are largely unconvincing.
</P>
<P>
   Such claims, however, whether pro and con, are beside the point.
</P>
<P>
   The only valid point is the fairness of what's being attempted.
It isn't fair, nor is it virtuous, to attempt the economic
destruction of a legally constituted industry doing business in
good faith.
</P>
<P>
   While it's not fashionable to defend gambling, standing up for
fairness should never go out of style.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
