<HEADLINE>
FLOOD VICTIM'S FAMILY BLASTS KANSAS CITY'S RESPONSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The family of a Kansas City man swept to his
death as he waited for rescue on a Brush Creek bridge blasted the
city Thursday for its response to the Oct. 4 flash flood.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Louise Hudson also said she would not support a
half-cent sales tax proposed by Mayor Emanuel Cleaver because tens
of millions of dollars already spent on flood improvements weren't
enough to save the life of her son, Orlando Hudson, 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they should give them half of anything,'' she
said from her East Side home. ``What would they do with it this
time?''
</P>
<P>
   She and another son, Marvin Hudson, said they were incensed that
the city's flash flood warning system had been unplugged at the
Fire Department and that the city had no contingency plans for such
a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they knew this amount of rain was coming, backup plans
should have been put in place, like blocking off the Brush Creek
area and evacuations,'' Marvin Hudson said. ``It's hard to see a
big city like Kansas City acting like a bumbling country town.
People died, they lost their lives, because of this.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials confirmed Thursday that only four of 17 rainfall
and water level sensors scattered throughout the Brush Creek
watershed were operating the night of the flood.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver said that the Hudsons' anger is understandable but
misplaced, and defended the city's response to the flooding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most disturbing part of this is the painful question
bereaved families will ask: `Would my loved one have been saved?'
'' Cleaver said. ``I agree (with other city officials that) we
probably wouldn't have saved any lives, but I don't agree that we
are out of the way of some public anger.''
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials this week acknowledged that the city has never
prepared contingency response plans for flash flooding on Brush
Creek, even though the 1977 flood killed 25 persons.
</P>
<P>
   /{The Kansas City Star/} reported this week that a high-tech
$275,000 system that was supposed to warn city officials of flash
flooding on Brush Creek had been unplugged from an electrical
outlet at the fire communications center.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Kansas City Fire Department's receiving equipment
was unplugged and not receiving data since Aug. 16, the data were
recorded by the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters said that the sensors detected nearly three times
the amount of rainfall necessary to trigger flash flooding at least
30 minutes before seven persons, including Orlando Hudson, died
near the Prospect Avenue bridge.
</P>
<P>
   City maintenance workers spent Thursday assessing the condition
of the creek's monitoring system, said Terry Leeds, a storm water
manager with the Water Services Department.
</P>
<P>
   Leeds said that none of the six water-level gauges worked. The
operating portion of the system consisted of four rain gauges, two
each in Johnson and Jackson counties. He had no explanation for why
the gauges were inoperable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (gauges) that give you the best advance warning are the
precipitation gauges,'' Leeds said.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Hudson said the community should focus its anger with
the city's response on Prospect Avenue and its low bridge over
Brush Creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should protest and get together and walk that bridge,''
Dorothy Hudson said. ``They should have fixed that bridge years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver said that such improvements, and the ability to react
quickly to the next flood emergency, will be possible only if the
city raises the money to meet the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver said he will meet with Gov. Mel Carnahan today to
discuss the possibility of a special legislative session early next
month to authorize a special flood relief tax election. The city
hopes to hold the election on Dec. 8.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by voters, a one-half cent sales tax would be
imposed for 18 months and raise about $45 million for flood control
and storm sewer improvement projects throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver pointed to a proposed $250,000 expenditure in his sales
tax proposal for additional rescue equipment and training.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to ask themselves, what if the (flood warning
system) alarm had gone off?'' Cleaver said. ``We had no swift water
rescue equipment. Even if we could have responded, what would we
have responded with?''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver acknowledged the city could have done a better job of
Brush Creek planning. He said the city had been lulled into a false
sense of security by the lack of serious damage along the waterway
during the floods of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you looked down Brush Creek (in 1993) I believed that
finally, we had solved this problem, and no one began planning for
this catastrophe,'' he said. ``We were not prepared, and this city
cannot afford to have its citizens in harm's way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
