<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 10/16/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Oct. 16, 1998 -- BBO-STRAWBERRY-HOSPITAL,
10-16 -- Darryl Strawberry and his wife, Charisse, at a press
conference Friday following his release from Columbia-Presbyterian
Medical Center. Strawberry, who underwent surgery to remove a
cancerous tumor from his colon on Oct. 3, says he will remain in
New Jersey for 10 or 12 more days before returning home to Rancho
Mirage, Calif. ``Wow, I never thought this day would come,'' he
says. ``But it has.'' (George M. Gutierrez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WALTHAM, Mass. -- Oct. 16, 1998 --
BRANDEIS-UNIVERSITY-2, 10-16 -- The diversity of Jewish life at
Brandeis could be seen last week at a lunch observing Succoth, the
harvest holiday that recalls the Jews' wandering. ``Jews are no
longer trying to get into the American academic establishment,''
says Rabbi Arthur Hertzberg, a historian of American Jewry. ``They
are the academic establishment. The problem Brandeis had come to
solve has been solved.'' (Evan Richman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WALTHAM, Mass. -- Oct. 16, 1998 --
BRANDEIS-UNIVERSITY-1, 10-16 -- Among the national figures Brandeis
has attracted to the campus are Robert Reich, the former Secretary
of Labor, shown last week teaching a graduate course called Social
Issues and Problems: Inequality and Work. ``What I have done is
really clearly define and articulate what we are all about,'' says
Jehuda Reinharz, president of Brandeis, who has embraced celebrity
in his attempt to revamp the school's identity. (Evan Richman/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
