<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 10/16/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Oct. 16, 1998 -- BBO-STRAWBERRY-HOSPITAL,
10-16 -- Darryl Strawberry and his wife, Charisse, at a press
conference Friday following his release from Columbia-Presbyterian
Medical Center. Strawberry, who underwent surgery to remove a
cancerous tumor from his colon on Oct. 3, says he will remain in
New Jersey for 10 or 12 more days before returning home to Rancho
Mirage, Calif. ``Wow, I never thought this day would come,'' he
says. ``But it has.'' (George M. Gutierrez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WALTHAM, Mass. -- Oct. 16, 1998 --
BRANDEIS-UNIVERSITY-2, 10-16 -- The diversity of Jewish life at
Brandeis could be seen last week at a lunch observing Succoth, the
harvest holiday that recalls the Jews' wandering. ``Jews are no
longer trying to get into the American academic establishment,''
says Rabbi Arthur Hertzberg, a historian of American Jewry. ``They
are the academic establishment. The problem Brandeis had come to
solve has been solved.'' (Evan Richman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WALTHAM, Mass. -- Oct. 16, 1998 --
BRANDEIS-UNIVERSITY-1, 10-16 -- Among the national figures Brandeis
has attracted to the campus are Robert Reich, the former Secretary
of Labor, shown last week teaching a graduate course called Social
Issues and Problems: Inequality and Work. ``What I have done is
really clearly define and articulate what we are all about,'' says
Jehuda Reinharz, president of Brandeis, who has embraced celebrity
in his attempt to revamp the school's identity. (Evan Richman/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 16, 1998 -- CONGRESS-CLINTON, 10-16
-- President Clinton arriving at a Rose Garden ceremony Friday to
celebrate what he calls a ``fiscally responsible balanced budget.''
Backed up by dozens of Democrats, Clinton basked in the bright
sunshine and gave his most rousing campaign speech of the political
year. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) PARIS -- Oct. 16, 1998 -- PARIS-FASHION-2, 10-16 --
Legacy is on the minds of Paris designers. John Galliano, whose
pleated and embroidered dress, left, adds wearability. Black lace
from Alber Elbaz's final collection for Guy Laroche, right. (Dan
and Corina Lecca/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) PARIS -- Oct. 16, 1998 -- PARIS-FASHION-1, 10-16 -- In
several ways, John Galliano and Karl Lagerfeld, whose spring 1999
collections for Chanel were shown Friday, have successfully taken
the best of history and reinterpreted it for modern utility. From
left, Lagerfeld's pale sheer blouse and pleated and appliqued
mushroom-tone skirt; Galliano's suit for an evening at the theater;
an orange leather jacket with silver sport pants, by Lagerfeld for
Chanel's new Beige label. (Dan and Corina Lecca/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Oct. 16, 1998 -- DOUGLAS-HISTORY, 10-16 --
Ann Douglas, author and historian. In a body of work that covers
almost a century and a half of American history, Ms. Douglas has
seen again and again how the private has become public. To her,
Kenneth Starr's investigation into President Clinton's sex life is
just the latest example. ``I feel some sort of horrified sense of
being caught in a re-enactment,'' says Ms. Douglas, 56. (Nancy
Siesel/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Oct. 16, 1998 -- ADV FOR SUN., OCT. 18 --
BIZ-GOLDFISH-CRACKERS, 10-16 -- Dale Morrison, Campbell's chief
executive, hopes consumers will say, ``Maybe I'll have soup'' for a
snack. The key question for Campbell is whether the smart
management that revived Pepperidge Farm can bring similar spice to
the company's flagship soup business. (Ozier Muhammad/NY Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) VANCOUVER, Wash. -- Oct. 16, 1998 -- ADV FOR SUN., OCT.
18 -- EXCLUSIVE-COLUMBIA-HCA-2, 10-16 -- James Alderson, a former
hospital accountant in Montana, waited five years before a fraud
case he filed against four giant hospital companies was unsealed.
Alderson and his family could share as much as 25 percent of any
recovery made in the government's false-claims fraud case against
Columbia/HCA and Quorum Health Group - an amount that could reach
into millions of dollars. (Rich Frishman/NY Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) VANCOUVER, Wash. -- Oct. 16, 1998 -- ADV FOR SUN., OCT.
18 -- EXCLUSIVE-COLUMBIA-HCA-1, 10-16 -- For five years James
Alderson, a former hospital accountant in Montana, kept quiet about
a whistle-blowing fraud case he filed under seal against four giant
hospital companies. His role in the case finally became known
earlier this month when the case was unsealed. (Rich Frishman/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MILAN, Italy -- Oct. 16, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 18
-- GLAM-ROCK, 10-16 -- Tom Ford's glittering dress for Gucci. Now,
as myriad glam influences seem to be percolating back into pop
culture in music, theater and fashion, the question is whether this
trend is the expression of an authentic, grass-roots revival, or a
fabrication of the buzz machine. (Corina Lecca/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Oct. 16, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 18 --
ABOUT-CARS-ODYSSEY-2, 10-16 -- The1999 Honda Odyssey's dashboard is
designed for efficiency, above, and its seating configuration can
be easily transformed for passengers and cargo. Much larger than
its predecessor, the new Odyssey matches Chrysler's long-wheelbase
minvans, sold as the Dodge Grand Caravan and Plymouth Grand
Voyager, and Ford's Windstar in dimensions. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Oct. 16, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 18 --
ABOUT-CARS-ODYSSEY-1, 10-16 -- Honda has crashed the minivan party
with a new model, the 1999 Odyssey, which is just arriving at
showrooms and is even more magical than Chrysler's offerings. It's
Chrysler's toughest competition yet. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- Oct. 16, 1998 -- ABOUT-CARS-BMW, 10-11 -- In a
``B'' movie, BMW would stitch together the M Coupe on a dark and
menacing night as lightning crackled against a castle in deepest
Bavaria. The fastest car BMW has ever sold in the United States,
this $42,370 Go Kart has two sport seats, room for two golf bags,
and the kind of razor-edged maneuverability that Scott Doniger, the
company's M brand manager, likens to a ``four-wheeled motorcycle.''
(New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Oct. 16, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 18 --
BIZ-5-QUESTIONS-TOYOTA, 10-16 -- In the three years he has been
president of the Toyota Motor Corp., Hiroshi Okuda has become known
as much for his black belt in judo as for his outspoken views and
aggressive moves to revitalize the once very conservative
automobile maker that the stock market values as Japan's largest
publicly traded company. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) PALO ALTO, Calif. -- Oct. 16, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT.
18 -- BIZ-PROFILE-KAWASAKI, 10-16 -- Guy Kawasaki, who is known for
his assists in a weekly pick-up basketball game, aims to match
technology ventures with investors at Garage.com. Kawasaki, 44, has
taken a leave of absence from Apple to concentrate on Garage.com,
an Internet-based company that will match high-technology
entrepreneurs with private investors. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Oct. 16, 1998 -- BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN, 10-15
-- Through two years as a celebrated heart-transplant patient,
Frank Torre has continued to savor the game that has been both his
and his brother, Joe's, life: World Series first baseman for the
Milwaukee Braves four decades ago, Rawlings sporting goods
executive, friend of Allan (Bud) Selig, now the commissioner. ``The
first time I took Buddy into a clubhouse, he told me, 'Someday I'll
own a ball club.' `` (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Oct. 16, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 18 --
FIELDS-RICHARD, 10-16 -- Bertram Fields, left, and Dominick Dunne
at ``21.'' Fields, the swashbuckling Hollywood attorney who has
done legal battle on behalf of Tom Cruise, James Cameron, the
Beatles and nearly every major film studio, was being feted for a
scholarly book called ``Royal Blood: Richard III and the Mystery of
the Princess.'' (Thomas Dallal/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
