publicly traded company. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) PALO ALTO, Calif. -- Oct. 16, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT.
18 -- BIZ-PROFILE-KAWASAKI, 10-16 -- Guy Kawasaki, who is known for
his assists in a weekly pick-up basketball game, aims to match
technology ventures with investors at Garage.com. Kawasaki, 44, has
taken a leave of absence from Apple to concentrate on Garage.com,
an Internet-based company that will match high-technology
entrepreneurs with private investors. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Oct. 16, 1998 -- BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN, 10-15
-- Through two years as a celebrated heart-transplant patient,
Frank Torre has continued to savor the game that has been both his
and his brother, Joe's, life: World Series first baseman for the
Milwaukee Braves four decades ago, Rawlings sporting goods
executive, friend of Allan (Bud) Selig, now the commissioner. ``The
first time I took Buddy into a clubhouse, he told me, 'Someday I'll
own a ball club.' `` (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Oct. 16, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 18 --
FIELDS-RICHARD, 10-16 -- Bertram Fields, left, and Dominick Dunne
at ``21.'' Fields, the swashbuckling Hollywood attorney who has
done legal battle on behalf of Tom Cruise, James Cameron, the
