<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981016.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2227 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILITIA-FORT-HOOD-PLO     10-16 2011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITIA-FORT-HOOD-PLOT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Agents arrest Texas militiamen
 &HT;    By Cara Tanamachi
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The crackle of a loudspeaker broke the still
morning air as dawn seeped through the trees into the crowded
campgroundsat Colorado Bend State Park early on July 4, 1997.
``This is the FBI. Mr. Glover. Mr. Dorsett. We have warrants for
your arrest.''
</P>
<P>
   Two dozen agents, armed and decked out in paramilitary gear,
watched as militiamen Bradley Playford Glover and Michael Leonard
Dorsett emerged from their tents, hands in the air. In seconds,
agents had the men in handcuffs and on their way to jail.
</P>
<P>
   Glover and Dorsett had taken different routes into the militia
movement, but they were united that morning in the belief that
Chinese troops were training at Fort Hood, 100 miles to the east,
FBI agents say. Glover, a retired Navy intelligence specialist from
Kansas, and Dorsett, a roofing contractor from Fort Worth, also
feared an invasion by U.N. troops.
</P>
<P>
   The men had planned a pre-emptive strike with guns and pipe
bombs on Fort Hood later that day, according to information from a
yearlong undercover investigation by Missouri State Police.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say Glover and Dorsett are extremists on the fringe
of a militia movement that has given rise to dozens of domestic
terrorism plots since the 1995 bombing of the federal building in
Oklahoma City in April 1995. FBI and police have thwarted plots to
assassinate judges, poison water supplies and even blow up the
FBI's national fingerprint identification center.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, Congress has allocated more than $370 million to FBI
counterterrorism programs. Local and federal officers have beefed
up surveillance of some extremist groups of the so-called patriot
movement, made up of people who generally believe the government
has subverted citizens' rights. Many militia members point to gun
control laws or ballooning tax rates as evidence the government has
overstepped its bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Glover and Dorsett eventually pleaded guilty to weapons charges
and await sentencing next month in federal court in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The morning of their arrest, agents found a loaded handgun under
Glover's pillow and more arms in his white Ford pickup, including
four other pistols, two rifles, a silencer, 1,600 rounds of
ammunition, fatigues, riot gas and a militia handbook.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, eight other people in several other states were
arrested in connection with the plot against Fort Hood.
</P>
<P>
   Glover's attorney says that his client had no intention of
bombing or attacking Fort Hood, that he only wanted to see for
himself whether foreign troops were stationed there.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officers and groups that monitor extremist
militia organizations, however, say that Glover and Dorsett posed a
serious threat and represent the more dangerous segments of the
patriot movement.
</P>
<P>
   Investigations tricky
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say the beginnings of a plot to bomb Fort Hood
emerged in 1996, during a meeting in Kansas City, Mo., of the Third
Continental Congress, a gathering of 30 representatives of militia
groups from across the country.
</P>
<P>
   At that three-day meeting, in a bare room at a Holiday Inn early
in November 1996, the group of mostly white men discussed their
hopes for a new government, one that would in their minds better
protect the rights laid out in the Constitution. Among them,
quietly listening, were two undercover Missouri State Police
officers, including Sgt. Greg Hug.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, where pro-gun and militia groups have long been
active, state police have been aggressively investigating
suspicious members since 1992. ``Here in Missouri, we take these
groups seriously,'' Hug said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigating militias is a tricky business. The vast majority
of members, said Hug, are people who do not intend to break the
law. And law enforcement must walk a thin line between sniffing out
extremists bent on violence and preserving individual rights. Hug
said while most people at the meeting talked of parlimentary
procedure and constitutional law, one man, Ronald Griesacker, spoke
about forcibly overthrowing the government.
</P>
<P>
   He inspired two couples to join him in breaking from the main
group. Authorities have said Griesacker is a con man who used
rhetoric to persuade militia members to give him money and shelter.
He and the couples toured the United States, trying to recruit
followers.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, they ended up meeting and training at Glover's home
in Towanda, Kan. Glover was then a prominent member of the Kansas
Militia.
</P>
<P>
   Griesacker was later ousted from the group when Glover and
others became convinced he was a man of words and not of action,
Hug said.
</P>
<P>
   Glover, 58, stepped in as an informal leader for the group. A
retired Navy intelligence operative, he owned a computer consulting
firm in Towanda.
</P>
<P>
   Glover is divorced with two sons, one a West Point graduate and
Army captain, the other a graduate student in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Some who know Glover say he is an intelligent man who in recent
years became increasingly convinced of elaborate conspiracies
within the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether valid or not, in his mind there are political threats
to the stability of this country,'' said Frank Jackson, a Dallas
attorney who is representing Glover. Through his attorney, Glover
declined to be interviewed for this article.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley is a remarkable, bright, articulate person,'' Jackson
added. ``He didn't drop out of the sixth grade. He isn't some kind
of nut that crawled out of the woodwork.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Glover became active in the Kansas Militia,
doing media interviews predicting the downfall of the government,
which he believed had been infiltrated by foreign agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realize one thing,'' he told the Kansas City Star in 1994.
``We're not turning against the government, the true approved
Constitution of the United States. We're turning against a rogue
element, a cancer against the body. And we're going to cut that
cancer out and restore the health of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Hug said Glover suffered from what he called a ``Red Dawn''
syndrome, after the movie of the same name, whose main character
leads an underground resistance against communists who have taken
over the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``They watched 'Red Dawn' constantly, and this got them fired
up,'' Hug said. ``They believed they were going to be precipitators
of the great guerilla war.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorsett, 43, believed the system had failed him, say those who
know him. Dorsett's attorney declined to comment for this article
and advised Dorsett not to speak until after his sentencing
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Dorsett found himself divorced twice and in
tax trouble, with the IRS claiming he and his business, Texas
Roofing Unlimited, owed almost $7,000 in taxes, according to court
records.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Pitcavage, a militia historian and consultant to law
enforcement agencies across the country, said some militia members
are drawn to the idea of conspiracies to explain troubles in their
own lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people join these groups because they can't quite cope
financially with the capitalist world,'' Pitcavage said. ``They
lose their jobs, they have mortgage problems, tax problems, divorce
problems _ they just can't cut it. And human nature being what it
is, they externalize the blame. They believe this was done to them
by someone, most often the government, and that makes them angry
and desperate.''
</P>
<P>
   In Glover's group, members believed strongly in a malicious
force behind the United Nations. Many patriots share the fear that
some disaster, spawned by a foreign invasion or an internal
government conspiracy, will lead to the declaration of martial law,
depriving U.S. citizens of their constitutional rights.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing themselves as freedom fighters, Glover, Dorsett and two
Midwest couples, along with several others, plotted to attack
foreign troops at American army bases, including Fort Hood and an
Air Force base in New Mexico, Hug said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In June 1997, we got a call from Glover, asking us to join him
to attack Red Chinese troops at Fort Hood,'' Hug said. ``Myself and
my partner tried to talk him out of it. But he was insistent. They
started amassing a lot of ammunition and automatic weapons. They
said they were going hunting at the base on July 4. We knew they
were serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Glover and Dorsett had picked the Fourth of July because the
base would be open and filled with families celebrating the
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Glover and other members soon sold their homes, businesses and
belonging so they could be mobile and have ready cash, Hug said.
Two members of the group went to Creede, Colo. to set up a safe
housein the remote mountain village, where Glover and Dorsett were
to hide after their mission.
</P>
<P>
   Hug and his partner notified the FBI, which began trailing
Glover and Dorsett in Arlington, where they lived a short time. On
July 3, FBI agents saw them load their pickup with guns and other
equipment, including fatigues and bulletproof vests.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Holmes, an FBI agent who was part of the team that would
take Glover and Dorsett into custody, said agents worried about a
host of possible complications. The campground was crowded. Agents
feared Glover and Dorsett might have planted booby traps.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was considered a high-risk arrest because you have
explosives, you have weapons and you have individuals that pretty
much are considered armed and dangerous,'' Holmes said. ``That we
took them into custody without a single shot fired _ this was good
day in law enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Some militia members, however, say that Glover and Dorsett's
arrest is just another example of overzealous officers unfairly
targeting militias.
</P>
<P>
   Militia advocate Ed Wolfe of Oregon, who maintains a Web site
called Caged Patriots at www.involved.com/ewolfe/caged/ which
documents alleged mistaken arrests of militia members, says the
idea of two men plotting to attack the nation's largest army bases
``ludicrous.'' Wolfe said officers are overly suspicious of militia
members because they own guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patriots are people who love the government and the
Constitution, perhaps more than officers do, but they are also the
ones who will point out when the government has overstepped its
bounds,'' Wolfe said. ``The government sees us as a threat. That's
why today if you work to organize a militia, you might as well
paint a target on the back of your head.''
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents and Texas state troopers say they do not investigate
groups simply because of their beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only become involved when someone engages in an illegal
act,'' Holmes said. ``Until and unless they do, we do not become
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   New laws have strengthened anti-terrorism efforts, including the
1996 Effective Death Penalty and Public Safety Act, which added the
death penalty to the range of punishment for bombings and other
acts of domestic terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The American Civil Liberties Union, among other constitutional
rights groups, has criticized much of the anti-terrorism
legislation, saying that it broadens the investigative powers of
the FBI and threatens individual rights. They say, for example, the
1996 act includes an overly broad definition of terrorism that
could lead to improper labeling of some political groups as
terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   Membership in many militia groups seems to be shrinking,
according to the Anti-Defamation League, which tracks extremist and
hate groups. But ADL officials say they suspect more groups are
going underground, making membership numbers harder to gauge. Wolfe
said people fear retaliation from the government, which is why some
groups are not as vocal as they once were.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jackson said Glover is stoic about what likely will
be a five-year prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tells me that he was trained in his intelligence work how
to be a prisoner of war, and that's how he'll approach his
incarceration, for better or worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
