<P>
   EDITORS: ALL budgeted arts, travel, style and business stories
for Sunday, October 18, have moved. Budgeted Week in Review stories
will move Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   FEATURE STORY
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-THEATER (Undated) _ Like book publishing before it _
until the last decade, a quaint holdout against the forces of media
consolidation _ the theater is now becoming ``content'' suitable
for synergistic annexation and exploitation by our new
entertainment conglomerates. By Frank Rich.
</P>
<P>
   FILM AND VIDEO
</P>
<P>
   BELOVED-FILM (Undated) _ What is most impressive about the film
version of ``Beloved'' is not that it simplifies Toni Morrison's
difficult esthetic to attract a wider audience and become a
blockbuster in the process, but that it takes an opposite tack: It
stubbornly reinforces a literary way of looking at things.By Will
Joyner.
</P>
<P>
   IAN-MCKELLEN-FILMS (Leeds, England) _ There is something rather
touching about Ian McKellen's new enthusiasm for cinema. Now, at
59, he has acquired an appetite to work in movies, to do what for
the best part of four decades he found unappealing. Is it fame that
he is after? By Alan Riding. With Photo.
</P>
<P>
   FASCISM-MOVIES (Undated) _ Humor may be, in its essence,
anti-fascistic: It takes what is most self-important, most
unyielding and most unforgiving, and dissolves it into absurdity.
Fascism meets its match in farce. That is the approach, delicately
taken, of the new Italian film ``Life is Beautiful,'' the winner of
the grand jury prize at the 1998 Cannes Film Festival. By Edward
Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   THEATER
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-WIT-CANBY (New York) _ In ``Wit'' the main character
dies at the end but, for the next two hours that pass in a wink,
the audience is treated to the kind of theatrical experience of
which legends are made. We come to know and appreciate the mind and
substance of this singular character and of the playwright who
conceived her, as well as the ravishing potential of the singular
actress who plays Vivian: Kathleen Chalfant.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   AZNAVOUR-MUSIC (Paris) _ Charles Aznavour may well be the only
person who remembers his first visit to New York in 1948. This
week, as Aznavour embarks on a new American tour, public
recognition is the least of his problems. Having sold close to 100
million albums, he now enjoys the magical status of international
musical legend. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   JUDY-GARLAND-MUSIC (Undated) _ Until the release of ``Judy'' (32
Records), a four-CD career retrospective that comes with an
excellent video showing highlights from her 1963-64 television
variety show, Judy Garland's recorded legacy was scattered among
several different labels. This set, produced by Joel Dorn and his
son, Adam, with the Garland archivist Scott Schechter, encompasses
the breadth of Garland's recording career. By Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-NOVELTIES (Undated) _ Planned obsolescence may work well
in the auto industry but less well in classical music, which has
invested the bulk of its holdings in the used-symphony and
used-opera business, and has lots of trouble convincing listeners
that the new models are any good. By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   PRINCE-EDWARD-TV (London) _ Prince Edward, 34, the youngest son
of Queen Elizabeth, is beginning to see some financial success in
his own film production company, Ardent Productions. And although
competitors in Britain's television industry complain that he is
shamelessly trading on his connections to advance his career, he
has managed to insure new-found respect for Ardent by crossing the
all-important continental divide and selling a number of his
programs to the United States. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES
</P>
<P>
   MINIATURE-OBJECTS-ANTIQUES (Washington) _ Last month, 70 of
Daniel Brush's exquisitely detailed steel and gold miniature
objects went on view here in ``Daniel Brush: Gold Without
Boundaries,'' a retrospective exhibition at the Renwick Gallery of
the National Museum of American Art. The show, through Jan. 10,
coincides with the publication of an elaborately illustrated book
about the artist's metal works. By Rita Reif.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (Moved in `t' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-POLAND-JEWS (Warsaw, Poland) _ Seelking vestiges of
Jewish Bialystok. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-TUNISIA (Undated) _ In Tunisia, the Romans built
monuments whose ruins evoke the empire. By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   CYBER-TRAVEL (Undated) _ Surfing the net: Vacation planning. .
By L.R. Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ How to pack, or when ironing is
not an option. Betsy Wade.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Washington Monument closed; All aboard
the Britannia; Touring the Northeast; Easier travel for the
disabled; Gizmo heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: There will be no TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A this week.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   STYLE (Moved in `l' category)
</P>
<P>
   PARIS-FASHION (Paris) _ Men, naked but for a diaper, writhing
sensually like Nijinsky on a bed of pink rose petals, are not what
a fashion-show audience comes to see. But few would be telling the
truth if they claimed that they minded this backdrop to the bounty
of airy, magical dresses and redoubtable slithery suits that were
the John Galliano collection. By Constance C.R. White.
</P>
<P>
   FIELDS-RICHARD (Undated) _ On Wednesday night, a double-A list
of the friends and clients of Bertram Fields gathered at the ``21''
Club to offer congratulations. Another legal victory for the
swashbuckling Hollywood attorney? Not exactly. This time, Fields,
who has done legal battle on behalf of Tom Cruise, James Cameron,
the Beatles and nearly every major film studio, was being feted for
a scholarly book in defense of an altogether different client,
Richard III. By Andrew Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   ROLEX-ENVY (Undated) _ Rolex is the main noun in the
international language of success. By Stephan Talty.
</P>
<P>
   GRACE-SLICK (New York) _ Somehow the Palm Court at the Plaza
Hotel, with its harpist and doilied dessert plates, seems like the
last place where Grace Slick would want to meet. But here she
comes, dressed mostly in black, looking startlingly like herself
even though the Feed Your Head Queen of Jefferson Airplane, the
voice that launched a thousand trips with her 1960's anthem ``White
Rabbit,'' turns 60 next year. Judging from how good she looks,
either she took far fewer drugs than anyone imagined, or the
cosmetics industry should start marketing an LSD eye cream. By Alex
Witchel.
</P>
<P>
   GLAM-ROCK (New York) _ Gabe Doppelt was scrambling. As VH-1's
creative director of fashion, Ms. Doppelt co-produces the cable
music channel's annual Fashion Awards, and each year she
commissions designers to create outfits for the show's opening,
purportedly around a rock-related theme. But, she admits, ``Every
year I look for the appropriate collision of fashion and music, and
I never really find it.'' This year promised to be no different,
until Ms. Doppelt heard that a movie about the glam rock movement
had won an award at the Cannes film festival, and her antennae
began buzzing. By David Handelman.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Some worthy plants are victims of
gardeners' prejudice, among them marigolds because of their scent,
goldenrod because it resembles ragweed and gladioluses because they
are so often the flower of choice at funerals. By Cass Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   WEEK IN REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Oct. 18, will move Saturday in the `a' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTHYISM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Recently declassified Soviet and
U.S. documents indicate there was some truth to Sen. Joseph
McCarthy's charge that communist agents were at work in the U.S.
The data has unleashed a flood of scholarship and revived old
debates. By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ECON-REVIEW (Jerusalem) _ The Israeli business community
and foreign investors have a deep interest in seeing a genuine
Israeli-Palestinian accord. While the political arguments have
focused on security and land, the economic case for achieving peace
is a powerful background factor as Netanyahu and Arafat meet. By
William Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   POLLS-VOTERS-REVIEW (Undated) _ With the Republican-led House
moving toward an impeachment investigation of President Clinton,
voter turnout will be especially important this year; polls on who
will turn out are therefore also important. A look at how to assess
pre-election polls. By Michael R. Kagay.
</P>
<P>
   HATE-CRIMES-REVIEW (Houston) _ Laws against hate crimes raise a
paradox: such laws are designed to magnify an offense and show our
condemnation of it, but in extreme cases such as murder, these laws
may be unnecessary, since the person convicted would probably get
the maximum punishment anyway. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   BAD-SAMARITANS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The case of David Cash, who
witnessed a fatal attack on a child but did nothing to intervene or
report it, has revived a longstanding debate about whether
bystanders should have a legal duty to help strangers in peril. By
Jeff Stryker.
</P>
<P>
   ANCIENT-SEX-SCANDAL-REVIEW (Undated) _ In a coincidence
confirming that sex in politics is truly ancient news, the Semitic
Museum of Harvard University is exhibiting cuneiform tablets from a
corruption-and-sex investigation from Mesopotamia circa 1400 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-U.S.-BANKS-REVIEW (Washington) _ There are striking
parallels between the United States in the late 1980s as it
struggled to address its savings &AMP; loan crisis and Japan in 1998 as
it faces a banking system near collapse. Those similarities offer
lessons about what and what not to do. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   SACRILEGIOUS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The play ``Corpus Christi'' has
refueled debate over a purported double standard: is offending
Christians not as bad as offending other religious or ethnic
groups? But the deeper and more complicated issue is what is fair
and what goes over the line in dealing with religious themes. By
Peter Applebome.
</P>
<P>
   STARR-REVIEW (Washington) _ Democrats want to make Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr their chief witness at the House impeachment
hearings. A look at whether this would help or hurt their cause. By
Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   BIG-NUMBERS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The numbers: they keep getting
bigger. Partly because of recent financial developments, gigantic
figures like a trillion have become less abstract and more real. By
Michael T. Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS (Moved `f' category)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service has moved the following Money
and Business articles for release Sunday, Oct. 18, 1998:
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SECTION FRONT
</P>
<P>
   ECON-COLUMN (Undated) _ An expanded version of the weekly
ECON-COLUMN that offers a report card on the nation's economic
expansion. By Louis Uchitelle. With graphics.
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-COLUMBIA-HCA (Undated) _ Exclusive interview with
James F. Alderson, the small-town accountant who filed suit on
behalf of the United States charging four giant hospital companies
with fraud. For years Alderson stewed with the belief that the
companies _ the huge Hospital Corp. of America and three of its
corporate spinoffs _ had cheated the government with bogus expense
claims. While working at a Montana hospital run by one of those
companies, Alderson himself had been instructed to create a second
set of books recording different expenses than those reported to
the government. He had refused, saying it was unethical. Then his
world fell apart. By Kurt Eichenwald. With exclusive photos.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-WATCH (Undated) _ Weekly feature looking at developments
in the world's stock markets. By Gretchen Morgenson. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE THE SECTION
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-GOLDFISH-CRACKERS (Norwalk, Conn.) _ Campbell Soup
reinvigorated Pepperidge Farm, led by the classic but newly cool
Goldfish cracker, using smarter marketing and brand extensions. Can
they do the same for the rest of the profitable but slow-growth
company? By Constance L. Hays. With Photo and Graphics.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-PROFILE-KAWASAKI (Undated) _ Guy Kawasaki has taken a leave
of absence from Apple Computer Inc. to concentrate on Garage.com,
an Internet-based company that will match high-technology
entrepreneurs with private investors. ``I want to help the next
Apple get started,'' he said. By Roy Furchgott. With Photo.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-ETHICS (Undated) _ Welcome to the modern workplace, where
companies are so concerned about wrongful-termination suits that
silence often takes the place of honest communication. Most
managers with power to dismiss have faced the problem: whether or
not to let people know why a colleague has been let go. By Jeffrey
L. Seglin.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-CATALYST-WOMEN (Undated) _ A recent survey by a women's
research group found that the boards of directors of 71 companies
among the Fortune 500 were made up entirely of men. To those who
have followed the results of such annual surveys by Catalyst, a
nonprofit organization in New York, the news undoubtedly sounded
familiar. The fact that roughly 14 percent of the 500 largest
companies do not have a single women director begs a simple
question: ``Why?'' By Adam Bryant. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-PRELUDES (Undated) _ For a year, Edward Lecomte listened to
an incessant stream of talk about ``the market.'' Friends boasted
about booming stock portfolios, his sister made a bundle in a
mutual fund and colleagues badgered him to jump on the bandwagon.
So last winter, Lecomte, 37, decided it was time to become a
player. His experiences will amuse, dishearten and perhaps terrify.
By Abby Ellin.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-5-QUESTIONS-TOYOTA (Undated) _ In the three years he has
been president of Toyota Motor Corp., Hiroshi Okuda has become
known as much for his black belt in judo as for his outspoken views
and aggressive moves to revitalize the once very conservative
automobile maker that the stock market values as Japan's largest
publicly traded company. By Sharon R. King. With Photo.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-WITH-LEWIS (Undated) _ ``I've got a calm personality, so
I don't get too excited when we go way up, and I don't get too down
when we go way down,'' said Gary Lewis, the manager of the Van
Kampen Emerging Growth fund in his 45th floor Houston office. This
is fortunate, because funds like the one Lewis manages, which
invested in small and mid-cap stocks with higher price-earnings
ratios, have taken it on the chin. By William R. Long.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Interview with manager of Scudder
Japan Fund. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-MUTUAL (Undated) _ The roster of value players at Mutual
Series will remain the same after chief executive officer Michael
Price officially departs next month, but they will be getting new
positions. By Carole Gould. With Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-ASIA (Undated) _ Asian stocks, bonds and real estate are
not all that have been marked down for immediate clearance. From
Hyundai's humble econoboxes to Honolulu's choicest penthouses,
other merchandise made, owned or offered by Asians is also priced
to sell. By Allen R. Myerson.
</P>
<P>
   LYDELL-HOTEL-PROFILE (Sheridan, N.Y.) _ Ransom Lydell guessed
right 17 years ago when he thought that there would be a booming
market for the lily-like perennials called hostas. But spotting a
money-making opportunity is one thing. Exploiting it is another. By
Laura Pedersen-Pietersen.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Undated) _ As backward as it may sound, some
companies have a bias against people who've had the brashness to
blaze their own trails. By Michelle Cottle.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-INTEL (Undated) _ A technology investor has no choice but
to own Intel, right? Maybe. But not everyone believes Intel is a
compelling buy at this price. By Lawrence M. Fisher. With Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-DIARY (Undated) _ Weekly column highlighting business news
of the week.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOS
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT-CARS-ODYSSEY (Detroit) _ Honda has arrived at the minivan
party with a new model, the 1999 Odyssey, which is even more
magical than Chrysler's offerings, and Chrysler faces its toughest
competition yet. By Michelle Krebs. With Photo.
</P>
<P>
   STAND-ALONE GRAPHIC
</P>
<P>
   IN-MY-WALLET (Undated) _ A voyeuristic short feature that lets
readers see business personalities in more dimensions than they are
usually portrayed. This week: John Reed and his wallet.
</P>
