<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2250 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROP9-SFCHRON &LR;      10-16 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROP9-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Money Power _ Utilities Bankroll `No on 9' Campaign   By Rebecca Smith  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Proposition 9, the electric-rate rollback measure, is shaping up as
the most lopsided fight in this election, with opponents
outspending proponents by a 30-to-1 margin.
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than 99 percent of the ``No on 9'' money has come from
California's three giant electric utilities _ Pacific Gas and
Electric Co., Southern California Edison and San Diego Gas &AMP;
Electric, &UR;  &LR; according to Chronicle research.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's safe to say this is the most lopsided campaign'' this
year, said Kim Alexander, president of the California Voter
Foundation in Sacramento, a nonprofit research group.
</P>
<P>
   Some of $30.1 million raised by the ``No on 9'' campaign has
ended up in unusual hands, including the Democratic and Republican
parties, the firm co-owned by California Senator Steve Peace, who
helped write the state's electric deregulation law, and Los Angeles
television personality David Horowitz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The state's deregulation law allowed the big three utilities
to continue charging consumers for investments in nuclear plants
that would become uneconomical in a free market.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 9 proponents call that deal a ``bailout'' and want
the utilities' shareholders, not their customers, to pay off about
$6 billion in debts on the nuclear plants.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would force the utilities to cut their rates by at
least 10 percent _ on top of a 10 percent rate cut that took effect
January 1.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents _ who include consumer activists Ralph Nader and
Harvey Rosenfield, author of the 1988 insurance-rate rollback
measure, Proposition 103 _ raised just $1.22 million through
September 30.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of that money was spent to gather the 700,000
signatures needed to get the measure on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any money,'' said Nettie Hoge, Proposition 9
proponent and executive director of The Utility Reform Network in
San Francisco. ``You won't be seeing any TV, any radio ads from us.
All we've got is `Yes on 9' buttons.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, opponents of Proposition 9 have raised $30.1
million, of which $29.8 million came from the three investor-owned
utilities. By law, these campaign contributions must be paid by
shareholders, not ratepayers.
</P>
<P>
   With Proposition 9 money mostly pouring into one coffer, the
result for voters is a one-sided shout of radio and television
commercials. The message opponents are trying to drive home is that
Proposition 9 is a deceptive initiative that would raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The utilities vow that if Proposition 9 passes, they will sue
the state for reneging on the deregulation deal. If they win that
case, they say taxpayers will wind up paying for any rate
reduction.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the ``No on 9'' campaign's expenditures have raised
eyebrows:
</P>
<P>
   _The campaign paid $106,000 to Horowitz, whose ``Fight Back with
David Horowitz'' television show has been syndicated for 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Emmy-winning Horowitz made a 28-minute ``special show''
appearing on cable TV stations that purports to uncover the
``secret rip-offs'' of the Proposition 9 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Although the program has a slim ``No on 9'' banner across the
top of the screen, some viewers might mistake it for a television
news show.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Horowitz cites an ``independent study'' that warns
of huge tax increases if Proposition 9 passes. He doesn't disclose
that the author of the study, Metropolitan West Securities of
Sacramento, was paid $103,974 by the ``No on 9'' campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Horowitz bristles at suggestions the video exploits his name
and reputation and objects to descriptions of his Proposition 9
show as an ``infomercial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an educational program,'' said Horowitz. ``An infomercial
sells something. This is not selling anything. I don't do
infomercials.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The ``No on 9'' campaign donated $500,000 to both the
Republican and Democratic parties after they pledged to oppose the
measure. ``The money is to help (the parties) communicate their
feelings to their party members in slate mailers,'' said Allan
Zaremberg, chairman of the ``No on 9'' coalition and president of
the California Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders say those donations, though legal, give the appearance
of a quid pro quo in which endorsements were sold. ``It's very
unusual, if not unprecedented, for money to come out of a campaign
and into a political party,'' said Bruce Cain, associate director
of the Institute of Governmental Studies at the University of
California at Berkeley. ``Money usually goes the other way,'' from
parties to campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   _ The campaign paid $39,641 to a film-production company
co-owned by Peace, D-San Diego. Payment covered production work on
the Horowitz video.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand it may subject me to criticism,'' said Peace,
chief financial officer of Four Square Productions and chairman of
the Senate Energy, Utilities and Communications Committee. ``But
I'm not going to tell my partners they can't do business with
someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Key to the ``No on 9'' campaign are the endorsements that run
like movie credits at the end of its commercials.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign has garnered hundreds of endorsements, from the
League of California Cities, California Labor Federation, both
candidates for governor and others.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Yes on 9'' side has only a few endorsements, including
Consumer's Union, The Utility Reform Network, environmentalist
David Brower, singer Bonnie Raitt and the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   In the race for endorsements, the ``No on 9'' side has a huge
advantage: starting with a combined &UR;  &LR; utility workforce of 39,000
people, any of whom can be tapped for service.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E has distributed campaign volunteer cards to many of its
20,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Watsonville's acting mayor, Oscar Rios, said he endorsed the
``No on 9'' campaign after a PG&AMP;E employee approached him. ``They
contact you and say, this is the reason we would like you to be
against it,'' Rios said. ``If no one had contacted me, I wouldn't
necessarily have taken a position.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaign workers have found a willing ear in many communities,
because of the utilities' history of community service and
charitable giving. PG&AMP;E, for example, donated $9.9 million to 735
community organizations last year. All told, the three utilities
gave charities $21.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives them lots of chits they can call in,'' said Jim
Shultz, director of San Francisco's Democracy Center, a nonprofit
that encourages grassroots politicking.
</P>
<P>
   Not all endorsements work out as smoothly as intended. A ``No on
9'' endorsement by the Consumer Federation of California has split
the organization _ a coalition of labor and consumer groups.
</P>
<P>
   The ruckus began when a Consumer Federation committee
recommended that the organization remain neutral on Proposition 9
since members were deeply divided.
</P>
<P>
   When utility worker unions pushed for the vote anyway _ and the
board voted to oppose the proposition _ six of the board's 36
members resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Nelson quit because she didn't want her name used by a
campaign she opposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're an alliance. You can't take a position on an issue like
this when the members are so divided,'' said Nelson, president of
Mill Valley's Consumer Research Foundation, a nonprofit educational
group.
</P>
<P>
   Even without $30 million and hundreds of endorsements, the ``No
on 9'' campaign had a big advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Political experts say California voters, frustrated at being
asked to decide complexities that they feel are the responsibility
of the state Legislature to sort out, are in a mood to vote down
most initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of studies indicate that `no' money is more powerful
than `yes' money,'' said Cain, of UC Berkeley. ``And if they have
more money, too, then you get something called the `asymmetrical
negative spending' effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, this means the odds greatly favor the `no'
side.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Recent Field Poll data bears this out. Results show voters
oppose Proposition 9 by a 2-to-1 margin, though 36 percent still
are undecided.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
