<SLUG> BC-SHAW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 D.E. Shaw Explains BofA Loss   By Sam Zuckerman  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The Wall Street firm whose complex investment strategy generated
huge losses for BankAmerica Corp. got into trouble when the prices
of U.S. government securities soared while the markets for other
kinds of debt collapsed, the firm's founder and chief executive
said yesterday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Shaw, the computer scientist who heads D.E. Shaw &AMP; Co.,
said in an interview on the cable TV financial network CNBC that
his firm's strategy was to sell Treasury bonds and buy riskier debt
instruments, hoping to garner profits if the price gap between the
two kinds of investments narrowed.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, just the opposite happened in recent weeks, causing the
portfolio that the firm managed for BankAmerica to plunge in value.
Shaw said the losses were magnified when other firms with similar
investments began to dump their holdings.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we missed _ and it's an important lack and something I
feel very bad about _ is the magnitude of a risk factor that we had
identified but turned out to be much worse than we expected: the
effect of forced liquidations in the market,'' Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw managed $20 billion in debt securities for San Francisco's
BankAmerica, one of several portfolios it ran for the bank in
exchange for a $1.4 billion loan. The two companies split profits
and losses 50-50.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's debt portfolio tanked when Long-Term Capital Management,
a giant investment fund with a similar strategy, nearly collapsed
late in September.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's losses in the BankAmerica debt portfolio prompted the
bank to take a $372 million write-off when it reported profits
Wednesday for the September quarter. The report was issued two
weeks after North Carolina's NationsBank Corp. bought the San
Francisco bank and took its name.
</P>
<P>
   The new BankAmerica agreed to buy the entire debt portfolio from
Shaw, which otherwise might have been forced to sell securities at
fire-sale prices.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said the firm's losses were multiplied because it borrowed
heavily to build up the size of the BankAmerica debt portfolio.
Analysts estimate that it took on $19 in short-term loans for every
$1 BankAmerica lent it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question we used more leverage than, with the
benefit of hindsight, we should have,'' said Shaw, a Columbia
University professor before he founded the firm 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said his firm remains financially healthy and that its
other investments continue to be profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Both Long-Term Capital and Shaw use computers to trade on tiny
variations in the prices of securities in different markets.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a New York law firm filed a class-action suit
accusing Hugh McColl, chief executive of the new BankAmerica, of
concealing the bank's Shaw losses when he spoke at a post-merger
news conference at the beginning of the month.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a Wall Street Journal article about BankAmerica
and Shaw, Representative Edward Markey, D-Mass., asked the SEC
yesterday to clarify what information is considered ``material''
and therefore must be made public immediately, Bloomberg News
reported.
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica said in a statement issued yesterday that it
disclosed Shaw's losses ``as they were known.''
</P>
</TEXT>
