<SLUG> BC-COMPTROLLER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Official Warns Banks Against Loose Lending   By Sam Zuckerman  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The day after the Federal Reserve warned of a looming credit
crunch, a top U.S. regulator came to San Francisco to admonish
bankers that their lending standards are too loose.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a speech at a meeting of bankers and bank regulators
yesterday, Julie Williams, the acting comptroller of the currency,
said the current global economic slowdown means that bankers must
be especially careful in making loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not succumb to the temptation to declare victory over
lax underwriting of new loans,'' Williams declared.'
</P>
<P>
   Williams' stance highlights the conflict between those
policymakers who worry about overly aggressive lending and those
who fear that a clampdown on credit could tank the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve officials have been sounding the alarm that
risk-wary bankers are pulling back from lending. If that continues,
they warn, the economy could be starved for credit, turning a
slowdown into a full-fledged recession.
</P>
<P>
   When it announced its move to cut short-term interest rates on
Thursday, the Fed cited ``growing caution by lenders'' as a key
reason for its action.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters after her address, Williams said she only
wants bankers to steer clear of imprudent loans, such as those made
to high-flying investment funds that have produced billions of
dollars in losses in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want banks to stop lending,'' Williams said. ``We
just want to make sure that if economic times get a little choppy,
they are going to remain healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Long-Term Capital Management, the giant hedge
fund that nearly collapsed last month, lenders appeared to have
been overawed by the firm's managers, which included two Nobel
Prize-winning economists, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The lenders ``don't appear to have understood exactly what the
firm was doing with all of that money,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica Corp. earlier this week reported a $372 million
write-off on a loan to D.E. Shaw &AMP; Co., a Wall Street firm that
uses computer-driven investment techniques similar to those that
brought down Long-Term Capital.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, whose agency regulates BankAmerica, declined to
comment on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Williams became interim chief of the Office of the
Comptroller of the Currency, one of three federal bank regulatory
agencies, while the Senate considers President Clinton's nomination
of Washington tax lawyer John Hawke for the job. Williams formerly
was the agency's top lawyer.
</P>
</TEXT>
