<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 With Founders Gone, How Will PalmPilot Fare in 3Com's Hands?   By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Now that its three guiding spirits have left Palm Computing, some
people wonder how the plucky little PalmPilot will fare in the
hands of 3Com Corp.
<TEXT>
<P>
   PalmPilot is the pocket-size gizmo that stores phone numbers and
calendar entries and retrieves e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Launched in 1996 by technical guru Jeff Hawkins, business maven
Donna Dubinsky and marketing chief Ed Colligan, the PalmPilot
became such a hit that Palm Computing, the device's parent company,
was acquired by U.S. Robotics, which in turn, was bought by 3Com.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Palm's founding trio have quit 3Com to form a
new startup, JD Technology. At the Agenda Conference on Tuesday in
Phoenix, JD will announce plans for a new generation of handheld
devices based on the Palm operating system, which they have
licensed from 3Com.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Mann, editor of Handheld Systems Magazine in San Luis
Obispo, wonders whether Palm Computing will be able to keep up its
growth now that it has lost the people who provided its
entrepreneurial soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd give (the Palm division) 18 months on the basis of their
current momentum,'' Mann said. ``Beyond that, it's a crap shoot
unless 3Com gets some inspired new leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Janice Roberts, the 3Com senior vice president who now runs Palm
Computing, said it's not as if all the talent walked out the door
with Hawkins, Dubinsky and Colligan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're approaching 400 full-time employees inside Palm,'' said
Roberts, adding that it was the company's very size and success
that prompted the founders to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sound political or bureaucratic or slow, but
managing a business that has grown this large doesn't appeal to
everyone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins and Dubinsky were on their way to Phoenix for their
``coming out'' presentation at Agenda and could not be reached. But
Colligan tried to dispel notions that their departures heralded
Palm's demise.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times when founders leave it's a bad sign, but
nothing would be further from the truth,'' he said. ``Palm is going
through the roof. I'd like to say it's cause we set it up so
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Roberts acknowledged a culture clash between Palm and
3Com. Palm must cope not only with growth _ the division should
have more than $500 million in revenues this year _ but also with
the strain of being a corporate stepchild.
</P>
<P>
   Palm is building two buildings in Santa Clara, which are
separated from 3Com headquarters by a creek. ``The team here calls
it the moat,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Purdy, editor of the Mobile Letter, an industry
newsletter, is betting that 3Com will help Palm mature without
stifling its creativity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realize that 3Com's new president, Bruce Claflin, used to head
the group at IBM that licensed the Palm technology,'' Purdy said.
``This is the most successful handheld computer ever. 3Com's not
going to throw that away.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Purple Prose: &LR;  Is Oracle Chairman Larry Ellison the
inspiration for the male character in a romance novel titled ``A
Hard Hearted Man''?
</P>
<P>
   That's what enquiring minds want to know based on some
tantalizing evidence linking the book's author, Melanie Craft of
San Francisco, with the software magnate.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that Craft and Ellison did attend a state dinner
together last October, which President and Mrs. Clinton put on to
honor Chinese President Jiang Zemin. And a source close to Ellison
confirmed that the software billionaire and the author have been
involved in more than affairs of state.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, it's just conjecture whether the Ross Bradford
character in Craft's novel is loosely modeled on Ellison. On the
surface, the answer is no. The novel is set in Africa, where
Bradford, a handsome, middle-aged land baron, becomes enamored of
Lilah Evans, a headstrong 28-year-old archaeologist.
</P>
<P>
   But after peeling back the physical layer, some similarities
appear. Bradford's heart is hardened by a rough childhood that
inoculates him against love, just as Ellison, who was given up for
adoption, had a rocky relationship with his adoptive parents.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are descriptions such as the one describing
Bradford ``as a Roman emperor, powerful and remote.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, any Ellison parallels may be imaginary or, at best,
wishful thinking on Craft's part. I couldn't reach the author for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The story ends happily, with Evans accepting the diamond
engagement ring proffered by that ``hard-hearted, hard-bodied man
who melted her defenses and made her feel want _ and love.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail (abate(at
sign)sfgate.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
