<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROJANS WILL TEST REBOUNDING GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PULLMAN, Wash. _ The research was completed late this week and
an already dubious accomplishment became a record. No USC team has
ever blown a 21-point second-half lead, so last week's 32-31 loss
to Cal was the biggest collapse ever suffered by the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the hard part.
</P>
<P>
   The reeling Trojans must overcome that demoralizing loss in the
hostile environment that is the Palouse, when they visit Washington
State tonight at 7:15.
</P>
<P>
   It will be chilly. It will be dark. It might be wet. And USC's
season likely hangs in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking forward to it. I've heard so many things,''
freshman quarterback Carson Palmer said. ``I talked to a couple
girls on the soccer team who were just up there. They said it's
terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer only said what most of the players are thinking, although
the Trojans have won their past four games in Pullman. Perhaps it
is more a question of whether the Trojans can forget the Cal loss
long enough to regain their morale against Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   USC (4-2, 2-1) appears to have gotten off to a nice start, but
last week's disaster has thrown everything _ including a bowl
appearance and the team's confidence _ into question.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident,'' Palmer said. ``We know we should have beat
Cal.''
</P>
<P>
   USC's final six games are considerably tougher than the first
six, and while Washington State (3-3, 0-3) might be struggling,
this isn't exactly a road-tested Trojans team. It enjoyed five of
its first six games at the Coliseum, with a trip to Florida State
the only time it left Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real crossroads game for us,'' USC coach Paul
Hackett said. ``How do we bounce back from what was a very
disappointing one-point loss? It will be a real benchmark game for
us in terms of how we respond to adversity. How does this team
respond to a tough situation?''
</P>
<P>
   Always trying to create an us-against-the-world mentality in
even good circumstances, Hackett actually didn't need to resort to
propaganda to assess the Trojans' current atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's buried us,'' Hackett said. ``The only way to put
it behind you is to play another game.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if it has to be at Washington State. And for the first
time, a game on artificial surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is their season. This is their bowl,'' Hackett said.
``This is a big game for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   That last statement is beyond dispute. The Trojans continue to
have the worst passing offense in the Pacific-10 Conference, and
now even the defense is coming under scrutiny. It has given up more
than 400 yards a game the past three contests and appeared to wear
down for the first time in last week's loss to California.
</P>
<P>
   It has been torched by Arizona State tailback J.R. Redmond (214
yards) and Cal wide receiver Dameane Douglas (13 receptions) the
past two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you evaluate the first half of the season, the strength of
the team is defense,'' Hackett said. ``We still believe we have a
good defense.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the offense, a lot could sway on how tailback Chad Morton
performs. Morton (bruised back) said he can play, but Hackett
doesn't want to make a final decision until kickoff. Even then, he
is worried that one hard hit on the artificial turf could aggravate
Morton's injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't play the game with Chad Morton, it's a different
game,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: With a close battle at center, Hackett had not decided
whether Eric Denmon or Matt McShane would start. ``Flip a coin,''
he said. Linebacker Mark Cusano (sore thigh) will play but
sophomore Zeke Moreno will start. Right guard Travis Claridge might
be forced to play some right tackle tonight if starter Ken Bowen
encounters any problems. The Trojans are shorthanded because Matt
Welch has mononucleosis and did not make the trip.
</P>
</TEXT>
