<HEADER>
A2261 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN     10-16 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE MAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ When Jaumal Bradley pulls off his shoulder
pads, his nicked, worn torso exposes the scars where bullets grazed
him and knives cut his flesh. His arms are big, strong and defined,
but there's a portion near the bicep he detests. Tattoos tell the
tale of his adolescent life. Markings of a gang.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his Cal State Northridge teammates know the story. Many
others don't ask because it's not really cool to ask.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, a junior running back making his first start tonight,
is particularly quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have time, I'll tell you all about it,'' Bradley was
saying. ``All about how I got here.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, with No. 16 CSUN not playing at Sacramento State
until 6:05 p.m., time was available. That's when Bradley embarked
on a doozy of a tale.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 14, I was involved in gangs,'' Bradley said. ``I
was committed to the California Youth Authority at age 15. I did 7{
years in the California Youth Authority. For gang involvement. I
started hangin' with the wrong crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the wrong place at the wrong time and I had to take
responsibility for that instead of telling on somebody. My natural
leadership ability showed but in a negative way.''
</P>
<P>
   He went from being a star at Gahr High in Cerritos to jail.
</P>
<P>
   At some point during his sentence, between race riots and
stabbings inside, Bradley said his isolation helped him develop
peace of mind.
</P>
<P>
   The day Bradley was released from jail he showed up at Mt. San
Antonio College in Walnut, a second-chance-type place where
football coach Bill Fisk accepts once-troubled kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was recommended as being a good, hard worker from someone I
know with the (California Youth Authority),'' Fisk said. ``They
didn't want him going back to his neighborhood. He called us and he
was a serious student and a serious athlete. He was either
studying, on the football field or in the weight room lifting when
he was here.''
</P>
<P>
   In 18 months, Bradley rose to captain of Mt. SAC's football team
and was an integral part of a national-championship team that went
13-0 last season. He also worked a pair of jobs _ busing tables and
parking cars _ while going to school and earning his associate's
degree with a 3.6 GPA.
</P>
<P>
   College recruiters believed he was reformed, and Fisk said some
high-profile programs inquired. But there was a catch. As part of
his sentence, he wasn't allowed to leave California before his 25th
birthday _ which isn't until January.
</P>
<P>
   So CSUN, which Bradley didn't even know about, became an option.
Then Bradley met first-year coach Ron Ponciano.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' Bradley said, ``I fell him love with coach Ponciano
the first day I saw him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano shares an equal fondness toward Bradley. Strong
practices and an extreme unselfishness pushed Bradley, who missed
spring ball because of ankle surgery, into the backfield mix. He
led CSUN with eight carries, which produced 21 yards, and had four
catches in last week's upset of Montana.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the most unselfish player I've been around, along with
(linebacker) Brennen Swanson,'' Ponciano said. ``When it's a bad
situation, he'll usually find something positive to say, and that's
a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley speaks from experience. He's seen the depths of race
riots in jail, of spending 23 hours a day in a 110-degree cell. He
does community speeches and serves not as an example to many of his
cousins.
</P>
<P>
   His good behavior since leaving jail prompted the California
Youth Authority to give him an early discharge, making him able to
leave the state.
</P>
<P>
   He has a 14-month-old daughter, Jaion, and is engaged to Tyna
Hall. He's also on track to graduate with a degree in urban studies
and is playing football for a ranked team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any pressures or problems right now. I'm free,''
Bradley said. ``I don't have any parole or probation or
restrictions at all. I have a 1-year-old daughter. I'm doing well
in school. We're winning. My life is fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
