<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981016.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2264 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GANG-CIRCLE17-COX     10-16 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GANG-CIRCLE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gangs may face Indian `circles'
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon and Angela Shah
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Three months after filing Texas' first gang
injunction, Travis County District Attorney Ronnie Earle is looking
to break more new ground, floating the idea of bringing neighbors
and accused criminals together in ``circles,'' a dispute resolution
technique borrowed from Native American tradition.
</P>
<P>
   And the five people targeted by the gang injunction _ a court
order that makes them subject to arrest for congregating in a
Northeast Austin neighborhood where they allegedly sold drugs _
could be among the first test cases.
</P>
<P>
   Earle's office has approached East Austin religious leaders as
well as the lawyers of the gang injunction defendants to discuss
the idea of having defendants, accompanied by people close to them,
sit down with neighbors and crime victims so everyone can talk
about how offenders can make amends to the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea here is to give the power back to the
neighborhood,'' Earle said. ``(Circles) are very effective in
holding offenders accountable in ways that the traditional criminal
justice system does not do.''
</P>
<P>
   Earle said circles were widely used by Native Americans and
other indigenous people around the world. In recent years, the idea
has caught on in the American criminal justice system. Earle said
he learned more about them from a judge from Canada's Yukon
Territory and later watched the circle process on a Minnesota
Indian reservation.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it would work: An accused criminal _ Earle said those
accused of drug and low-level property crimes like burglary would
be the best candidates _ would choose a family member or someone
close to them and meet with their victim or with residents from the
neighborhood where the crime was committed.
</P>
<P>
   Earle said a prosecutor would also be in the room, and judges,
probation officers or others familiar with the case could choose to
attend. The defendant could opt to bring his or her defense lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of a trial atmosphere, Earle said, each person would
speak in turn and say whatever he wanted. There would be no debate
or interruptions. The defendant and his representatives could
describe what kind of person he is and the circumstances
surrounding the incident. Victims could express their anger.
Neighbors could talk about how crimes affect their peace of mind.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant would have to accept responsibility for the crime,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then everyone involved would try to come to an agreement on the
proper punishment, Earle said. And that could be anything from
going back to school to some form of creative community service to
jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a consensus, we're going to follow the recommendation
of the circle'' and take that recommendation before a judge, Earle
said.
</P>
<P>
   Earle thinks going eyeball-to-eyeball with neighbors will make
more of an impression on offenders than another trip through the
revolving door of the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   And he's dangling the possibility before the defendants in the
gang injunction, who are currently under court order barring them
from hanging out together, loitering near pay phones, and other
activities in the area around Cameron Road and Broadmoor Drive in
Northeast Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The injunction is a civil action, not a criminal charge, and is
currently temporary. A full trial is scheduled for Nov. 9 before
District Judge Wil Flowers. The defendants have fought the
injunction, saying they are not gang members or drug dealers and
the action violates their civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Francis Williams, a defense lawyer representing defendant Percy
Prejean _ who is in jail after having his probation on a drug
charge revoked _ said he plans to recommend that Prejean
participate in the circle if Earle can pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than having Big Brother take care of the problems, the
community takes care of the problem, and I like that,'' Williams
said. ``If (Earle's office) had come up with this before violating
everybody's rights and trampling on the Constitution, we would have
said, `That Ronnie Earle is really innovative, we support him.'''
</P>
<P>
   The other lawyers have not decided whether to participate, said
Ann Del Llano, president of the American Civil Liberties Union
local chapter and a lawyer for Shang Yahoshua, another of the
injunction defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Del Llano said she became very interested in the circle idea
after Earle's office started talking about reduced sentences for
two pending drug charges if Yahoshua participates in a circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start talking like that, people come to the table in
a hurry,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Earle declined to comment on how the circles would affect the
injunction or specific criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Austin police officer Darryl Jamail, who patrols Northeast
Austin, said he is skeptical that an agreement forged at a meeting
would keep the alleged drug dealers away from the target
neighborhood for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deal with (the defendants) every day and I see the attitude
of `I'm going to break the law anyway,' '' Jamail said. ``If it
doesn't have teeth in it, I don't think this is a good option.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamail said the temporary injunction granted by Flowers in
August is working well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very noticeable difference,'' he said, ``and without
the drug dealers out there you don't have the buyers creating
traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Rotter, a long-time resident of the nearby Pecan Springs
neighborhood who has worked with police and prosecutors to fight
crime in Northeast Austin, said he is also skeptical, but willing
to try.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the fact that they are gang members in the first
place, I wonder about their sincerity,'' Rotter said. ``They don't
really care how their activities affect other people who live
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I will come if it'll make a difference,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
