</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES AIM TO DERAIL YANKEE EXPRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He is the American League batting champion for the
winningest team in American League history. He plays center field
in the baseball capital of the world. But ask the New York Yankees'
Bernie Williams about his season, and he pauses, digesting it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get so caught up in thinking, `Do, do, accomplish, goals,
let's go, do it, do it,' that we sometimes lose sight of what we
have done,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   What Williams and the Yankees have done this year is astounding.
An AL-record 114 wins, a sweep in the Division Series and a
six-game victory in the American League Championship have brought
them to their 35th World Series and second in three years.
</P>
<P>
   The first was a celebration for an underdog team that knocked
off the defending champion Atlanta Braves. This one, against the
San Diego Padres, sets up as a vindication of their seasonlong
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '96, we weren't supposed to win,'' said shortstop Derek
Jeter. ``This year, we're supposed to win. That's the biggest
difference. Everyone expected us to get here, but we expected us to
get here, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great season, no matter what happens. I don't think
(losing) would make our season a failure, but it would be a huge
disappontment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres, making their first World Series appearance since
1984, are certainly a worthy foe. No Series ever has pitted two
teams with more combined victories than this one. The Yankees and
Padres won 212 regular-season games, two better than the Orioles
and Reds in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is New York, and the Yankees are a team so
decorated, they already have a set of rings from 1998. Those came
courtesy of pitcher and part-time jeweler David Wells, who had
rings made up for his teammates after his perfect game in May.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, who opposes Kevin Brown in Game 1 of the 94th World
Series Saturday night, showed imperfect judgment on Thursday,
declaring on Howard Stern's radio show that the Yankees would beat
the Padres in five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``BALK RADIO,'' teased the Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   ``YANKS IN FIVE!'' chirped the Post.
</P>
<P>
   As New Yorker Billy Joel might chime in, ``You had to be a big
shot, didn't you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``For the people out there, no, I am not predicting anything in
five,'' said Wells, who explained he was mostly trying to get Stern
to move on to another topic. ``I think San Diego is an outstanding
team, and I don't think it is fair to myself, my teammates or
anybody else out there, even the Padres, to predict anything like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   If recent history is a barometer, Wells probably will be wrong
anyway. The last six World Series all have lasted at least six
games, a streak unsurpassed in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres, underdogs in beating the Houston Astros and the
Braves en route to the pennant, are making just their second World
Series appearance. The first was in 1984, when San Diego lost _
yes, in five _ to a Detroit Tigers team that won 104 regular-season
games. These Yankees are the only AL team since then to post more
victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (World Series) was something that the city always has
talked about since, because we don't have the great tradition of
the Yankees where it happens all the time,'' said Padres third base
coach Tim Flannery, who played for the '84 team. ``That was our
year. We had come from behind in dramatic fashion to beat the Cubs
to get to the World Series to face an incredibly talented Detroit
team who was destined to win everything that year.
</P>
<P>
   `` ... But if you're asking me if I think we're going to get our
(butts) kicked by these guys like we did against the Detroit
Tigers, we don't look at it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ignore that smiling, swinging Friar mascot, and there's
not much about the Padres that looks out of place in this setting.
They have a bona fide ace in Brown, a Hall of Famer in Gwynn, a
50-home run bopper in Greg Vaughn, a Gold Glover and former MVP at
third base in Ken Caminiti and baseball's premier closer, Trevor
Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   They're also battle-tested. Eleven Padres were on playoff teams
before arriving in San Diego, and eight others have prior
experience with the Padres, who lost in the Division Series two
years ago. This is a team assembled for this stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``What separates teams when they get to this arena is experience
above the shoulders,'' said Padres general manager Kevin Towers.
``You have to have talent to get here, but sometimes youth and
inexperience overcome you. A team like this is not in awe of
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but this, unmistakably, is New York, home to 49 World
Series. When the Yankees host their 35th starting Saturday night,
baseball will feel right at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be wild,'' Jeter said. ``It's like a Broadway
play, center stage. The World Series seems like it only should be
played in New York.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
