<SLUG> BC-CAR-MARK-MARTIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARK MARTIN, DRIVEN TO SUCCEED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Mark Martin says there is perhaps only one
way left for him to overhaul Jeff Gordon and win the 1998 NASCAR
Winston Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we can win it except by default. Like, if he
\RGordon\S got hurt,'' Martin said. ``And I don't want to win it
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   At the tail end of the self-described greatest season of his
racing career, victory by default will not cut it for the
obsessive/compulsive Martin. Nor would it have set well with Julian
Martin, Mark's father, who was killed in a plane crash Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   His relentless pursuit of Gordon for what would be Martin's
first Cup championship has been juxtaposed against a similarly
determined effort to learn what caused the twin-engined plane
piloted by his father to go down. The crash, near the Great Basin
National Park in Nevada, also took the lives of Julian's wife and
Mark's stepmother, Shelley, and their daughter, Sarah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to know what got my hero,'' Martin said of his
father, who was 62 and an accomplished pilot. ``He was nicknamed in
the '70s `The Cat,' because he had to have had nine lives to live
through the '70s. And he went \Rdied\S in the late '90s, if that
tells you how many times he cheated death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to know what happened to him.''
</P>
<P>
   These have been the issues vying for Martin's undivided
attention this summer _ another race of one-on-one against Gordon;
another day alone with the memories of his fallen hero.
</P>
<P>
   Martin will start sixth tonight in the historic, inaugural
nighttime running of the Pepsi 400 at Daytona International
Speedway, 288 points behind Gordon with four races remaining.
Martin dropped 114 huge points to Gordon at the Winston 500 last
week at Talladega Superspeedway in Alabama, and the consequences of
another plate-race scrape cannot be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do the math,'' said Martin, twice a runner-up this decade in
points chases involving seven-time champion Dale Earnhardt.
``Assuming that nothing goes wrong for us, and everything in the
world went upside down for them \RGordon and his crew\S, then the
race would be on. That's not much of a way to look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   With a career-high seven victories and 23 top-10 finishes in 29
starts, Martin has spent 1998 typically _ as he is fond of
describing it _ racing his guts out. But Gordon, the series
champion in 1995 and 1997, has maintained the top spot he assumed
after the Save Mart/Kragen 350 at Sears Point Raceway 14 races ago.
Gordon, who has a series-high 10 victories, has won seven of the
past 14 races and finished in the top five in the other seven.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, the cornerstone of team owner Jack Roush's five-car
stable, is the only driver to rank among the top 10 in the final
Winston Cup points standings from 1989-1997. That is nine
consecutive years that have been very good, but not good enough to
hoist the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might not be as good as Jeff Gordon. Maybe I shouldn't win a
championship,'' said Martin, 39. ``And I'm man enough to say it. I
won't measure myself against that. I won't measure myself against
how many championships I win. I've won a lot of races \R29 total\S.
That's important to me. I've been fairly successful. And I have a
decent amount of respect throughout the garage.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's single-mindedness about racing might have gotten him
past the initial shock of the fatal plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   He learned of the accident after he had run second, naturally,
to Gordon on the road course at Watkins Glen, N.Y. The next Friday,
Martin qualified the No. 6 Valvoline Ford Taurus fifth at Michigan
Speedway. On race day, he finished fourth and more or less berated
himself after the race for not delivering a victory in memory of
his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was amazed at the focus he was able to give that weekend,''
said Jeff Burton, driver of the No. 99 Exide Batteries Ford and
Martin's team for Roush Racing. ``That made such an impression on
me _ and some people criticized him for that. I can't figure that
out. Everybody deals with things differently. And it would have
made Julian Martin mad for Mark not to run in that event. Mark
knows that. That comes with maturity.''
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup team owner Bill Davis, a longtime Martin family
friend, said Mark is in many respects a carbon copy of his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything they do, they've got to do it the best, the
hardest,'' said Davis, who got to know Mark through their fathers'
involvement in the trucking business in Arkansas. ``From drinking
to driving fast to staying up partying all night to running trucks
to race cars, it didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what a tough deal. Mark is having his greatest year ever
of racing and his dad isn't here to share it with him. I know
that's the hardest thing for him, because Julian dedicated his life
to Mark and to Mark's career in racing.''
</P>
<P>
   After Martin won the UAW-GM Quality 500 at Charlotte Motor
Speedway this month, Roush promised Martin that he would be part of
a championship with his team _ either as driver or participant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of things we're going to do beyond the time
when Mark drives these cars,'' Roush said. ``Mark is a great
championship driver. I've raced in many series for over 30 years
and I've never raced with anybody that has a better nose for
accumulating points and keeping his car out of harm's way than
Mark.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
