</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERFECT STAGE FOR GWYNN'S FIRST YANKEE STADIUM VISIT: GAME 1 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No one has ever called Tony Gwynn ``Mr. October.''
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, on the eve of the 1998 World Series, the man who has
played the sometimes-less-than-desirable role of ``Mr. Padre'' with
so much class for 16 seasons got his first look inside the place
where Octobers, and Mr. October, live eternal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've flown over Yankee Stadium. We've driven by it in a bus. I
mean, I had a cab take me here. I was going to Shea Stadium but he
took me here instead, so I've never been in the Stadium. Seen it
from TV. Seen it from the outside, but I'd never been in it,'' said
Gwynn, whose National League career has never once brought him to
the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Now, his first-ever game here will be Game 1 of the World
Series. And just to build the drama, Gwynn took the subway up from
Manhattan for Friday's workout. Gwynn got off the train, walked
right out to center field and into hallowed Monument Hall _ just to
give his inaugural visit a touch of the epic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really big,'' was how Gwynn described his first trip
inside big, white castle _ home of all the old Yankee legends and
ghosts, not to mention the current residence of the ubiquitous
owner, George Steinbrenner, and his $70 million band of American
League champs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to imagine what it was like when they were playing.
Babe Ruth and Joe DiMaggio and Lou Gehrig. But still, when you come
in by the train, you don't realize it's right in the
neighborhood,'' Gwynn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting off the subway, I was coming down the stairs thinking
there's a store right there and people are walking by it like it's
no big deal and I'm like: `There's Yankee Stadium.' And people are
looking at me like `What's the matter with him?'''
</P>
<P>
   Ballparks are not just ballparks. And all ball clubs are not
created equal. Tony Gwynn knows all of this.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and the Padres are as different as Big Apple and
California Sunkist oranges. More different, in fact. The Yankee
media guide says here that starting Saturday night, when Game 1
begins in the House That Ruth Built, the Bombers will be playing in
their 35th Fall Classic. They have won 23 times.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres, at last count, had appeared in all of one World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we got smoked,'' said Gwynn, whose first full season was
in 1984, when the Tigers ran all over the Padres _ a World Series
experience that bequethed not one shred of greatness to the Padre
franchise's ``legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing Gwynn remembers about '84, besides losing, is
Kirk Gibson standing on the field at Tiger Stadium, screaming at
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was like, `This is Detroit! This is a real baseball field!'
I was like, `OK, I didn't even have anything to do with the first
two games,''' Gwynn said.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson and the Tigers went on to win three straight at Tiger
Stadium, whipping Gwynn and the Padres, who had no ammunition to
combat the ghosts and rabid fans of Tiger Stadium, not to mention
the fire-throwing arm of Tiger pitcher Jack Morris. Like the
114-win Yankees they meet Saturday night, the Tigers were the best
in baseball that year.
</P>
<P>
   The '84 ouster did nothing to alter the perception that the
Padres were a quirky Southern California team with the hideous
brown uniforms and absolutely no tradition, no history. Gwynn, the
eternal good humor man, can laugh at all the nonsense associated
with his team.
</P>
<P>
   Like how once, former Padres owner _ McDonald's baron Ray Kroc _
was so angry and humiliated after a four-error loss, Kroc got on
the public address system and offered a refund to fans who stayed
to watch the nine-inning disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Another time, former general manager Buzzy Bavasi was caught
flipping the bird to fans after a game. Bavasi tried to deny it,
but TV cameras had caught Bavasi's bird in full glory.
</P>
<P>
   And Gwynn was there, standing on the steps of the dugout at Jack
Murphy Stadium, the night Roseanne Barr sang that twisted version
of the ``Star Spangled Banner.'' It was an act of patriotic
sacrilege so awful, so ridiculous, but so Padre-esque, even Gywnn
could not keep a straight face.
</P>
<P>
   As for team records? Postseason glory? World Series? On that
subject, Gwynn is a little more sanguine. Here at the Stadium, even
Gwynn understands the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we have five World Series games to our credit and Mickey
Mantle alone hit something like 18 postseason homers. Our history
is Kurt Bavecqua going to the plate, going deep and blowing kisses
to the crowd. That's what you're fighting against. Look at the
stuff associated with us. It's not positive,'' Gwynn said.
</P>
<P>
   But this time around, starting Saturday, Gwynn believes the
Padres can take an important step toward turning some heads and
altering perceptions.
</P>
<P>
   He will always have his own amazing successes _ his annual
flirtation with being baseball's next .400 hitter; his eight league
batting titles, 13 All-Star appearances and five Gold Gloves.
</P>
<P>
   But starting today, right in the heart of the Bronx, in the
belly of the beast of Yankee Stadium, Gwynn is looking for
something big to happen not to him, but his franchise, which has a
new ownership and a new demeanor and, possibly, a new waterfront
ballpark on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compare us on paper, we've got no chance,'' Gwynn said. ``But
in between the white lines, you never know. You can't get caught up
in the fact that you're here. They've been in 35 World Series.
We've been in two. But we're going to win. I realize who we're
playing and who we're going against and how difficult it's going to
be, but both sides want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, Mr. Padre seemed inspired by all these Yankee ghosts,
all this Yankee tradition dripping with history. Mr. Padre would
not mind if some of that old Mr. October magic rubbed off this
autumn.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
