<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONIMALS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FURRY `MONIMALS' COSTUMES FOR COMPUTERS STAMPEDE OFF STORE
SHELVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN SIDENER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. _ They're furry. They're useless. And they're
stampeding off of store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale's Go-Video is marketing Monimals, furry costumes that
dress up a computer monitor as a cow, sheep, moose or lion. The
effect is enhanced by a screen saver that adds an animated face and
sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get some black and white fur with horns, a cow face
staring at you, chewing its cud,'' said Dan Halaburda, director of
sales/special markets for Go-Video. ``It's just a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   If a cud-chewing cow doesn't float your boat, try the antlered
moose with a shy streak, who runs off into the woods to hide behind
trees; or the cowardly lion who trembles before a mouse; or the
sheep who jump fences and might be therapeutic for insomniac
computer users.
</P>
<P>
   Monimals cost $24.95 for a 14-inch or 15-inch monitor, and
$26.95 for a 17-inch monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Go Video is the exclusive U.S. distributor for the ``funware''
product, which marks a departure from its core product line of
dual-deck VCRs.
</P>
<P>
   Monimals were dreamed up in London. The exclusive U.S.
dealership was offered to Go-Video through a mutual friend.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the early sales of Monimals have come from word-of-mouth
advertising, Halaburda said. The company introduced Monimals in
August, but has not yet begun a full-scale marketing campaign.
Go-Video displayed the product at last week's Fall Internet World
trade show in New York, where it was a crowd favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sales have been very good,'' Halaburda said. ``And we haven't
even begun to crank up the official PR machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Go-Video figured the furry computer accessory would sell well to
schools and parents. A silly face lift might make technology less
intimidating, they reasoned.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not where the hot sales have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's staggering the number of adults who are buying them for
themselves,'' Halaburda said. ``I never knew so many people out
there collected cows. And pigs are hot. We've got to come out with
a pig.''
</P>
<P>
   Go-Video is already looking at several possible expansions of
the Monimal line. Companies might want to add their logo to give
them to customers. And college and other sports mascots could add
many other potential characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of school mascots,'' Halaburda said. ``We
might have to come out with a Sparky the Sun Devil.''
</P>
<P>
   The firm has sold 20,000 of the fuzzy computer accessories to
date and officials are almost giddy over the prospect of having one
of the hot gifts of the Christmas season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope so,'' Halaburda said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope it's the next pet rock.'' &QL; 
Jonathan Sidener can be reached at 444-8169 or at
jon.sidener(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-16-98 2308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
