<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSE BOWL BRACES FOR SHOOTOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Two months ago, it sounded silly. Now, not so
silly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to one of my friends on Oregon (tailback Derien
Latimer),'' UCLA quarterback Cade McNown recalled. ``And he said at
the beginning of the season, `We're going to win the national
championship.' I thought, `Wow, they have high ambitions.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But so far, he's on the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, No. 11 Oregon is one of the nation's biggest surprises
entering today's showdown against No. 2 UCLA at the Rose Bowl,
where the teams might score as many points in 60 minutes as some
score in an entire season. Combined, they're averaging 98.6 per
game _ and there's nothing normal about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be scoreless,'' said Washington State coach Mike
Price, who's faced both teams this season.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will there be a shortage of individual talent, especially in
green and yellow. Oregon quarterback Akili Smith leads the nation
in passing and might be the best athlete UCLA faces all season.
Ducks tailback Reuben Droughns leads the Pac-10 in rushing and has
with three 200-yard games. The receivers, Damon Griffin and Tony
Hartley, average eight catches and 160 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks have smashed all comers _ home and road, conference
and nonconference _ and done so more impressively than UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave the game to UCLA,'' Price said of a 49-17 loss two
weeks ago, in which the Cougars committed four turnovers. ``We
didn't to Oregon. The Ducks can score on anybody and they'll score
on UCLA.''
</P>
<P>
   The flaw in Price's argument is competition. Whereas UCLA proved
its worth last week at Arizona, the Ducks have faced a slew of
stiffs _ including Stanford, San Jose State, Texas-El Paso and
Michigan State. Oregon has also been unable to stop the run,
allowing 154.5 yards per game, seventh in the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   Either the Ducks can't stop the run or they were so far ahead
they didn't try. The answer comes today.
</P>
<P>
   The plot figures to follow one of two courses. Perhaps it'll be
the shootout most expect _ a last-possession-wins circus, 52-48,
45-42, something like that.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps the defenses will make a surprise appearance, keep
the score in the 30s and let turnovers decide.
</P>
<P>
   For those expecting 100 points, consider the relationships
involved: UCLA coach Bob Toledo was Oregon's offensive coordinator
from 1983-88, and Bruins playcaller Al Borges held the same post
with Oregon in 1995. UCLA defensive coordinator Nick Aliotti was
just that with the Ducks from 1988-94; he remains extremely close
to Oregon head coach Mike Bellotti and attended UC Davis with
several Ducks coaches.
</P>
<P>
   What it means is this: The offensive systems are almost
identical. What the defenses face today, they face each day in
practice. Fewer adjustments are required. Recognition _ of
formations, blocking schemes and pass patterns _ is high. Some of
the plays are !ital!exactly!off! the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot like what we do here,'' Aliotti said. ``That can't
hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   What of the respective psyches? Can UCLA recreate the emotion it
used in Tucson? Last Friday night's meeting, which ended in tears
and a group hug, is not easily repeated. Hoping to grab his
players' attention, Toledo gave a brief history lesson after
practice Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mention the 1988 team (ranked No.1), which was ahead of
Washington State 28-3 at halftime and lost 31-28 because it didn't
play four quarters,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have played in games of this magnitude, both last
year and this. More, they've been behind and kept their poise,
trailing Arizona four times before breaking the game open in the
fourth quarter. But the Ducks have done neither. This is their
first game on grass and their first game in the glare of postseason
importance since the 1994 Rose Bowl run.
</P>
<P>
   The sky-high Smith has had trouble sleeping this week, so
excited is he about duelling McNown. Droughns, from Anaheim, and
Griffin, from Monrovia, have craved the chance to perform with
friends and families in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing paralyzes a team like sensory overload. And what if the
Ducks fall behind?
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players are hungry to gain respect,'' Bellotti said.
``We'll have plenty of emotion involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe too much.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
