<HEADER>
A2361 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-2NDLD-     10-16 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER BUDGET DEAL, IT'S TIME TO WRITE THE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (subs to recast story, primarily in its first half; also some new
details)  
 (ATTN: Ind., Miss., Ohio, La., Texas, Ga.)  (See also CONGRESS-PORN, CONGRESS-CLINTON, CONGRESS-SURPLUS) 
(bl) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A day after celebrating a much-delayed agreement on
a final federal budget package, Congress did not have a budget bill
in place to vote on and postponed Friday's planned action on the
$500 billion deal until next week.
</P>
<P>
   With just 17 days until the midterm elections, most lawmakers
fled the capital for their campaigns at home, with some of them
grousing about excessive spending, numerous details still
unresolved and much of the bill still unwritten.
</P>
<P>
   Some conservatives, mainly in the House, were upset with some of
the bill's major provisions, like the use of part of the surplus
for a $20 billion supplemental package for so-called emergencies
like extra military spending and solving the Year 2000 computer
problem, and with the absence of a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Congress cannot vote on the budget until the bill's final
language is drafted, which no one has had time to do since
top-level negotiators agreed Thursday afternoon on the broad
outlines. The vote, which was expected Friday, was put off and, for
the fifth time since the Oct. 1 start of the fiscal year, Congress
had to arrange more temporary financing to keep the government
running.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of top-level bargainers _ including House Speaker
Newt Gingrich, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott and White House
chief of staff Erskine Bowles _ were in the room for the final
deal. Excluded were the committee chairmen and the heads of the
appropriation committees, who are now trying to write the precise
language of the bill, which could run more than 3,000 pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a bunch of free-thinkers in the room,'' said one
top congressional aide.
</P>
<P>
   The details that remained to be nailed down, and written, ranged
from precisely how to spend $6 billion in aid to farmers to how to
respond to people with an allergy to peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich and other members from Georgia, a major
peanut-producing state, are trying to block a Transportation
Department regulation that would force airlines to create a
``peanut-free'' zone to protect passengers with allergies. The
regulation would prevent peanuts from being served within three
rows of such passengers on domestic flights.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has nothing to do with federal spending, but the
spending bill is the last opportunity in this session of Congress
for members to have their special provisions addressed.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked into the budget agreement is a measure that would
restrict children's access to pornography on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The lag time before the bill is officially closed is making some
conservatives nervous that more members will try to add provisions
that will further expand a bill they already consider overly
bloated, and that few will have time to read. And some worry that
once the hometown pork that is stuffed into the bill is publicly
revealed, voters could put pressure on their elected
representatives not to support it.
</P>
<P>
   To stay within its spending limits for a balanced budget,
Congress or the president can designate something an emergency
without having to pay for it by cutting from other programs. That
means, in effect, that they would be using money from this year's
anticipated $70 billion surplus to pay for such so-called
emergencies, which may or may not meet the definition of a one-time
unforeseen disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives, who are concerned chiefly about busting the
budget, questioned the agreement to use the surplus for the
president's $10 billion for ``emergencies'' like dealing with the
computer bug and the Republicans' $9 billion, much of it for
military hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, virtually everyone on Capitol Hill expected the
budget to pass _ eventually.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rep. Mark Souder, R-Ind., said: `Most of my friends, who are
predominantly activist conservatives, are split about 50-50. If tax
cuts were your primary thing, then you're unhappy, but many
conservatives have a mixed agenda. My position is, hold the nose
and vote yes. We have no tax cuts and far too much spending that I
oppose, but that's the nature of compromise. Every member has a
little different focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Souder said he liked the extra money for defense spending, and
he liked the price supports for farmers. Hog farmers in his
district, whose biggest customers were Japan and China, had been
hit hard by the collapse of Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republicans said the bill seemed skewed in favor of the
Democrats. They cited two reasons: Clinton needed to curry favor
with Democrats to shore up support if the House votes to impeach
him, and Republican leaders feared that if they had stood up to
Clinton, they might have forced a government shutdown and
Republicans would be blamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton was buying votes,'' said Rep. David Hobson, R-Ohio.
``He was sucking up to the liberal Democrats so they would support
him in impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. W.J. (Billy) Tauzin, R-La., said the leaders seemed
motivated by a desire to avoid the political damage they incurred
from the partial government shutdowns of 1995 and 1996. He also
cited the president's need to placate the left by adding costly
domestic programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination of the lessons learned three years ago and the
scandal on the president's side yielded the inevitable result, a
budget that leans way to the left,'' Tauzin said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said he would probably support the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be enthusiastically,'' he said. ``I think we would
have gotten a tax cut, but for the scandal. If the president had
not been caught up with the scandal, he probably would have
followed the Dick Morris strategy and moved towards the center.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said he recognized that some conservatives were wary of
the agreement. But he sought to reassure them that the package
served their interests.
</P>
<P>
   He cited the increase in defense spending. And he noted that the
Republicans had blocked several items, including needle-exchange
programs in the District of Columbia, national education testing
and U.S. contributions to a United Nations program that pays for
family planning in China, which many in Congress object to because
China has a policy of coercing abortions and forcing sterilization.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said the agreement was the best that could be achieved
``when you have a conservative Republican Congress and a liberal
Democratic President.''
</P>
<P>
   A few remained outright hostile to the bill, as much for the
hasty way in which it was cobbled together as for what it
contained.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Barton, R-Texas, said: `I'm voting no unless something
revolutionary happens between now and Tuesday. I think it's the
process that gives the president the ability to stonewall until the
very end and then hold us for ransom. The Republican leadership in
the House and Senate did a good job of limiting the highway
robbery, but it's still gone too far beyond the spending caps.''
</P>
<P>
   Also angry at the rushed endgame was Rep. Gene Taylor, D-Miss.,
who took to the House floor and said he could not support the final
bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to urge my colleagues to vote no,'' Taylor said.
``We have stayed here this long. We can stay a little bit longer.
And I am going to encourage my colleagues to continue to vote no
until we are given adequate time to study the measure that is
brought before us, and then and only then should we be making a
decision for over hundreds of billions of dollars worth of
programs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
