<SLUG> BC-BBO--BLINEBURY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Don't dismiss Padres in New York minute
<TEXT>
<P>
   By FRAN BLINEBURY &QL; 
Houston Chronicle &QL; 
NEW YORK _ So much for low-key.
</P>
<P>
   David Wells said it probably would take the Yankees five games
to finish off the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   He said it less than defiantly. ``Oooh, five,'' was Wells'
response the other morning when prodded for a prediction on the
nationally syndicated Howard Stern radio show.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Stern is as neat a fit with baseball as George Will
with the Crips or the Bloods. So other than the blaring front-page
headlines of New York tabloids, nobody gave it much thought.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager Joe Torre shrugs. That's Boomer.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees center fielder Bernie Williams shrugs. That's Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees fans from the Bowery to the Bronx shrug. That's Wells.
</P>
<P>
   With Game 1 of the World Series tonight, a great deal of
shrugging is going on in the Big Apple. Most of it in the direction
of the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   After all, San Diego is not the team (Braves) that compiled the
best record in the National League this season and is not even the
team (Astros) with the better record in its NL Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   What the Padres do not have is a supposed Hall of Fame pitching
staff and a self-proclaimed pedigree as the ``Team of the '90s,''
like Atlanta. What the Padres do not have is a monster everyday
lineup with a bunch of .300 hitters and 100-run producers, like the
Astros.
</P>
<P>
   What the Padres do have is one thing: A chance. No more, no
less.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a fitting climax
</P>
<P>
   After two rounds of the American League playoffs, where they
were barely challenged by the Rangers and Indians, this is at least
a change and gives us hope the 94th World Series can live up to all
of the wonderful events in the magical season that preceded it.
</P>
<P>
   There was the gripping summer of the home-run chase with Mark
McGwire and Sammy Sosa crashing past Roger Maris and history. There
was the voluntary end to Cal Ripken Jr.'s consecutive-games streak
at 2,632. There was a rookie fireballer named Kerry Wood blazing
onto the scene with a record-tying 20 strikeouts in a game against
the Astros. And there was, at long last, a figurative hug, an
embrace by American fans of the grand old game after years of
bitterness that followed the last baseball strike.
</P>
<P>
   What the game needs to top off a dream season is a World Series
that lives up to the hype as the Fall Classic and, strange as it
might sound, by pitting the storied Yankees and tradition-barren
Padres, this could be it.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. If it had been a New York-Atlanta series, the
two teams that have won one World Series title each in this decade
could have decided once and for all which is the true ``Team of the
'90s.'' But a matchup between the deep pockets of George
Steinbrenner vs. the deep pockets of Ted Turner also would have
reinforced the notion that championships are for sale only to the
highest bidder with the highest, most star-studded profiles.
</P>
<P>
   Now here come the Padres, out of the bottom left corner of the
map, with a collection of grizzled, scrappy veteran hitters, an ace
in Kevin Brown and the unlikeliest of NLCS MVP's in Sterling
Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   Three flukes and you're champs
</P>
<P>
   Was it just a fluke the 98-win Padres beat the 102-win Astros?
Was it another fluke they also beat the 106-win Braves? Well, if
that's the case, then who says flukes can't come in threes with the
114-win Yankees next?
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees should win. They probably will. But it would not be
wise to dismiss a team that is full of momentum and confidence and
has beaten Randy Johnson (twice), Tom Glavine (twice) and Greg
Maddux to get here.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Yankees' previous playoff opponents, Texas and
Cleveland, the Padres have a legitimate ace in Brown, who has given
up just two runs in three postseason starts. He also has a career
record of 12-3 and a 2.50 ERA against the Yankees from his AL days.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres also have a lefty starter in Hitchcock, who has
developed a full repertoire of pitches to go with his forkball
since leaving New York a few years back and developed confidence.
Hitchcock beat Glavine and Maddux in the Atlanta series and the
Yankees, historically, have had more trouble with lefties.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres also have a go-to guy at the plate in Jim Leyritz.
Greg Vaughn, Tony Gwynn and Ken Caminiti have hobbled through the
playoffs; Leyritz, the former Yankee, has carried them with his big
stick.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, they seem overmatched. In the win column, they look to
be in too deep.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres shrug. In this season of baseball history and magic,
all it takes is a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to Fran Blinebury on the Sports Page radio show on KPRC
(950 AM) from 5-7 p.m. weekdays. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
