<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2364 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA--CLEMENS-HNS &LR;      10-16 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA--CLEMENS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Clemens shares baseball, life with sixth-graders
<TEXT>
<P>
   By ALAN TRUEX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL; 
``My name is Roger Clemens and they call me the Rocket.''
</P>
<P>
   With that self-introduction, the All-Star pitcher of the Toronto
Blue Jays began an interview session Friday at Spring Branch Middle
School _ just four miles from where Clemens lived as a child.
</P>
<P>
   A commanding presence at 6-4 and 230 solid pounds, Clemens
passed out autographed baseball cards and then stood in front of a
sixth-grade class, which included his son Koby, and held up a
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever heard bacon sizzle? That's what this sounds like when I
let it go.''
</P>
<P>
   He demonstrated pitching grips and talked baseball, but mostly
he provided lessons on life. His might be easy now as an $8
million-a-year pitcher, but it was difficult in his childhood. His
father died when he was 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in our basement, and he had a heart attack and an
ambulance came, and I didn't know what was going on,'' he told the
boys and girls in the language arts class of Liz Laconis. ``It was
a very traumatic time for me at a young age. My grades might have
suffered a little after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times when I got detention hall and bad grades. I
got picked on; people messed with my locker.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, 36, was being filmed for ESPN's Conversation in the
Classroom, which will air at 6:30 p.m. Friday. The concept is
children act as reporters, interviewing a pro athlete.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Spring Branch pupils asked Clemens if he knows Randy
Johnson, the Astros' pitcher who is about to become a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I know Randy,'' Clemens said. ``I hope he wants to stay
here and play. He may or he may not.''
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson goes elsewhere, the Astros could trade for Clemens,
who is expected to win an unprecedented fifth Cy Young Award after
claiming the American League's triple crown by leading the AL in
victories (20), ERA (2.65) and strikeouts (271).
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always the possibility I might play here,'' Clemens
said. ``There's a possibility of new ownership in Toronto in the
next month, and we'll have to see what they do with the budget,
which way they're going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   His contract has two years remaining, but an escape clause
allows him to force a trade if he believes the Blue Jays are not
trying to compete for a pennant next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to win in Toronto,'' Clemens said. ``But if that
doesn't happen, my first choice would not be to go to a powerhouse
like New York, which is always going to be competitive, and is
further from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather go to the Texas Rangers or to Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   After starting slowly this season, the Jays rallied with a 34-18
finish for an overall 88-74 record: good, but not good enough for
the postseason, which is where Clemens wants to be.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to spend as much time as possible with his wife,
Debbie, his high school sweetheart at Spring Woods, and their four
boys: Koby, Kory, Kasey and Kody.
</P>
<P>
   One of the students asked Clemens why his children have names
beginning with K. ``That's what you write down in the scorebook
when it's a strikeout,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Family time is precious when dad plays baseball for a Canadian
team. The children spend the summer in Toronto, but during the
school year the boys are in Houston most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss the opportunity to go home and see them,'' Clemens
said. ``We try as a family not to go more than two weeks without
getting together. Sometimes Koby might get out of school on a
Thursday so he can see me, and we'll get him a tutor.''
</P>
<P>
   He was asked about his musical tastes. He prefers top-40 rock,
and country, but the music in the Blue Jays' locker room varies
because it's chosen by that game's starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have pitchers who like to blast heavy metal, and we've got
guys from the Dominican Republic who play their music,'' Clemens
said. ``When it's my turn I might play rock to get people in a good
mood, and some days I'll play country to get them to relax.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he ever ``gets mad at the umpires,'' Clemens
laughed and said, ``OK, cut the tape.''
</P>
<P>
   He has a painful memory of the 1990 AL Championship Series, when
he was ejected for foul language that offended plate umpire Terry
Cooney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty keyed up out there and I've gotten in trouble for
letting my emotions get the best of me,'' Clemens said.
</P>
<P>
   He warned the children that they too will suffer anxieties and
face ``a lot of tough calls.'' He said he ``lost three or four
close buddies in high school'' because they ``tried to drag me
down'' into drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time I was in the back seat of a guy's car, and I made him
let me out of the car,'' Clemens said, ``because they were doing
some things I knew they'd get in big trouble for.''
</P>
<P>
   He has seen promising careers destroyed by players who couldn't
resist temptations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next thing you know, they're out of the big leagues, and
they're saying, `I could have been a great baseball player,''' he
said. ``You don't want to look back on middle school or high school
and say, `I could have done this and I could have done that.'
You've got to try to be the best you can be now.''
</P>
<P>
   He was asked if he is going to win the Cy Young Award that goes
to the best pitcher in each major league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope so,'' he said. ``I said last year it was great to win
my fourth Cy Young Award so I could give one to each of my boys and
they could put it in their own house some day and remember all the
hard work their dad did to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   The many hours of weightlifting, the many miles of running have
contributed to 233 wins and remarkable durability for a power
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have fun playing the game,'' Clemens told the
sixth-graders. ``I like to hear you guys cheering and clapping when
I have two strikes on a big hitter and I'm trying to strike him
out.''
</P>
<P>
   When the time comes to retire, Clemens said he ``will do a lot
of work in the community and stay involved with kids like you.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rocket seems a long way from burning out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
