<HEADLINE>
CSUN WELCOMES BACK DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Derrick Higgins won't take a charge in a pickup
game. That's suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from that, he'll do anything defensively to stop his
opponent. It's an attitude more than an approach. One that was
lacking for Cal State Northridge's men's basketball team the moment
Higgins broke his right foot in the Matadors' fifth game last year.
</P>
<P>
   And an attitude Higgins will bring into today's first official
practice as Division I teams across the country break out the
basketballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word `defense' is secondary to everyone now,'' said
Higgins, a 6-foot-3, senior guard. ``You have to have the crossover
and dribble between the legs and the reverse dunk. You can get all
that, but my first priority is to get the ball back.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no coincidence CSUN allowed seven more points per game last
year than during the 1996-97 season. The Matadors, who went 12-16,
lost six games by seven points or less, a sure sign they missed
Higgins.
</P>
<P>
   ``He turned around games with his steals,'' CSUN associate head
coach Michael Johnson said. ``Against Northern Arizona we were down
six with three minutes to play and he had three steals and we
won.''
</P>
<P>
   During his one healthy season at CSUN, Higgins averaged 11.6
points. But it was his school-record 74 steals that caught
everyone's attention. When he broke his foot last season, Higgins
was averaging 10.2 points and 5.4 rebounds per game. Yet it was his
defense everyone noticed.
</P>
<P>
   It started during games with his brother, Keith, a former
Matador. They would play one-on-one, and the defense was ferocious.
That's where Higgins developed excitement about defense, and he
relishes the work that goes into being a good defender. That's why
he's been able to withstand the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   A junior college transfer, Higgins is about to begin his fourth
fall practice after the NCAA granted him a rare sixth year of
eligibility in June. He used his redshirt season after breaking his
left foot during the first week of practice during the 1995-96
season and has pins in both feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if anyone's gone seven years,'' Higgins, 23,
said. ``That would be a record. Even I can't do that. If it hurts,
I won't tell anybody. They won't even know. I could be on the court
grimacing and hurting. I'm playing defense. I don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Higgins didn't exactly select this drawn-out process for using
his eligibility, but if you're going to use a sixth year, this is a
nice time to do it. Despite returning two starters and four
letterwinners from last season, much is expected of CSUN.
Particularly in the Big Sky Conference.
</P>
<P>
   It's because five redshirts return, including point guard Markus
Carr. And it's because of the arrival of 6-foot-9, 250-pound Rico
Harris. He's an NBA prospect who transferred from Los Angeles City
College, where he averaged 24 points and 15 rebounds a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of our individual work has been just on defensive
positioning,'' CSUN coach Bobby Braswell said. ``We have to play
good defense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
